<HEADLINE>
GARCIA KEEPS HEAD STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Could buddies Fernando Vargas and Robert Garcia of
Oxnard be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, the IBF junior middleweight champ, has a knack for
finding trouble. He's scheduled to defend his title against Ronald
Wright but only if he's not sent to jail for pending assault
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Garcia was asked what he'd like to do after his
boxing career: He wants to be a cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seriously considering that,'' said Garcia, who defends his
IBF junior lightweight title against Diego Corrales tonight on the
Mike Tyson-Orlin Norris undercard. ``I think a lot of kids in the
neighborhood look up to me. I think I could do a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, the bad boy, commands much more attention and money than
Garcia because of his remarkable skills, Olympic background and
notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, like Vargas, is undefeated _ (32-0, with 24 knockouts) _
but has yet to receive universal recognition or anything close to a
seven-figure payday. He'll make a career-high $200,000 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   He outpointed Harold Warren in March of last year to win the
title and has defended twice, the last time a decision over capable
John John Molina in January.
</P>
<P>
   His handlers have spoken to those of WBC champion Floyd
Mayweather about a title-unification bout early next year. Garcia
would be a significant underdog against the richly talented
Mayweather, but a victory could make him a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of fight I need, the kind of fight that will
prove I'm a great champ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's Corrales, an unbeaten (28-0, 23 KOs)
resident of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia hasn't fought since the Molina fight, nine months ago. He
had been scheduled to face Derrick Gainer in June but pulled out
because he objected to the judges selected for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   That layoff and the fact Corrales is 6-feet tall _ Garcia is 5-7
_ make this a potentially difficult fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't box, if he stands in front of me, that will be
good,'' Garcia said. ``I heard he's going to box, though. It'll be
a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Big Bear two months focusing completely on Corrales.
I'll be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up: If Tyson defeats Norris tonight, he's expected to face
Shannon Briggs on Jan. 29 at Madison Square Garden in New York. No
contracts have been signed.
</P>
<P>
   The other Norris: Norris' younger brother, former junior
middleweight champ Terry Norris, has been training the past few
months and plans to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Norris (47-9, 31 KOs) hasn't fought since he was stopped by
Laurent Boudouani in November of last year and is thought to be
washed up. One rumor has him facing Julio Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual card: A card featuring boxers from the United States
against kung fu martial artists from China is scheduled for Dec. 11
in St. George, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters will be required to observe the rules of their
discipline, meaning the boxers cannot kick. Eight bouts of five
rounds each are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The show could be on cable or pay-per-view television, depending
on whom promoter Ron Weathers is able to sign to fight. He has
spoken to Hector Camacho and other well-known boxers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get recognizable champions, it could be on
pay-per-view,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
