<HEADLINE>
LORD GREY, 89, QUEEN'S LAST GOVERNOR IN ULSTER  
 BERNIE PRIVIN, 80, BIG-BAND TRUMPETER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Lord Grey of Naunton, the last official representative of the
queen of England in Northern Ireland, died Oct. 17 in Naunton,
Gloucestershire. He was 89.
 &HT;    From 1968 to 1973, Grey was governor of Northern Ireland, the
British province. After that the post was abolished and Britain
appointed a secretary of state for Northern Ireland, based in
London.
 &HT;    Although Grey's responsibilities were largely ceremonial, they
included a few important duties like formally appointing the prime
minister and reviewing legislation.
 &HT;    He previously served as governor of British Guiana, as Guyana
was then known, and later of the Bahamas.
 &HT;    While previous governors in Ulster often remained aloof from the
workings of government, Grey was known for his diligent examination
of proposed legislation and for not being afraid to point out what
he regarded as errors.
 &HT;    Ralph Francis Alnwick Grey was born in Wellington, New Zealand,
on April 15, 1910. He was educated at Scotts and Wellington
colleges in New Zealand and received a law degree from Auckland
University College.
 &HT;    In 1936 he was accepted by the British Colonial Administrative
Service, and the following year he was posted to the Eastern
Provinces of Nigeria. He rose steadily through the ranks of the
Colonial Office and was noted especially for his efforts to combat
the practice of kidnapping children and slave trading in Nigeria.
 &HT;    He was knighted in 1956, and was raised to the peerage as Baron
Grey of Naunton, the town in Gloucestershire where he had settled.
 &HT;    Grey's wife, Esme Kirkcaldie, died in 1996.
 &HT;    He is survived by two sons and a daughter.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernie Privin, a big-band trumpeter who performed and recorded
with Tommy Dorsey, Benny Goodman, Artie Shaw, Louis Armstrong and
others, died on Oct. 8 in White Plains Hospital in White Plains,
N.Y. He was 80 and lived in Hartsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was colon cancer, said Elwyn Walshe, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Privin bought a trumpet the day after hearing Louis Armstrong at
the Apollo Theater when he was 13. He taught himself how to play,
and six years later he joined the Tommy Dorsey orchestra, replacing
Charlie Spivak. In 1938 he joined the Artie Shaw orchestra, then at
the peak of its popularity, and was the soloist on ``Traffic Jam,''
among other compositions. In the early '40s he spent two years
working with Benny Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his military service as trumpet soloist in Glenn
Miller's Army Air Force Band, and after being discharged he
returned to Goodman's band, Late in the '40s he was hired by the
CBS Staff Orchestra, a job he kept for 25 years, playing in such
shows as ``The Ed Sullivan Show.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Ethel; two daughters, Beth Ochs of
Riverside, Calif., and Amy Privin Schwartz, of Gilbert, Ariz.;
three grandchildren, and nine sisters and brothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
