<HEADLINE>
AT HOME AGAIN, A LEADER EXHORTS COUNTRYMEN TO REBUILD EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``Indonesian'' to ``international'' in graf 2 and
to make grafs 3 and 4 more precise.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ With controlled fury, as if with each word
he could begin to rebuild his shattered homeland, the leader of
East Timor, Jose Alexandre Gusmao, exhorted his weeping countrymen
Friday to show the world their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we would suffer!'' he shouted, his words echoing
through a microphone across a vista of burned and vandalized
buildings, and broadcast on international television. ``But we are
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under threat from the Indonesian-backed militias that continue
to torment East Timor in a campaign of organized vengeance, Gusmao
was flown in secret on Thursday night to the capital, Dili, on an
Australian military plane.
</P>
<P>
   As he addressed a crowd of 500 people on his first visit home
since his arrest and imprisonment in Indonesia in 1992, Gusmao was
flanked by foreign bodyguards in battle fatigues, holding rifles
and scanning the surroundings through dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the man who is widely seen as the future leader of
an independent East Timor was a signal of the slow rebirth of the
territory, which was ravaged by the militias in response to its
vote of nearly 80 percent on Aug. 30 to become independent of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of national humiliation on Wednesday, the Indonesian
national assembly formally accepted that vote. The recognition of
the democratic choice of the territory it invaded in 1975 coincided
strangely with the assembly's choice of a new president, an
experiment in electoral politics after a generation of one-person
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao's words Friday, enunciated slowly and fiercely in the
local language, Tetun, seemed to try to begin East Timor's revival
by infusing his people with a sense of determination and hope for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will show the world, we will show Indonesia, we will show
ourselves that we can do it!'' he shouted to the crowd, in which
most people had lost their houses and possessions and many were
still searching for missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether it was tears or rage or the battle cry of
a former guerrilla leader that caused his voice to break and seemed
to fill each word with pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put in the past the evil they have done to us,''
Gusmao said. ``Tomorrow is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The return was a month after the arrival in Dili of the first
elements of the 8,000-member security force.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as it deploys slowly throughout the territory, the force
has begun to engage in small fire fights with militias. Military
officers say they believe that some of the militia members are in
fact renegade Indonesian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The international force has also begun finding evidence of
killings in twos and threes and fours, bodies in wells, in creek
beds, in ponds and in fields. But so far, the troops and U.N.
officials say, they have not found evidence of the large-scale
massacres that had been feared.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is expected in the coming days to approve the
creation of an international administration for the newborn nation,
backed by 10,000 soldiers, that would run its affairs for two to
three years while Gusmao and his allies put a government apparatus
in place.
</P>
<P>
   That process will require the writing of a constitution, the
passing of laws and the creation of the fundamentals of an
independent nation, from law enforcement to electrical power
supply.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The creation of a new East Timor will literally be from the
ground up. Most people now have no houses. Those with houses often
have no roofs. And for now, few building materials or tools are to
be found anywhere in the burned and vandalized territory.
</P>
<P>
   Small markets have sprung up in Dili and in some other towns.
But they sell almost nothing besides vegetables and black-market
Indonesian military rations. International aid agencies have begun
streaming into the territory, often competing or working at cross
purposes with one another, according to officials there.
</P>
<P>
   Many groups have set up clinics and hospitals, and the news from
those centers offers a rare encouraging sign _ there is little
evidence of starvation, epidemic or injury by armed men.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of East Timorese have been driven from
their houses and are still too frightened to return from
mountainside refuges. But the humanitarian disaster that had been
feared has not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking in this aftermath is the seeming pointlessness
of the campaign against the East Timorese. Six weeks after it
began, it is evident that the rampage of destruction, killings and
forced evacuations _ unlike many other eruptions of violence around
the world _ was not fired by any ideology, territorial claim,
ethnic conflict or tactical design.
</P>
<P>
   The rampage appeared to be an almost wholly negative enterprise
of retribution, engineered by what may have been a relatively small
group in the Indonesian military, against a people who had rejected
them after a failed 24-year campaign of armed pacification.
</P>
<P>
   As they departed, Indonesian soldiers or their militia
surrogates set fire to almost every administrative building,
including their own barracks, that could be used by a new
government. On the burned out buildings they left graffiti that
served as explanatory captions like ``Freedom in the jungle.'' And,
in a warning that people there would starve: ``A free East Timor
will eat stones.''
</P>
<P>
   But the last small units of Indonesian soldiers are pulling out
now, following the vote of their parliament, and Friday the last
word belonged to Gusmao.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to kill us,'' he said. ``But we are still here,
crying and suffering but still alive. We will rebuild our homeland.
Nothing can stop us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
