<HEADLINE>
REPORT ON HALF-NAKED
 NEWSCAST TURNS OUT
 HALF-BAKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - It was just the kind of tasty morsel a critic of TV
news loves to munch. A new nightly newscast, featuring anchors and
re porters wearing bikinis and Speedos, is coming soon on cable TV.
<TEXT>
<P>
   How low can TV news go?
</P>
<P>
   ``The broadcast is slated to debut in January, from Miami's
South Beach,'' reported the media maga zine Brill's Content in its
November issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all goes as planned, Bare Essen tials News will deliver the
national news in a half-hour time slot be tween 5 p.m. and 7 p.m.
every week night.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's Florida producers are ``scouring the top journalism
schools for talented young journalists who have good grades and
great bodies,'' said a blurb in the Los Angeles Times last month.
</P>
<P>
   A producer said the show was squarely in line with the finest
traditions of TV journalism. All news programs pander for ratings,
he said, and his is just the first that's willing to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give it that much. But what a sterling example of how
shallow television news is becoming, I thought. It reminded me of a
recent complaint by another TV news critic, Bill Moyers. Pressures
to attract more viewers have led many TV operations to seek ``the
fastest, cheapest, easiest way to get an audience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What could be cheaper than drawing people to news with sheer sex
appeal?
</P>
<P>
   My ranting was cut short, however, when I found a story about
the show from the Miami Herald. Terry Jack son, the paper's TV
critic, wrote earlier this week that the Brill's report about Bare
Essentials News airing in January was overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Schorr, a Miami entrepreneur who came up with the fleshy
idea, told him the show was just an idea that hasn't gone much
beyond the concept stage. Schorr told me the same Thursday, Oct.
21st.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald's story said Nicholas Varchaver, senior editor at
Brill's Content, acknowledged that the magazine ``didn't nail down
the very tentative nature'' of the show before giving it prominent
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blew it,'' Varchaver is quoted as telling the Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brill's Content considers itself a media watchdog and
regularly puts the bite on other journalists, this was interesting.
</P>
<P>
   I called Varchaver to confirm his candid admission.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ``We blew it'' quote was taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Those words referred to a part of the story that said the same
producers had come up with a hit show called Senior Prom, a dating
game for people over 50, that was syndicated in 35 markets.
Varchaver said he could find no evidence that the dating show ever
aired. The maga zine will say so in a correction next month.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he doesn't think the bikini-clad newscast will
ever go on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Then why not also set the record straight about Bare Essentials
News?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our story demonstrated skepticism about that show,'' Varchaver
said, lamely.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the sort of weaseling you would expect from a
magazine that preaches accountability and pub lishes in each issue
a statement of principles saying journalists ``should be eager'' to
correct ``mistakes of fact, context and fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine reported that a show using half-naked newscasters
is scheduled to be broadcast in three months, and it's not true.
The editor doesn't believe the show will ever be broadcast, yet he
contends no correc tion is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   That seems irresponsible not only to me, but also to Schorr, the
man who would like to produce the newscast but concedes it's still
little more than a concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brill's has egg all over its face,'' he said. ``It ran a story
reported by an intern without verifying it. The mag azine lambastes
other media for premature and inaccurate reporting. That's exactly
what this was.''
</P>
<P>
   TV news is often justly criticized for superficial reporting,
for jumping on an attention-grabbing item and pumping it up. Here's
a case of the same thing being done by a maga zine, one that
aspires to be an aggressive watchdog tracking down slipshod
journalism. Brill's got the story wrong and ought to set it right.
Steve Wilson can be reached at (602) 444-8775 or at
steve.wilson &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
