<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WATERHEATERS2TAKES-KA     10-23 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF WATER HEATERS OFFER TO REPLACE DEFECTIVE PART 
</HEADLINE>
 HEATERS 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's largest manufacturers of water heaters, trying to
stop mounting legal and public relations problems, have agreed to
repair up to 14 million water heaters that have a defective piece
of plastic pipe.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, filed late Thursday at the U.S. District Court in
Kansas City, will include mass mailings and ads in hundreds of
newspapers to notify customers of the problem. The industry had
previously downplayed the problem but is offering the agreement to
settle class-action lawsuits across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge still must approve the settlement, but it has
been agreed to by the manufacturers of virtually every water heater
made in the United States and two dozen law firms who have sued
them.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, first reported on in January by The Kansas City
Star, involves a piece of plastic pipe called a dip tube, which
funnels cold water to the bottom of the water heater. A defect in
the tubes causes them to disintegrate, making the water heater less
able to produce hot water and clogging water lines with plastic
chips as the tubes dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement would replace, if the consumer files a claim, dip
tubes in any of an estimated 14 million water heaters made from
August 1993 to October 1996. In addition, those who have already
paid for repairs will be able to be reimbursed for at least $175 of
their expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who believe that their faucets, dishwashers and other
plumbing or appliances have been ruined by the plastic chips also
will be eligible to have those items repaired or replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys and others involved in the settlement declined to
specify the settlement's price tag. But if 10 percent of affected
consumers took advantage of the offer, the expense could exceed
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the settlement is Perfection Corp., the Ohio company
that made the defective dip tubes, which cost less than $1 each.
The manufacturers say they will seek to recover from Perfection any
costs for correcting the dip-tube problem.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Perfection said Friday that a dispute with its
insurers kept it from joining the proposed settlement. The proposed
settlement's costs, if they all had to be paid by Perfection, would
put the company's future in doubt, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This threatens Perfection's existence,'' said William Mertens,
an attorney for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed settlement is a striking turnaround from earlier
this year, when Perfection and the water-heater companies
downplayed the problem. Perfection, the primary supplier of dip
tubes to the water-heater industry, acknowledged that from 1993 to
1996 it had left out an important additive that kept the tubes from
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   But while millions of defective tubes were in use, Perfection
and the water-heater companies insisted that the number that would
fail would be quite small _ perhaps no more than 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were raised over how accurate such an estimate could
be since the defect had not been publicized but at least 10,000
heaters had been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers usually reimbursed customers for repairs if
the problem was brought to their attention, but there was no recall
of the heaters or notification to affected consumers. Indeed,
earlier this year the manufacturers' Web pages didn't even mention
the dip-tube problem.
</P>
<P>
   That low-key approach, as much as the defective dip tubes,
seemed to arouse the ire of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Phelps of Northbrook, Ill., recently spent $250 to
replace a faucet that had been clogged by the plastic chips before
he saw a news story about the dip tubes and discovered his water
heater had the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can break, but I'm less forgiving if they don't admit
it,'' said Phelps, the editor of an engineering magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The water-heater companies and Perfection now concede that they
underestimated the problem, although they still believe only a
fraction of the defective dip tubes will fail.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the problem spread, so did the manufacturers' legal
and public relations woes. The proposed settlement seeks to make
the debate about the number of tubes that will fail irrelevant
because all of the defective dip tubes _ whether they have begun to
disintegrate or not _ would be eligible for replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to do the right thing,'' said Ralph Phalen, an
attorney for Humphrey Farrington &AMP; McClain in Independence and
co-lead counsel in the settlement talks. Phalen and his colleague,
Garrett Hodes, filed the first class-action lawsuits against the
water-heater makers.
</P>
<P>
   The water-heater companies approving the settlement are Rheem
Manufacturing Co., American Water Heater Group, Bradford White
Corp., A.O. Smith Water Products Co. and State Industries Inc.,
which says it used the defective tubes only in late 1994 and early
1995. A manufacturer of commercial water heaters, Lochinvar Corp.,
also has endorsed the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   None of the settlement's provisions will go into effect until
they are approved by U.S. District Judge Howard F. Sachs, who among
other things will look at its fairness to consumers. But court
documents specify what the manufacturers have agreed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who have already made repairs will have until June 30,
2000, to file a claim for reimbursement up to $175, which will
automatically be deemed ``reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Any costs over that amount will have to be approved by a
``special circumstances panel'' made up of plumbers. The panel
members are to be approved by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Those who haven't made any repairs will have until Dec. 31,
2000, to file a claim to replace the dip tube and _ if the tube is
dissolving _ to flush out their water heater and water lines. They
will receive a certificate that will be given to the plumber who
does the work.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
