<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF WATER HEATERS OFFER TO REPLACE DEFECTIVE PART 
</HEADLINE>
 HEATERS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Class-action lawsuits have been criticized for often failing to
do little more than generate fees for lawyers. Attorneys filing the
dip-tube lawsuits will receive fees up to $5.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Baker of Orange Beach, Ala., says he'll do his part to
make sure the manufacturers pay. He recently spent two weeks trying
to find out why there were plastic chips in his bath water before
finally being told about the dip tubes.
</P>
<P>
   He was so angry at the lack of available information that he
stood up during his church's services to tell the congregation
about the dip tubes and that he was available to share the
information he had gathered.
</P>
<P>
   After services, about two dozen people told him that they, too,
had the problem, he said. Some had tears in their eyes, he said,
after telling him they had already paid for the repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just sad,'' he said. ``You shouldn't have to go through
this.'' (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-POLICY-BOS &LR;      10-23 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-POLICY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE WORLD TURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All American presidents nearing the end of their terms become
lame ducks. But there are different degrees of presidential
hobbling. Unfortunately, President Clinton and some conservative
Republicans in Congress are restricting Washington's freedom of
action in a world that will not wait for a new US president to take
office.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries cannot be faulted for reading the Senate's vote
this month against the Test Ban Treaty as a troubling symptom of a
dysfunctional superpower. Although Republican administrations
initiated the arms control process that led to the test ban and the
United States ceased testing nuclear weapons during the tenure of
George Bush, a cluster of isolationists and arms control skeptics
in the Senate played on enmity for Clinton to defeat the treaty. At
the same time, allies such as Britain and France that had ratified
the treaty must have been bemused by Clinton's dilatory efforts to
lobby for votes in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The unpleasant truth is that no party and no faction wins if
America's allies and rivals sense that US foreign policy might be
paralyzed for 15 more months by domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's opponents in Congress may have potent reasons for
disliking him, but some of their efforts to humiliate him risk
humiliating the country and undermining its security.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Clinton makes a harmful mistake if he tries to
preserve his own legacy by berating Republicans for their
obstructionism in order to endow his party with winning issues for
attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties, Congress, and the president need to act on an
understanding that there are some matters more grave than winning
partisan political advantage. And if such an understanding is to
permeate the country's political class, the press will have to play
its part in preserving some perspective on political conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty is an important
story not because it signified a personal rebuke of Clinton but
because it might make it harder to keep India, Pakistan, China, and
Russia from developing nuclear weapons. When Republicans refuse to
appropriate the funds promised to Israel and the Palestinian
Authority to implement their Wye River Agreement, the crucial
consequences will be played out in the geopolitics of the Mideast,
not in political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the advent of a new administration, a number of
international challenges will confront the United States. In each
of these there ought to be room for a debate that leads to a
national consensus. But consensus will be possible only if
Clinton-haters in Congress subordinate their personal animus to the
general good and if Clinton performs the hard political task of
consulting and courting a responsible opposition _ as he did in
garnering support for NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   On the docket right now are negotiations with Beijing for
China's accession to the World Trade Organization. One of Clinton's
worst blunders was his failure to accept trade concessions offered
to him last April by China's prime minister, Zhu Rongji. Clinton
mistakenly thought there would be too much Republican opposition to
a WTO deal. He failed to count votes, and he compounded his error
with a display of political cowardice. Now it will be much harder
to obtain the bipartisan consensus needed to bring China into the
WTO and end the annual debate over China's trading status with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another question that cannot be postponed is how to prevent
North Korea from developing nuclear arms and long-range missiles.
After an extensive review of policy toward North Korea, former
defense secretary William Perry told the Senate this month that if
Pyongyang ``is willing to forgo its long-range missile program as
well as its nuclear weapons program, we should be willing to move
step by step on a path to a comprehensive normalization of
relations, including the establishment of a permanent peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative strategy, a resort to military containment,
would be ``expensive and dangerous,'' Perry said. To avoid those
costs and dangers, Congress will have to muster bipartisan support
for the track leading to normalization, and the White House will
have to orchestrate cooperation among the United States, Japan, and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Peace in the Mideast, China's entry into the WTO, and the taming
of North Korea _ these matters are too serious to be decided by the
narcissistic feuds of domestic American politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SALMON-BOS &LR;      10-23 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SALMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPHILL SWIM FOR ATLANTIC SALMON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt's proposal to add the Atlantic
salmon to the endangered species list has put federal and Maine
officials at odds after several years of cooperation. A smooth
working relationship between the two levels of government is vital
if the species is to be rescued.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict emerged earlier this month when a report by two
federal agencies found the wild Atlantic salmon close to
extinction. When Babbitt's office hinted it might change the status
of the salmon from ``threatened'' to ``endangered,'' Maine's
governor, Angus King, and Senator Olympia Snowe cried foul, calling
the move for tighter restrictions a betrayal of two years of
federal-state cooperation in restoring salmon stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The raw numbers are discouraging. Surveys of Maine rivers used
by salmon for spawning have found only 29 fish returning this year.
The issue is complicated by rapid growth of salmon aquaculture in
Maine, now a $60 million industry. Federal officials claim that
some of these fish are escaping and mating with wild salmon to the
detriment of the species. Maine officials counter that the problem
is European salmon escaping from Greenland hatcheries, over which
neither state nor federal officials have authority. In either case,
it is essential that dependable barriers prevent the escape of the
European hybrids used in Maine hatcheries, and spawning rivers must
be monitored against invasion by non-Atlantic salmon. Federal
officials also wisely recommend wider use of American hybrids,
which are less threatening genetically to Atlantic salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Fish farming can play a role in the economic recovery of Maine's
coast _ provided it is properly managed. The key is close
cooperation among governments and aquaculturists to preserve the
unique character of the Atlantic salmon, which is seriously
threatened despite what appeared only a few years ago to be good
chances of recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
