<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLPARK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK ABOUT NEW BALLPARK DOWNTOWN MAKES NO SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A couple of things distinguish David Glass
from most of the rest of Kansas City's sports fans and downtown
boosters. For one thing, he's got a lot more money. For another he
has a better sense of the area's needs when it comes to sports
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   His comments to The Kansas City Star sports columnist Jeffrey
Flanagan this week were a reminder of how lucky Kansas City is to
have Glass in charge of one of the community's most valuable civic
assets. As chief exec of the Royals, Glass seems dumbfounded by the
recent discussion of how wonderful it would be to build a new
downtown baseball stadium. His levelheaded reaction revealed the
extraordinary business savvy that put him on a career path to help
build the world's largest retail enterprise and ultimately head it.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Kauffman Stadium is ``one of the finest _ if not the
finest _ in baseball,'' he wondered, ``why...anyone would even talk
about a new baseball stadium in Kansas City is beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too. The reactive thoughts not only have focused on the lack
of need, but also on the community's spotty record of
accomplishment in such matters.
</P>
<P>
   If momentum for a new sports palace builds, has anyone thought
about where it would be situated? How about next to the snazzy
Power &AMP; Light District entertainment-retail-office complex proposed
for downtown? After the games, everyone could fall by Planet
Hollywood for a late dinner and nightcap. (Assuming, that is, the
Centertainment development gets built and Planet Hollywood doesn't
slide into oblivion.)
</P>
<P>
   South of Bartle Hall might have been another possibility, but
that area's recently been spoken for as a site for a performing
arts center. Given the promised development that hasn't come to
fruition there over the past couple of decades, though, it's a bit
early to start counting chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture? Those who call sports gabfest shows and chat
about building this or that sports facility don't seem to
understand how difficult it has become to make big Kansas City
dreams into big realities.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, nobody talking the talk seems able or willing to do
much more than talk. All the mindless palaver that occurs on sports
talkathons aside, those with power and money seem reluctant to do
big deals unless it's with other people's money.
</P>
<P>
   Union Station's rebirth, for example, certainly wouldn't have
been possible without average folk stepping up to the plate and
volunteering to be taxed to see this dream realized. Meanwhile, the
next big deal is occurring over in the other Kansas City as work
continues apace on the NASCAR track, which is a really big deal in
the annals of sports dreams coming true for a community.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom-line message of recent history in these pursuits, it
seems, is that some dreamers are in bad need of a reality check.
Talk, as always, is cheap. When it ignores the value of existing
assets, however, it's the mark of a community badly in need of
can-do leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
