A5974 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ABUSE-KAN &LR;      10-23 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 POLICE GIVE WOMAN A CHOICe: HER BROTHER OR HER GRANDKIDS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City was already on edge when Carl J.
Miera arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Pamela Butler had just been kidnapped. Then, Miera
_ a Colorado parolee convicted of sexually assaulting a 6-year-old
girl _ moved to the Hickman Mills area of south Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Police learned that Miera was staying with his sister, Lucy
Aguirre, who baby-sits eight young children _ half of them her own
grandchildren _ at her home.
</P>
<P>
   Miera, 46, spent the last 16 years in a Colorado prison. Aguirre
said he called two weeks ago saying he needed a place to stay while
he got his life back together.
</P>
<P>
   Miera, she said, had received death threats since his release
Oct. 7, so she agreed to let him move in.
</P>
<P>
   To her it was simply helping out family.
</P>
<P>
   To Kansas City police the arrangement did not seem so benign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has done his time,'' said Maj. Rachel Whipple. ``But
at the same time, I don't want him around kids. It's hard to
predict who is still dangerous and who isn't. But you just don't
put kids at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado authorities had alerted Kansas City police of Miera's
move. And upon his arrival Oct. 13, Miera registered as a sex
offender with the Jackson County sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors were notified by the South Patrol Division. Police
also contacted the Missouri Department of Family Services, and on
Wednesday an officer and a social worker visited the Aguirre home.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, they told her, was that she could not continue
to watch the children while Miera lived at the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was either him or my grandkids,'' Aguirre said
softly. ``They didn't even give him a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the children's safety comes first, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a responsibility to keep these kids safe while they
are in her care,'' said Family Services spokeswoman Deb Hendricks.
``We were just working with law enforcement to try to protect these
children.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Aguirre said, Miera packed his bags and
took the first bus back to Colorado to stay with another relative.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County sheriff's officials have since confirmed he has
left the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless he is actually committing a crime, we have no authority
to bother him, nor should we,'' Whipple said. ``But this is one
where we felt that possibly children were in danger, so we're
obliged to be a little more proactive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
