<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ACCREDITATION-KAN &LR;      10-23 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCREDITATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _Kansas City high school student Laura Prewitt
and her friends have heard the reassurances _ loss of state
accreditation won't keep qualified students out of good colleges.
But they're not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear one thing and something else always comes up, and I end
up asking more questions,'' said Prewitt, a junior at Lincoln
College Preparatory Academy who hopes to go to the College of
William and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Education voted this week to take away the
Kansas City School District's accreditation, effective next May.
</P>
<P>
   But admissions officers at area colleges say graduating from a
school that doesn't have state accreditation won't wipe out a
student's eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   If the student has good ACT or SAT scores, excellent grades in
hard classes and a strong class rank, the student's application
will be impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes personal interviews and college-administered entrance
tests in math or English also can help admissions officers decide
whether a student will succeed in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of ways to get at the truth,'' said Mark
Kopenski, vice president for enrollment at Rockhurst University,
which enrolls several dozen district students each year. ``If you
see a terrific kid from the Kansas City public schools and they
have great test scores and they're highly motivated, we won't shut
them out. We want that kid here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Smith, director of admissions at the University of
Missouri-Columbia, said admissions officers will work with students
who show promise, regardless of their school's accreditation
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to leave the students in the lurch in a time
when the school district will be working toward reestablishing
their situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Home schools, as well as many private and charter schools,
aren't accredited, but colleges evaluate those graduates on their
scores on the ACT or SAT, their grades and which classes they took.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Gordon has been a guidance counselor for 10 years at
Lincoln, where more than nine of 10 students went on to a four-year
college last year and where the students' average ACT score of 23.4
was the highest in the district.
</P>
<P>
   She said students continue to worry even though they've been
reassured that colleges still will consider them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much emotion that they're not hearing everything
they need to hear,'' Gordon said. ``I think this should be an
incentive for them to really apply themselves even more. Eyes pop
open when scores are good and the curriculum is challenging and the
student has done well.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lincoln is accredited by the North Central Association of
Colleges and Schools, which should help smooth the application
process, Lincoln's principal told students Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The North Central Association was established so that colleges
would know an applicant was coming from a school with good academic
standards, without investigating each high school themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Other Kansas City high schools _ Central, Paseo, Southeast and
Van Horn _ also have North Central accreditation. The association
does not accredit whole school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Accreditation through regional associations like North Central
is voluntary. The association looks at criteria including teacher
qualifications, school offerings such as classrooms and library
volumes, and students' academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shaw, Missouri director for the North Central
Association, said accredited schools are reviewed each year to
ensure they're meeting the association's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of state accreditation could hurt Kansas City schools'
reviews by North Central, if the loss further erodes teacher
qualifications and academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, it could have serious consequences, but it doesn't
mean that North Central would immediately say, `You're
unaccredited,' '' Shaw said. ``They'd say, for example, `You have
to clear this up before next year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Such uncertainties frustrate students who are looking toward
college.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Bell is a Lincoln junior who plans to apply to Spelman
College, a historically black college for women in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to leave Lincoln,'' she said. ``But I don't want
to stay if they lose accreditation and I can't go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Spearman, a Lincoln junior who hopes to be accepted at
Xavier University, said Kansas City high school students probably
should take the initiative and call the schools they want to go to
and ask how admissions officers will evaluate students from a
school district that is not accredited by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan is to end (high school) at Lincoln, but we're
worried,'' she said. ``Do we need to score higher on the SAT to
have colleges look at us? I believe (officials) to a certain
extent, but they've left questions unanswered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SCHOOL-KAN &LR;      10-23 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL DISTRICT TO ARGUE IN COURT AGAINST LOSS OF
ACCREDITATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple on Tuesday will hear arguments
on whether the Kansas City School District's loss of accreditation
will hinder its desegregation efforts and chances of being freed
from federal court control.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Education voted unanimously Thursday to
strip the district of accreditation, effective May 1, after it
failed to meet any of 11 performance standards on the latest state
review.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are asking Whipple to block the state's action
and seeking to have the state once again named as a defendant in
the desegregation lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents filed this week, district lawyers argued that
the loss of accreditation _ the state's stamp of approval _ would
make it impossible for the district to improve student performance.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain how Whipple will act. But in a January court
order that dismissed Missouri as a defendant in the desegregation
lawsuit, Whipple wrote: ``The state should be warned by its
twenty-one year involvement in this case against taking any actions
which might prevent the (district) from ultimately fulfilling its
court-ordered remedial goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren,
said Friday he thought the state's action certainly will have that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want for the district to meet its court-ordered
obligations sooner or later,'' Benson said. ``The state action may
have made later more likely.''
</P>
<P>
   State Education Commissioner Robert Bartman on Friday said he
did not think the state's action and the court's goals are mutually
exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court-ordered goals and our goals are about the same,''
Bartman said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said no one in Kansas City should have been caught off
guard by the state board's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was describe the condition of education in the
Kansas City district,'' Bartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Jay Nixon, whose office would represent the
state in the desegregation lawsuit, could not be reached for
comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   School district officials contend losing accreditation would be
financially devastating, speed the student brain drain from the
district, upset efforts to maintain the racial balance in schools,
and make it harder to recruit and keep good teachers. Those factors
would combine to make it nearly impossible to narrow the
achievement gap between black and white students, something the
court has said the district must do if it hopes to return to local
control.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of accreditation also could prompt the district to request
a postponement of a January hearing to determine whether the
district should be freed from federal court control.
</P>
<P>
   Desegregation Monitoring Committee Chairman John Murphy said the
district would have a tough time arguing it had done everything it
could to eliminate segregation if it was unaccredited. Being
unaccredited would make it even more difficult to meet that
standard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Catch-22,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the terms of the three-member Desegregation
Monitoring Committee expire in March and it's uncertain what would
happen to the advisory group if the district sought to postpone the
January hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all up in the air,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   In a semi-annual report to the court filed Friday, the
Desegregation Monitoring Committee expressed hope about the current
administration's ability to make improvements. But the committee
warned that too many distractions are making it hard for new
Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. to focus on student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The Desegregation Monitoring Committee harshly criticized the
school board, accusing members of pursuing personal agendas and
playing to audiences instead of addressing crucial academic issues.
The report also accused the board of interfering with Demps'
leadership, trying to influence hiring and pushing favored
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those findings, Murphy said he was still disappointed by
the state board's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the district was beginning to make some progress,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a difficult hurdle for the new
superintendent to overcome even though none of it his fault. The
superintendent needs to rally community support for the school
system. That is extremely difficult to do when you demoralize the
entire community and that's what the loss of accreditation does.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some district officials fear the loss of accreditation
could be the death knell for the district.
</P>
<P>
   Once unaccredited, district students immediately would be able
to enroll in surrounding districts willing to accept them. The
Kansas City district would be responsible for tuition and
transportation costs for students who choose to attend other
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said the state hoped to stop any transfers this year by
delaying the effective date of the accreditation vote to May 1. He
thought it unlikely, however, that the district could show enough
improvement by then to avoid the loss of accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My presumption is if they can show some substantial efforts
that have the potential to lead to gains, they'll want to come back
and argue that the status of being unaccredited should be set aside
or at least delayed,'' Bartman said. ``But from my perspective, I
can't imagine the data changing by May 1.''
</P>
<P>
   District officials also fear the transfers could accelerate the
``devastating talent drain that has afflicted the (district)''
since a 1995 Supreme Court ruling that struck down the
interdistrict transfer portion of the desegregation remedy.
</P>
<P>
   District lawyers argued that the talent flight gathered momentum
as the district closed buildings and cut programs, reduced the
magnet school system and returned to predominantly neighborhood
schools. The advent this year of charter schools _ publicly funded
schools that operate free of many local and state regulations _
furthered accelerated the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest achieving pupils of the district have been
siphoned off and the transfer out provision will hasten the
departure of the remaining few,'' district lawyers wrote in their
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers argued that the retention of middle-class students is
important to the district not only because they tend to score
higher on standardized tests, but because they serve as peer models
for their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their departure will leave a more uniformly poor and lower
achieving student body behind and deprive the district of at least
one asset available to most Missouri school districts having a more
economically diverse student body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
