<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-POLLUTE-DIESEL-AZR &LR;      10-23 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTE-DIESEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIESELS GIVE VALLEY BROWN CLOUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new report, released just as the Phoenix area enters the
winter pollution season, traces the Brown Cloud directly to the
exhaust pipes of the very same motorists who lament the stain it
leaves on Phoenix's horizon.
</P>
<P>
   It documents that diesel engines spew out a disproportionate
share of the microscopic bits of soot and grime that create the
visible pollution. And it discounts the belief that the desert
terrain is the reason why the Phoenix metro area is bedeviled by
the Brown Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the report, prepared for the Maricopa Association of
Governments, targets diesel engines and fuels for cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings could lead to recommendations by MAG,
which represents Valley city, town and Maricopa County governments.
But one state lawmaker is prepared to act already.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Allen, chairwoman of the House Environment
Committee, said she'll take a hard look at the report's findings.
She may incorporate them into legislation, even if it means taking
on the powerful trucking industry and the business community that
increasingly relies on trucking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' the Scottsdale Republican asked. ``We have nothing
to lose but a Brown Cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Berry, vice president of Swift Transportation Co. and a
member of the technical committee that is overseeing the Brown
Cloud study, opposes requiring cleaner diesel fuel in Arizona. &QL; 
NATIONAL STANDARD SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Berry wants a national diesel-fuel standard. This would
set a uniform requirement for truckers, who travel cross-country,
and avoid a patchwork of clean diesel and dirty diesel states, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, could take an act of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phoenix's visual pollution has become as reliable a
winter phenomenon as the tourists who flock here.
</P>
<P>
   State studies show that the Brown Cloud is advancing, even as
the Valley has made big strides in meeting federal health standards
for two other major pollutants: ozone and carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Over five years, the Arizona Department of Environmental Quality
found that average daytime haze is 40 percent dirtier. The news is
worse for the ``cleanest'' hours of the day. They are now 93
percent dirtier.
</P>
<P>
   If these trends continue, the agency predicts, what was
considered ``dirty'' air in 1998 will become the norm in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the (air-pollution) trends, and they've made
remarkable progress in everything,'' said Tom Moore, air-monitoring
manager for the DEQ. ``The exception is visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuous measurements made by the DEQ since 1993 paint a
deteriorating picture of Phoenix's visi bility.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only long-distance views that are obscured or
obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   ``More importantly, if you're standing in it (the urban haze),
you don't see as well,'' Moore said. &QL; 
SIGHTS LOSE COLOR, FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   That means that the subtle red tones of Camelback Mountain are
blurred, and the dramatic folds of other urban mountains get ironed
out by layers of fine pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   The main cause: The 64 million miles traveled daily by Phoenix
area commuters.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown Cloud study, started three years ago in response to
growing concern about visible pollution, echoes the air-monitor
findings.
</P>
<P>
   A draft copy of the report identifies particulate matter that is
2.5 micrometers or smaller as the main ingredient of urban haze.
The carbon particles contained in the exhaust of both gasoline and
diesel engines absorb light, creating the dark color that gives the
Brown Cloud its distinctive hue.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny bits of exhaust also scatter light, creating a haze
which disrupts long-distance vision and detracts from the sky's
blue color.
</P>
<P>
   Other bits of particulate matter also mix into the Brown Cloud,
but in much smaller proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Dust, for example, makes up about half the particulate matter in
the metro area, but accounts for less than 10 percent of the
visible pollution. That's because natural dust is too large to
scatter light and create a Brown Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   The fine particles in the Brown Cloud pose a health threat,
especially for the very young, the elderly and those with
respiratory problems. They threaten tourism, clouding the clear
views and blue skies that visitors expect of Phoenix winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about the quality of life,'' Allen said. ``Those of
us who live here don't like it.'' &QL; 
MEDICAL CONSEQUENCES
</P>
<P>
   On the medical front, the American Lung Association of Arizona
sees the Brown Cloud as a major health issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diesel exhaust is to outdoor air what secondhand smoke is to
indoor air,'' program director Dave Feuerherd said.
</P>
<P>
   The study &UR; found that diesel exhaust makes up nearly one-third of
the total exhaust, even though only 3 percent of the registered
vehicles in Arizona are diesel powered, according to the state
Motor Vehicle Division.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the report suggests that cleaner diesel fuel,
cleaner diesel engines and diesel-exhaust controls should be the
focus of efforts to reduce the Brown Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   That's music to the ears of advocates such as Feuerherd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clean up our gasoline for carbon monoxide, and you know
what?'' he asked rhetorically. ``We don't have any violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for ozone pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What entity, what force, is preventing us from cleaning up our
gasoline to deal with particulates?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Allen knows the force of the trucking lobby, but said last
week that she's willing to take them on again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, she sponsored a bill that would have introduced to
Arizona a cleaner-burning diesel fuel mandated by the California
Air Resources Board. The bill died after a crowded, contentious
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Allen doesn't blame the trucking industry for protecting its
interests. Truckers large and small complained that a new fuel
would drive up their costs and possibly drive some out of
business. &QL; 
PUBLIC PRESSURE NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the general public puts more presure on the
Legislature,'' she said, ``I don't think we'll get CARB
(California-required) diesel.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, the trucking industry representative, said the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency is working on a low-sulfur diesel
fuel, and ARCO is experimenting with a diesel formula that would
create emissions as clean as those from natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe you can get a better, cleaner fuel,'' Berry said.
``I don't care what the recipe is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuel issues aside, Berry questions whether the steps recommended
in the Brown Cloud report will make a noticeable difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the regional (MAG) council approves the report, then
what?'' he asked. ``Does the Brown Cloud go away? I understand it
does not.''
</P>
<P>
   The report will be reviewed at a public workshop Oct. 25th at
1:30 p.m. at the MAG offices, 302 N. First Ave., Suite 200,
Phoenix. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
