<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-RACISM-KAN &LR;      10-23 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACISM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK CONGRESS MEMBERS LABEL SENS. ASHCROFT, BOND `RACIST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE, SCOTT CANON, DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two black members of Congress, including Rep. William Clay of
St. Louis, have branded Missouri Republican Sens. John Ashcroft and
Kit Bond ``racist'' for their work in defeating Ronnie White for a
federal judgeship.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, in the final term of a 32-year congressional career,
lashed out first on Thursday. ``I don't have to bite my tongue,''
the Democrat told Fox News. Ashcroft and Bond ``both committed
racist acts in denying this individual (White) a chance to
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Rep. Maxine Waters, a California Democrat, echoed
Clay and accused the senators of an ``evil, racist act.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the fresh allegations, the senators Friday defended
their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, these smears have gone too far,'' Ashcroft said in a
statement. ``An accusation of prejudice or racism is meant to hurt,
and it does hurt. Every person is a special creation of God. I
believe that the same God who judges all of us by the contents of
our characters, not the colors of our skins, calls on me to do no
less.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bond aide referred reporters to an opinion piece the senator
wrote for The Kansas City Star this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, I was compelled to vote against Judge
White's confirmation,'' Bond wrote. ``In spite of the recent
attempts to sully my reputation with baseless renunciations, I
remain certain that my decision was the right one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said he voted against White because of opposition from
Missouri's law-enforcement community.
</P>
<P>
   Clay said he did not know how voters would respond next year
when Ashcroft, a Republican, runs for re-election against
Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan. But, he said, ``I hope they would
reject a racist like Ashcroft to serve in the U.S. Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting along party lines Oct. 5, the Senate rejected White, the
first black judge to serve on the Missouri Supreme Court, on a
54-to-45 vote. The opposition of Ashcroft and Bond, the two
senators from White's home state, was considered pivotal to White's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft led the opposition, citing what he called White's weak
record on capital punishment. Bond announced his dissent the day
before the vote. Other Republicans cited Bond's stand as the reason
for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Waters accused Bond of lying in an interview on WGNU Radio of
St. Louis. Black leaders have complained that Bond promised to
support White during his re-election campaign last year. Bond has
denied he made such a pledge.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Star the congresswoman also took aim at
Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went to his colleagues and told them this was a
re-election issue to him, I sincerely believe what he was saying
was, `I am appealing to the worst instincts in my white
constituents and pointing to this black man as not being competent.
My campaign will be built around how I stopped the black man,' ''
Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not apologize for calling him a racist and I will not
apologize,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has said political considerations played no role in his
opposition to White. On Friday, he continued to insist that White
was ``soft on crime.'' He also cited White's contention that
highway drug checkpoints are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nomination was rejected on the merits, principally the
nominee's poor record on the death penalty and drug enforcement,''
Ashcroft said. ``Americans of every color are entitled to effective
protection from violent criminals and illegal drugs. I will not
knowingly support any judicial nominee for a lifetime appointment
who is soft on crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has refused to say whether he regards Ashcroft's
opposition to White as racist, but has said that political
considerations drove the rejection. White has not commented on the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Angry, racially tinged rhetoric has been mounting in Congress
since White's defeat. Minorities have said they face tougher
scrutiny in gaining Senate approval for top appointments.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, black lawmakers in Congress called on President
Clinton to use ``recess appointments,'' a constitutional method by
which the president can bypass the Senate and put judicial
candidates on the bench. The legislators unveiled the unusual
strategy during a rally Thursday that was organized by
African-American lawyers and law students to protest the Senate's
rejection.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said Friday the administration
does not comment on the possibility of using recess appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Toiv cited an Oct. 21 letter from the Missouri Fraternal Order
of Police to the National Sheriff's Association that objected to
the sheriff group's opposition to White.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one more piece of evidence, if more was needed, that
Judge White's record was distorted for partisan political
reasons,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, House Minority Leader Tom Daschle, a South Dakota
Democrat, complained that the GOP was demonstrating a pattern of
``anti-minority sentiment.'' The most recent example, Daschle said,
was the embattled nomination of former Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, an
Illinois Democrat, as ambassador to New Zealand. He also cited
White's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, threatened to derail the Moseley-Braun
nomination if the former senator fails to apologize for critical
remarks she made six years ago about the Confederate battle flag
flying over the South Carolina capitol. Moseley-Braun was the
nation's first black woman senator.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of White's defeat, black leaders in Kansas City and
St. Louis have pledged to mount aggressive campaigns against
Ashcroft next year. They said statistics from the Missouri
Democratic Party prove that White's record on the death penalty is
similar to the records of several Ashcroft appointees to the
state's high court.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said he has supported ``scores'' of blacks for judicial
nominations and for top jobs in the executive branch. Those
appointments include Fernando J. Gaitan Jr. as the first black on
the Missouri Court of Appeals, Western District, in Kansas City.
Gaitan now serves on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to support African-Americans for the federal
bench because America needs their strong minds,'' Ashcroft said. He
said he would not consider race as part of the appointment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American should recognize that African-Americans have
suffered discrimination and been victimized many times over,''
Ashcroft said. ``Because African-American leaders charge that
members of the community are victims of racism again, in the White
nomination, I can understand how some African-Americans believe
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their charge is both false and divisive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
