<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASIA-2000-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVENTY THEATERS TO GET `FANTASIA/2000'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALENCIA, CALIF. -- Santa Clarita Valley moviegoing received a
status upgrade as The Walt Disney Co. announced the Edwards Imax
theater in Valencia will be one of only 70 theaters worldwide to
show ``Fantasia/2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment giant plans to keep the film limited to Imax
theaters for four months after it opens on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Valencia, located 30 miles from downtown Los
Angeles, the chain announced Friday it will show the updated
animated classic in three other Southern California theaters:
Cathedral City, Irvine and Ontario. The Valencia venue became the
second Imax outlet in Los Angeles County this summer, joining the
California Science Center south of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Disney and Toronto-based Imax have designated
about one-third of the world's 200 Imax theaters as sites for
``Fantasia/2000.'' It will screen at 38 U.S. locations and at 32
sites in 14 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The film will feature seven new segments plus ``The Sorcerer's
Apprentice'' from the 1940 original, a marriage of classical music
and animation that initially bombed before becoming recognized as a
breakthrough film. ``Fantasia/2000,'' supervised by Walt Disney's
nephew Roy Disney, includes interpretations of compositions by
Beethoven, Gershwin, Saint-Saens, Shostakovich and Stravinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets went on sale Friday along with the launch of the
fantasia2000.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Disney, who is vice chairman of the corporation and
executive producer of the film, is betting that filmgoers will be
attracted by the uniqueness of the Imax format, which uses
80-foot-high screens and a film image 10 times larger than the
conventional 35 mm frame. If Disney is right, ``Fantasia/2000''
could surpass the record $72million in grosses taken in during the
past two years by MacGillvray Freeman's ``Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney has not yet disclosed if it will take ``Fantasia/2000''
into conventional theaters once the four-month period has ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `Fantasia/2000' will play to packed houses for those
first four months,'' said entertainment analyst Kevin Skislock of
Laguna Research Partners, noting that the film could be a major
draw for school classes during daylight hours. ``It will create a
lot of fanfare because of the unique way it's breaking. Disney has
seized upon a new technology to reach audiences more effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Skislock also said the performance of ``Fantasia/2000'' could
help relieve Wall Street concerns about Imax's future, including
whether the market for giant-screen venues is saturated and if
mainstream-type films can succeed in the Imax format. Its success
could spark other studios to make similar forays into the
giant-screen market, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Skislock and other analysts have also suggested that Disney may
eventually buy Imax if the partnership goes smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
