<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S ON-GOING LESSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Phil Jackson knows a lifetime of ill
free-throw shooting isn't fixed overnight, so he's taking a
measured approach where Shaquille O'Neal's percentage is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it right now? Twenty-four (percent)? I'd like it to be
25 tomorrow, 26 the day after,'' the Los Angeles Lakers coach said
Friday night before the Lakers played their final game in the Forum
_ a 112-100 exhibition loss to the Phoenix Suns before a
less-than-capacity crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has assigned assistant coach Tex Winter _ who once
tutored Dennis Rodman in the same manner _ to work daily with
O'Neal. The results so far have been, well, difficult to see.
</P>
<P>
   After going 5 for 15 Friday, O'Neal actually !ital!improved!off!
to 27.1 percent (13 for 48) in the exhibition season, making his
career mark of .536 look downright respectable by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging part is that O'Neal delivered in the clutch
Thursday. After missing his first 10 foul shots, he hit his 11th
try to force overtime in an eventual victory over Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   So what are Winter and Jackson advising O'Neal? Jackson is
mostly mum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say one word about that, and that's that he doesn't have
a rhythm when he's on the line,'' he said. ``It's all about finding
a rhythm and the timing of being into his shot.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, O'Neal chalks it up to lack of concentration but
said Winter is trying to get him to put more arc in his shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably need to take a little bit more time,'' said O'Neal,
who scored a game-high 37 points Friday. ``Usually when I try too
hard, I don't do well. I'm probably just trying too hard. Because
you know I want to shut all you guys up. ... That's the only `but'
I got in my life. Everything else I'm perfect at. Perfect albums,
perfect movies, perfect low-post game. Perfect life. But `he's not
a good free-throw shooter,' so I mean I always hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said he welcomed the chance to take critical foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``And most of the time when I'm put in that situation, the best
things always happen for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting Bison: Bison Dele, who in his previous life as Brian
Williams won a championship with Jackson's 1997 Chicago Bulls, is
retiring rather than play for the Detroit Pistons. Might he put off
retirement to rejoin Jackson? That's an idea Jackson wouldn't mind
pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great addition it would be for our team,'' Jackson
said. ``It'd be a luxury to have a player like him. But that's not
possible, he's retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   The enigmatic Dele has five years and $36.45million left on his
contract but is reportedly in Lebanon, running a water-treatment
plant he owns (``I heard he's going to desalinate the ocean near
Lebanon. That's some far-out stuff,'' quipped Jackson).
</P>
<P>
   But the coach isn't sure what to make of Dele, who he called
``one of my best students I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a special relationship with Brian Williams,'' he said.
``I don't know Bison Dele. I've never met him, we've never had a
conversation. If Brian Williams wants to talk to me about playing
basketball and he comes and tells me that he's Bison Dele, yes,
we'll have a conversation, we'll have lunch together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Robert Horry left the game in the first half
because of a sore left knee and did not return. Horry, who suffers
from chronic tendinitis in both knees, is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Knight's sprained right ankle is healing but Jackson
figures Knight won't be ready to open the season Nov. 2 and
predicted he would start the season on the injured list.
</P>
</TEXT>
