<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-COYOTES-LAD     10-23 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-COYOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Los Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray called
timeout early in the third period Friday night, he was one angry
parent.
</P>
<P>
   The team had blown a two-goal lead and now they trailed the
Phoenix Coyotes, who made a habit of beating up the Kings last
season.
</P>
<P>
   This was a new year and a new building and the Coyotes are a
team the Kings have to beat to reach the NHL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings lost 6-3 in front of a booing crowd of 16,572 at the
Staples Center. They weren't just beaten, they were outplayed.
Although Ian Laperriere scored two goals for the Kings, the Coyotes
scored short-handed in the second period and added the game-winner
early in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Daron Quint blew past the Kings defense, went by Bryan Smolinski
and sailed a goal over the left shoulder of Kings goalie Stephane
Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   It only got worse from there, when Phoenix had goals just 10
seconds apart by Keith Tkachuk and Mika Alatalo with less then six
minutes to go in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's jaw clenched during the timeout, but it didn't help.
After starting the season 3-1, the Kings are 1-2-2 in their last
five and winless in the last three.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset spared the Kings further damage when he stopped Rick
Tocchet on a breakaway midway during the third period, but it
didn't matter. The Kings had just four shots on Phoenix goalie
Mikhail Shtalenkov during the first 10 minutes of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov, elevated to No.1 goalie in the absence of holdout
Nikolai Khabibulin, stopped 23 shots to raised his record to 5-1-1.
Fiset, who has played in all but one period of the Kings first nine
games, had 28 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Laperriere's second goal, which beat Shtalenkoa close in after a
pass from Brad Chartrand, came just 1:13 into the second period and
gave the Kings a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Coyotes, who went 5-1-0 against the Kings last
season, no lead was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had a man advantage with 15:35 left in the second
period when defenseman Keith Carney went off for hooking. But
Phoenix's captain Keith Tkachuk won the ensuing faceoff and passed
to Teppo Numminen, who got the puck to Dallas Drake at center ice.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kings' blue line, Drake fired a long shot past Fiset to
cut the lead to 3-2. Drake's shot tipped off defenseman Garry
Galley and the misdirection confused Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   Numminen was at the center of the Coyotes' tying goal, digging
the puck out of the corner and setting up Trevor Lefkowski for a
25-foot slap shot that beat Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lefkowski's first goal of the season. It was Numminen's
third assist of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had vowed not to come out sluggishly Friday, the way
they had Wednesday in the home opener when they fell behind winless
Boston and had to struggle for a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did that we could be looking at a long night,'' Murray
said. ``Phoenix is a very explosive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray found that out later, but in the first period, the Kings
scored first.
</P>
<P>
   Laperriere, limited to one assist and a minus-four in eight
games, found himself in front of the net when the puck trickled off
Aki Berg's stick. He fired it through the legs of Mikhail
Shtalenkov to give the Kings a 1-0 lead with just 3:54 gone in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Coyotes are off to their best start in franchise history
for a reason. Just five seconds after Brian Smolinski went off for
hooking, Travis Green tied the game with a power play goal.
</P>
<P>
   For Green, the former Duck who has taken over as first-line
center in the absence of suspended center Jeremy Roenick, it was
his fifth goal in the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, however kept the pressure on and scored in the final
minute of the first period to take a 2-1 lead. Ziggy Palffy, a
former teammate of Green's with the New York Islanders, poked in a
rebound with 17 seconds left after Rob Blake's blast from the point
got away from Shtalenkov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
