<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LOOKING FOR WAY OUT OF MIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the nature of USC's topsy-turvy season that
satisfactory explanations have become the Trojans' latest casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Why has USC struggled in the fourth quarter of nearly every game
this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had an answer, I would shout it off rooftops,'' USC coach
Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   No one saw Hackett screaming atop Heritage Hall this week, so
the solution apparently remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes today's 12:30 p.m. game against Stanford at the
Coliseum even more important for the Trojans (3-3, 1-2), who are
still searching for an identity and struggling to remain bowl
eligible at the halfway mark of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A game with Stanford would normally be an elixir for any
problems, but in a role reversal, the Cardinal (4-2, 4-0) is atop
the Pacific-10 Conference and hoping today's contest will solidify
its status as Rose Bowl favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they're playing, they're pretty cocky and confident,''
USC free safety David Gibson said. ``And they should be. They know
what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Trojans. They want a victory, because a loss will
basically turn this season into a complete disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game, as important as it is for Stanford, it's huge for
us,'' Gibson said. ``This is a big momentum game for us. I wouldn't
have expected Stanford to be where it is, but we have to deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're where we are, what you need to do is get a
victory,'' Hackett added. ``Just to find a way to get out of the
funk we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans may have lost three games, but they still haven't
lost their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be the turning point for us,'' wide receiver
Windrell Hayes said. ``There's probably more frustration for us
than anything else. We know we have the ability to play with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference for the Trojans is that they play four of their
final six games at home. They are 1-3 this season away from the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this from the very beginning, playing on the road is
no fun,'' Hackett said. ``When you open the season with four out of
the first six games on the road, three of which are tough places to
play, you might come up short if you are not a real strong, strong
football team. And we just were not able to make the plays we
needed to make.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly been Stanford's problem, at least in the Pac-10.
The Cardinal has demonstrated it can win on the road, with
victories at Arizona and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still some skepticism that sooner or later, the
Cardinal's bubble will burst. Even Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham
admitted he didn't expect the Cardinal to be undefeated in the
Pac-10 in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat of a surprise because we've played some very
difficult opponents and had some some success against them and
probably in some of the places that have not been traditional
Stanford favorites,'' Willingham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
