   The problem is that denial and self-denial at the highest levels
bring the unauthorized biographers out of the woodwork. St.
Martin's pulled ``Fortunate Son'' off shelves on the ground that if
Hatfield were a convicted felon that would undermine his
credibility _ as if authoring such works as an unauthorized
``X-Files'' encyclopedia lent him much credibility in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The everyday lies expected in politics can loom larger when they
are under oath or inside the pages of a book. By offering books of
half-truths, publishing offers a moral mirror of politics. But
politics offers the distinct evils of sinning and lying about it.
In publishing, lying can be a crime in itself, since it can
constitute libel.
</P>
<P>
   If Hatfield invented the cocaine charge, that's a serious crime.
But if he's merely a convicted felon who hired a hit man, that
doesn't preclude him from being a successful writer. Indeed, St.
Martin's Press underestimates the forgiveness of the American
people. People might not mind a former convict writing a book as
long as the book is really good. The literati are especially
forgiving, as shown by Norman Mailer's fondness for ``Belly of the
Beast,'' written by the murderer Jack Henry Abbott. And three of
the world's greatest novels were written in prison; John Bunyan,
Cervantes and Dostoyevsky all did time.
</P>
<P>
   The American dream expressed in both politics and literature is
the dream of rebirth and redemption, the notion that anyone can
reform and move on: Former drug users can have political careers;
former felons like Hatfield can write non-fiction works with 54
pages of source notes. The public can forgive almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, that is, except a bad book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6066 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-23 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 (jt)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists Find Enzyme Linked to Alzheimer's
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known for years that to forestall or treat
Alzheimer's disease they needed to prevent hard balls of debris
from accumulating in the brain. Now researchers at Amgen have taken
the first step toward that goal. They found an elusive enzyme that
snips a brain protein in two, initiating the formation of the
debris. The next challenge, experts say, is to find a drug that
will block that enzyme. If the scientific theory is correct, such a
drug might halt the death of brain cells in people with the disease
and even prevent the disease in people destined to get it.
</P>
<P>
   A Drop in Gun Violence
</P>
<P>
   A seven percent drop in homicides last year was entirely
attributable to a decrease in killings committed with guns,
according to a report released by the Federal Bureau of
Investigation. The decline appears to be the clearest evidence yet
that recent efforts to reduce gun violence through new laws and
police pressure are working. There was also a 10 percent drop in
robberies carried out with guns, accounting for the biggest
decrease of any one category of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Starr Resigns
</P>
<P>
   After overseeing the five-year, nearly $50 million investigation
that led to the impeachment of President Clinton, Whitewater
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr resigned. He was replaced by
Robert W. Ray, a 39-year-old career federal prosecutor who vowed to
complete the inquiry of Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton ``in a
prompt, reasonable and cost-effective manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said his resignation had been prompted by the ``intense
politicization'' of his office's work. White House aides have
already portrayed Ray as an ideologue. Starr rushed to his
successor's defense, saying the criticism should be met with
``sharp and immediate condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Exile Denied
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Papon's efforts to flee justice didn't last long. The
89-year-old former civil servant convicted last year of helping to
send hundreds of French Jews to Nazi death camps was supposed to
start serving his 10-year-sentence on Wednesday. Instead, he issued
a defiant statement saying his only honorable choice was to flee
France and go into exile. Papon was a fugitive for only a few hours
before Swiss police caught up with him in a Gstaad hotel on
Thursday night. Swiss officials handed him back to the French and
he was in jail by Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Money Game Widens
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and top Republican lawmakers agreed
to overhaul America's financial system, repealing Depression-era
laws that have restricted the banking, securities and insurance
industries from expanding into one another's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The deal paves the way for banking conglomerates to offer
consumer services like brokerage accounts and auto and casualty
insurance. It will enable other financial conglomerates to provide
public stock offerings to their corporate clients but loans as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Indicting McDonnell Douglas
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted McDonnell Douglas _ a unit of
Boeing, _ and a state-owned aerospace company in China on charges
of conspiring to hide important details of a 1994 sale of American
machining equipment. The equipment was intended for a McDonnell
Douglas airliner project in China, but six of the machines were
diverted to a Chinese military plant, although they were never put
to use. The companies denied any wrongdoing and vowed to contest
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists Unite
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists normally help people who are depressed, but now,
as a result of the rise of managed care, some are feeling so
depressed they have taken an unexpected action _ they joined a
union. The New York State Psychological Association and its 3,200
members affiliated with the American Federation of Teachers. Their
hope is the million-member teachers' union will use its lobbying
clout in Albany and Washington to gain psychologists a better deal
from HMOs on reimbursements and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   A Faulty Antidote
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon may have moved closer to solving the mystery of
``gulf war syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   A report it commissioned said an experimental drug given to some
250,000 American troops sent to the Persian Gulf may be linked to
chronic symptoms afflicting thousands of veterans, including
fatigue, muscle pain, memory loss and sleep disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials tried to dampen expectations about the drug,
pyridostigmine bromide, saying more study was needed. But it was
the first time the Pentagon acknowledged a possible cause after
years of ruling out others, including gas attacks.
</P>
<P>
   One Less Candidate
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole pulled out of the presidential race _ before she
had even officially announced her candidacy and long before a
single ballot had been cast. She said she couldn't raise enough
money to compete with the financial fortunes raised by Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas or inherited by Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, money is not the only way to grease a campaign. Mrs. Dole
failed to capitalize on her strengths. She boasted of an
``historic'' campaign as a woman but sent a mixed and uncertain
message about what that meant. She missed several opportunities to
build support. After making a splashy gun-control announcement in
front of a pro-gun crowd in New Hampshire, she did not follow
through. After coming in a strong third in the Iowa straw poll, she
vanished from public view.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Reform Loses
</P>
<P>
   The Senate played its accustomed role in the struggle to
overhaul the campaign finance law: for the fourth consecutive year
Republicans used a filibuster to kill the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The action left the effort to ban large dollar donations to the
political parties in limbo: test votes showed it had a majority of
53 senators behind it, though not the 7 more votes needed to break
the filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who has put the battle
against special interest money at the center of his presidential
run vowed the issue will not die. But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
swore the legislation will not live.
</P>
<P>
   And the money chase for 2000 went ever on.
</P>
<P>
   Teen Worries, Up and Down
</P>
<P>
   Being an American teen-ager today seems both scarier and safer
than a few years ago, according to a new nationwide poll of more
than 1,000 teen-agers by The New York Times and CBS News. The
survey found that more than half believed that their school could
conceivably be struck by the kind of massacre that devastated
Columbine High School in Colorado. But in their more immediate,
everyday lives, teen-agers reported feeling safer: Only 24 percent
said they feared becoming a crime victim, compared to 40 percent in
1994, and concern about violence was generally down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
