</P>
<P>
   None of this even gets at the emotional aspect of Rogers' having
to pitch with no margin for error, when he was more likely to throw
an easily hittable pitch, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that poor pitcher,'' said Carl N. Morris, the chairman
of Harvard University's statistics department and a longtime
baseball fan. ``He's got to put the ball over the plate in the
biggest game of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Valentine, his decision was hardly an unusual
one, particularly because it created the possibility for a
force-out at any base as well.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fans are very likely to see similar strategies again
this week in the World Series. Under their manager, Bobby Cox, the
Braves issued more intentional walks than any other team in the
National League this year. In game five against the Mets, in fact,
Cox intentionally walked the bases loaded and then watched his
relief pitcher walk in the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   The intentional walk often looks even worse when used earlier in
a game, when a high-scoring inning is more important to avoid than
a single run. At that point, the walk gives the batters a free
base-runner, who can become a free run.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier playoff series against the Boston Red Sox, Mike
Hargrove, the manager of the Cleveland Indians (who has since been
fired), had the shortstop Nomar Garciaparra walked to load the
bases in the third inning. The Indians were leading, 5-3, at the
time. The next batter promptly hit a grand slam, putting the Red
Sox ahead, 7-5, in a game they went on to win.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, do people who are paid to make smart baseball
decisions often err here?
</P>
<P>
   There is actually a nice theory to explain it, Morris said. In
1982, Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman, then professors at Stanford
University, wrote that people often assess ``the probability of an
event by the ease with which instances or occurrences can be
brought to mind.'' They called this the principle of
``availability.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers envision a slugger crushing a home run before they
adequately consider a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, tourists worry about an apocalyptic plane crash, not
the far more likely fatal highway accident. Homeowners spend
hundreds of dollars on a burglar alarm when simply getting rid of a
gun they own would make their families much safer. And dieters
these days eschew food with fat in it _ fat they can envision
ending up on their midsections _ for low-fat foods that in fact
pack more calories that eventually will turn into body fat.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``innumerate'' decisions, to borrow a word popularized by
John Allen Paulos, a math professor at Temple University, have
clear consequences. Thousands of people really do die on the
highways and from accidental gunshot wounds. The United States,
despite years of obsessing over weight, is more obese than ever.
And, though the stakes are of course far lower, pitchers do
sometimes walk in the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, criticizing a single decision at the end of one of
the most exciting playoff games in history may be a bit harsh.
After all, Valentine ordered an extraordinary five intentional
walks during the previous game, Steve Hirdt of the Elias Sports
Bureau noted. No runs scored after any of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger point stands: Even if intentional walks eliminate
a short-term problem, on average they may create more long-term
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That is cumulative risk. It's a concept worth pondering for
anyone who travels, eats or will be managing this week in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
