46-year-old man, who in July said he would never wear unsightly
artificial arms with metal hooks, now takes a pen from a visitor
with his prosthetic and proudly writes down his name on a
reporter's notepad: Lamine Jusu Jarka. In a country where less than
a third of the people can write, isn't it a shame that Jarka's
handwriting is now barely legible? It will improve, he vows.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government has done almost nothing for the amputees.
A few months ago, rumors swept the camp that the government had
gotten German surgeons to come here, and that transplants were
being performed in Europe. They became angry at the government when
the Germans never came.
</P>
<P>
   If the current peace agreement between the government and the
rebels hold _ hopes were raised Friday by a United Nations decision
to send 6.000 peacekeepers _ what will happen to the amputees? Will
the government take care of the thousands who are estimated to have
lost limbs to machetes? Even if the will exists, what can the
government do in a nation that is regarded as the world's poorest
and where everything must be rebuilt? The question is complicated
by the peace agreement, which granted amnesty to all combatants.
Foday Sankoh, the head of the rebellion responsible for most of the
war's atrocities, acknowledged his group's guilt months ago.
Recently, though, he has been backpedaling. Atrocities? Not me. He
appears more interested in the commission on mineral resources that
he will head. He has never visited this camp.
</P>
