<HEADER>
A6069 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CHILE-IDENTITY-REVIEW     10-23 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-IDENTITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIA WOULD NOT BE AMAZED BY CHILE TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Chileans like to call themselves the English
of Latin America, referring to their reserved social etiquette and
taste for afternoon tea, proper high-cut clothes and Tudor
architecture. Probing even deeper into the national psyche, Chilean
intellectuals identify national traits that hark back to another
English century entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call us Latin Victorians,'' said Raquel Olea, a prominent
literary critic. But with a difference: ``The Chilean is totally
without anguish about his hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Victorians? Well, there is a strong similarity. Like the
outwardly proper classes in Britain a century ago, Chileans put on
a strait-laced front behind which all sorts of naughtiness go
undiscussed. But at the same time, as Ms. Olea points out, the
Protestant Victorians in Britain were guilt-ridden while the
overwhelmingly Catholic Chileans go to church, confess and leave
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how Chileans deal with and, in some cases, avoid
dealing with such difficult and morally charged matters as divorce,
abortion and teen-age pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Chile is the last country in Latin America where divorce is
still illegal, even though the rich and middle class can easily get
annulments through well-connected lawyers who know which judges
will oblige and which will not. Most couples who break up do not
bother seeking annulment at all, since it is expensive and usually
requires lying in court. They simply separate and then match up
with new, common-law partners.
</P>
<P>
   The practice helps explain why almost half of the couples who
live together in this overwhelmingly Catholic country are not
married and almost half of the children born here are born out of
wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of abortion. Due to a 1989 decree by
Gen. Augusto Pinochet just before he left power, Chile is one of
only four countries _ El Salvador, Malta and Andorra are the others
_ that prohibit the procedure under any conditions, even in cases
involving rape or the life of the mother. A handful of women go to
jail every year after they are caught recuperating in hospitals
from the effects of botched abortions. Still, clandestine abortions
are so common that health experts estimate that the abortion rate
in Chile is among the highest in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to stop the clandestine abortions, conservatives
in the Senate proposed a law last year to increase the length of
jail terms for doctors, midwives and others convicted of performing
abortions. The conservatives lost by a single vote, and promise to
fight on.
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant teen-agers are legally forbidden to seek abortions, of
course, and are given few other options. Moralistic high school
principals force many to quit their studies, at least until they
give birth, and girls who are showing are asked not to attend
graduation. In just one of many double standards, young fathers
study on and graduate without sanction. And sex education is almost
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public discourse is one thing, and the way people live is
another,'' said Mariana Aylwin, a former Christian Democratic
congresswoman and senior official in the Education Ministry. ``Our
social elite is very conservative, but I don't know a city in the
world with more motels and infidelity. This is a very hypocritical
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Jocelyn-Holt Letelier, an historian at the Santiago de
Chile University, calls double standards ``the Chilean solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chile is traditional, but it is not an orthodox conservative
country,'' he added. ``It is a morally flexible country. If there
is a gay person in the family you accept it without ever talking
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Victorian-like values also creep into the realm of public
expression. More than 50 films and 700 videos have been banned by
government censors in recent years, usually for their sexual
content or criticism of traditional religious practices. Martin
Scorsese's 1988 film ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' for
instance, could not be shown legally here until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Historians and social commentators say Chilean morality has many
roots, one of which is Chile's isolation; the separation from the
rest of the world by deserts, an ocean and Andean peaks, analysts
say, has slowed the spread of new social trends. Another reason is
the lasting Spanish colonial heritage, which gives the military and
the Catholic Church unquestioned authority. Still another is the
lasting shadow of the dictatorship of Pinochet, particularly in the
areas of abortion and reduced public support for family planning.
</P>
<P>
   Others point to the conservatism of the media _ including two
Church-dominated television channels, one run by the Catholic
University and another by the conservative Catholic organization
Opus Dei.
</P>
<P>
   The church is a powerful institution in virtually every Latin
American country, but it fills a unique political space in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the church in neighboring Argentina, which supported the
military juntas of the 1970s despite violations of human rights,
the Church here was one of the few institutions to raise a public
voice against the excesses of the Pinochet dictatorship. The
liberal political role the Church played in the 1970s and 1980s,
paradoxically, now gives the Catholic hierarchy added weight in
defending many of the moral positions previously promoted by the
very military dictatorship it opposed.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Chile is tradition-bound, social change is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress recently gave illegitimate children full legal
rights and struck down a law that made male homosexual intercourse
illegal. Two years ago the Chamber of Deputies passed a divorce law
similar to Spain's _ allowing divorce after a two-year separation.
But conservatives and church leaders have so far been able to block
enactment in the more conservative Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A nascent gay rights movement is beginning to make an impact,
and is even receiving government financial support to combat the
spread of AIDS. Just this month, seven transvestites protested
police brutality before the Supreme Court building and received a
surprising amount of media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been changes but it is much too slow,'' said
Soledad Larrain, a 50-year-old psychologist at the University of
Chile who has been living in a common-law marriage the last several
years, after having her first marriage annulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two children and a grandchild and I have effectively
been married two times,'' Ms. Larrain said. ``But according to this
society, I'm considered to have been single all my life. It's
totally absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
