<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-23 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CYBERSPAT MAKES HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By KATIE HAFNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month marks the 30th anniversary of the Arpanet, the
Internet's predecessor. Then again, maybe it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at Los Angeles was ground zero for
the Arpanet. Then again, maybe it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   This anniversary of the Internet has been a particularly
contentious one. Vice President Al Gore's misstatement to CNN last
spring that he ``took the initiative'' in inventing the whole thing
was roundly ridiculed by anyone with an inkling of the network's
true origins. But in recent months, several more genuine contenders
have stepped forward to stake a claim to this or that invaluable
piece of the invention, giving rise to a number of public spats.
</P>
<P>
   As barbs fly and longstanding friendships disintegrate, figuring
out just who did what when is more difficult than ever.
</P>
<P>
   I know about this problem at close range. In 1993, when I began
researching a history of the Arpanet, the story seemed a relatively
straightforward one. I scoffed when one of the Net's many fathers
said to me one day: ``Why are you even trying to write a history?
No matter what you write, it won't be the real story.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may be true of history in general, anyone who tries
to write the real story of the Internet right now will encounter a
welter of contradictory material. Now graying, the scientists who
took part in building the Net are busier than they ever were, not
inventing new technologies but telling their side of the story to
reporters, putting up time lines and history pages on their Web
sites and shooting off e-mail messages. The goal, of course, is not
to get rich but to secure a spot in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're witnessing is a case of history getting revised in
real time,'' said Peter J. Denning, a computer science professor at
George Mason University who took part in the development of the
Internet but has remained a largely silent observer. ``We are
watching the process of myth-making as it happens around us.
Eventually certain people will emerge out of the myth and lots of
what's been accomplished will be ascribed to them, even if they
didn't do it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The revision of history while the principal participants are
still alive is not new. The author Stephen E. Ambrose said he
grappled with the phenomenon recently when writing about the
construction of the transcontinental railroad 130 years ago, an
immense project in which dozens of luminaries like Sen. Thomas Hart
Benton and the industrialist Leland Stanford had a hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see how those people fought each other,'' he said.
``They would write letters to The Railroad Journal, or Horace
Greeley's paper, saying, `I'm the one who first suggested it's
possible to build a railroad across the country.'''
</P>
<P>
   To try to sort it out for himself, Ambrose relied on a
well-established body of literature. His advantage was not having
to fend off calls from Leland Stanford's p.r. agency. Nevertheless,
he found no consensus. ``I threw up my hands,'' Ambrose said.
``Don't ask me who first thought of it. I could give you a lot of
entries into the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Brinkley, a professor of history at Columbia University,
says it's a common problem. ``History is constantly being revised
in informal ways, in popular culture and in private
conversations,'' he said. ``There are always many different
versions.''
</P>
<P>
   What's new, Brinkley said, isn't the revisionism as much as the
presence of the Internet as a revisionist's tool, providing an easy
way to spread one's own version of events. The latter-day
equivalent of fighting it out in letters to the editor is to spam
the world with your take, using the Internet as an amplifier.
Whoever is fastest with the send button, whoever has the lengthier
``cc'' list, is most likely to rise above the din.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars are wondering if the Internet will make the process of
historical inquiry more difficult. ``The word definitiveness comes
to mind,'' said Neil M. Postman, a professor of communications at
New York University. ``Print is more definitive. Books preserve
information. The Internet moves information. So with information on
the move, appearing and disappearing, and without gate-keepers, it
diminishes the credibility of claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do electronic versions of events have a way of drifting
more quickly and easily into the public's consciousness, but they
underscore how quickly other information can disappear from the
record.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the continuing paternity battle over the
Internet, Denning pointed to 1989, a more subdued time in the Net's
evolution, when a symposium commemorating the 20th anniversary of
the Arpanet took place at UCLA. Back then, the Net was still
relatively obscure and there was nothing much at stake. In
attendance were the very men slugging it out today. A transcript of
the event has them lavishing one another with praise and credit.
But that transcript exists not on the Internet but on paper tucked
away in the archive of the Charles Babbage Institute of Computer
History in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever remaining solidarity there might be among the Net's
founding fathers is increasing strained. There is one contingent
that stands by early September, when the network got its first
node, as the birth date of the Arpanet. Others continue to claim it
was late October, when the first electronic bits passed from UCLA
to a computer at the Stanford Research Institute, about 300 miles
to the north. Some profess to have invented packet-switching, the
data transmission technology that made it all possible. Still
others claim to have had the idea for a network in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brinkley does not believe the Internet will hamper
historians' ability to gather facts. ``I don't think the Internet
has reinvented history,'' he said. ``It's just expanding and
complicating it a bit. History is always contested, and over time
frivolous claims get discounted, and more serious claims get more
attention, and eventually there's a consensus around a particular
answer. You won't have the open-ended disputes that are going on
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Time may also slow the rush for recognition. Every so often, the
Internet is not glorified but blamed _ for inflation, for the slump
in dot-com stocks, for widening the gap between haves and
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the true dark side comes along, you won't see people
scrambling to take credit for that part,'' Denning said. ``It will
be, `That's not the part I had anything to do with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll say that was Al Gore's part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6513 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-23 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CYBERSPAT MAKES HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
