<SLUG> BC-CELEBS-IPO-REVIEW-NYT8 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7  
 MARTHA STEWART VS. THE   WWF9: THE FINAL CONFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz 10  in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez 11  in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt 12 ) 
 By GEORGE JOHNSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news from Wall Street last week drew attention to probably
the most startling contrast imaginable in American popular culture:
Martha Stewart and the World Wrestling Federation, both going
public to investors on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Stock buyers were clearly more enamored with the mistress of
domesticity than with the minders &UR; 13 &LR;  of Stone Cold Steve Austin
and The Rock. She reportedly became a billionaire overnight, at
least on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, Ms. Stewart and the WWF &UR; 9 &LR;  have a lot in
common, if you take a warped look at quotations from the current
issues of her magazine, Martha Stewart Living, and the wrestling
federation's two magazines, WWF &UR; 9 &LR;  Magazine and WWF &UR; 9 &LR;  RAW.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts follow.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture Alterations  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Inevitably you have more guests than dining-room chairs. So
you drag a couple of chairs in from another room, but they are a
different style. To unify this motley collection, make a matching
set of chair-back covers.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : At the 1999 Royal Rumble, Mick Foley was blasted 12
times by a chair swung by The Rock. A few weeks later, the Road
Dogg &UR; 14 &LR;  drilled Al Snow four times, swinging a chair on ``Raw.''
... Unprotected chair shots are metallic reservations for the
``Alzheimer's Hilton'' and competitors in this business try to
avoid them at all costs.  &QL; 
Aromas!  &QL; 
Martha: You can follow your nose the 15 miles between the two
shops; the irresistible smell of cinnamon sugar and hot biscuits
pulls you from one to the other.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : Nothing rejuvenates pure evil like the putrid smell of
his victims' blood.  &QL; 
A Love of the Wild &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Do you know? Some species of cactus _ prickly pears _ grow
wild on well-drained, sunny sites as far east as Florida and
Massachusetts, and up into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : As Boss Man left the dressing room, Snow leaped onto
him from a platform _ blasting him with a steel chair and dragging
him into the dressing room, where Boss Man battered Snow with a
case containing his dog, Pepper, and hit him with a blackboard.
Snow rammed his rival's head into a glass case and a garage door,
and the pair continued their fracas onto the street.
</P>
<P>
   They soon wound up fighting at an outdoor cafe and in a downtown
Minneapolis bar ... Snow borrowed a chain from a customer to use as
a weapon, delivered a moonsault &UR; 15 &LR;  from the bar, hit the Boss Man
with a billiard ball and scored the pin on a pool table after
smashing the former corrections officer with his own nightstick.  &QL; 
Sandwiches  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Open-face sandwiches are layered with roasted vegetables,
ham, turkey and Swiss, then heated until the cheese melts. They are
served with homemade dill pickles and sweet-potato wedges.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : A ``Rock sandwich'' doesn't consist of meat or tuna
fish but instead several fresh slices of smoked ``shut your mouth''
and some honey-baked ``smackdown &UR; 16 &LR; .'' There's no cheese _ The
Rock doesn't like cheese! Rolls  &QL; 
Martha: Today, with time in short supply, fresh-baked dinner rolls
are a particular treat. While they take a little more effort, rolls
are no harder to bake than bread. They are, of course, nothing more
than bread dough that has been formed, usually by being rolled in
the palms, into smaller, individual portions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : D'Lo &UR; 17 &LR;  countered with the Real Deal, a tilt-a-whirl
slam and legdrop &UR; 18 &LR; . When he tried somersaulting onto his rival,
though, Jarrett rolled out of the way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Decorating  &QL; 
Martha: Ask the children to help decorate (the Thanksgiving table).
They can place felt finger puppets atop candy sticks for a sweet
yet simple centerpiece; older kids can cut and glue paper shapes
for a Mayflower centerpiece and help arrange plates and cutlery.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : ``As fans of body art,'' the wrestler Prince Albert
says, ``of course we're concerned about maintaining a clean and
safe environment when we pierce and tattoo. We wouldn't want
someone's nipple or tongue to get infected and turn green!''  &QL; 
Women Getting Together  &QL; 
Martha: I think I tasted some of Sara's food at a party in New
York, asked to meet her, and persuaded her, and her friend Jane
Stacey &UR; 19 &LR; , a baker, to come and work for me in Connecticut as
chefs in my growing catering business ... They immediately made the
parties I catered even more special.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : Smarting from a recent attack by the champion, Tori &UR; 20 &LR; 
came into the ring with fists swinging, debilitating her rival with
series of suplexes &UR; 21 &LR; . After bouncing off the ropes, Ivory slid
under her foe's legs, drove her face into the mat and executed a
giant swing.
</P>
<P>
   Tori &UR; 20 &LR;  tackled her opponent, spun her upside down and hoisted
her over her shoulders. When Tori &UR; 20 &LR;  tried a sunset flip, however,
Ivory shifted her weight and fell on top of the contender for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the humiliation, Ivory tried ripping off Tori's &UR; 20 &LR; 
outfit after the bell. Suddenly Luna _ absent from the Federation
for months _ stampeded into the ring and chased the Women's
Champion back to the dressing room.  &QL; 
Cravings &UR; 22 &LR;   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: In some families, [Thanksgiving is) largely about stuffing.
After the first helping, the guests all wait for their fullness to
subside so they can have more.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : Gangrell &UR; 23 &LR;  has a hunger, a thirst, an appetite for
control over and complete domination of others. Within him is an
innate drive to lead a tribe of men he can manipulate _ bend to his
will.  &QL; 
Bluster  &QL; 
Martha: Even people who cherish the blustery winds of winter agree
that they are best left outdoors where nature intended.  &QL; 
The WWF &UR; 9 &LR; : You call yourself a fan? Well, son, if you're not a
member of the Squared Circle Club, you're just a piece of trash!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
