<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Oct. 24:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-VISAS (Moscow) _ Exclusive: The U.S. Embassy in
Moscow has sharply curtailed the number of visas issued to
Russians, particularly students and scholars, even as Washington
insists it wants to spread Western values in Russia. Embassy
officials say they need to be particularly vigilant after the
Russian economy collapsed last year, but critics say the embassy
has overreacted and that many worthy candidates have been cast
aside. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-COLUMNIST (Soweto, South Africa) _ A former jitney
driver who now writes a newspaper column about living with HIV has
received an outpouring of support, which has surprised many in a
country where the taboos about discussing AIDS are often
impenetrable. By Rachel L. Swarns &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-CLERIC-TRIAL (Teheran, Iran) _ At his trial next week,
Abdullah Nouri, a key figure in Iran's Islamic reform movement,
will face the most serious charges leveled against any Muslim
cleric since the Islamic takeover _ insulting the prophet Mohammed
and the Ayatollah Khomeini, backing banned political parties, and
``propagating'' friendly ties with the United States and Israel. By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ASSESS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Having anointed its new
leaders this week, Indonesia now finds itself facing the even more
daunting task of redefining and reconstructing a nation whose
institutions, politics, economy and sense of purpose had been
bankrupted by the long rule of former President Suharto. A news
analysis. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires) _ Unemployment and crime are
up, wages are down, and polls show that a growing number of
Argentines think their politicians are stealing fortunes.
Argentines want change, and every recent poll shows that they will
get it, electing Buenos Aires Mayor Fernando de la Rua as president
on Sunday. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ABORIGINES-BRUTALITY (United Nations) _ When Letty Scott, an
Australian who traces her maternal ancestry to a community of
desert aborigines, decided to go international with her campaign
against what she sees as persistent police brutality against her
people, she found help in some unexpected places. Not least was
Foxwoods, the Connecticut casino resort run by Pequot Indians. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   BERGER-ASSESS (Washington) _ Sandy Berger, the national security
adviser, in a speech to the Council on Foreign Relations in New
York last week, tried to provoke a national debate on foreign
policy. Judging by the early reaction to his address, he succeeded,
at least in the short term. But the debate that he initiated
centered as much on politics as on policy. A news analysis. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY-DANUBE (Budapest) _ Hungarian scientists and government
officials warn that ice moving down the Danube in the coming months
may pile up and form a dam behind the bridges bombed by NATO in
Yugoslavia and cause extensive flooding. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-ANDREOTTI (Rome) _ Closing a chapter in Italian postwar
history, a three-judge panel in Palermo on Saturday acquitted
Giulio Andreotti, seven times prime minister of Italy, of charges
that he was the Sicilian Mafia's main protector in Rome. The
tensely-awaited verdict was a vindication for the 80-year-old
Andreotti, who has spent much of the last decade in court. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SOCSEC (Washington) _ President Clinton dropped one of
the most contentious elements of his plan for bolstering Social
Security's finances in his Saturday radio address, and called on
Congress to break the partisan deadlock over how to prepare the
retirement system for the aging of the baby boom generation. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ At a fund-raiser last Thursday,
President Clinton asked one of his closest friends in the Senate,
Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, how the negotiations had been
going with Republicans over the most important financial
legislation since the Great Depression. Dodd was not optimistic
about the bill, which had reached the point of do or die. But over
the next few hours, Dodd returned to the Capitol and, with a
handful of other Democrats from the banking committee, slowly
managed to turn Sen. Phil Gramm, chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, around in an emotional confrontation. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   BUTLER-BOOM (Undated) _ These are lucrative and stressful times
in the annals of household help in the United States. Never before
have there been so many wealthy Americans with so many big houses
that need tending. Yet many of these new rich need as much
schooling in the art of living large as the students in butler
school, according to Mary Louise Starkey, founder of the Starkey
International Institute for Household Management, a school in
Denver that markets itself as the Harvard of high-end household
help. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ICON-VANDALIZED (Los Angeles) _ In recent weeks, images of the
Virgin de Guadalupe, patron of Roman Catholic Mexicans and a
revered icon, have been defaced in more than a dozen incidents on
the walls of bodegas and storefronts in the bustling Hispanic
neighborhood south of downtown. But there has been no civic outrage
and, in fact, few officials and police officers outside the
neighborhood knew about it. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-ACTIVISTS (Boulder, Colo.) _ These are tough times for the
thinning ranks of grass-roots activists trying to persuade
Americans and their local leaders that the Year 2000 computer
problem, better known as Y2K, poses risks that demand serious
family and community preparations. So tough that about 40 of them
from around the country decided to take time out &UR;  &LR; for some
face-to-face commiseration, strategizing and emotional refueling
with their peers. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KLAN-RALLY (New York) _ The Ku Klux Klan holds a rally the
day after a federal appeals court barred them doing so while
wearing masks that shield their faces; counter demonstrations
expected. (Eds: Rally is scheduled to begin at 2 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-GOV-MCCAIN (Phoenix) _ The decision by Arizona Gov. Jane
Hull to endorse Texas Gov. George W. Bush over Sen. John McCain,
the state's favorite son, exemplifies the formidable barriers
McCain faces as he pursues the Republican presidential nomination.
Despite broad appeal on his military record and his feisty
independence, he seems to lack the political base that's the other
ingredient of winning campaigns. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ The preponderance of New York
banking and brokerage firms at the top of Bill Bradley's donor list
has set him apart from the other leading candidates for the
presidency. A thorough look at Bradley's fund raising; who gives to
him and why? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENT-STUDENTS (Reynoldsburg, Ohio) _ Spurred by the deadly
rampage at Columbine High School, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms is working with a threat-evaluation company to develop
a computer information program to help administrators spot troubled
students who might be near the brink of violence. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) ``Liberties'' by Maureen Dowd: It could
be a long time before we see a woman president in Washington. But
we'll see one in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Foreign Affairs'' by Thomas L.
Friedman: The most important story out of Russia last week was
buried in the business pages.
</P>
