<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT A CANDIDATE IN UNIFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although Al Gore has been on the national political
stage for decades, there is much that many voters still do not know
about him, and he has recently been drawing attention to one of
those blind spots: his military service in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign advertisements that began airing last week, Gore
highlighted that service. And for an article in the current issue
of Talk magazine, Gore gave hours of interviews on his decision to
go to war.
</P>
<P>
   These portraits seem designed to flesh out a man often seen as
wooden and perhaps to distinguish him from other presidential
candidates _ most notably, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has
long faced questions about whether his family pulled strings so he
could spend the Vietnam years as a pilot in the Texas Air National
Guard in Houston. But they raise a question, especially in the
context of the Oval Office's current occupant: Are voters impressed
much by a politician's military record or lack of one?
</P>
<P>
   Historians and political analysts said there is no simple
answer, but that in general a military record holds less sway than
before. These experts cited a variety of reasons, beginning with
the fact that more than half a century since the end of World War
II, serving in the military is more the exception than the rule for
most Americans, and is not expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see plenty of candidates for the House and Senate, and they
all gives us a resume, and it may say National Guard duty,'' said
Stuart Rothenberg, editor of the Rothenberg Political Report, a
nonpartisan newsletter that interviews and evaluates candidates.
``But most of the time, the candidates are crowing as to what
church they go to or whether they're in the Rotary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican who is arguably Bush's chief rival for the
party's presidential nomination, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, was a
prisoner of war in Vietnam. But that aura of heroism has perhaps
paled next to the famous surname and tens of millions of dollars in
campaign contributions that have helped propel Bush into the lead.
And Bush _ who has said he is not aware of any favoritism leading
to his noncombat Vietnam experience _ does not seem particularly
worried about voters homing in on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in 1992 gave Bill Clinton something of a pass for
avoiding Vietnam, just as voters have given passes to many
Republican and Democratic members of Congress who also found ways
out of that conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although a letter to a draft board that showed Clinton worried
about his ``political viability'' contributed to his critics'
dismissal of him as ``slick Willie,'' it did not sink him at the
polls. In the primaries, he beat Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska,
who won the Medal of Honor in Vietnam. In the election, Clinton
beat President George Bush, a decorated World War II veteran, as
well as Ross Perot. In 1996, Clinton trounced a decorated World War
II veteran, Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   There remain prominent politicians whose military backgrounds
undeniably burnished their credentials and smoothed their ascents
to office, among them Sens. McCain, Kerrey, Max Cleland, D-Ga., and
Chuck Hagel, R-Okla. But historians and political analysts noted
that those men were decorated heroes, and the political plus of
that special status does not mean that it is a political minus to
have no record of military service at all.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Greenstein, a presidential historian at Princeton
University, said that voters' reaction to a candidate's military
background depends on the type and details of the service. The
political historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. added, ``It depends
on the war.'' In the case of Vietnam, the conflict most relevant
for the largest number of politicians today, Americans' ambiguity
toward the war translates into a willingness to forgive men who
avoided it.
</P>
<P>
   David Doak, a Democratic strategist in Washington, said that
when he worked on the recent campaign of Gov. Gray Davis of
California, polling and focus groups suggested that Davis earned
points when voters learned of his service in Vietnam. But that same
research showed that he stood to lose points if he cited an
opponent's avoidance of service, Doak said.
</P>
<P>
   That dynamic suggests that Gore must be careful in how he
presents his own military history, which is not one of dramatic
combat. Rather, he was an Army journalist, an attractive assignment
that has attracted its own scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gore plays it right, it could soften Gore's somewhat
stiff profile and also peg him in some voters' minds as a moderate,
Doak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think military service helps Democrats in particular,'' he
said. Rightly or wrongly, he said, ``It sends a signal that they're
not run-of-the-mill ultra-liberals.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
