<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6084 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING-2     10-23 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET CONNECTIONS PROPEL BRADLEY'S FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Texas, Ariz., Md., Ind., Calif., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the biggest surprises of this campaign year
has been former Sen. Bill Bradley's ability to be competitive with
Vice President Al Gore in the campaign cash sweepstakes. Bradley
has raised nearly $20 million this year and has more cash in the
bank than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's fund-raising prowess should come as no surprise,
despite his claim to be running as an insurgent candidate who
espouses an overhaul of campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   He was a legendary fund-raiser in the Senate _ raising $9
million a full year before his last Senate campaign, in 1990, and
outspending his opponent, Christie Whitman, now New Jersey's
governor, 15-1. He was one of the top congressional recipients of
money from corporate political action committees before forswearing
their donations this year. He was called ``king of the bundlers''
in 1990 by the Center for Responsive Politics for his ability to
gather scores of $1,000 contributions from individuals employed by
top investment banks, insurance companies, media concerns and law
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bradley's surprisingly strong challenge to Gore is backed
by numerous corporate titans, especially those from Wall Street.
But it is not only as a candidate that Bradley has benefited from
Wall Street's largess: When he left public office in 1996, he
earned $300,000 as a consultant for J.P. Morgan and reaped more
than a million dollars from paid speeches, many delivered to
audiences of financiers, bankers and health executives.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's generosity to Bradley is noteworthy for another
reason: It does not appear to be rooted in favorable legislative
treatment. While he was in the Senate, Bradley espoused proposals
that the financial world opposed, including an increase in the
capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   In his presidential quest this year, Bradley's list of top
fund-raisers includes John Thornton, co-chief operating officer at
Goldman, Sachs; Douglas Warner, chairman of J.P. Morgan; Richard
Fuld, chief executive of Lehman Brothers; John Steffens, head of
brokerage operations at Merrill Lynch; Joseph Flom, senior partner
at the law firm Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, who is a
powerhouse in the world of corporate takeover battles; Sanford
Weill, co-chairman of Citigroup; Thomas Labrecque, recently retired
president of Chase Manhattan; and Louis Susman, a managing director
at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Each has enlisted dozens of bankers and traders from his firms,
as well as wealthy friends and relatives, as $1,000 contributors to
Bradley's campaign. Major Wall Street investment houses are the top
six sources of income for Bradley's campaign, accounting for nearly
$600,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the easiest fund raising I have seen in my
30-year history of raising money in politics,'' said Susman, the
unofficial national finance director for the Bradley campaign. ``We
don't have a Wall Street strategy per se, but Bill has had a
relationship with many of these people over many years and we
involved them early on to see what they could do among their
friends and associates.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of these top executives, their donations to Bradley
are not hedge contributions, in which a donor puts down money on
several candidates. None of the top bankers _ with the exception of
Susman, who also gave $1,000 to the candidacy of Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., ``as a favor to a friend'' _ has so far contributed to any
other presidential candidate, according to records of the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's fund-raising network extends well beyond Wall Street.
He has also used his contacts from 10 years as a player with the
New York Knicks of the National Basketball Association to recruit
top sports stars as fund-raising draws. He used a year as a
visiting lecturer at Stanford University in 1997-98 to nurture
relationships with lawyers and venture capitalists in the
technology corridor south of San Francisco; they have already
raised more than $2 million for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is the preponderance of New York banking and brokerage
firms at the top of Bradley's donor list that sets him apart from
the other leading candidates for the presidency. Only two Wall
Street firms are in Gore's and McCain's top 10 lists of
contributors; only one makes Gov. George W. Bush's list of 10
biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   The only firm to make the top 10 list for all four candidates is
Goldman, Sachs, whose partners and their families have contributed
$22,455 to McCain, $60,250 to Gore, $77,250 to Bush _ and $210,000
to Bradley. Bradley's success is even more notable because
Goldman's former chairman, Robert Rubin, was chairman of the
National Economic Council and treasury secretary in the Clinton
administration. Rubin is so far sitting out the 2000 presidential
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's familiarity with top bankers, brokers and bond traders
grew from his 18 years of service on the Senate Finance Committee.
He was one of the primary authors of the landmark 1986 tax bill and
the architect of a plan to address the Third World debt crisis in
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But even Bradley's opponents cannot point to anything specific
in his Senate career that would account for Wall Street's loyalty
and generosity. He proposed an increase in the capital gains tax,
advocated abolition of a variety of tax shelters and urged banks to
take substantial losses on their loans to struggling economies _
all positions that at times put him at odds with financial
executives.
</P>
<P>
   So what accounts for Bradley's popularity on Wall Street?
</P>
<P>
   Partly it is geography: Bradley attended Princeton University in
New Jersey, represented New Jersey in the Senate and still lives in
northern New Jersey. Partly it is familiarity with the people and
the lingo of Wall Street _ J.P. Morgan hired him consultant within
weeks of his leaving the Senate in 1997. Partly it is his position
as the only Democratic alternative to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And he also helped to give New York something no other area
politician has ever delivered: two NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't any of the policies that make him popular,'' said
Mark Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association.
``Part of it is he was a Knick, and a very successful one at that.
A lot of the Street are sports fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used the two years between retiring from the Senate and
establishing his presidential committee late last year to lay the
political and financial groundwork for his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his work at J.P. Morgan, Bradley signed on as a
consultant with the Gartner Group, a telecommunications research
firm in Stamford, Conn. The company paid Bradley $131,000 in 1998,
according to the personal financial disclosure statement he
released this year.
</P>
<P>
   He took part-time appointments at the University of Maryland,
Notre Dame University and Stanford, earning $170,000 last year for
a handful of lectures at each school.
</P>
<P>
   He gave more than 60 speeches _ at an average of $25,000 each _
to a variety of corporations, law firms and interest groups. Among
them were Rhone-Poulenc Rorer, a pharmaceutical company; Health
Care Information and Management Systems Society; the National Home
Equity Mortgage Association; the Association of Investment
Management Sales Executives; Key Bank; Barclays Global Investors;
the American Association of Health Plans, and First Union Capital
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   So last winter when he announced his intention to seek the
Democratic nomination for president, he had not only a rich list of
potential donors from three successful Senate campaigns, but a new
cache of contacts from his two years out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his proven ability to raise money and win elections,
Bradley seems to have benefited from disaffection among some
Democratic Party donors with Clinton and his chosen heir, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the initial interest in Bradley is the result of
Clinton-Gore fatigue,'' said Bonnie Reiss, a top New York
fund-raiser for Bradley and a member of his advisory board, ``a
feeling that they need to wash their hands of the whole
administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
