<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-23 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHY CAN'T A WOMAN ...  
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It could be a long time before we see a woman
president in Washington. But we'll see one in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   This is tinseltown's scenario about how it could finally happen,
as laid out in a script called ``Madame President'' being developed
by the producer David Foster:
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is ousted in a scandal. The president
appoints an old law school pal, Sen. Diana Bradley, in his place.
The president has a stroke. Diana cha-chas into the Oval Office.
Then our fabulous presidentress slaps around sexist Arab leaders
and takes revenge on a sexist, water-polluting billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would probably want to cast an Emma Thompson type, without
the accent,'' says Pierre Weidemann, Foster's director of
development. ``You wouldn't put Melanie Griffith in it. You're
looking for a powerful woman, like Meryl Streep in `The River
Wild.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Elizabeth Dole exits, everyone's wondering what sort of woman
will ever be able to crash through our stereotypes and tuck those
nuclear codes into her pony-skin Fendi Baguette.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption is a man in a dress. A Margaret Thatcher type,
without the accent.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists, pointing to the paltry number of women running
states and the handful of female senators, are not optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men and women would be much tougher in judging a woman
candidate for president than for senator or governor,'' says Bob
Teeter, a Republican pollster. ``People want to feel safe and
comfortable. They're picking the kind of person they can trust to
go sit in the Oval Office and make value judgments for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Ferraro's vice-presidential candidacy proved that
women do not vote for women just because they are women.
</P>
<P>
   One top Republican strategist bluntly asserts: ``It's been a
longtime secret among political consultants that women hate women
candidates. Women are bred to compete. It's the old thing: You get
12 guys, you've got a football team. You get 12 women, you've got a
riot.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more latitude in attitudes now. Younger women are
more willing to vote for women, and to cut checks.
</P>
<P>
   When there is the element of revenge, women do seem to respond
by gender. Women have flooded to Ashley Judd's ``Double Jeopardy,''
and they enjoy taking revenge on a no-good man in politics, too.
</P>
<P>
   After the white, male Judiciary Committee trashed Anita Hill,
women voters sent a passel of women to Congress. After Bill
betrayed Hillary, her polls shot up so dramatically she decided to
run for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Elizabeth Dole did not get much of a revenge ride when Bob
Dole belittled her and said he wanted to send money to John McCain.
She was just left with a disorganized campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's annoying to hear people argue that she was hurt because of
her gender. But it's even more annoying to see that George W. Bush
is helped because of his.
</P>
<P>
   A female candidate never could get away with confessing, as W.
did, that she's weak on foreign policy but knows whom to ask.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman running for president had said she would rely on the
kindness of advisers to tell her what to do in East Timor, or
stumbled on the pronunciations of several global hot spots, she
would have been immediately dismissed as a dizzy dame.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Ferraro confused the terms ``first strike'' and ``first
use'' in 1994, there was a ruckus. It evoked a picture of the
redheaded Lucy yakking into the red phone, desperately trying to
recall missiles launched because of a misplaced word. Dr.
Strangelucy.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbleheadedness and laziness didn't upend W.'s campaign for two
reasons. It is assumed (falsely) that he hung around his father's
White House long enough to pick up some knowledge, even
subliminally, on his dad's favorite topic. And W. shrugged off
foreign policy with the bravado of the cool football player who
isn't studying for his chemistry exam.
</P>
<P>
   Men can still wing it and be president. Women can't.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary wins a Senate seat, she'll immediately be cast by
liberals and feminists as ``Madame President.'' Emma Thompson,
without the accent.
</P>
<P>
   It would require a Sisyphean effort, though. A political
consultant once had an idea for a novel that might do the trick _ a
la ``Magnificent Seven'' or ``Ocean's 11.'' The most wily, grizzled
strategists come out of retirement and band together for one last
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission impossible: the election of the first woman
president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
