</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCYCLOPEDIAS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBER ENCYCLOPEDIA: THE HIGH ROAD AT A HIGH COST 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Internet users stampeded to visit the Encyclopaedia
Britannica's sleek new Web site last week, the venerable
intellectual icon was nearly road kill on the information highway.
</P>
<P>
   Britannica.com is busily adding computers to handle the more
than 10 million people who tried to peruse its site. But the
company also faces a much bigger question: Will its vaunted
reputation for rigor be compromised by its decision to give free
access to its vast stores of knowledge?
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this decade, annual sales of the familiarly
bound volumes plummeted by roughly 80 percent as Britannica
miscalculated, refusing to produce a cheap, computer-based version
of the storied publication , from which most adults in America used
from grade school on and cribbed at least one science report.
</P>
<P>
   While Britannica was charging up to $2,000 for a 32-volume
edition of books, Microsoft was often giving away CD-Rom versions
of its Encarta encyclopedia to buyers of new computers. When
Britannica produced a CD-Rom, it was $1,000 initially versus $50
retail for Encarta. And when Britannica first joined the World Wide
Web, it did so with a subscription-only site, charging a fee for
access in a medium where nearly all information sites are free.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Britannica.com has joined the Internet mainstream with a
free site that is supported by the sale of advertising and by links
to an array of products for sale. But whether the new economics of
the Internet age will allow the Encyclopaedia Britannica to support
itself as a living document, constantly updated and renewed, is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly face an uphill battle,'' said Thomas S.
Wurster, a vice president at the Boston Consulting Group and
co-author, with Philip Evans, of ``Blown to Bits: How the New
Economics of Information Transforms Strategy'' (Harvard Business
School Press), which is expected to be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Britannica was always thought of as a trusted adviser, known
for its rigorous quality,'' Wurster said. ``But on the Internet,
others, like Yahoo, have a better identity with core users. Because
Britannica will no longer be getting any revenues from their
content, their success will very much depend on whether they can
attract eyeballs to the site,'' and therefore be able to charge
advertisers higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the main competitors for Britannica.com are not
other encyclopedias but online services like Yahoo and America
Online is not lost on Britannica. By offering free content, it
removes any advantage gained by serviceable but generally lesser
products like Encarta, based on the old Funk &AMP; Wagnalls
encyclopedia. And Britannica.com includes not only its entire
encyclopedia but also articles from magazines like The Economist,
Esquire and Sports Illustrated, news links, stock quotes, an
Internet search service, links to Barnes &AMP; Noble's online bookstore
and other commercial sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to be the premier knowledge destination
site,'' said Kent Devereaux, senior vice president for product
development and editorial at Britannica.com, based in Chicago. ``We
have found that the entire definition of the encyclopedia has to
change. If that puts us into the same space as Yahoo and America
Online, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Working to insure that its intellectual edge is not lost will
be, in addition to the traditional team of Britannica researchers,
a second group of content specialists. Their focus will be
preparing weekly updates on current events _ a vast improvement
over the biennial updates of the old print version _ plus taking
advantage of the Internet's audio and video capabilities. While
adding researchers, it has eliminated the door-to-door sales staff
that accounted for most of the cost of the printed version.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming response to Tuesday's unveiling of
Britannica.com showed that the name Britannica retains its cachet
in this country and around the world. If Britannica.com can
continue to attract a passionate audience among the information
generation, it will serve as a stellar example of how companies
that are late adapting to new technologies can end up on top _ if
they have a superior product. But such a brainy product must still
compete in a medium based on entertainment and commerce as much as
information.
</P>
<P>
   And just think what might have been: Even if Britannica.com
eventually completes an initial public offering of stock, it will
probably never catch up to Yahoo's $46 billion market value. For
succor, Britannica.com might consult its own Web site. The
Encyclopaedia Britannica has no entry for ``business failure.'' But
type in those words on its search engine and a visitor will be
offered the chance to buy a potentially helpful book _ titled
``When Things Go Wrong: Organizational Failures &AMP; Breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
