<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BERGER-ASSESS-625&AMP;ADD     10-23 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERGER-ASSESS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: POLITICS AND FOREIGN POLICY TANGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the end of his unusually pointed speech
challenging the Republicans as new isolationists, the national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, vowed to keep up the drumbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to slide silently into isolationism,'' Berger
told a packed room at the Council on Foreign Relations in New York
on Thursday night. ``We're going to rant and rail all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who added the aura of a campaign to his speech by
appearing afterward on a late-night television interview show, said
he was hoping to provoke a national debate on foreign policy.
Judging by the early reaction to his address, he succeeded, at
least in the short term. But the debate that Berger initiated
centered as much on politics as on policy.
</P>
<P>
   To many critics it seemed that if Berger was serious about
initiating this kind of debate, he could have started much earlier
_ for example, after President Clinton signed the global nuclear
test ban treaty in 1996, rather than after it was rejected this
month by the Senate. To these people, the campaign now seemed too
little too late.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Berger contrasted what he referred to as the
engagement of the Clinton administration with the retreat to
isolationism of the Republicans. He castigated the opposition for
forging a ``survivalist foreign policy'' that was short on foreign
assistance and loath to live up to responsibilities abroad. And he
singled out the defeat of the test ban treaty as the moment that
distinguished those who were responsible from those who were not.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who was using the occasion at the Council on Foreign
Relations to make a comeback after harsh criticism of the White
House's management of the treaty vote, had barely stopped speaking
when the responses began.
</P>
<P>
   The House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, said Berger
was speaking on behalf of a ``frustrated'' administration that had
been unable to get what it wanted out of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Others wondered aloud whether Berger's intention was truly about
fundamental foreign policy issues, including reversing the decline
in money for foreign programs, or whether it was to gain a
campaign-year advantage for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants the money, but whether this is a serious tactic to
get the resources for foreign policy, I'm deeply skeptical,'' said
Morton Abramowitz, a former U.S. ambassador to Thailand and Turkey.
``The decline in resources on foreign aid can't be blamed in one
shot on Congress. The president does not know how to reverse it and
doesn't show much interest in doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most startled reaction came from Republicans who see
themselves as supporters of U.S. involvement abroad but who do not
believe that opposition to the test ban treaty should be used as a
litmus test of isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he does is lump everyone together,'' said Robert Kagan, a
fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace and a
contributing writer at the Weekly Standard, a conservative
political magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're skeptical about China, for Berger that's a
manifestation of isolationism,'' he said. ``If you worry about
Russia, that's another manifestation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kagan said it was a misreading to state that isolationists in
the Republican Party caused the downfall of the test ban treaty.
``Look who voted against the treaty _ Senators Chuck Hagel, John
McCain, Richard Lugar _ that's the international wing of the
Republican Party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a potential for Berger to exploit the differences
between the two wings of the Republican Party on foreign policy,
several Republicans said. But instead, Kagan said, the speech ran
the danger of unifying the Republicans in a presidential election
year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Berger's speech came as the White House was beginning
negotiations with the Republican leadership on the budget and after
Clinton vetoed legislation the week before last that fell $2
billion short of the White House request for foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign policy demands, including money pledged to Israel
and the Palestinians for going ahead with last year's peace deal
and for the United States' dues and debts at the United Nations,
emerged last week on the short list of White House priorities.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be slight movement toward winning agreement on
the U.N. financing, Republican congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief delegate to the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke,
continued to press Republicans to stop an amendment that banned
U.S. financing of family planning clinics abroad from being
attached to the U.N. legislation. Clinton vetoed such legislation
last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Republicans stressed that members had little to
gain in an election year by appearing in favor of spending money on
the United Nations. If Washington fails to pay part of its dues by
the end of the year, the United States will lose its seat in the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has shepherded legislation that calls
for payment of the arrears in exchange for administrative reforms
at the United Nations. But his spokesman, Marc Thiessen, pointed
out the quandary for Republicans in taking a positive position on
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't made Helms a hero in conservative circles,''
Thiessen said. ``How many Republicans lose sleep if we lose our
vote in the General Assembly? A handful. But the Clinton
administration cares, and if they want it to happen, it's up to
them. They've got to be flexible to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some skepticism about whether the Clinton administration
would follow through on a foreign policy debate, Berger's speech
and his pledge to persist recalled a campaign by Henry Kissinger in
his last two years as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between liberals who complained about U.S. intervention
in Vietnam and conservatives who were concerned about detente with
the Soviet Union, Kissinger tried to invigorate the loss of
momentum in foreign policy by making a series of speeches around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   He articulated his view of the United States' role in the world
and tried to address newer issues of the period, including energy.
</P>
<P>
   If Berger decided to keep his pledge to persist with a foreign
policy debate and Clinton joined him, they could make an important
contribution, said Leslie Gelb, president of the Council on Foreign
Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the Clinton administration to keep pressing on this
point, or the idea of having a national debate won't work,'' Gelb
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
