<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-VISAS-ART     10-23 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-VISAS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARY OF ABUSES, U.S. SHARPLY CUTS VISAS FOR RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The U.S. Embassy in Moscow has sharply curtailed the
number of visas issued to Russians, particularly students and
scholars, despite Washington's avowed desire to spread Western
values in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of Russian students who sought to study in the
United States using private funds were refused visas this year,
about twice the rejection rate of previous years. Embassy officials
suggested that students from impoverished Russia _ potentially part
of the country's opinion-making elite _ will be tempted to try to
settle permanently in the affluent United States.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the reason given for refusing a visa _ that the
applicant appeared to have insufficient ties, such as children, to
Russia _ echoed the Soviet practice of allowing citizens to travel
abroad only if their loved ones stayed behind to insure the
relative's return.
</P>
<P>
   The tightened visa policy followed the August 1998 economic
collapse in Russia and is part of a broader and increasingly
rancorous debate over the procedures for inviting foreign students
to the United States. Applicants from nations like South Korea and
Thailand, which have also undergone economic crises, have reported
increasing problems too in obtaining visas.
</P>
<P>
   But the visa policy has especially important implications for
Russia, where the United States has has been struggling to
encourage democracy and influence public opinion. The Clinton
administration has defended its policy of engaging Russia and
treating the country as a partner, and recently announced a
vigorous campaign against what it calls the ``new isolationists''
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, U.S. Embassy officials deny that they have been
overly strict. Laura Clerici, the consul general, asserted that
consular officials needed to be particularly vigilant after the
1998 collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Russians think that bureaucracy is something to be gotten
around,'' she said in an interview. ``They give us all sorts of
paper that is false.''
</P>
<P>
   But American educators and former diplomats say that the embassy
has overreacted and that many worthy candidates have been cast
aside.
</P>
<P>
   They note that the embassy's statistics do not show Russians
hurrying to flee abroad after the ruble collapsed. Overall, visa
applications have not increased since August 1998 _ although the
number of rejections have _ and student applications have actually
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visa policy is at cross-purposes with U.S. foreign
policy,'' said Greg Guroff, the former director of a U.S.
government office that encourages educational and cultural
exchanges. ``The American policy had been to expand contacts. Now
the consular policy appears to be to turn down young people,
particularly on private education exchanges.''
</P>
<P>
   The visa policy has been a shock to many young Russians. Despite
a general upsurge in anti-American sentiment _ most evident in the
street protests outside the U.S. Embassy during the Kosovo conflict
_ educated Russians, particularly the young, are still attracted to
the United States. They find it hard to understand why they have
suddenly become undesirables.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has a number of ways to attract Russian
students. There are government-financed exchange programs that can
last for a few weeks or for years. In 1998, 6,000 visas were
granted to Russians under such programs. But Russians also attend
American universities and colleges using F-type visas, where the
education is paid for by the student or other private sources or is
supported by a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 83 percent of all F-type visas applied for during the
prime student application months of June through August were
granted. This year, the acceptance rate for that period slipped to
62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ruslan Shevdov, 27, is a case in point. He had appeared to catch
a lucky break when the small Moscow-based trading and agricultural
company he joined after leaving the food service division of the
Russian army offered to send him to the United States at its
expense to earn a degree in business administration and to perfect
his English.
</P>
<P>
   Accepted by Adelphi University in Garden City, N.Y., Shevdov had
hoped to begin his studies this fall. But his request for an F visa
was rejected three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I didn't fit the student profile,'' Shevdov said.
``Maybe they think I am too old. I tried to assure them that I plan
to return. My parents live here. This is the country where I grew
up. I can call my friend here at any time and he will come. How
would I live there?''
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials said they would not discuss individual cases.
The six-member team that handles nonimmigrant visas at the Moscow
consulate makes hundreds of decisions like this, often on the basis
of a five- or 10-minute interview.
</P>
<P>
   Besides looking for fraudulent applications, they try to divine
if a student or scholar has an unbreakable tie to the homeland that
will spur return. Interviews often amount to hurried discussions of
an applicant's marriage status, family life and assets, often
conducted by a junior Foreign Service officer.
</P>
<P>
   The burden of proof that a Russian has no plans to emigrate,
even legally, falls on the applicants. They may find it hard to
argue that what appear to an American to be meager rewards are
sufficient for a decent living in Russia. Shevdov, for instance,
earns about $900 a month, low by American standards, but a
respectable sum for a Muscovite.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars have also had problems. Taras Ivchenko, a 34-year-old
assistant professor at Moscow University, is a specialist in
Chinese linguistics who graduated from Beijing University and wrote
his doctorate in Chinese. Encouraged by several American
professors, he wanted to visit the United States for several weeks
last summer to help translate a Ming dynasty manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 10-minute interview in May, Ivchenko was unable to
persuade the U.S. Embassy to grant him a tourist visa. He earns
$150 a month and has no substantial property. His wife, father and
sister live here, but that apparently was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ivchenko said the consular officer who interviewed him suggested
his chances for a visa would be better if he had children he could
leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of Soviet times,'' the soft-spoken Ivchenko
said in an interview. ``I would like to work on a project or two in
the United States, but I am not interested in emigrating there. I
belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   American academics report increasing problems in obtaining visas
for Russian students or faculty members. The University of
Pittsburgh had to campaign for one of its Russian graduate students
to complete a doctorate program after he returned home for the
funeral of his father.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Southern California fought hard to overturn
the denial of a visa for a promising student it had recruited for
its graduate program in Russian literature. The student was told
there was no point in studying in the United States since there was
plenty of Russian literature at home.
</P>
<P>
   But the universities do not always win. The University of
Maryland was recently left without a Russian instructor when the
candidate it picked was denied a visa.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Lekic, director of the university's graduate program in
Russian language, said the faculty had gone through a careful
selection process and had never experienced a problem with Russians
refusing to return home when their visas ran out.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Embassy concluded that the university salary the
Russian instructor was being offered was too appealing compared
with his modest pay at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the Soviets would not let people leave,'' she said.
``Now when Russia is opening up, we are behaving like Soviets.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy officials insist that they need to be vigilant
because there has been talk in Moscow of many Russians ``jumping
ship,'' and the black market price of forged visas has risen.
</P>
<P>
   But student applications for F visas between June and August
declined to 1,645 this year, compared with 2,181 in 1998. Embassy
officials also concede that there has never been a comprehensive
study to determine whether Russian students eventually return, or
emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   The tough U.S. visa policies are driving Russian students to
other countries. ``We are really shooting ourselves in the foot,''
said Dennis Whelan, a Moscow-based lawyer who advises visa
applicants. ``We are simply ensuring that all the upper and middle
managers in Russia get their training in Europe so that they make
their primary business contacts with our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost half a million tuition-paying foreign students were
enrolled in American institutions in the 1997-98 academic year.
They bring in money, as countries like Britain increasingly
recognize, loosening up visa regulations to attract foreign
students.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Certainly, Britain won in the case of Maria Ushakova, 17, the
daughter of a leading Russian businessman. Ms. Ushakova wants to
become a psychoanalyst and take over her mother's practice, but her
request for a visa to attend college in Pennsylvania was repeatedly
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, her family says, she was told there was no point
in studying in the United States since Russia did not have a
tradition of psychoanalysis and a foreign-trained specialist would
never find employment at home. Her father then obtained a letter
from a Russian clinic saying it would gladly hire his daughter once
she finished her training.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ushakova received a visa on her fourth try. By then,
however, she had missed the start of the school year in the United
States. Offended, her father said, by all the refusals and worried
that she might not be able to renew her visa to finish her
education in the United States, she is now studying in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
