<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review for
Sunday, October 24, have moved. 
(jt) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; On the dress page: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-REVIEW (Undated) _ What makes the brain unique among
bodily organs is that its cells are arranged in a very specific
manner _ in delicate constellations that somehow reflect the
knowledge gained from being alive. The result is a world of
individuals, a place where the very idea of a brain transplant is
absurd. You are what you think, and what you think is laid out in
your own imitable neural structures. But just how malleable is this
cellular filigree? By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ In the last decade, even as its economy
has gone from bad to worse, Japan has evolved, beyond the West's
field of view. Change has come so far now that even if Japan wanted
to keep it a secret, it no longer could. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also moving in the `a' category: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ News highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-HEROES-REVIEW (Washington) _ American voters have long known
Vice President Al Gore as the son of a distinguished politician, as
an avowed environmentalist with a best-selling book on the topic
and as President Clinton's loyal liege. But recently, Gore has been
reminding the electorate of another, less commonly cited dimension
of his history and identity: his military service in Vietnam. But
does anyone care about war heroes anymore? By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-RISK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Travelers do it in the wake of
a terrorist attack when they decide to drive to Florida for
vacation rather than get on a plane. Diners do it when they forego
a sandwich at lunch and then load up on iced tea and fat-free
cookies in the mid-afternoon. And Bobby Valentine, the manager of
New York Mets, did it during the sixth game of the National League
Championship Series, perhaps costing his team a chance to advance
to the World Series. Call it the misunderstanding of cumulative
risk. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ENCYCLOPEDIAS-REVIEW (Undated) _ As Internet users stampeded to
visit the Encyclopaedia Britannica's sleek new Web site last week,
the venerable intellectual icon was nearly road kill on the
information highway. Britannica.com is busily adding computers to
handle the more than 10 million people who tried to peruse its
site. But the company also faces a much bigger question: Will its
vaunted reputation for rigor be compromised by its decision to give
free access to its vast stores of knowledge? By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ This month marks the 30th
anniversary of the Arpanet, the Internet's predecessor. Then again,
maybe it doesn't. As barbs fly and longstanding friendships
disintegrate, figuring out just who did what when is more difficult
than ever. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBS-IPO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The news from Wall Street last
week drew attention to probably the most startling contrast
imaginable in American popular culture: Martha Stewart and the
World Wrestling Federation, both going public on the same day.
Investors were clearly more enamored with the mistress of
domesticity than with the minders of Stone Cold Steve Austin and
The Rock. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also moving in the `i' category: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-IDENTITY-REVIEW (Santiago) _ Chileans like to call
themselves the English of Latin America, referring to their
reserved social etiquette and taste for afternoon tea, proper
high-cut clothes and Tudor architecture. Probing even deeper into
the national psyche, Chilean intellectuals identify national traits
that hark back to another English century entirely. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-RELIGION-REVIEW (Jakarta) _ It doesn't take a
theologian to describe the political role of Islam here. ``We are
Muslims, but when we vote, we put Islam to one side,'' said Hasan
Bisri, a 60-year-old fisherman, as he waited to cast his ballot.
``In Indonesia we put the nation first and our religion second.''
This may sound odd to many Americans, who for 20 years have looked
at Iran as the model for Islamic rule and are therefore wary of the
prospect of Islamic clerics taking power anywhere. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-REVIEW (Freetown) _ The camp for amputees lies on a
hill in the most scenic stretch of Freetown, a favorite spot for
British vacationers before war destroyed Sierra Leone. Most of the
amputees in this camp _ there were 516 when Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright paid a visit Monday _ were mutilated by rebels
who advanced on Freetown last January. Many were taken to the
city's main public hospital where they languished for days; then
many went to a refugee camp at the national stadium where they
languished for weeks. Eventually they arrived at this camp, which
is run by Doctors Without Borders. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
