<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-72     10-23 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUR ON STATUS QUO, ARGENTINES VOTE FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Crime and unemployment are up, wages
are down, and polls indicate that a growing number of Argentines
think their politicians are stealing fortunes. Voters want change
after 10 years of Peronist rule, and every recent poll suggests
they will get it, by choosing the decidedly downbeat mayor of
Buenos Aires, Fernando de la Rua, as president in the elections on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As in every Argentine political campaign, the candidates have
led the obligatory gaucho processions through the pampas and danced
in the streets of Buenos Aires with tango stars. But unlike so many
campaigns of the last century, there has been virtually no
violence, no charges of fraud, no capital flight and no
interference from the military.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the deepest recession of the decade, the political
oratory has been mostly muted and moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years after military rule ended, the sobriety of the
campaign suggests that civilian democracy has been completely
consolidated in Argentina and a centrist consensus has emerged in
economic and foreign policy. If de la Rua does win, he will end a
decade of rule by the Peronists, who have never left power
peacefully before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics have become routine in Argentina,'' said Rosendo
Fraga, a leading pollster. And that is saying a lot in a country
that less than a generation ago was a cauldron of infighting
between Peronist labor leaders, right-wing military officers and
radical students marching beneath the slogans of Che Guevara.
</P>
<P>
   But neither de la Rua nor his main rival, the Buenos Aires
governor, Eduardo Duhalde, appears to have inspired much interest
among the voters. Attendance at political rallies has been smaller
than in other election years, and polls indicate that there is
increasing cynicism about politicians and their ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign has been downright boring,'' said Roberto
Bacman, another Argentine pollster, who drew a sharp distinction
between the current campaign and ``the last three elections in
which strong slogans defined the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants change,'' he added, ``but moderate change, with
more transparency and honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what de la Rua, who represents the center-left
Alianza coalition, has said he will offer. He has pledged to sell
the presidential jet, Tango 01, as a sign of austerity, prosecute
tax evaders and dishonest politicians, and impose federal control
over corrupt local police forces.
</P>
<P>
   He has also promised to cut a growing government budget deficit
while keeping the peso pegged one-to-one to the dollar, the
cornerstone of President Carlos Saul Menem's economic policy over
the last nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a moral force that will confront frivolity and
trickery,'' de la Rua promised at a rally in the city of Rosario on
Tuesday, repeating his sweeping critique of the current government
as a stronghold of fraud and privilege. ``We are going to end this
party for the few.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to shrug off polls showing him 15 points behind, Duhalde
of the governing Justicialist Party has pledged to slash the
value-added tax from 21 percent to 15 percent, reject demands by
the International Monetary Fund to cut public spending by nearly $2
billion, and grant unemployed housewives a minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duhalde has had trouble finding a coherent campaign
message, and for months has feuded with Menem over leadership of
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicated that de la Rua and Duhalde were in a close race
until three months ago. Then, trying to energize the traditional
labor base of the Justicialist Party, which was founded by Juan
Domingo Peron, Duhalde lunged toward traditional Peronist populism.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining about Argentina's mounting foreign debt, he
suggested a worldwide one-year suspension of debt-servicing by
Third World countries. It was a line that used to win applause in
the 1980s. This year, the response was an 8 percent fall in the
Argentine stock market, which forced Duhalde to beat a hasty
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   With Duhalde looking reckless and capricious, his poll ratings
plunged in early July and he never recovered. He was further hurt
last month when his provincial police force botched a hostage
rescue, needlessly killing two hostages in an uncontrolled spree of
gunfire.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde sought to revive his campaign at a mass rally in the
Plaza de Mayo last Sunday by playing the populist card again. He
implicitly lashed out at the International Monetary Fund, which is
currently pressing Argentina for budget cuts in exchange for an aid
package that could reach $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people say enough to the adjustments, enough to the
tightening of the belt,'' Duhalde said. ``We're not against having
more rich people, we're against having more poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the event was upstaged by Menem, who remains titular leader
of the Justicialist Party and who wanted the Justicialist
nomination himself despite a constitutional ban against a third
consecutive term. Menem refused to attend the rally, choosing
instead to dine with several labor leaders in the resort of Mar del
Plata in a well-publicized planning session for a presidential run
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Menem aides leaked to the press last week that as soon as
Duhalde is defeated, ``Menem 2003'' posters will be plastered
across Buenos Aires. Meanwhile, senior Economy Ministry officials
have said it would be no tragedy if de la Rua won.
</P>
<P>
   To win the presidency on Sunday, a candidate needs at least 45
percent of the vote, or at least 10 percent more than the
second-place candidate. Otherwise, the top two candidates face a
runoff next month. The new president will be inaugurated Dec. 10. A
variety of recent polls suggest that de la Rua will not need a
second round to win.
</P>
<P>
   Economic issues have dominated the campaign, with the country in
its deepest recession of the decade and unemployment running near
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua has promised to improve the economy by increasing
investor confidence, thereby bringing down interest rates. His
approach is orthodox, promising to reduce a current government
deficit of $5 billion by at least $1.5 billion by cutting wasteful
spending and corruption and prosecuting tax cheaters. He promises
tax incentives for small and medium-size businesses to spur
employment.
</P>
<P>
   He says he will lower production costs to make Argentine
companies more competitive on world markets by deregulating public
services, which he argues will cause communications and energy
costs to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The most detailed economic plan has been offered by former
Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo, who has urged an across-the-board
cut in taxes and government regulations. With little campaign money
and a small organization, he is expected to come in third with
about 10 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But in case Duhalde should make a last-minute comeback and force
a second-round runoff, Cavallo could become the kingmaker by giving
his support to one candidate or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde proposed his economic platform as a bill to Congress _
one that would reduce the value-added tax to 15 percent from 21
percent and give tax cuts to companies that did not lay off
workers. But he could not even mobilize enough members in his own
party to reach a quorum in the House of Deputies for the bill to be
debated. The program's failure in Congress only served to highlight
the divisions within the Justicialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Justicialist Party is roundly rejected, it will
continue to control the Senate until at least the 2001 elections.
It will also control most of the gubernatorial seats as well as the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of divided government has most analysts
predicting that de la Rua will not take Argentina in a sharply
different direction even if he does win the landslide victory
predicted by the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And with Menem leading the Justicialist Party at least for the
next several months, it is probable he will continue to have a say
in what happens in the presidential palace even after he clears his
desk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
