<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN'S NEW LEADER STRUGGLES TO ASSEMBLE CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan's new military ruler remained
holed up Saturday as he had been for almost a week, trying to
figure out whom he would name to a seven-person council of military
commanders and technocrats that is likely to govern the country for
the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   The army chief, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, who took over in a
bloodless coup 12 days ago, promised in a speech to the nation last
Sunday that he would stamp out public corruption, repair the
country's broken-down economy and eventually restore democracy. But
he is still struggling to put together his team.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Rashid Qureshi, spokesman for the armed forces, said
Friday that the members of the National Security Council, to be
headed by the general, would be made public Saturday. Then on
Saturday, he said he hoped it would be Sunday, but he made no
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Musharraf does make his final choices, he has no
immediate plans to hold a news conference. Instead, the military's
media office will release a list of names that may also include
some of those who will serve in other capacities in the new
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to explain the thinking behind it,'' said
Qureshi. ``He could do that if it was one, two, three individuals.
But how do you talk about a group of 10 to 15 people?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the elected government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was
overthrown, the general has given two nationally televised
addresses to the nation and made photo-op appearances, including
one with his family and their two Pekinese dogs, Dot and Buddy. He
has offered no time frame for when he will allow new elections to
be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not with an ulterior motive,'' Qureshi said. ``He doesn't
want to say it will be six months, a year or two years, and not be
able to fulfill it. He's said it will be done as soon as possible
once the major reforms are put in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time since the coup, Musharraf has been out of
sight, conferring with other generals and with financial, political
and legal experts.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday he sat through a five-hour series of briefings from
economists. The country is mired in a deep recession and is
perilously close to defaulting on its debts to international
lending institutions. In the aftermath of the coup, it is not clear
that the International Monetary Fund will continue a $1.56 billion
line of credit to Pakistan that had made it possible for the
country to pay back earlier debts to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generals know the economy is make or break for the future
of Pakistan,'' said Maleeha Lodhi, the editor in Islamabad of the
English-language daily, The News, which has been very supportive of
the coup. ``They understand that explicitly. They talk to me about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The now-deposed prime minister, Sharif, remains under house
arrest, as do a number of his closest advisers, at undisclosed
locations. In a statement on Thursday, Sharif's party, the Pakistan
Muslim League, did not condemn the coup, but said rather mildly
that it regretted what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The party demanded a return to democracy and the release of
Sharif, but it also said it did not want a confrontation with the
army.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no organized opposition to the military
take-over. Islamabad's streets were completely quiet Saturday.
There were no protests, no banners, no proclamations of outrage.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, an alliance of 19 political parties that had
united before the coup in their opposition to what they considered
the dictatorial, corrupt rule of Sharif have praised the general's
policy agenda.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tellingly, they have not called for immediate elections. ``In
the west, people think this is the death of democracy,'' said Imran
Khan, the cricket star who has thus far had an unsuccessful career
in politics. ``Here we think democracy now has a chance. The
political process had been hijacked by a political mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the general named three retired military officers
and a judge to serve as the governors of Pakistan's provinces.
Their relatively advanced age and their military ties have led some
political analysts to speculate that Musharraf is trying to keep a
tight hold on power, despite his pledge to devolve power from the
central government to the restive provinces.
</P>
<P>
   The country now waits to see whom Musharraf picks for the
National Security Council that he will head. The general, now
referred to here in headlines as the ``CE'' since he named himself
``chief executive'' of Pakistan, is still army chief. The council
will also include the chiefs of the naval and air staffs, as well
as four specialists in law, foreign policy, finance and national
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a preponderance of civilian technocrats of
extremely high integrity and professional ability,'' said Qureshi _
who later called back to say he had been instructed to make it
clear that he was not ruling out the inclusion of politicians of
high moral character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
