<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL MAKES PROGRESS TOWARD U.N. PRIVILEGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Israel, isolated at the United Nations for 50
years, is very close to securing a place in a regional group from
which it can compete for a Security Council seat and other
positions, Israeli and Western diplomats said last week.
</P>
<P>
   These diplomats said that members of the regional group known as
Western Europe and Others _ which includes countries as far afield
as Australia and New Zealand _ are nearing unanimity on an
agreement to give Israel at least temporary membership. Only one or
two countries are holding out against the move, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision is not likely before next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finally getting close to the finish line,'' said Dore
Gold, Israel's chief delegate to the United Nations. Gold, whose
term is about to end, said in an interview that he had spent a lot
of time over the last two years struggling ``to eliminate this
collective discrimination against the Jewish state in the U.N.
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 15 Security Council seats _ those not occupied by the
five permanent members, which are Britain, China, France, Russia
and the United States _ rotate among all other nations, which must
be nominated by regional groups to maintain regional balance on the
council.
</P>
<P>
   While many nations are never nominated for a seat, only Israel
has effectively been barred from the competition altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Under the essentially Victorian world view that prevailed when
U.N. regions were established half a century ago, Israel should be
part of the Asian regional group.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arab nations in that group _ which covers everything
``east of Suez,'' as Orientalists once described more than half the
world _ have resisted all efforts by Israel to be included.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have been cool for several reasons to Israel's request
for membership, diplomats say. Some did not want additional
competitors for the Security Council's rotating seats. Others were
concerned about potential Arab retaliation if Israel were admitted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, some European diplomats said the idea of
admitting Israel was dying of its own accord as Middle East peace
talks faltered and the government of the former prime minister,
Benjamin Netanyahu, was blamed for a lack of progress.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of peace efforts under the new Israeli government
of Prime Minister Ehud Barak has changed the atmosphere, diplomats
say.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, which has government-to-government relations with most
U.N. members, has nevertheless been vulnerable, especially during
the Cold War, to collective attacks in the organization by groups
of nations such as the old Soviet bloc or the Nonaligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's place in the organization was most severely set back,
along with U.S. attitudes to the United Nations, when in 1975 the
General Assembly passed a resolution equating Zionism with racism.
That resolution remained on the books until the first Clinton
administration, when Madeleine Albright, as the U.S. representative
here, was able to get it rescinded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Diplomats say that when Richard Holbrooke arrived in August as
the U.S. representative, one of his first tasks was to finish the
job of bringing Israel the full benefits of U.N. membership. U.S.
officials say that some of his earliest meetings were with Gold and
Jewish organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question but that the credit for the final push
belongs to Ambassador Holbrooke,'' Gold said Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
