<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-PROFITS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NAMES DO NOT EQUAL PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Memo to Hollywood executives: You might want to
reconsider the $20 million-plus salaries you're paying A-list
talent and the nine-figure movies you're green-lighting.
</P>
<P>
   A new study by a Rutgers University economics professor that
will appear in the next issue of the Journal of Business finds that
stars don't help a film's profitability, nor did big budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, movies with big stars or lots of special effects sell more
tickets. But because the costs are so much greater, they rarely
turn a profit for their studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study leaves us wondering why the star system is such a
cornerstone of Hollywood and why studios keep turning out
big-budget films loaded with (costly) special effects,'' said S.
Abraham Ravid, author of the study and a panelist at a conference
on Hollywood economics Friday at California State University,
Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Ravid, who analyzed close to 200 films with budgets greater than
$1 million released during the 1990s, conducted the study to test
the two major reasons why studios hire stars: To signal that the
movie is a high quality project and to assure that the star's
drawing power will bring in enough moviegoers to justify the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he discovered, is that major stars do indeed boost
revenues, but that is due mostly to the fact that they participate
in big-budget films. Additionally, there's no significant
relationship between a film's budget and its profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stars do very well for themselves and their agents, but they
do not do much for the studios,'' Ravid asserted.
</P>
<P>
   So why do studios continue to make such expensive gambles in the
first place? Ravid, who is scheduled to teach a course in economics
at UCLA in January, believes such choices stem from the difficulty
in forecasting the success of an individual movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A star may be hired simply because the industry faces extreme
uncertainty and executives wish to be covered in case a project
fails,'' he said. ``If everybody is after a given star, signing him
or her to a project may be a safe bet for an executive who is
concerned about job security.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cyffka, 20th Century Fox's senior vice president of
finance and the single studio executive on the panel, defended
studios, saying they spend big money on stars and special effects
hoping to launch the next ``Titanic,'' even if it means too many
``Wild Wild West''s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a limit to what you can lose on a project,'' once
you've paid salaries and the special effects budget, Cyffka said.
``What you can make on a hit is so much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   As for stars, Cyffka noted, they represent a form of insurance
that boosts the probability of a strong opening. ``You pay a lot
for that insurance,'' he explained. ``There's a limited supply of
really top stars, so it creates an imbalance that allows stars and
agents to get the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravid isn't the only one questioning the budgets of Hollywood's
movies. Studio executives have been claiming they have been cutting
costs in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Motion Picture Association's figures showed that
the average production cost per film slid 1.3 percent to $52.7
million, but that had followed a stunning 34 percent jump for 1997
films. Additionally, average marketing costs jumped 14 percent to
$25.3 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ravid said one area that clearly generated above-average
returns: movies with G and PG ratings, particularly due to their
ability to generate significant home video revenues. Ravid noted
that Disney's ``The Lion King'' cost $55 million to make in 1994,
then produced $313 million in domestic box office, $454 million in
foreign box office, $520 million in video revenues and $3 billion
in merchandise sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is likely that, if anything, most studies and lists
underestimate the revenues of G movies, which are more amenable to
ancillary products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that two other areas have a slight positive
impact on the bottom line _ sequels and movies that generate large
numbers of reviews, even if the critics don't like the film. ``Even
with low quality and less stars, a sequel still works better than
the average film,'' Ravid noted.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the study paints Hollywood executives in a
less-than-flattering light. ``The fact that stars do not increase
return on investment but sequels seem to be weakly more profitable
supports the view that the industry is run not by knowledgeable
insiders . . . but by uninformed insiders who guess and fail in
projecting the success of a movie,'' Ravid said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur S. DeVany, an economics professor at the University of
California, Irvine, echoed Ravid's conclusions about stars and
their impact, noting that their presence creates a paradox by
raising expectations and lowering potential profitability. He
stressed that Hollywood needs to focus more on content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real star is the movie,'' DeVany said. ``Budgetary
decisions ought to be made on creative content.''
</P>
<P>
   The panelists also stressed that executives face a complicated
task in predicting a film's success. ``It's like trying to predict
the next earthquake,'' DeVany said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
