<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ABORIGINES-BRUTALITY-     10-23 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORIGINES-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT INDIANS BECOME RICH ALLIES IN AN ABORIGINE WIDOW'S
CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Switzerland, Britain, Conn.)   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ When Letty Scott, an Australian who traces her
maternal ancestry to a community of desert Aborigines, decided to
go international with her campaign against what she sees as
persistent police brutality against her people, she found help in
some unexpected places. Not least was Foxwoods, the Connecticut
casino resort run by Pequot Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``God took me there,'' said Ms. Scott, whose husband, Douglas,
was found hanged in a prison cell in the northern Australian city
of Darwin in 1985 after he had been detained on a charge of using
obscene language. The police said it was a suicide. She calls it
another case of killing under torture.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, armed with the results of official and
unofficial Australian investigations, reams of paper devoted to
still-unanswered questions about her husband's case and police
photographs of the death scene released to her by a former prime
minister, Paul Keating, Ms. Scott began looking for international
attention to a cause she says is not just hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death rates of my people have skyrocketed,'' she said in
an interview last week. She thinks too many are recorded as
suicides.
</P>
<P>
   In her search for allies, or at least sympathetic audiences, Ms.
Scott, whose grandmother came from the Anmatyerre aboriginal nation
in Australia's Central Western Desert region, has joined many other
indigenous peoples around the world who are building bridges to one
another, aided by easier communications.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, for example, a group of Cree Indians from
Canada went to Nepal to teach mountain villagers how to organize to
oppose a large hydroelectric project that threatened to disrupt
their homes, traditional life and livelihood. Jose Ramos-Horta, the
East Timorese independence leader, has contributed time to teaching
tribal people and indigenous minorities how to deal with large
international organizations. There are many other examples.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scott, an artist who says she is about 46, started her
campaign on her own. She pulled together enough money to come to
the United States _ a sympathetic former police officer in
Australia was one of her benefactors _ to try to get a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived in New York with only one contact, an American
marine biologist she had met on Australia's north coast, she said.
He, in turn, told her about the Shinnecock Indians of Long Island.
She had also heard about them through Indian cultural organizations
found in a phone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shinnecocks said to me, `We'll take you to the brothers on
the other side _ they've got money,' '' she said. The brothers were
the Mashantucket Pequots, a small tribe that had become fabulously
rich on its casino profits.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Thomas, a Mashantucket Pequot tribal council leader, got
the call. ``People from the Shinnecock reservation contacted me and
said, `Michael, you have to hear this lady's story,' '' he said in
an interview Thursday. `` `You will probably want to help her.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas arranged for Ms. Scott, her son, Nathan, 15, and Daniel
Taylor, a family friend who volunteered to help her with
correspondence and logistics, to stay at the Foxwoods Resort Casino
in Mashantucket, Conn. He also called together tribal staff members
to devise a game plan for Ms. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequot then paid for Ms. Scott to return to Australia and
plan a trip to meet with U.N. human rights panels in Geneva and New
York, with a stop in London to meet other human rights groups. That
trip was also a gift from the tribe, which has been generous in
supporting the cultures of other indigenous groups in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, she was put in touch with American Indians working on
international projects for indigenous people. The United Nations
has set aside a decade to promote these varied cultures. The
American Indians in Geneva gave Ms. Scott a place to stay and got
her a hearing at a U.N. human rights subcommission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she is back in the U.S., where I am in the process of
setting up meetings with various and sundry congressmen and
political leaders,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without getting terribly corny,'' he added, ``we've been
taught to believe that when we are blessed we are meant to share
those blessings, or they are taken by the creator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
