<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ICON-VANDALIZE-700(2T     10-23 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICON-VANDALIZE-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVERED ICON BECOMES MYSTERIOUS TARGET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She stands resplendent in her green robe, the
protective patron of Mexicans everywhere, painted in a bright mural
on the wall of the Gonzalez Party Supplies store on San Pedro and
22nd streets in South-Central Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago, in the dark of night, somebody obliterated
the face and praying hands of this image of the Virgin of Guadalupe
with a wide roller of white paint, and scrawled in blue: ``666''
and the words, ``La Bestia,'' Spanish for the devil.
</P>
<P>
   It was actually the second attack on the mural, one of more than
a dozen on the walls of bodegas and storefronts in this bustling
Hispanic neighborhood south of downtown to have been defaced in
recent weeks. The first time, the Gonzalez family promptly
repainted the Virgin, a revered talisman of the Roman Catholic
faithful who, believers say, came as an apparition of the Virgin
Mary to Juan Diego, an Aztec convert to Christianity, in the hills
outside Mexico City in 1531.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't even last a week,'' said Juan Gonzalez, who owns the
electronics store that adjoins his mother's party goods shop.
``They came back and painted her face and hands. I think it's
local. It's some religious thing. It's hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why it's happening, or who is responsible. Up and
down San Pedro Street and Central Avenue, the spines of a
neighborhood that was once heavily black but has been flooded in
recent years by immigrants from Mexico, merchants expressed alarm
and bewilderment, wondering why anyone would attack a symbol so
universally admired in their community that even Hispanic gang
members wear tattoos and T-shirts with the image of the Virgin of
Guadalupe to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any idea,'' said Marta Rocha, who works with her
father, Ismael, at their Restaurant Familiar at San Pedro and 41st
Streets, where an image of the Virgin was defaced about a month
ago. ``We had just finished repainting it.''
</P>
<P>
   But this peculiar urban mystery has prompted no civic outrage.
Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan is a devout Roman Catholic, with
a prayer chapel in his back yard, but he was unaware of the
vandalism in South-Central until a reporter called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' said the mayor's press secretary, Deputy
Mayor Noelia Rodriguez, who said the reporter's call was the first
City Hall had heard of it. ``It's tragic. I know the mayor doesn't
know about it. In that community, especially, the Virgin is
protected and respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Camilo Jose Vergara, a sociologist and photographer who has
recorded life in inner cities from the Bronx to the barrios here,
noticed the vandalism on a recent visit. Vergara, whose exhibition
``El Nuevo Mundo: The Landscape of Latino Los Angeles,'' closed at
the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum of the Smithsonian
Institution in New York last month, has spent years driving the
avenues and alleyways of South-Central, tracking the importation of
familiar Mexican iconography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin is the sweetest symbol, and also the most powerful
symbol for Mexico,'' Vergara said. ``It's their mother. I mean,
everyone else can let them down, but not the Virgin.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is all the more puzzling that anyone would deface such a
revered symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants wondered if it might be the work of Hispanic
evangelical Protestants, angered by the Catholic icon. Some
speculated that it might be teen-agers. Others wondered about
Hispanic gang members, or ``cholos,'' and some of the murals are
pocked with the graffiti of the 38th Street gang.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Phillips, a lecturer in anthropology at the University
of California at Los Angeles, who just published ``Wallbangers''
(University of Chicago Press, 1999), a book on the graffiti of Los
Angeles gangs, said she highly doubted that gang members were
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so strange,'' Ms. Phillips said. ``Typically, if there's
a whole mural, and there's any part of the Virgin on it, the rest
may be written over but she's spared. But this time, it's like
she's the target. I think that it's just one person. It's localized
within that area. I toyed with the idea for a while that it could
be a racial thing, but in that particular neighborhood, those two
populations have been living close together in relative peace for
such a long time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most merchants said they had not even bothered to complain to
the police. Gonzalez's fiancee, Elvia Partida, said she had called
the local police station and was told that unless there was overt
evidence of a hate crime, there was nothing the police could do.
</P>
<P>
   One police sergeant on patrol with his partner in the
neighborhood the other day, who declined to give his name, said he
was unaware of the vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   When a visitor pointed to an example of fresh blue paint over
the image of the Virgin painted on the wall of the L.A. Meat Market
at Central Avenue and 49th Street, the sergeant said: ``I mean,
it's a liquor store. Graffiti around here is so common. Unless it's
a church or a house of worship, people don't complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Dwaine Roberson, the supervisor of the Newton
Division's burglary and vandalism detective unit, said he had not
heard of any complaints about defaced images of the Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally foreign,'' Roberson said. ``I haven't heard
anything, I haven't seen anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Partida said she first noticed the vandalism about a month
ago, at the time of a procession on Olvera Street in downtown Los
Angeles to welcome a reproduction of an image of the Virgin of
Guadalupe brought from the Basilica of Our Lady of Guadalupe in
Mexico City for an American tour. Legend has it that after
appearing to Juan Diego, the Virgin left an imprint of her image on
his cloak; that original image lies inside the Basilica, and on his
visit to Mexico earlier this year, Pope John Paul II commissioned
the reproduction and elevated Guadalupe's feast day, Dec. 12, to a
higher level feast day for Catholics in North America and South
America.
</P>
<P>
   Father Gregory Coiro, a spokesman for the archdiocese of Los
Angeles, had not heard of the defacement. He said that even
storefront churches in South-Central without a tradition of
religious imagery often painted the Virgin of Guadalupe on their
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of this graffiti makes me think that it could be
coming from some non-Catholic or anti-Catholic Christian sect,''
Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the mystery lingers, and rankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows,'' said Margarita Pacheco, an elderly woman
pushing a stroller with a baby down San Pedro Street the other day,
frowning at a defaced Virgin on the wall of Wally's Liquor Market.
``It's very bad. It's the mother of God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
