<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-HEADQUARTERS-ART     10-23 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HEADQUARTERS-ART-705(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. BUILDING SHOWS ITS AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ At first glance, the headquarters of the United
Nations looks nearly as new as the day it was built. The black and
white tile floors sparkle. Fresh paint adorns the walls. The
paneled chambers of the General Assembly and the Security Council
still glow with the elegance of the dreams that inspired them.
</P>
<P>
   But half a century after the cornerstone was laid on Oct. 24,
1949, a closer look reveals that the most prestigious symbol of New
York City's claim to international stature is deteriorating at its
core, beset by hundreds of millions of dollars in structural and
environmental problems and without the money to fix them. In fact,
if the United Nations had to abide by city building regulations _
diplomatic immunity spares it _ it might well be shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Roofs leak. A marble wall in the Dag Hammarskjold Library has
threatened to collapse. Asbestos insulation needs to be replaced.
Plastic sheeting was installed to protect library desks and
computers from dripping water. And some motors and water pumps that
keep the building running are so antiquated that spare parts are no
longer made.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more alarming is that among New York City's high-rise
office buildings, the 39-story U.N. headquarters is singularly
without a sprinkler system, as the city's fire code normally
requires. One of the emergency exits available to delegates in case
of fire is the third-floor roof of the Conference Building, which
``has deteriorated beyond repair and needs to be replaced,''
according to a proposed new budget.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations acknowledged the obsolescence of its
headquarters in a proposed budget, for 2000 and 2001. It reported
that ``new safety and environmental standards require the
renovation of existing buildings to meet modern standards in such
areas as fire safety, access for the disabled, interior air
quality, asbestos abatement and safe handling of dangerous or toxic
materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Connor, the undersecretary-general for management, said
that the complex was made with good materials and has been
maintained as magnificently as possible.
</P>
<P>
   When the building was erected, it was considered an
architectural masterpiece, the product of collaboration by an
international team of 11 architects, including Le Corbusier and
Wallace Harrison. At the brink of the 21st century, to bring it up
to standards would cost about $800 million, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, which persuaded the United Nations to
settle in New York and provided an interest-free loan for building
the headquarters, shows no interest in helping. It has yet to pay
more than $1 billion owed to the world organization in back dues
and assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to do it outside the regular budget,''
said a U.S. official, ``because I don't see the climate of Congress
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly could levy a special assessment on member
countries. If so, Washington would be expected to pay its customary
25 percent of the cost. The U.S. official doubted that Congress
would consent, and suggested that the renovation be subsidized with
donations from foundations and the general public. Congress, as a
condition of appropriating the U.S. dues, has insisted that the
United Nations' regular budget not increase.
</P>
<P>
   The building's decay dates to the onset of the United Nations'
now-perennial cash squeeze in the mid-1980s, after the Reagan
administration pushed the government's fiscal year back from
January to October, in effect stiffing the United Nations out of
nine months worth of dues.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a shortage of cash, exacerbated by Congress'
unwillingness to pay up, has forced the United Nations to finance
peacekeeping missions and other political crises at the expense of
housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chronic poverty of the U.N. has bugged them from the
beginning,'' said William Luers, the chairman of the U.N.
Association of the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   Renovating the complex has become a question of not just money
but also logistics, in finding alternate work space for 6,000
employees in New York. The options under consideration include the
once unthinkable _ whether to move out of the headquarters, at
least temporarily.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Relations with New York City have cooled since Mayor William
O'Dwyer welcomed the United Nations in 1949 by proclaiming Oct. 24
U.N. Day. In April 1997, during a dispute over diplomatic parking,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani suggested that it would not be so terrible
if the United Nations left town, though its presence generates an
estimated $3 billion a year in business and other revenue for New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has since refused to intervene in the new controversy
over Donald Trump's plan to erect a high-rise apartment tower at
U.N. Plaza that would dwarf the United Nations, prompting a protest
from the secretary-general, Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters now costs nearly $10 million a year to heat in
winter and cool in summer, in part because of 5,400 windows
installed back when energy was cheap. And asbestos insulation in
place for nearly 50 years is drying out, prompting second thoughts
about gutting the familiar glass-and-marble landmark. ``If we do
that,'' a U.N. official fretted, ``we would spread environmental
hazards all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri Madarshahi, the president of the U.N. Staff Council, an
umbrella group of unions representing U.N. employees, described the
asbestos problem more succinctly. Fifty years ago, she said, ``they
used asbestos behind every air conditioner in the building.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget identifies some other areas of more
immediate concern, totaling over $22 million in repairs over the
next two years. They include work on the roofs of the Conference
Building, the General Assembly and the Secretariat, and structural
repairs to the Dag Hammarskjold Library and its glass facade.
</P>
<P>
   Other costs add up. A new sprinkler system could cost as much as
$50 million. Just upgrading the fire alarms to eliminate
deficiencies identified during an internal inspection would cost
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wein, a spokesman for the city's Department of Buildings,
said that the federal government does not require diplomatic
facilities built before 1993 to comply with local mandates, which
exempts the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The codes cannot not be enforced in any case, because an
agreement signed by the United States prevents inspectors from
entering the U.N. compound without consent. A second agreement on
diplomatic immunity and privileges shields the United Nations from
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Bender, the officer in charge of managing the U.N.
headquarters, pointed out that it met all codes when it was built
50 years ago. He said that he has worked with the city to correct
problems. Except for the absence of sprinklers, and fire alarms
that are not state-of-the-art, Bender said, ``the building is by
and large code-compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials emphasized that the renovation would not only
correct the building's long-term deterioration but also bring it up
to the city's building and fire code standards.
</P>
<P>
   Electromagnetic fields generated by transformers and power lines
in machine rooms have also caused morale problems. Employees in the
vicinity complain of headaches and nausea as well as jittery
computer monitors. Some worry about the risk of more serious
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect that we are not breathing clean air and enjoying a
healthy environment,'' Ms. Madarshahi said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether electromagnetic waves pose a health hazard is still
unproved. And Binder said that the building's air quality, tested
twice a year, has been found safe.
</P>
<P>
   By next spring, the 188 member countries of the United Nations
will begin sifting through the alternatives for the headquarters.
Summing up the debate, Assistant Secretary-General Toshiyuki Niwa
said: ``Would you like the U.N. to operate for the next 50 years,
in which case what do you do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't take it for granted that this building can last
for the next 50 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
