u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      10-23 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS WEST APPEALS FOR CALM, RUSSIA PRESSES WAR IN CHECHNYA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Rebuffing Western appeals that it seek a political
solution in the North Caucasus, Russia continued its attacks in
Chechnya Saturday and proceeded with plans to increase its forces
in and around the breakaway republic to 100,000 men _ a jump of
40,000 from just a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Chechnya said that Russian planes had bombed the
airport at Grozny and that Russian forces had severed a key road
between Chechnya and its western neighbor Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   There was still no indication whether Russian troops outside
Grozny would escalate the conflict further by trying to fight their
way into the Chechen capital. Russian military officials have sent
conflicting signals on this key question, saying they do not plan a
frontal assault on the city but that their presence there is just a
matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Russian and Chechen rebels might replay
their bloody confrontation of 1994-96 in Grozny, which was largely
destroyed, has alarmed the West, whose concern about the Chechnya
fighting increased markedly with the massive explosions on Thursday
that leveled a marketplace in the Chechen capital, killing many
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen leaders said the explosions were caused by a Russian
rocket attack, an account supported by some reporters on the scene,
and that 143 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials first denied any role in the explosions, then
said the blasts were the work of Russian special forces trying to
destroy an arms cache in the capital. Prime Minister Vladimir V.
Putin then denied any Russian involvement, putting the blame on
Chechen gangs.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott,
warned in a statement late Friday that the increase in violence in
Chechnya had ``raised concern'' about prospects for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, the American point man on Russia, said that Russia's
last war in Chechnya indicated that a purely military solution was
not possible and that the Kremlin should initiate talks with
Chechen leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright reinforced the message
Saturday. Ending a visit to Africa, she said she would speak to the
Russian foreign minister, Igor S. Ivanov, probably during her
flight back to the United States from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the last 36 hours have been of great concern,''
Albright said in Nairobi, according to Reuters. ``We consider the
action deplorable and ominous.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication Saturday, however, that the Kremlin was
about to heed the American desire for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving a meeting with European leaders in Helsinki on
Friday, Putin, a potential successor to President Boris N. Yeltsin,
said that Russia intended to press its fight against Islamic
militants. His ratings in the polls have climbed as Russia has
pressed ahead with a military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly after the September bombings of apartment blocks in
Russia that killed some 300 people, many Russians accept the
Kremlin's line that it has little choice but to pursue the military
option in Chechnya, which has been largely lawless since the 1996
war ended with Russia's withdrawal and the breakaway republic's
official status left in limbo until 2001. Russian authorities have
blamed Islamic militants in Chechnya for August incursions into
neighboring Dagestan _ where Moscow's rule is more accepted than it
is in Chechnya _ and for the apartment bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Russian politicians have urged that the Kremlin
begin negotiations. Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the Yabloko
party, said Russia should try to achieve an ``inter-ethnic
compromise'' in the region and his party was willing to serve as a
mediator.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed alarm that the war could turn in a brutal struggle
between Russia and Islam. Yavlinsky's party was initially very
hawkish but became more critical of the military campaign after the
Russian military began a ground offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov also said that Russia
should be prepared to talk. Primakov has opposed an all-out ground
war and pointedly refused an invitation to meet with President
Boris N. Yeltsin earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary to begin negotiations from a position of
strength,'' Primakov said, adding that it is not clear who Russia's
negotiating partner in Chechnya might be.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from the North Caucasus also met Saturday in southern
Russia. Ruslan Aushev, the president of Ingushetia, said he would
present proposals from Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov. Maskhadov
is discredited in Russia, where many politicians believe he has no
control over the Islamic militants and worry that the Chechens
would take advantage of any let-up in fighting to regroup their
forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
