<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDISTRICTING RAISES STATES' ELECTION STAKES  
 A FAILED TRUCE AMONG LEAPFROGGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Va., Ariz., Iowa, N.H., La., Mich. ,S.C., Wash., Texas)  McCAIN WELCOMES RIVAL TO WEB SITE  
(lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most states will not hold legislative elections until next year.
But Virginia is an exception. It will vote this year, on Nov. 2,
with all 140 seats in its Senate and House of Delegates up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom have the stakes been higher.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Southern states, Virginia has been trending
Republican. The party already controls the state Senate and the
three top state jobs _ governor, lieutenant governor and attorney
general _ and it has big hopes that it can gain control of the
House of Delegates.
</P>
<P>
   How big?
</P>
<P>
   Big enough for President Clinton to travel to Virginia on Friday
to raise money for the Democratic defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Democrats have a difficult time in Virginia,'' Clinton
said, alluding to his failure to carry the state in 1996 and the
Republican's subsequent success in winning the top three elective
jobs and a one-seat edge in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   What the president did not dwell on but every Democrat at the
gathering knew was that come Nov. 2, all the Republicans need to do
to seize full control of the state is maintain that narrow hold on
the Senate and pick up two seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In the long history of the Old Dominion, Republicans have never
controlled the state legislature and all of the top state elective
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But history is not the real issue. History has nothing to do
with why the stakes are so high in this election.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is raw political power. And Virginia is but one
of 50 states that will be caught up in the struggle for such power
this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   The party that controls Virginia, or any other state, going into
the new millennium will pretty well decide how that state's
legislative and congressional districts are drawn after the 2000
census. And if the control extends from the governor down through
the legislature, almost anything the party does to district lines
will probably stand, barring a successful court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It goes almost without saying, too, that a state party with that
kind of control can also push through almost any governing agenda
it wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Redistricting takes place only once every 10 years, making it
relatively rare in politics. A rough rule of thumb holds that the
political party that controls both the governor's office and the
legislature in a state can redraw district lines so that one of
every five districts tilts in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, that formula could result in a change of control in
Congress. To take an extreme example, in California, which has 52
congressional districts, redistricting could change party control
in as many as 10 districts, a crucial number in a Congress as
closely divided as the current Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Given stakes so immense, it is little wonder that when
Virginia's governor, James Gilmore, was trying to pump up his
troops last Tuesday for a final pre-election push, he did not
hesitate to reach deep for hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire future of Virginia,'' Gilmore declared, ``will be
decided in these elections.''
</P>
<P>
   A Failed Truce Among Leapfroggers
</P>
<P>
   For a while it looked as though the war between the states over
next year's schedule for presidential caucuses and primaries was
over. The dozen or so upstart states that had been leapfrogging
each other in the headlong scramble to be the first to caucus or
hold a primary seemed by last weekend to have sorted themselves out
or to have given up hope that national party leaders, especially
Democratic leaders, would countenance more leapfrogging.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional old nominating schedule, it appeared, would be
retained for Election 2000. Iowa would hold the first caucuses, as
always, and New Hampshire would hold the first primary, as always.
</P>
<P>
   True, the nominating process would start almost a month earlier
because of all the leapfrogging already approved, and the nominees
might be known little more than a month after that. But however
early the process might start or end, Iowa and New Hampshire would
still go first, Iowa on Jan. 24 and New Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It was too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The armistice lasted just five days.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Louisiana Republicans announced that they, not
Iowa, would hold the first caucuses, on Jan. 15. They said their
state party rules required it. (Louisiana Democrats are sticking
with a March 14 primary.)
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Republicans countered by recalling that Louisiana tried the
same ploy in 1996 but only a couple of candidates showed up to
campaign, hardly enough to make the contest a genuine first test.
The other candidates, according to Iowa Republican leaders, were
scared off by threats that Iowa voters might punish them if they
strayed south, something the Iowans warned could happen again in
the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   So will Iowa now try to leapfrog ahead of Louisiana's new date,
or stay put?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone seems to be pretty comfortable where we are,'' Kayne
Robinson, Iowa's Republican chairman, replied confidently.
</P>
<P>
   Good thinking, said Mike Francis, Louisiana's Republican
chairman. ``Otherwise,'' he warned on Thursday, ``we'll just keep
hopping.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the Democratic National Committee moved
determinedly on Friday to restore some nominating stability and
head off more Louisiana-like hopping. It ruled that Arizona,
Michigan, South Carolina and Washington could not move their
primary and caucus dates forward several weeks to join or get ahead
of other states that had leapfrogged from March into February.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed by the decision, Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan told
the committee that the nation's nominating process had become a
``cockamamie'' ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   McCain Welcomes Rival to Web Site
</P>
<P>
   This being the age of the computer, almost every presidential
candidate has a site on the World Wide Web, some fancier than
others but all of them overflowing with self-serving biographical
data and the latest on what the candidate is thinking and doing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, pull down Sen. John McCain's site _
www.mccain2000.com _ and the Arizona Republican serves up ... click
here for the latest speech ... or here for today's campaign
schedule ... or here to make a donation ... or here if you are from
the Bush campaign ... or ... say what?
</P>
<P>
   Just trying to ``make it easier for the Bush campaign to surf
our site,'' a note to users explains.
</P>
<P>
   As the senator's computer people tell it, the McCain site
received more than a million ``hits,'' or visits, in the first half
of October, with more than 4,500 of them coming from the Bush
campaign, twice as many as from any other source.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush people counter that they have ``better things to do
than spy on who's using our Web site.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
