<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EVEN PLAYERS HAVE THEIR WORLD SERIES MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz recalls the acrid smell of burning
automobiles. Jim Leyritz still tries to will Carlton Fisk's fly
ball foul. Kevin McGlinchy shudders at the televised horror of
Mookie's grounder going under Buckner's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the World Series memories drive athletic little boys to
become major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series is different. The 50 Braves and Yankees who
began the 1999 World Series on Saturday night were united in
knowing that the baseball season shifts a mighty gear after the
league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   These games are not ``the finals.'' These games are the World
Series. No matter how much the television people yammer about
``post-season records,'' it is just a case of some network having
too many computers for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   It is irrelevant if modern players approach the records of Berra
and Mantle and Ford and Gibson and Fingers. Nowadays a batter or
even a relief pitcher could play 19 post-season games in October,
whereas the old Yanks and Dodgers never played more than seven at a
time. It is like comparing kumquats to persimmons.
</P>
<P>
   Those players earned their World Series statistics when there
was no prelude _ no league championship series, no division series,
just the best teams from the American League and National League
deciding it all.
</P>
<P>
   Even with league playoffs, the World Series brings the little
boy back in these grizzled professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, only a few minutes after his current team, the
Mets, had lost a crushing 11-inning decision to the Braves, Turk
Wendell from Pittsfield, Mass., was asked if he had been looking
forward to a Subway Series in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm a Red Sox fan, and I was hoping they'd get in,''
Wendell blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   And Wendell was not alone. Last week, Tom Glavine from Concord,
Mass., who would start for the Braves Saturday night, admitted,
``My sister, who still lives up there, must have called me 15 times
during the course of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I still keep an eye on the Red Sox; obviously, the kid
in me is happy for the Red Sox,'' Glavine added, shortly before the
Red Sox went to their preordained defeat to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Many players insist they gave away those childlike fantasies
when they began earning major league paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rooted for the Reds and the Yanks when I was a kid, but that
kind of dies out,'' said Walt Weiss of the Braves, who grew up just
north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first World Series memory? The Yankees winning the World
Series,'' said Paul O'Neill, from Columbus, Ohio, who now plays
for, but of course, the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is the romantic concept of the Red Sox, those doomed
regional heroes, that stays alive longest in the hearts of a few
ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger, the Dartmouth graduate who has had a fine season
as the Braves' left-handed reliever, still quivers at the
recollection of a certain home run by Bucky Dent of the Yankees in
1978, not in a World Series but in a special playoff with the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the East Coast rivalries are more intense,'' noted
Remlinger, who grew up around Plymouth, Mass. ``I remember crying,
`How can he do that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger added, ``The World Series is what all kids grew up
on,'' but he admitted that post-season plays like the fantastic
stop and throw home by Weiss to help the Braves beat the Astros, or
the two extra-inning thrillers with the Mets, are as good as
baseball gets.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the World Series stands apart. John Smoltz, the
bearded sage from Warren, Mich., recalls his father taking him to
Tiger Stadium to see if their team could wrap up the 1984 World
Series in the fifth game. They could, and fans near the stadium
burned cars and menaced the neighborhoods that long and ugly
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad showed me how people react to victory,'' Smoltz said
the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he still rooted for the Tigers, Smoltz seemed to fight
a very human inclination to say yes. What he said was: ``I still
root for the three other Detroit teams. And since I live here now,
I root for the three Atlanta teams, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, the prodigal Yankee, knew where his boyhood heart was _
with the Reds, against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up near Cincinnati,'' he said. ``I remember staying up
late in 1975 to watch the sixth game. I remember Fisk's home run. I
was very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Leyritz is treated like General Sherman in these parts for
the way he torched the Braves with his three-run, game-tying homer
in the fourth game of the 1996 World Series. To some children in
Atlanta, he is the latter-day version of Carlton Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy, the fine young Atlanta relief pitcher from Walden,
Mass., also had a baseball memory. It was 1986, and he stayed up
late with his parents on a Saturday night to watch their New
England team put away those upstarts from Shea Stadium, only to
have the awful event take place close to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, McGlinchy was the Braves' pitcher when the Mets
staged their comeback in the stirring 15-inning game last Sunday in
that very same Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed an inhumane stretch for a journalist to bring up that
linkage to McGlinchy. Besides, Mookie's moment happened in a World
Series whereas McGlinchy's bad inning took place in a championship
series. The Red Sox never recovered whereas the Braves have moved
on to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody will make baseball history, wonderful or hideous, in
the next week or so. What happens now is a season unto itself. It
is the World Series.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
