<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RECALLING THE ORIGIN OF WHAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Andruw Jones went for a walk, the dream of a Subway Series
was nice while it lasted. Maybe next year.
</P>
<P>
   During that dream, in a recent column about past Subway Series,
it was written here that ``hardly a man is now alive who saw the
first one in 1921.'' But at least one man was not only alive, he
was on the telephone from Miami Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Nat Potamkin,'' he said. ``I'm 94 and I saw all
eight games at the Polo Grounds that year.''
</P>
<P>
   All  &UR; eight &LR;  games? Yes, that original Subway Series was played
in the third and final year of an experimental five-of-nine-game
format. The New York Giants won the last three games for a 5-3
verdict over the New York Yankees, who had acquired Babe Ruth from
the Boston Red Sox in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last out of the last game,'' Potamkin recalled, ``was made
at third base on a tag by Frankie Frisch for an unusual double
play.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the ninth and John McGraw's Giants leading, 1-0,
behind the little left-hander, Art Nehf, second basemen Aaron Ward
walked. On a hit-and-run, the Giants' second baseman, Johnny
Rawlings, made a spectacular stop of Yankee third baseman Frank
(Home Run) Baker's sharp grounder and threw to George (High
Pockets) Kelly at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rawlings got him by half a step, then Kelly saw Ward trying
for third and threw to Frisch,'' Potamkin said. ``Ward made a high
Ty Cobb slide, but Frisch held onto the ball for the double play.''
</P>
<P>
   But who is Nat Potamkin, how did he happen to attend all eight
games of that first Subway Series when he was 16 years old, and
what else does he remember about the New York of that era?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a kid from South Philadelphia, where all the tough guys
were,'' he said. ``The Philadelphia Inquirer had a contest for
selling subscriptions. The top 50 would get a trip to the World
Series that year. Not just kids, old guys, anybody. I sold 200,
maybe 300 subscriptions, I forget exactly, but I finished 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went up to New York in a bus and stayed at the Breslin
Hotel, 29th and Broadway. We not only went to the Series, we went
to the Hippodrome; they had elephants on the stage. We went to the
movie `When Knighthood Was in Flower' with Marion Davies. We went
to fights at the old Garden over near the real Madison Square.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Polo Grounds, where both teams played home games during
the season, Potamkin and the other prizewinners sat in what he
called the ``pavilion'' behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``During batting practice we went down to the box seats and
kibitzed with Babe Ruth,'' he said. ``He wasn't much of a talker
except to say, `Hiya, kid.' I had seen him before in South Philly,
out on the town at night after playing against the A's in the
afternoon. He'd be eating hot dogs and looking for a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller Huggins' Yankees, who had won their first American League
pennant that year, took the first two games, 3-0 on Carl Mays'
five-hitter and 3-0 on Waite Hoyt's two-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mays threw a submarine ball, underhand; he won 27 that
season,'' Potamkin said. ``Mays had killed the Indians' Ray Chapman
the year before, but it was Chapman's fault. He always bent over
the plate. Hoyt was a cute pitcher, like Whitey Ford. Not
overpowering, a good curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won the next two games, 13-5 and 4-2, despite the
Babe's only homer in Game 4. During the season he had hit a record
59 with 171 runs batted in and a .378 average. (Harry Heilmann of
the Tigers hit .394).
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 the Babe bunted for a hit and beat it out as Hoyt
allowed the Yankees a 3-2 lead, but by Game 6 the Babe was out of
the lineup with an infected elbow and a sore knee. As the Giants
won the last three games, the Babe's only appearance was as a
pinch-hitter in the finale. He grounded out before Ward's walk and
the Series-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nehf won that last game, a nice left-hander, he knew every
hitter,'' Potamkin said. ``Shufflin' Phil Douglas and Jesse Barnes
each won two games. Wally Pipp was the Yankee first baseman, a tall
thin guy. He didn't do much. Oh, I got arrested. We had some extra
tickets that we were scalping, but when they took me before the
magistrate, he said, `Get outta here.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Nat Potamkin was a dropout from South Philadelphia
High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents never knew it,'' he said. ``My friends got me
report cards and I filled 'em in. I boxed a little in the burlesque
shows in South Philly. I was a boxing commissioner here in Miami
Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   For exercise now, Potamkin hits the heavy bag twice a week at
the Eden Roc Hotel spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never finished high school, but I loved going to libraries.
I got in Dickinson Law School and passed the bar in West Virginia.
You probably know of my youngest brother, Victor, the big New York
auto dealer. When he started it, I put up some money to help him.
His boys run it now and I still get my checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nat Potamkin laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot to tell you, I saw the 1922 Giants-Yankees Series at
the Polo Grounds too,'' he said. ``I finished 23rd in the Inquirer
subscription contest that year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
