<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' GENERAL MANAGER CONTINUES TO MEET RISING EXPECTATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Texas, Mass., Ga.)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the age of 59, John Schuerholz is a dinosaur. His
colleagues represent an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Tyrannosaurus rex, Schuerholz is not extinct, but he has
become a throwback to another age, a time when baseball general
managers could reasonably expect to hold on to their jobs as long
as they were not stealing money or their boss' wife. These days
general managers are jettisoned as easily as managers.
</P>
<P>
   Not Schuerholz. He recently celebrated his ninth anniversary as
general manager of the Atlanta Braves, matching his previous tenure
with the Kansas City Royals, a team he left voluntarily. For 18
years he has run major league organizations, signing players,
trading them, building championship teams. None of his peers has
done it as long or as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Schuerholz keeps watching his peers change. In
the past few months, five general managers, one-sixth of the major
league population, have been fired or resigned. Milwaukee and
Colorado have named new general managers; Anaheim, Baltimore and
Seattle still have vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a natural development,'' Schuerholz said of the
volatility of the job. ``With all of the money owners have invested
in these teams, there's a lot more at stake. They have expectations
that whoever is running it, they expect that person to be very
proficient and very effective and very productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners, he added, are not as willing to be patient as they once
were when the money involved was a fraction of what it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably comes with what's happening in the industry,'' he
said, ``how much more we're paying, how much more franchises cost,
how much more is invested in these enterprises. They expect us to
be better at what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Increased costs are not new, but the escalation of the increase
in costs has had an impact on owners' thinking and nerves. As
payrolls have risen dramatically, a select circle of teams has
emerged as perennial challengers for the World Series, the Braves
and the Yankees included.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a handful of us,'' Schuerholz said of some teams,
``who have been so good for so long and whose expectations are so
high internally and externally, that the bar has been set higher
for all of us in these organizations _ general manager, manager,
coaches, players. Expectations go higher and higher and higher.
More is expected of us. That is a fact. The bar is set higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar sometimes is set inordinately high, the dean of general
managers said. ``We should be congratulated on one hand for
building a team and an organization that so much is expected of,''
he said, ``but on the other hand, there should be a little
understanding about what the pressures are that come with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Schuerholz's stewardship, the Braves have never seen the
post-season take place without them. Ten general managers who have
been in their positions longer than a month have never seen their
team play in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   One general manager, Frank Wren, did not reach his first
anniversary on the job in Baltimore Saturday. If the Yankees do not
win the World Series, another, Brian Cashman, may not make it to
his second anniversary in February.
</P>
<P>
   But just as a fired manager seeks another chance and another and
another, once a general manager has general managed, the job gets
in his blood. How else explain the desire of Pat Gillick, 62 years
old, to get the Seattle Mariners' job that became vacant with the
departure of Woody Woodward, who had been the longest-serving
general manager with the same team.
</P>
<P>
   Gillick retired once, leaving the Toronto Blue Jays after the
1994 season, then was lured back into active duty a year later when
Peter Angelos, the Baltimore Orioles' owner, offered him $750,000 a
year for three years. The end of that term could not come soon
enough for Gillick, but here he is back in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the people out there,'' he said of the Mariners.
``They're all good people. I get along real well with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gillick has wavered in his desire to compete for the
Mariners' position. ``I had some interest,'' he said, ``but after I
thought about it for a while, I pulled out of it. Then I talked to
them again. So the thing is up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillick acknowledged that he still has the ``itch'' to do the
job, though he said, ``It certainly has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In some way,'' he added, ``as far as putting a team together
to win, I think you can do it more easily than before because of
free agency. Unfortunately, because of the economics of the game,
they're moving people around faster.''
</P>
<P>
   THE EXECUTIVE GRAPEVINE
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Bob Watson, former general manager of the Houston
Astros and the Yankees, seemed to be headed for the Anaheim Angels'
job, or so went the word along the baseball grapevine. Now Bill
Stoneman, a Montreal Expos' executive, is viewed as being on the
verge of being hired.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Stoneman, who has been the Expos' vice
president for baseball operations for 15 years, would come as a
surprise to executives, player agents and players who experienced
his executive style when he briefly served as the Expos' general
manager in the late '80s. His style was so abrasive that the Expos
changed his duties so that he would not deal directly with players
and with agents whose players the club wanted to sign.
</P>
<P>
   One executive who knows Stoneman well said he has not changed
since those days. The Angels' interest in Stoneman did not surprise
the executive. He said Stoneman and Tony Tavares, the Angels'
president, are ``like two peas in a pod.''
</P>
<P>
   CHECKING TORRE'S FINANCES
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Torre signed a two-year contract extension with the
Yankees this year, his salary for 2000 and 2001 was believed to be
$2 million each year. However, information on managers' salaries
distributed to the clubs lists Torre's pending salary as 50 percent
more, $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The lower figure would have matched Jim Leyland's salary with
Colorado before he resigned, though $500,000 of his $2 million was
deferred, and the amount Felipe Alou basically receives from
Montreal, though his salary is listed as $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The higher figure puts Torre far ahead of other managers.
</P>
<P>
   The new salary certainly is insurance against Torre's being
fired.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for, say, the Detroit Tigers to pay Larry Parrish
his $425,000 salary for next season; it's another for George
Steinbrenner to pay Torre $3 million not to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Torre's new salary in perspective, the seven lowest-paid
managers will earn a collective $2.65 million next season, and it
will take the next salary on the scale to put the pay of eight
managers beyond Torre's.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Torre will earn more than Bobby Valentine ($1
million) and Tony La Russa ($1.8 million) combined.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' manager worked for $1.3 million this year, fourth
highest on the managerial pay scale. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GIVE THE RED SOX CREDIT
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the Boston Red Sox could not live out their
once-in-a-lifetime fantasy: beat the Yankees in the American League
Championship Series, avenging 1978 and every other dirty deed the
Yankees have perpetrated against them, then beat the Mets in the
World Series, gaining revenge for Bill Buckner and the rest of the
1986 gang.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox, or more specifically their general manager, Dan
Duquette, deserve recognition for a remarkable job this year. The
loss of Mo Vaughn was supposed to render the Red Sox offensively
impotent and doom them to a finish lower than dirt, but they had an
immensely better year than Vaughn did as Duquette recast the team
in a different image.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox batted .002 below their 1998 average, hit 29 fewer
home runs and scored 40 fewer runs. But they won two more games
than they did last season. They did not make up for the missing
offense by playing better defense. They committed 22 more errors
and allowed 18 more unearned runs than a year ago. It was the
pitching that carried the Red Sox to their unexpected success.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff, led by the incomparable Pedro Martinez, had
a lower earned run average this year, the lowest in the league;
allowed fewer home runs and runs; walked fewer batters, and struck
out more.
</P>
<P>
   But once the pitchers got the Red Sox to the playoffs, their
hitters erupted, scoring 44 runs in winning the last three games
against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   With Vaughn leading the offense a year ago, the Red Sox scored
11 runs in beating the Indians in the first game of the division
series, then scored a total of &UR;  &LR; nine in three consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   How did Vaughn do with Anaheim?
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was to blame, but the Angels won 15 fewer games than
they did last year and finished 22 games farther away from first
place. Vaughn, hampered by an ankle ailment most of the season,
batted .281, his lowest average in seven seasons, and hit 33 home
runs, his lowest output in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Vaughn could lead an Anaheim resurgence next season,
but a healthy Ramon Martinez could join his brother in making the
Boston pitching even stronger and position the Red Sox to finish
ahead of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the same as beating the Yankees in the playoffs
and taking their place in the World Series, but that scenario would
play in Boston.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
