<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-920&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR FROM FASSEL, WHEATLEY FINDS HIS NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Mich., Texas)  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Tyrone Wheatley began his comeback with the Oakland
Raiders this season, pounding his way to a conference-leading five
rushing touchdowns, there was a time last year when he fought to
overcome the chaos in his football life, a chaos that almost caused
him to quit the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   His impressive season with the Raiders, which continues Sunday
against the Jets, is all the more remarkable considering his
mind-set in September of last year. The Giants were playing the
Raiders in Week 2 and Wheatley, then with New York, was inactive
for the game because, he says, coach Jim Fassel wanted to look at
other players. Wheatley did not complain. Instead, he cheered his
teammates from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants lost, 20-17. During a team meeting one day later,
Wheatley and other players said, Fassel exploded at the team for
its lackluster play. It was deserved criticism. But what he said to
Wheatley disturbed the running back. Wheatley says that Fassel
yelled, ``Tyrone, you need to stop crying about playing time and
focus on losing weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley had been through battles with the former Giants coach
Dan Reeves. Reeves had not wanted to draft him, preferring running
back Rashaan Salaam, who is now a bust after being cut by the
Raiders before this season. Then came disputes with Fassel.
Wheatley thought that if Fassel was going to chastise him even when
he was not in the game, then he would never get a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley made up his mind to quit after the stormy team meeting.
He planned to inform general manager George Young and Fassel the
next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Then something interesting happened. To boost his sagging
spirits, Wheatley popped in videotapes of himself playing at the
University of Michigan and watched as he sliced and diced across
the field. It was that Wheatley whom the Giants considered worth
selecting in the first round of the 1995 draft. Next Wheatley put
in another tape, from his days at Robichaud High School in Inkster,
Mich., where he played eight different positions and was the
state's player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley was suddenly energized. He asked his brother, who was
sitting next to him, ``Do I stink?''
</P>
<P>
   No, his brother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say that just because I'm your brother,'' Wheatley
replied.
</P>
<P>
   His brother said no again. Then Wheatley called friends in
Michigan and asked the same question. He got the same answer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last week what had kept him from leaving the game,
Wheatley said, ``Watching those tapes made me stubborn, and I
believed in myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley, who is listed at 227 pounds with the Raiders compared
with 235 or more last season, was right all this time. He was a
good player. Now, he may be the best power runner in football.
</P>
<P>
   He is a key part of a Raiders team that has a solid chance of
making the American Conference playoffs. He has rushed for 403
yards on 97 carries, and his five running scores have tied him with
Jacksonville's James Stewart for the conference lead. Wheatley has
put up his numbers despite splitting time with Napoleon Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley, one of the most intelligent players in the league as
well as one of the nicest, spoke honestly during an extensive
interview about himself, Reeves, Fassel and his topsy-turvy NFL
career.
</P>
<P>
   On Reeves: ``Reeves always talked about how I didn't work that
hard. But he didn't work that hard his last few years in New York.
Reeves allowed some players not to work hard, but then would try to
make an example of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley said that during a practice in his rookie year, 1995,
he was running hard up the middle and a veteran defensive player
told him after the play: ``What are you doing, rookie? Don't run
like that. You're making us look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley also said that Reeves never let him forget that he
pulled a hamstring muscle while running sprints on his first day of
training camp. ``Reeves has a long memory,'' Wheatley said. ``If a
player makes a mistake, you will never hear the end of it. But when
Reeves made mistakes, he never admitted to them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Fassel: ``I just didn't catch his eye. I guess he didn't see
anything special. He never had an open mind with me. From the
moment we met, he said, `This is a new start.' But he wasn't
telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley admits he deserves some blame for his problems with
Reeves and Fassel. ``Yes, I was wrong some of the time,'' he said.
``But I saw some situations and I said, `This is not going to get
better.' I could have moved Mount Rushmore and Fassel would not
have believed in me. So I purposely became ho-hum. The way I
walked, the way I talked. I didn't give up on my teammates, I just
stopped trying to impress Fassel because he had his mind set.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, asked to comment, said his relationship with Wheatley
started on a sour note and never recovered. But he said he had no
bitter feelings about Wheatley and wished him the best. Reeves
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley's history presents a conundrum: Did he lack motivation?
Or did he never get an honest chance from either coach, thus
sapping his motivation?
</P>
<P>
   His success in Oakland seems to indicate the latter. Wheatley is
now happier than he has ever been. The Oakland coaching staff told
him his past was not relevant and for the first time during his
professional career, he believed his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley looks back on the day he almost quit the Giants, and
cannot believe how close he came to leaving the sport he loves. The
Raiders are happy he changed his mind.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Price of Pass Rushing
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' Michael Strahan, in addition to being perhaps the
best defensive end in football, is also a skillful boxer. He knows
a good right hook when he sees one, and against Dallas last Monday
night that's exactly what he was seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, the Cowboys' Pro Bowl offensive tackle,
Erik Williams, hit Strahan in the face while attempting to block
him. At least once Williams flat-out punched Strahan, in full view
of officials. On another occasion, Williams jammed his hands under
Strahan's face mask, scratching him.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, Strahan's face showed a slight
bruise under his eye, in addition to a scratch. It was just another
day at the office with Williams, who has a reputation as one of the
league's leading cheap-shot artists.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan was asked what strategy a defender could use when a
blocker aggressively puts his hands in a defender's face and the
officials do not call a penalty. ``You take it and hopefully the
referee will notice,'' he said. ``That didn't happen this time.''
Then the Giants' Pro Bowl lineman added that the officials'
``contacts must have fallen out.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan's frustration is understandable. Defensive linemen are
the last truly unprotected football species. They are still kicked,
chop-blocked and punched, and officials still often let the abuse
happen without throwing a flag.
</P>
<P>
   The players' union is trying to persuade the league to make the
rules tougher. That may happen in the next few years. Until then,
players like Strahan should start wearing an iron mask under their
helmets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
