<HEADLINE>
AT THE CENTER OF THE RANGERS' PROBLEMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Canada)   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching P.J. Stock cover Eric Lindros is like watching a
barking terrier chase a sport utility vehicle. What would the
terrier do if it actually caught the SUV? What would the SUV do to
a terrier that accidentally slipped beneath its moving wheels?
</P>
<P>
   Stock was recalled from the minor leagues by the Rangers last
week after Lindros and his Flyers bullied and beat the Rangers by
5-0 in Philadelphia on Wednesday night. Although half a foot
shorter and 46 pounds lighter than Lindros, Stock has the moxie to
harass Big No. 88. He helped neutralize him Friday night, and so
the Flyers won by only 2-0 in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Stock sensed some success when Lindros ``kept turning to the ref
and saying, `Get this kid off my back,' and the ref came by and
told me, `Kid, I don't know what you're doing, but if you want to
keep playing, you stop that.' Kind of gave me a hint things were
going all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Rangers should assign Stock to check Mark Messier
when his Vancouver Canucks visit Sunday night. You remember
Messier: older fellow, big, bald and sometimes scowling? He was the
captain when the Rangers won the Stanley Cup in 1994, and he left
them as a disenchanted free agent in 1997. Like Lindros, Messier
also enjoys bullying Petr Nedved, the Rangers' top center. It was a
Lindros attack on Nedved that led to Stock's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Although rude treatment of Nedved is symbolic of current Ranger
difficulties, it is hardly their only concern. They have lost four
of their last five games and three in a row, the last two by
shutouts. They are 4-6-1 with a league-leading payroll of almost
$59 million. Expensive free agents like Tim Taylor and Valery
Kamensky have missed games with injuries. Their most expensive free
agent, Theo Fleury, is underachieving and pressing, and so is
Nedved.
</P>
<P>
   Their captain, Brian Leetch, the attacking defenseman, has no
goals in 11 games on a team desperate for goals. Leetch is a master
of the power play, but the Rangers' power play is 4 for 51, one of
the worst in the league. Acknowledging that ``our top guys have got
to be on the scoresheet,'' Leetch added: ``It's my job, it's Petr's
job and Theo's. And we haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rangers may lack clubhouse leadership, it was
interesting to see Leetch showered and dressed Friday night only 22
minutes after the final boos echoed around the Garden. Perhaps he
had an appointment with his old pal, Messier, in town to play the
Islanders last night. Maybe Mess can help Leetchie find a way to
stop a slump that could endanger the jobs of the Rangers' coach,
John Muckler, and their general manager, Neil Smith.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to jump to conclusions and declare that
the Rangers are regressing and that their roster is a doomed
mixture of past-prime talent, it is also a fact that their roster
would be seriously flawed even if all their current players were
healthy and performing well. They do not have enough good centers
or young veterans in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Without a strong No. 2 center, the lead role may demand too much
from Nedved, who is more suited to a No. 2 role anyway. Manny
Malhotra, last season's promising rookie center, was little used
Friday, a sign that Muckler is dissatisfied with a kid Smith touts
as a future star. Taylor, a veteran checker, has been injured a lot
in recent years. Smith must have known this when he signed him for
more money than any other team was willing to pay. Mike York, the
other center, is an unproven rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recently signed another center, Alexandre Daigle, a
top draft choice of 1993 who has washed out with three teams. He
plays in the minors in Hartford. The Rangers actually considered
adding Daigle to their roster last week. In international
communications code, there are three declarations of distress:
``SOS,'' ``mayday'' and ``We've just signed Alexandre Daigle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ulf Samuelsson, the former Ranger signed by the Flyers last week
as a free agent for less money than Smith is paying Kevin Hatcher,
has been unimpressive since arriving via a trade from Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Samuelsson. As a Ranger, he used to battle Lindros
and take his abuse. With Friday's game nearly over and the Rangers
pressing, Samuelsson raked his stick across Kamensky's face, then
crunched Fleury into the glass.
</P>
<P>
   By then, half the Garden fans had left and even the booing
seemed halfhearted. Do Ranger fans expect failure after missing the
playoffs for two consecutive springs? The Rangers play 10 more
games before the quarter mark of their schedule. That will be the
time to seriously evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the slump, Fleury said, ``It's not the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not, but you can see it from here.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
