<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBER THINKS HE HAS WHAT IT TAKES TO MAKE THE BIG PLAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tiki Barber remembers turning to look for the pass,
his back to the defense, and thinking: catch it and get out of
bounds. There were 27 seconds left in a tie game. The Giants were
on their own 41-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Barber grabbed the ball and turned for the sideline. Out of the
corner of his eye, he saw an opening. It wasn't the biggest
opening. He would have to instantaneously split two defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still thinking: `Out of bounds, stop the clock,'''
Barber said last week, recounting what became the pivotal play in
the Giants' upset of the Dallas Cowboys on Monday night. ``But
there was a way to get past those guys if I could just get there
fast enough. It flashed into my head: `There really is no other way
we'll go 60 yards in 20 seconds. I'm going. I'm going, right
now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barber turned up field, knowing better than anyone the risk he
was taking. He was about to call on a player not seen inside the
Giants' jersey No. 21 since 1997. That Tiki Barber of two years ago
routinely made chancy dashes, running headlong into an
over-pursuing gang of defenders _ shooting the rapids, the players
call it _ and coming out the other side unharmed. He looked
swifter, smoother, shiftier.
</P>
<P>
   But one day the rapids jumped up and bit him. Barber hurt his
knee. He recovered but he did not look the same. He did not feel
the same. Worst of all, he did not think about himself the way he
once did. It was as if the brace on his right knee smothered the
creativity once so evident.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, nothing seemed to work the way it once did. People
in the pro football community started to say that the darting,
flashy Tiki Barber of 1997 was gone forever, the victim of an
incurable bum knee.
</P>
<P>
   It was on a Monday night against Dallas almost exactly a year
ago that Barber had turned to catch four passes and dropped each
one. Now, a season later, he had not only caught the ball, he was
going to find out just who was inside his jersey, inside his
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Which Tiki Barber would make this burst up field?
</P>
<P>
   He sliced between the defenders, ran away from another, broke
outside to the sideline, alone but for his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this,'' he said he thought at the time. ``We're
going to win. I've just won this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber was knocked out at the 3-yard line by the fastest man on
the field, Deion Sanders. Seconds later the Giants won the game,
13-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans came up to me on the street last year and said, `I'm
scared to death whenever you get the ball,''' Barber said in an
interview from his Manhattan home last week. ``Stuff like that
hurts. I know it's just the way some fans can be. But it makes you
realize nobody's going to help you get back to where you were
except yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game, which also included an 85-yard punt return
for a touchdown, does not make Barber's 1999 season the year to
erase all of Barber's 1998 failings. He's still just the third-down
back and the punt returner, a small piece of a stumbling Giants
offense. But there is something devilish about how Barber has gone
about this season. Privately, he has predicted how it would unfold
for him step by step. He said he would have a quiet training camp,
and he did, albeit with flashes of brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks ago, as the Giants prepared to open their season
with the rookie Sean Bennett as the new starter at running back,
Barber watched the hub-bub enveloping Bennett from his locker a few
feet away and said: ``That was me two years ago. Now I'm going
right under everybody's radar. I don't mind. Because I'll tell you,
this team is going to need me. I guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of those comments this week, Barber nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew people felt I had become expendable,'' he said. ``We
had two, quote-unquote, hot-shot draft picks. I thought, `OK, we'll
see.' I knew what I had done to get better and I knew I would
surprise everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What Barber had done was strengthened the muscles around his
damaged right knee. He had lost weight, weight he had gained
intentionally on the foolish notion he needed it to be more durable
in the National Football League; in fact, he said, all it did was
slow him down. He worked out ceaselessly.
</P>
<P>
   When he got married this spring and honeymooned in Europe, he
called ahead to arrange high-tech workouts at gyms in various
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man was really angry and hurt,'' Giants safety Percy
Ellsworth, a former teammate of Barber's at the University of
Virginia, said. ``He worked out this off season like someone trying
to fix an injustice. He's a soft-spoken, intelligent guy, but don't
let him fool you. He's got a tough, hard streak.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also got something up his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Monday's game to be the highlight of my season,''
Barber said. ``I've got 10, hopefully more, games left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
