<HEADLINE>
U.S. MEDIATOR EXTENDS EFFORT TO RESCUE ULSTER ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ George Mitchell, the former U.S.
senator turned mediator, extended his attempt to rescue the
faltering Northern Ireland peace agreement past its expected end
Saturday night, saying more time was needed ``in view of the
gravity of what is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after daylong talks with Ulster's feuding
politicians, Mitchell warned that ``there should be no false
optimism _ significant differences remain.'' But he said
conversations in the last few days of his formal review, now seven
weeks old, had persuaded him that ``the parties are making a
sincere and serious effort to bridge those differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mandelson, the new British secretary for Northern Ireland,
said the exchanges between the rival politicians had become more
promising. ``They trust each other more now than they have
before,'' he told reporters outside the Stormont Castle Buildings,
scene of the talks. ``The politicians are talking more seriously
and in a more mature way than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   The main difference that continues to deadlock progress in
putting into place the April 1998 peace accord centers on the
refusal of the province's largest party, the Ulster Unionists, to
permit Sinn Fein, the political ally of the Irish Republican Army,
into government without a beginning to IRA disarmament. Sinn Fein
argues that no such condition was included in the agreement and
that it cannot compel the paramilitaries to turn over weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has resisted increasing calls to signal its willingness
to disarm or to declare an end to its war, including one this week
in a long editorial in the Dublin-based Irish Times. At the same
time, many Ulster Unionists have toughened their stance on the
issue, warning their leader, David Trimble, not to give any ground.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust and polarization had appeared to be deepening in the
last week, producing gloom where 18 months before there had been
euphoria and provoking pessimistic statements about the outlook for
any success in Mitchell's review.
</P>
<P>
   All the parties fear being identified as the cause of the
breakdown of an arrangement that has rid Ulster of most political
violence for more than two years, after three decades in which more
than 3,300 people died.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was the chairman of the original talks and began the
current review on Sept. 6 at the request of the British and Irish
prime ministers. He returned to the United States overnight but
said he would be back on Wednesday for a final push.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trimble has been under pressure from dissident members of his
party not to compromise the position known in Unionist shorthand as
``no guns, no government.'' Two former allies, John Taylor, the
party's deputy leader, and Jeffrey Donaldson, a member of the
British Parliament with designs on the party leadership, have both
withdrawn their support for the peace agreement and faulted Trimble
for pressing ahead.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Trimble struck back in a feisty signed article in
the Belfast News Letter. ``At every stage in the process,'' he
said, ``there has been no shortage of advice from prima donna
Unionists about the dangers and pitfalls of taking risks or of
negotiating with our opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Unionists, who are largely Protestants, are so called because
they believe in keeping Ulster as part of the United Kingdom, while
Republicans, most of whom are Catholics, want to see Northern
Ireland ultimately become part of the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble cited no names, saying simply, ``Certain elements within
the Unionist family do not know how to cope with change.'' He added
that ``presently Sinn Fein refuse to accept that they need to
change.'' The likening of Unionist behavior to that of Republicans
is something unfamiliar in the politics of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also reflected one of the intriguing products of
the drawn-out talks _ the association between Trimble and Gerry
Adams, the Sinn Fein president. Until this past year, the
Protestant leader would not speak directly to Adams, but they now
regularly hold meetings and on Friday night they dined together
with Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   After a particularly difficult session on Sept. 21, Adams
emerged to say with irritation that the Ulster Unionists must start
accepting the fact that Sinn Fein is their ``best bet'' for
achieving political compromise with Republicans. And Republicans,
he added notably, must recognize that Trimble is theirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
