<SLUG> BC-NY-WINERY-SALE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLED ITALIAN BUYS PROMINENT LONG ISLAND WINERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore.)  (mk) 
 By HOWARD G. GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hargrave Vineyard, perhaps New York state's most
famous winery and the one that gave birth to the 26-year-old Long
Island wine industry, has been sold to a titled Italian citizen and
his American wife.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners, Marco Borghese, a prince, and Ann Marie
Borghese, who have no previous experience in the wine business,
acquired the 80-acre estate, in Cutchogue, on Friday. Borghese said
the sale price was ``in the neighborhood of $4 million.''
</P>
<P>
   That figure tops all the others in a burst of sales this year.
Since January, the turnovers of three Long Island wine estates _
Corey Creek for $1.5 million and Laurel Lake and Peconic Bay for $2
million each _ and bids on another have drawn the international
wine world's attention to the Suffolk County industry's potential
for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Lake was acquired by a consortium of Chilean investors;
New Yorkers bought the other two. The sales have driven up the
prices for a dwindling supply of open farmland, real estate sources
say.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island industry is also being expanded by major
enterprises like the new Martha Clara Vineyards, owned by the
former bakery owner Robert Entenmann. He plans to break ground for
a $4 million, 25,000-square-foot tasting room in Mattituck next
spring, to be followed by a $2 million or $3 million winery.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Alexander, who lives in Boca Raton, Fla., and is the
owner of the National Basketball Association's Houston Rockets,
also plans to build a winery. This summer he bought farms totaling
86 acres, in Cutchogue and Mattituck, for a reported $1,481,500,
and said that he expected to close soon on a third, a 68-acre farm
in Mattituck.
</P>
<P>
   Borghese, interviewed Saturday in Manhattan, said that he
planned to triple production, which has ranged from 6,000 to 11,000
cases of wine a year; to create a local and national sales force,
and to expand sales beyond New York state, probably first into New
Jersey, Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   He said the first new grapes to be planted would be nebbiolo,
the grape used in Piedmont, Italy, to make Barolo and Barbaresco,
and sangiovese, the primary Tuscan grape used in Chianti.
</P>
<P>
   The Borgheses plan to overhaul the public areas, including the
tasting-and-sales room and a baronial dining room, and to bring
some winemaking equipment from the cellars into a huge barrel room
that is visible to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners have no experience in the wine business and are
undertaking on-the-job training not only in grape growing and
cellar work but also in marketing and sales. They said they bought
the property to enter a new business and create a new lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   They won't lack for winegrowing advisers. ``I think I have
access to anybody in Italy,'' Borghese said with a laugh. ``Members
of my family are already scouting.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa Hargrave said that she and her husband, Alex, would
remain as consultants for two years and that the winery staff was
expected to stay in place during and after the transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Borgheses inherit the 1999 vintage. The harvest and
processing of the grapes were finished in the last two weeks.
Although the new company that owns the property is called Castello
di Borghese LLC, the Borgheses said they expected to retain the
Hargrave Vineyard name at the property.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw in this deal is going back to my roots,'' Borghese
said. They include a boyhood on a family estate of thousands of
acres in Scarperia, near Florence. The family moved to Rome when he
was 16.
</P>
<P>
   His Roman family traces to 12th-century Siena. It produced a
pope, Paul V, cardinals and a number of prominent citizens. The
Borgheses were famed as patrons of the arts and letters. Cardinal
Scipione Borghese built the Villa Borghese gardens in Rome, and the
family home, in the gardens, had been a palace and is now a museum,
the Galleria Borghese.
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves put the property up for sale in the spring of 1998
at a $3.3 million asking price. Negotiations with the Borgheses
began last April.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Alex and Louisa Hargrave founded the East End's first modern
wine estate, on Route 48, in 1973 when they planted European wine
grapes in what had been potato fields. Their red and white wines
have always reflected their Francophile leanings.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as a consequence of their early gamble, the North and
South Forks of Long Island are home to 25 producers, with 2,786
acres of vines owned or leased by them and small-scale grape
growers. In 1998, 221,000 cases of wine were made, and this year
the industry has projected about 255,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves' influence, wine experts say, has extended to the
entire Northeast. By planting vinifera grapes like cabernet
sauvignon, merlot and chardonnay, they say, the Hargraves gave
heart, in a risky business, to winegrowers who had tied their
futures to safer but commercially unpromising French-American
hybrid grapes like Seyval blanc and baco noir, and to old
indigenous varieties like Concord and Niagara.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Borgheses live in Philadelphia. Borghese sold his interest
in a luxury leather goods company early this year. Mrs. Borghese
sells luxury jewelry to private customers. The new owners, who have
three children and expect to move to the estate in the next few
days, acquired 80 acres, 20 of them planted by the Hargraves and 35
more used under contract with other owners, as well as the winery,
its tasting room and the Hargraves' house in the rear of the
sprawling property.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves' choice of new owners may seem surprising to their
colleagues, because many had surmised that the estate would be
turned over to experienced professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for someone European,'' Mrs. Hargrave said.
``I've said that Long Island needs a European investor. It
validates us all.'' Other Long Island producers, as well as
vintners in New York's two other major winegrowing areas, the
Finger Lakes and the Hudson Valley, have often expressed hope for
foreign investment because of the confidence it implies in the
future of the state's sizable wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Their model is California, which has long been awash in European
investment, and, to a smaller degree, Oregon, whose wine industry,
which specializes in pinot noir, was given a boost when the
Burgundian producer Robert Drouhin founded Domaine Drouhin there in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Italian surnames now occupy an even larger niche than before in
Long Island's wine industry: Gristina, Macari, Pellegrini and
Pugliese, along with John Petrocelli, who is building the $6.1
million Raphael, a merlot-oriented winery in Peconic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6204 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-VIOLENT-STUDENTS-2NDT     10-23 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENT-STUDENTS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 REYNOLDSBURG, Ohio: Vita said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   School officials here expressed confidence that the
confidentiality of student records required by law would not be
breached by Mosaic. They emphasized that the software would not be
connected to any central data program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds OK, so long as you don't wind up labeling kids,''
said Shelly Darby, who works at the Sun Tang Luck restaurant and is
the mother of a second-grader here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's kind of scary stuff out there,'' Ms. Darby said. ``But
there can be a real fine line between a kid out to get attention
and a really troubled kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She drew an empathetic nod from Aron Ross, the assistant
superintendent of schools in Reynoldsburg, a city of 35,000 just
east of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few dramatic, sad incidents have spawned hysteria,'' he
explained, describing a nightmarish week of baseless rumors and
countless alarms that caused midnight checks on school lockers
after the Columbine killings. And through repeated meetings with
anxious parents, Ross said, the question remains: What else can we
do so it doesn't happen here?
</P>
<P>
   ``School people in my situation must respond to this new reality
directly,'' he said. ``It used to be a platitude, but no longer,
about creating an environment where students and teachers are safe
and feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The de Becker company describes itself as a specialist in
high-stakes assessments. On its Internet site (www.gdbinc.com), the
company has posted a detailed series of explanations and
reassurances about the school software. ``School administrators
would use Mosaic-2000,'' the company asserts, ``only in situations
that reach a certain threshold (e.g., a student makes a threat,
brings a weapon to school, teachers or students are concerned a
student might act out violently).''
</P>
<P>
   The system ``merely brings organization and expert opinion to a
process every principal already has,'' the company says.
</P>
<P>
   The company has not determined the overall cost of the program,
but Ms. Montgomery, the attorney general, described it as ``very
affordable'' at less than $10,000 for the high school.
</P>
<P>
   The Mosaic systems are ``very well thought out and valuable
tools,'' said James Perrotti, chief of police at Yale University,
which for five years has used the Mosaic-2 program to assess
threats received by professors and students.
</P>
<P>
   Perrotti, one of the experts helping to shape the Mosaic-2000
questions, said the system had offered effective warning about
potentially violent situations that were nipped in the bud. ``It's
not a real predictor but it's the next best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vita, the federal firearms official, says school officials need
Mosaic and other tools to deal with an ever more complex threat in
which relatively good students with access to guns may erupt
because they feel victimized by bullies or by the school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the hard ones for the school administrators to
identify,'' Vita said. ``It's easy to pick out the gang members
with tattoos. It's these other people that kind of surprise
administrators, and these are the ones they really need to
identify.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
