A6211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-2N     10-23 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUENOS AIRES, Argentina: of gunfire.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duhalde sought to revive his campaign at a mass rally in the
Plaza de Mayo last Sunday by playing the populist card again. He
implicitly lashed out at the International Monetary Fund, which is
currently pressing Argentina for budget cuts in exchange for an aid
package that could reach $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people say enough to the adjustments, enough to the
tightening of the belt,'' Duhalde said. ``We're not against having
more rich people, we're against having more poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the event was upstaged by Menem, who remains titular leader
of the Justicialist Party and who wanted the Justicialist
nomination himself despite a constitutional ban against a third
consecutive term. Menem refused to attend the rally, choosing
instead to dine with several labor leaders in the resort of Mar del
Plata in a well-publicized planning session for a presidential run
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Menem aides leaked to the press last week that as soon as
Duhalde is defeated, ``Menem 2003'' posters will be plastered
across Buenos Aires. Meanwhile, senior Economy Ministry officials
have said it would be no tragedy if de la Rua won.
</P>
<P>
   To win the presidency on Sunday, a candidate needs at least 45
percent of the vote, or at least 10 percent more than the
second-place candidate. Otherwise, the top two candidates face a
runoff next month. The new president will be inaugurated Dec. 10. A
variety of recent polls suggest that de la Rua will not need a
second round to win.
</P>
<P>
   Economic issues have dominated the campaign, with the country in
its deepest recession of the decade and unemployment running near
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua has promised to improve the economy by increasing
investor confidence, thereby bringing down interest rates. His
approach is orthodox, promising to reduce a current government
deficit of $5 billion by at least $1.5 billion by cutting wasteful
spending and corruption and prosecuting tax cheaters. He promises
tax incentives for small and medium-size businesses to spur
employment.
</P>
<P>
   He says he will lower production costs to make Argentine
companies more competitive on world markets by deregulating public
services, which he argues will cause communications and energy
costs to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The most detailed economic plan has been offered by former
Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo, who has urged an across-the-board
cut in taxes and government regulations. With little campaign money
and a small organization, he is expected to come in third with
about 10 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But in case Duhalde should make a last-minute comeback and force
a second-round runoff, Cavallo could become the kingmaker by giving
his support to one candidate or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde proposed his economic platform as a bill to Congress _
one that would reduce the value-added tax to 15 percent from 21
percent and give tax cuts to companies that did not lay off
workers. But he could not even mobilize enough members in his own
party to reach a quorum in the House of Deputies for the bill to be
debated. The program's failure in Congress only served to highlight
the divisions within the Justicialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Justicialist Party is roundly rejected, it will
continue to control the Senate until at least the 2001 elections.
It will also control most of the gubernatorial seats as well as the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of divided government has most analysts
predicting that de la Rua will not take Argentina in a sharply
different direction even if he does win the landslide victory
predicted by the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And with Menem leading the Justicialist Party at least for the
next several months, it is probable he will continue to have a say
in what happens in the presidential palace even after he clears his
desk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
