u s BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      10-23 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TO START MIRER AGAIN, BUT FOR HOW LONG?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ For the ninth time in only 39 games, Bill
Parcells is changing quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The ball will be back in the hands of the bemused Rick Mirer
when the Jets play the Raiders on Sunday _ a week after it had
suddenly and unexpectedly been handed to Ray Lucas. Parcells had
turned to Lucas because he was looking for more of a spark than
Mirer had provided, and the strategy worked up to a point. But
Lucas was injured on the final play of a 16-13 loss to the
Indianapolis Colts, so Mirer is back as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is among five different players who have started at
quarterback in the two-and-a-half seasons of the Parcells era, but
only one seems to have got it right, and he is out for the season.
That, of course, is Vinny Testaverde. It has been a continuum from
Neil O'Donnell to Glenn Foley to Testaverde to Mirer to Lucas and
back to Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason to think Mirer can do anything different
this time around? In two of his previous four starts, the Jets
failed to get a touchdown. After Mirer's last start, a 16-6 loss to
the Jacksonville Jaguars in a Monday night game, Parcells
complained that Mirer was not going downfield enough.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer retorted that he was not supposed to go downfield, that
the idea when he became a Jet was to use the various weapons the
club had. Don't try to do everything yourself. ``It's what he told
Vinny when he came,'' Mirer said. But of course no two situations
are similar. Testaverde had Wayne Chrebet and an otherwise healthy
supporting cast _ offensively and defensively. Seven Jets starters
have missed at least one game, eight if you count Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer will have one advantage this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his previous starts, he can throw to Chrebet, who had
missed the first five games with a broken foot and is perhaps the
best third-down receiver in the game. Against the Jaguars, Mirer
did not complete a single third-down pass when Keyshawn Johnson and
Dedrick Ward were his primary targets.
</P>
<P>
   In Chrebet's first game back, last Sunday, Lucas connected with
him five times in the first half and overthrew him at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet's return gives Mirer nearly a full complement of the
Jets' top offensive players: Johnson and Chrebet as the starting
receivers, Ward as the third receiver, running back Curtis Martin,
Eric Green at tight end and Richie Anderson at F-back. The only
player missing is Leon Johnson, the change-of-pace runner, who is
out for the season with a torn knee.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer has lighted up neither the skies nor the scoreboard. He
has barely completed half his passes. His average pass attempt is
under six yards. He has been sacked once for every eight passes and
has tossed seven interceptions to three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But almost any quarterback on a losing team has miserable
numbers. What he should benefit from is in an area apart from the
obvious addition of Chrebet, or of Martin, who enjoyed his
strongest game of the season against Indianapolis with 128 yards
rushing. Mirer should also be helped because the Jets' special
teams are coming back to the dominating level they showed in
Parcells' first season two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Because of John Hall's touchbacks as well as the kickoff
coverage, Jets opponents are backed up following kickoffs farther
than any team in the American Conference. Their opponents' average
drive begins on the 22-yard line. On the other side, the Jets have
become the third-best team in bringing the ball out, starting, on
average, past the 28.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets the ball in better field position, Mirer will not
have to open it up, even though he says, ``If that's what they want
me to do, I'll do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
