<SLUG> BC-BOAT-VOLVO-OCEAN-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK RUDIGER ENTERS THE VOLVO OCEAN RACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Fla., Britain, Germany, Australia, New
Zealand)   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the tender age of 6, in company with his parents and three
sisters, Mark Rudiger shoved off to sail around the world. The
Rudigers had a grand adventure, but their absolute goal was denied
when an onboard fire in the Mediterranean Sea cut short the cruise
and the family eventually returned home to California. But the
smell of salt air and the taste of offshore voyaging left a lasting
impression on the boy.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, Rudiger finally closed the circle on his
first circumnavigation. As the navigator for the skipper Paul
Cayard's EF Language _ the surprise winner of the seventh running
of the grueling Whitbread Round-the-World Race _ he did so in
stunning fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that the 45-year-old Rudiger's thirst to race
before the wild winds and epic seas of the Southern Ocean has not
yet been slaked. This Wednesday, in a reception at the San
Francisco Yacht Club, Rudiger will announce plans to lead his own
entry in the next edition of the quadrennial race around the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   The Volvo Ocean Race _ as it's now called to reflect its new
title sponsor _ will set out from Southampton, England, on Sept.
23, 2001. Before its conclusion in Kiel, Germany, some nine months
later, it will take competitors on a winding, 36,000-nautical-mile
passage. The course is made up of 10 legs with nine stopovers on
five continents, including United States calls at Miami and
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Bay Area native who works as a sailor and
sailmaker, Rudiger has laid out several financial scenarios for the
campaign. His ultimate goal is to raise $18 million in corporate
backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to build two new identical boats, and obtain an
existing boat from the last race for initial sailing,'' he said in
a telephone interview. ``We'd then use the new boats for sail
testing and crew testing, and pick one to use for the event. If
another sponsor came in, we could make the other boat available to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, Rudiger is one of 19 entrants to have posted the
initial 1,500 pounds (about $2,500) registration fee. Although the
final entry fee has yet to be established, Lizzie Green, a race
spokeswoman, said she expected it to be in the neighborhood of
250,000 pounds (about $416,900), payable next June.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Conner, who participated in the last two Whitbreads, is
the only other official U.S.-based entry thus far, though another
San Franciscan, John Kostecki, is heading up a team based in
Germany. ``But we have a lot more interest from the States,'' Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudiger is not the only Californian with round-the-world racing
experience beating the boards for corporate sponsorship. In July,
the veteran Around Alone single-handed skipper Brad Van Liew, of
Los Angeles, launched his search for funds to build an Open 60
yacht for solo events.
</P>
<P>
   As every U.S. America's Cup syndicate head will testify, the
competition for corporate dollars is fierce, but Rudiger is
undaunted. Like Kostecki, he plans to pitch international firms as
well as American corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding the money is a big deal,'' he said. ``But in reality
the hardest part about getting to the starting line comes after you
get the money. There are so many logistics involved, from designing
and building the boat, to putting together the crew and a great
shore team, to testing and training. It's a phenomenal
undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   In his quest to lure a backer, Rudiger wants to find a company
that will take more from the effort than media impressions. ``We'd
hope our corporate partners would enjoy the journey on a personal
level as well as meeting their marketing goals,'' he said. ``We
want to make this a syndicate where everyone can ride along for the
whole process. We'll have regular updates on the Internet and will
welcome input and suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the last Whitbread, Rudiger has sailed in the Transpac,
and aboard the software mogul's Larry Ellison's maxi-yacht Sayonara
in the Fastnet Race, and in last winter's tragic Sydney-Hobart
race, in which six sailors were lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an eye-opener, a reality check,'' he said. ``I'd seen
my share of nasty weather but nothing that serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudiger turned down offers from both San Francisco-based
America's Cup campaigns _ Cayard's America One and Dawn Riley's
America True _ to take part in the current competition in New
Zealand. ``I'm just more offshore oriented,'' he said. ``For all
that time and effort, I'd like to see a bit more of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he wouldn't mind teaming up with Cayard again on a
long-distance effort. ``When Paul wins the cup, he'll be pretty
busy keeping it here in the Bay Area,'' Rudiger laughed. ``But
maybe he'll come sail with me for a couple of Volvo legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
