<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-CANOE-NYT &LR;      10-23 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-CANOE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANOE TRIP TO A FAMILY HIDEAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we reached the west shore of Maine's Salmon Stream Lake,
there was only about an hour of daylight left, so we made haste to
load our canoe and make the crossing to the family camp on the tip
of the peninsula on the opposite shore.
</P>
<P>
   There was a stiff northeast wind blowing, but the venerable
20-foot Grumman aluminum canoe I leave upside down and tethered to
a spruce at the road's end was more than adequate for the half-mile
trip. Pushed by a two-horsepower outboard, we traversed the water
in less than 15 minutes, putting up a flight of eight Canada geese
on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly unloading, we went back to our four-wheel-drive pickup
for the second load and had all our gear and grub under cover
before darkness. Only then did my companion, Ruth Kirchmeier, have
a chance to have her first look at the camp, which might be more
properly called a lodge, because it is bigger than many one-family
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, I had virtually emptied the cookie jar to purchase
the lodge and the peninsula upon which it sits. On the peninsula
are a series of ``islands,'' mostly softwood, that cover about 100
acres. The remaining 100 or so acres is a glorious bog, or, as it
is described in the deed, a heath.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the early summer, my sons Steve and Jeff, my
grandsons and their young friends made several work trips to the
place. The lodge, built about a decade ago, needed to be closed in
on its south gable end, dormer windows needed to be installed and
several doors and windows had to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   All the materials, including a generator to run our power tools,
couches, chairs, tables, beds and tanks of propane gas, had to be
transported across the lake by skiff and canoe, after being hauled
down more than seven miles of logging roads to the lake's west
shore. The man who got the structure three-quarters completed
before calling it quits had used a helicopter to move workmen and
materials, but that was too rich for our blood.
</P>
<P>
   The lake _ about 60 miles north of Bangor and west of Interstate
95 _ is more than a mile long and a half-mile wide, and our camp is
the only building on its shores. In Penobscot County, the peninsula
is bounded by the lake on one side and Salmon Stream on the other.
</P>
<P>
   My sons and I had little chance to explore the place or to fish
it this summer and fall, although the teen-agers did find a little
time on some evenings for angling. They caught smallmouth bass up
to five pounds, pickerel and yellow and white perch, but no trout,
although an area resident, Jason McLaughlin, said that trout are
taken in late spring and early summer just below where the
south-flowing stream leaves the lake.
</P>
<P>
   My trip with Ruth was timed for just after the Oct. 1 opening of
the ruffed grouse and duck seasons up there. I also planned to do a
bit of fishing and to become familiar with the property.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the last light play over the summit of Mount
Katahdin about 30 miles to the northwest, Ruth and I went indoors,
tested the hand pump that pulls water from the lake, lighted the
propane and kerosene lamps and kindled a blaze in the metal
fireplace installed on a previous trip. We slept in front of the
fire that night as the wind moaned in the towering white pines
beside the camp.
</P>
<P>
   A sunny dawn greeted us and we went up the lake's east shore to
try to find our boundary marker. We failed in that, but in our
wanderings along the edge of the heath we found pitcher plants so
numerous that it was difficult to avoid stepping on them. We also
marveled at several white pines that were more than 3 feet in
diameter. Walking under the gloom of tall spruces and pines, I put
up a pair of grouse and shot one of them. In the canoe, we then
went up Salmon Stream on the other side of the peninsula to where I
had found wild cranberries in August.
</P>
<P>
   The stream and the lake had come up more than a foot since then,
but wearing waders, we quickly picked a quart of berries even
though moose and deer had preceded us. We were Millet's ``The
Gleaners,'' without the cloud of deprivation. For supper we had the
grouse and wild cranberry sauce, rice pilaf, carrots and parsnips
from our garden at home, and a tossed salad, all enhanced by an
excellent white wine.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six days, the weather determined our activities.
For two days the wind blew so hard that it would have been
foolhardy to go out in the canoe. Waves and whitecaps stormed down
the lake, leaving skeins of foam on the lee side of the peninsula,
and the rains came. At one point it blew so hard that trees were
snapped off or uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   The following dawn there was nearly two inches of snow on the
ground and the branches of spruces, pines and cedars were sagging
with their wet burden. Then the sun emerged and we were greeted
with brilliant fall colors against a white backdrop and the summit
of Katahdin draped in snow.
</P>
<P>
   In the days that followed, we managed to visit all the
peninsula's ``islands,'' but the woods were too dark and wet to
hunt grouse successfully. We set up a duck blind and put out
decoys, but the whistlers, mallards, teal and mergansers had
departed.
</P>
<P>
   I assembled a spinning rod, but never had the opportunity to use
it: too cold or too windy. We were content, nonetheless, with
chores and inside projects.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and a near gale from the southwest greeted us the morning
we departed, so I headed directly into the waves while crossing
until I reached the lee shore. Moose and deer tracks were in the
mud around the truck, and a ruffed grouse thundered from the edge
of the clearing and dove into the twilight under the spruces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
