<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-FINANCE-CONGRESS     10-23 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FINANCE-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW WORLD OF FINANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Even without new laws enacted by Congress, the financial world
has hurtled through many changes in recent years. Now with the
agreement in Washington on Friday to overhaul the nation's banking
laws, American businesses and consumers face even more
transformation. Legislation agreed to by the White House and the
Republican leadership will sweep away the Depression-era curbs that
have kept banks, securities firms and insurance companies from
moving into one another's arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deregulation is designed to help American companies
expand abroad and become more efficient at home. But the
breakthrough agreement was made possible by the lawmakers'
willingness to try to protect consumers and poor communities from
being trampled in the process.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Congress has attempted without success
to overhaul the nation's banking laws, while American financial
institutions found loopholes to get around some of the old
regulations. Banks have already moved in a limited way into the
securities business, which was barred by the Glass-Steagall Act of
1933. The Travelers Group-Citibank merger seemed a harbinger of
greater change. But as such steps accelerated, consumers had reason
to worry about access to credit, as well as technological threats
to their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The needed legislative overhaul was delayed as the various wings
of the financial industry waged expensive lobbying campaigns. Often
it seemed as if lawmakers were engaged in a big tease designed to
shake down the industry for campaign contributions, overlooking the
needs of consumers. Partisan hatreds in Congress at times made an
agreement unlikely. But in the House, Rep. Jim Leach, chairman of
the Banking Committee, managed to bring all sides together and
craft a bill that was mostly acceptable to the White House. Another
step forward came this month when the Treasury Department and the
Federal Reserve reached an accord to share oversight of banks
entering into new financial activities.
</P>
<P>
   The final impediment to a new bill was a series of disputes over
the right to privacy of consumers and the rights of long-neglected
poor communities not to be discriminated against. Both issues got
resolved in a way that was, on balance, positive. But it remains to
be seen how well the new regulations are to be enforced and what
penalties will be available. The agreed-upon bill requires
financial institutions to disclose their policies on collecting and
using financial information, and gives customers the right to stop
them from sharing information with other companies. States were
left with the right to regulate insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, a White House veto threat forced Sen. Phil
Gramm, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, to drop his
attempt to eviscerate laws that have long required banks to lend in
the same minority areas where they receive deposits. The White
House, in turn, accepted compromise language on enforcing the law
against redlining, pushed by Sens. Christopher Dodd and Charles
Schumer, two Democrats with insurance and banking industries among
their most powerful constituents. Finally, Speaker Dennis Hastert
and Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, also pressed Gramm to
accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
   A sweeping deregulation like this one comes along rarely. There
are sure to be unintended and adverse consequences, just as there
were after the telecommunications deregulation of 1996. The bill
that was put together over the last several weeks, with a marathon
negotiating session into the early hours of Friday, was testimony
to reasonableness on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   It is virtually certain to be passed in the Senate and House and
signed by President Clinton. But it will also be important for
Congress to continue monitoring the trends in the financial
industry. The principle of freer competition is the economic engine
of this era. But the other imperative is to demand openness,
financial prudence and safeguards so that the vast new
concentrations of wealth and power do not create new abuses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
