<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Oct. 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Strong, cold winds from the northwest will sweep across the
Northeastern and Middle Atlantic states in the wake of potent low
pressure over eastern Canada. Although there will be ample morning
sun near the coast, clouds will be plentiful for much of the day
over the interior. Snow squalls will whiten the mountains of
northern New England and the Adirondacks while scattered rain and a
few wet snowflakes occur farther south near the central
Appalachians and eastern Great Lakes. Some clouds and a few
sprinkles may reach coastal areas during the afternoon. Daytime
readings will average more than 10 degrees below seasonal
temperatures throughout the region. Wind gusts over 25 mph will be
common, adding to the chill of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly breezes and sunshine will cover most of the Southeast as
sprawling high pressure moves east from the Mississippi Valley.
Clouds will form near the Appalachians as the heated air near the
ground rises into the cold air aloft.
</P>
<P>
   After a cold dawn in the Missouri and northern Mississippi
Valleys, developing breezes from the southwest and plentiful
sunshine will sponsor a marked warming trend. Afternoon
temperatures will surge above normal over much of the northern and
central Plains. The milder air will spread toward the east Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A moisture-starved front will bring some clouds, gusty winds and
a few mountain showers to the interior Northwest. Meanwhile, most
of the Western states will be unseasonably warm with abundant
bright sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Frost Above Freezing
</P>
<P>
   Frost can coat the landscape when the official reading is above
32 degrees. On Sunday night in the interior Southeast, the first
frost will occur in spots where the mercury hovers above freezing.
Official thermometers are placed 5 feet above the ground. On a
clear night with light winds the air at the ground cools rapidly as
it loses radiation to space. As the night goes on, the layer of
cold air gets deeper, but the coldest and, thus, densest air hugs
the ground. The difference between the temperature near the ground
and the official air temperature can often be more than five
degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
