A6225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOMICIDES-NYT &LR;      10-23 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMICIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 KILLED ON UNUSUALLY VIOLENT NIGHT IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was an unusually violent night Friday on the
streets of New York City, full of shootings, stabbings and arson.
Within seven hours _ from 9:30 p.m. Friday to 4:30 a.m. Saturday _
the Police Department reported six killings across the city,
including the discovery of a woman gagged inside a burning house.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of homicides reflects a more general surge in the
murder rate this year, one that has concerned city officials who
have long believed that the department's concentration on
quality-of-life crimes and specialized anticrime units would keep
the rate on its six-year course of decline. Although the murder
rate is still down nearly 67 percent over the last six years, there
were 540 homicides from Jan. 1 to Oct. 17 this year, according to
the most recent statistics, a 7.5 percent increase from the 502
homicides during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's violence began not with a death but with the
critical injury of a man in the Coney Island section of Brooklyn.
The man, Errol Webster, 35, was standing on a corner when, police
said, an unknown man walked up and shot him three times, once in
each eye and once in the knee. Webster was taken to Coney Island
Hospital, where he remained in extremely critical condition
Saturday morning, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, in the Bushwick section of Brooklyn,
Charles Dantzler, 25, began to argue with a man who then pulled out
a gun and fatally shot him in the back, hand and leg, police said.
A man leaving a grocery store on the corner was also shot in the
leg, apparently by accident, police added. They said that man was
taken to Wycoff Hospital, where he was in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, at 10:35 p.m., a man was fatally shot as he stood
in the threshold of his Brooklyn apartment, police said. They said
two men were involved and that one of them shot the man once in the
head.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes passed before the next report of shots fired,
this time at an apartment building in the Astoria section of
Queens. Officers found Ronald Bradley, 33, of Brooklyn, shot in the
back, buttocks and arm. He died at Elmhurst Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Three-and-a-half hours later, at 2:40 a.m. Saturday, police were
called to another shooting in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Lamale Lawson, 28, had an argument with another man at a party
and the shot Lawson once in the chest and fled, police said. Lawson
bled to death.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, police and firefighters were called to a burning
building in the Jamaica section of Queens. The body of a
39-year-old woman was found inside with her head wrapped in duct
tape that covered her mouth and nose, police said, adding that the
fire appeared to be arson.
</P>
<P>
   Around 4:30 a.m., the body of a man who appeared to have been
stabbed to death was discovered in the Bronx, police said. The
victim appeared to be in his 30s, but police had yet to identify
him.
</P>
<P>
   There were no arrests and few leads in the killings, police
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
