<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FALLING FROM THE SKY
</P>
<P>
   Part One of a six-part investigative series by The Dayton Daily
News on the the recent rise in military air crashes and their
causes. The Daily News found that the U.S. military routinely sends
planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with
deadly safety problems. The series is based in part on
never-before-seen information from three databases from the Army,
Navy and Air Force safety centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MAIN _ The U.S. military routinely sends planes and
helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with deadly safety
problems. An 18-month Dayton Daily News examination found that
planes keep falling from the sky for the same reasons, that
hundreds of crashes can be linked to maintenance errors, and that
the military keeps hundreds of crashes off its yearly accident
totals. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-CASE _ After an F-16 crashed into a South Carolina
neighborhood and killed a man, the Air Force assured the
congressman representing the district that the plane had been
``trouble free.'' But a Dayton Daily News investigation into the
crash found that in the months preceding the Sept. 13, 1988, crash,
the engine had been on two other F-16s and removed after pilots
reported smoke and fumes in their cockpits. (Carollo, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-HOW _ The series wouldn't have been possible without the
release of three databases from the Army, Navy and Air Force safety
centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-WEB _ Where to find the complete series on the web.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: (This installment will be available as a CoxNet Focus page
by noon Friday, Oct. 22. Stories and photos will also move
separately.)
</P>
<P>
   Editors: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week. The layout
will be available Friday at 1 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 1023: MILITARY CRASHES _ The U.S. military
routinely sends planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are
plagued with deadly safety problems. An 18-month Dayton Daily News
examination finds that planes keep falling from the sky for the
same reasons, that hundreds of crashes can be linked to maintenance
errors, and that the military keeps hundreds of crashes off its
yearly accident totals. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-CASE _ After an F-16 crashed into a South Carolina
neighborhood and killed a man, the Air Force assured the
congressman representing the district that the plane had been
``trouble free.'' But a Dayton Daily News investigation into the
crash found that in the months preceding the Sept. 13, 1988, crash,
the engine had been on two other F-16s and removed after pilots
reported smoke and fumes in their cockpits. (Carollo, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   CRABBERS _ NORTH BEACH, Md. _ America's blue crab industry,
which hugs the Southern coastline from Maryland to Texas, is
threatened by imported crabs from Asia. This has caused
consternation around the Chesapeake Bay, where crabs have long been
the staple for watermen and packing houses. (Dart, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday in (a) national, (l) lifestyle and (f)
business categories.
</P>
<P>
   HARRAHS _ NEW ORLEANS _ Four years after a land-based casino in
downtown New Orleans went bankrupt, admitting that far too few
gamblers were losing far too little money, the re-structured
company is going against all odds and re-opening. Sure, it's
prettier and smaller and in a slightly more convenient location
than the first attempt, but just to stay afloat, Harrah's will have
to make far more in daily revenues than any other casino in the
region. When the doors open on Canal Street Thursday (Oct. 28), the
old questions will be asked again: Do New Orleanians or the
tourists who visit here really need another attraction? Is the
casino enticing enough to lure people away from Bourbon Street and
its bars and nightlife? And how will it compete against the
glittering offerings of the Mississippi Coast casinos, which are
just an hour away? (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NCSWAT _ MYOC, N.C. _ The rash of school shootings the past two
years has produced a new focus for SWAT-team training _ and new
life for anti-terrorist training programs. More than 200 SWAT
officers were at the Blackwater Training Center in North Carolina
for training that included a session on storming captive classrooms
at a facility the center calls Are You Ready High School. A look at
the training and an analysis of the latest trend in violent crime.
(Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS _ ATLANTA _ Long lines of immigrants needing legal
help form twice a week at Catholic Social Services on Peachtree
Street in Atlanta, site of one of the few free immigration clinics
in the Southeast. The immigrants need help applying for citizenship
or asylum or working out a problem with an employer, school or the
dreaded Immigration and Naturalization Service. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ A major trade dispute between the
United States and European countries over genetically engineered
food products is gathering steam. U.S. trade representatives have
charged that requiring labels that disclose the presence of
products grown from crops containing transplanted genetic material,
such as corn with a bacteria gene to kill insects, is an illegal
restriction under international trade law. But European officials
say they are adamant that they will insist on labeling, and in some
areas ban the products altogether. Billions of dollars in trade
ride on the outcome of the dispute. (Nesmith 1000).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   HELMS-ENVOYS _ WASHINGTON _ Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., whose opposition to the appointment
of Carol Moseley-Braun as ambassador to New Zealand reportedly
stems from a dispute over the Confederate flag, is no stranger to
ambassador confirmation fights. (Nesmith 850).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-AUCTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ Complaints about online auction
frauds are soaring, say the Federal Trade Commission and the
National Consumers League. Federal regulators are stepping up
efforts to find and prosecute the bad guys, but even some of the
people who have been ripped off say it's up to the industry and
consumer to protect themselves better. (Geewax, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-TIPS _ What consumers can do to protect themselves.
(Geewax, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-SUGAR _ WASHINGTON _ As the Clinton administration
prepares for international negotiations on a new world trade pact,
U.S. sugar producers are worried that pledges of freer trade could
open them up to foreign competition. Soft drink and other food
producers are hoping that will happen. (Lipman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Wednesday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ John McCain's campaign entered a new phase this week in
New Hampshire following the defeat of his latest campaign reform
bill (which he may turn to his electoral advantage) and the
withdrawal of Elizabeth Dole. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   UNITEDNATIONS _ With U.N. forces trying to keep the peace in
Kosovo and create it in East Timor, this much is obvious: On
occasion, at least, the U.S. government finds the U.N. to be a
fairly useful organization. Yet the United States, which was one of
the founding members of the international body 54 years ago this
Sunday, is just 10 weeks away from losing its vote in the U.N.
General Assembly. Under the organization's rules, the U.S. owes too
much money _ $1.7 billion, by the U.N.'s reckoning _ to retain its
voting power. But that debt will soon be paid if Ted Turner has his
way. When Turner announced in 1997 his gift of $1 billion over 10
years to U.N.-related causes, he wanted some of his money to go to
U.N. projects that help women, children and the environment. But he
also wanted to create a political climate conducive to having the
U.S. pay its U.N. arrears. And he has created an organization to
try to accomplish that goal. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PARENTING _ LONDON _ Call it the Battle of the Parenting
Gurus. On Oct. 30, Gary and Anne Marie Ezzo, two California-based
authors, will visit London, advising thousands of parents here to
feed their babies on a rigid schedule, leave babies to sleep
through the night by eight weeks, and spank children as young as 18
months. The pair have written a controversial Bible-based parenting
curricula that includes the popular book ``Growing Kids God's
Way,'' which has been used by more than a million parents. But Dr.
Penelope Leach, the so-called Dr. Spock of Britain, calls the two
Americans child abusers. She abhors spanking and has called on the
British government to stop the Ezzos from coming. (Emling, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PARENTING-BOX _ Box outlining the positions of the two sides and
their Web sites, books, etc. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Oct. 21, in the (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-HIGHTECH _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The Russian economy
is in turmoil. The country has suffered a decade-long brain drain
as the best minds have sought employment in America, Europe and
Israel. But a hearty band of high-tech enterprises is succeeding in
Russia, despite the odds. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION AUSTIN EDS: This is the topic of a conference to be
held at UT-Austin Oct. 28-30, sponsored by the university and Los
Alamos National Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHIP _ MOSCOW _ Imagine your computer running at least
twice as fast as it does now, maybe even faster. Move over Pentium.
Move over Athlon. Is there an E2k chip in your future? Probably
not. But a Russian computer designer has invented a microprocessor
that he thinks could revolutionize the speed of the world's
computers, if only he had the financial backing to develop it.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories MOVED Thurs., Oct. 21, in the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MACAU _ MACAU _ The checkered history of this indolent old
Portuguese enclave is about to end, and few are weeping as China
prepares to take over. Four hundred years ago Macau was far richer.
Portuguese traders dined on plates of gold because for a century
Portugal had a world monopoly on trade in silk, gold, porcelain and
silver with Japan and China. Twelve years ago, China and Portugal
had no trouble agreeing that the Portuguese should end their
occupation just before the millennium. Both sides have stuck to
this pact with little friction. And so on the evening of December
19, 2,500 guests from Portugal, Macau and China are due to gather
here just before midnight to toast the end of nearly 450 years of
Portuguese occupation. When the clock in the Macau cathedral
strikes 12 times, Portugal will lower its flag on the last and
oldest Western enclave in Asia. (Kunstel/Albright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MACAU-BOX _ Vital statistics and/or timeline on Macao.
(Kunstel/Albright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., Oct. 20.
</P>
