<HEADLINE>
BATON ROUGE BEGINS DOWNTOWN RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREA NEIGHBOURS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Planning officials and community leaders in
this state capital call a hotel now under construction on the
Mississippi River the first significant expression of confidence by
a private investor in their long-term planning for downtown
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   The developer-owner, Argosy Gaming Co., a riverboat casino
operation with gaming boats in five states, already operates Argosy
Casino Baton Rouge, one of two gambling boats docked downtown. The
company's $20 million, 305-room convention-center hotel now under
construction, the first hotel built downtown in 50 years, marks its
latest investment in the riverfront area, called Catfish Town.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening the casino in 1994, the company has invested $80
million in Catfish Town in the gambling boat, dock, garage and
100,000 square feet of ground-floor retail space that currently
houses only a restaurant and some meeting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   To secure licensing for its riverboat five years ago, Argosy
promised to begin construction of the hotel _ as yet unnamed _
within two years of completing the casino. But Jim Perry, president
of Argosy, said it had not been possible to get a bank to
underwrite the project.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the financial commitment made this year by the
state and city to begin a major expansion and renovation of the
Baton Rouge Centroplex, the city's three-building civic center, he
decided to start construction with the company's own funds. The
start of construction in August ended the company's liability for a
$300,000-a-month fine that it had been paying since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel doesn't work without the civic center and vice
versa,'' Perry said. ``The city created the right incentive to get
a hotel started.''
</P>
<P>
   The new riverfront and downtown developments implement Plan
Baton Rouge, the city's downtown revitalization program, developed
by Andres Duany, a pioneer of the New Urbanism movement, which
emphasizes pedestrian-friendly downtown environments.
</P>
<P>
   For Argosy, the most important part of the initiative is a
$30-million expansion and renovation of the 23-year-old Centroplex,
which is a block away from the new hotel. The Centroplex buildings
are connected by outdoor plazas and terraces in a block between
River Road and St. Louis Street.
</P>
<P>
   The building that fronts River Road has a 30,000-square-foot
arena where the Kingfish, Baton Rouge's professional hockey team,
and the Louisiana Bayou Beast, its professional arena football
team, compete.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a 30,000-square-foot exhibition hall for trade
shows, conventions and banquets. Behind this structure, a second
building holds the 2,000-seat theater where the Baton Rouge
Symphony and Baton Rouge Ballet perform. The Centroplex's 10-story
governmental building houses the mayor's office, district courts
and two floors of parking.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Post of Post Architects, the principal architect for the
Centroplex project, said its most significant part involves a new
exhibition hall, whose size has not yet been determined. The
current exhibition hall will become a grand ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Post's second priority will be to ``work on connectivity.''
River Road will be rerouted to remove a high-speed curve that cuts
between the new hotel and Centroplex, and pathways, sidewalks and
pedestrian bridges will be redesigned to guide Centroplex visitors
to two grand entrances to the complex _ one facing the river, the
other facing St. Louis Street.
</P>
<P>
   While the design phase has just begun for the Centroplex, a
half-mile away cranes have been at work since August on another
early phase of the downtown renewal. The state has broken ground
for the first two buildings in a $170 million expansion of Capitol
Park. There will be six new buildings in all, scheduled for
completion by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Located on Lafayette Street, a bluff that works as the river's
natural levee, the new LaSalle office building and a separate
540,000-square-foot parking garage will look out over the river,
nearly a mile wide as it passes downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of the Louisiana commissioner of
administration, Mark Drennen, and Duany, the new state buildings
have been conceived as a campus and they will maintain the art deco
style of the existing capitol buildings, which went up during the
reign of Gov. Huey P. Long in the 1930s, said Allen Eskew, whose
firm bearing his name is teaming up with CSRS Architects on the
LaSalle building.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-story, 367,000-square-foot office building will be clad
in stone and precast concrete to replicate the color and texture of
the state capitol's limestone. It will house the Departments of
Revenue and Natural Resources. The ground floor will include a cafe
as well as an exhibit on Sieur Robert Cavelier de La Salle, the
French explorer who named Louisiana for King Louis XIV.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, Drennen said, ground will be broken for
a third building, an eight-story, 475,000-square-foot office
building on North Third Street to house the Department of
Administration. Construction of the other three buildings _ two
office structures totaling 430,000 square feet and a
630,000-square-foot parking garage that will also accommodate a
public market _ will start soon, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Drennen had begun plans for the new state buildings before Plan
Baton Rouge, but they were reconceived under the influence of
Duany's community-oriented approach.
</P>
<P>
   In one change, another floor was added to the LaSalle garage.
``If we're able to attract a movie theater, they'll be able to use
this public parking garage,'' Drennen said. The garage will include
1,920 parking spaces and 10,000 square feet of commercial and
retail space _ most of which is reserved for a YMCA fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Planning also has started for a downtown visitors' center, a
20-acre riverfront park, a state museum and an arts center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if the state made these investments, the private
sector would step forward,'' Drennen stated.
</P>
<P>
   Recent property sales on Main Street indicate that
private-sector activity has picked up. There have been seven sales
in the last four months, totaling over $1 million. Main Street has
shaped up to be a design corridor, with three professional design
firms, a stained-glass shop and a hand-made furniture operation.
</P>
<P>
   On Third Street, a local entrepreneur, Bob Dean, has bought
eight buildings, calling the collection Deanopolis. The buildings
include an upscale office building, now called Dean Plaza, and a
reception hall, Lyceum Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1960s, downtown Third Street was home to Dalton's and
Rosenfield's department stores, Sears, J.C. Penney, the original
Piccadilly Cafeteria _ the foundation for what is now a chain of
more than 250 restaurants _ the Paramount Theater and numerous
smaller shops and eating establishments.
</P>
<P>
   All of the larger establishments either went out of business or
moved to the suburbs, but the presence of government employees
allowed a few lunch operations and stores to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Several new retailers and restaurateurs have capitalized on the
momentum, including Joey's Java coffee shop and M's Fine and Mellow
Cafe, a casual eating spot with blues and folk music in the
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   But the hotel is the most ambitious of the private ventures so
far. Perry, the developer-owner, said that he expected the
clientele to include people who come to do business downtown,
government employees visiting the capital from other parts of the
state, and convention-cisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy projects revenue this year of $60 million, up from $49
million in 1998, an increase that came about in part because East
Baton Rouge parish recently made video poker illegal.
</P>
<P>
   With the hotel under way, the planners' grand vision of a
pedestrian-centered downtown community is one step closer to
realization. Hotel guests will stroll from the hotel to Centroplex
or the casino, and on a calmer River Road to the recently
renovated, Gothic-style Old State Capitol, a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually one of their destinations will be a state-of-the-art
planetarium, for which ground is to be broken in January. They will
all be accessible on foot, in five minutes or less from the hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
