<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNING A CO-OP IN SPLITSVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Franck Amsallem was going through a divorce in
1992, the last thing he was concerned about, he says, was what
would eventually become of the co-op apartment in Brooklyn that he
and his wife had bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intentionally avoided dealing with it,'' Amsallem said.
``We just wanted to get the divorce over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Amsallem wants to sell the apartment, but the co-op board
will not permit a transfer of the shares and proprietary lease
without his ex-wife's signature. The only problem, he said, is that
his ex-wife is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do when somebody just disappears?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Amsallem's predicament might seem unusual, real estate and
matrimonial lawyers say that situations like this are more common
than most people think. In fact, they say, couples going through
stressful divorces often make decisions about the division of their
real estate that could later come back to hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the lawyers say, problems in transferring co-op shares
can come about as the result of even the most ordinary
circumstances, such as when one spouse dies and the survivor fails
to make sure that ownership of the co-op shares is registered
properly in his or her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all had these kind of nightmares,'' said Arthur
Weinstein, a Manhattan co-op lawyer and vice president of the
Council of New York Cooperatives and Condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that with co-op apartments, it is always
necessary for all registered shareholders to sign the documents
needed to transfer the shares and proprietary lease when the
apartment is being sold. That is usually not a problem when all
shareholders are alive and available, and agree to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Problems can arise, however, when one of the shareholders has
died, disappeared or, for whatever reason, declines to cooperate.
For example, Weinstein said, a common problem occurs when a husband
and wife own shares to an apartment in a form of ownership known as
``tenants in common.''
</P>
<P>
   With that form of ownership, he said, each spouse's ownership
interest is independent of the other's. Accordingly, he said, if
one spouse dies, that individual's interest in the shares passes
through his or her estate to heirs or beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   And when a shareholder's ownership interest passes to someone
else _ even a surviving spouse _ it is necessary to confirm the
transfer and record it on the co-op's books and records. That is
done, Weinstein said, by having the executor or administrator of
the deceased spouse's estate sign the necessary documents after the
estate has gone through probate.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon, however, he said, for a surviving spouse to
forgo the probate process entirely _ particularly when the only
significant asset the couple owned was the apartment itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the surviving spouse then tries to transfer the shares to
the apartment years after the other spouse's death, the process is
far more complicated,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, when shares to an apartment are owned by a
couple as tenants in common, and one of the owners dies, it is
usually necessary to obtain documents from the New York State Tax
Commission indicating that no outstanding estate taxes are due.
Those documents, known as tax waivers, are routinely obtained in
the probate process. Trying to get them years after a death for an
estate that was never probated is far more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back and reopen tax records that are years
old,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, most lawyers who represent co-op boards will
not permit the transfer of shares held by a surviving spouse
without some assurance that the deceased spouse's estate was
properly distributed. And the only way to be certain of that,
Weinstein said, is to have the surviving spouse go through the
process of probating the deceased spouse's estate _ even if that
means that the estate must go through probate years after the
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing the co-op wants is heirs of the decedent coming
out of the woodwork after the shares have been transferred,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid such a problem, Weinstein said, is for
co-owners of a co-op to hold title to their shares as ``joint
tenants with right of survivorship'' or as ``tenants by the
entirety,'' a form of joint ownership available to married couples.
</P>
<P>
   With such forms of ownership, Weinstein said, if one joint owner
dies, the survivor automatically becomes the sole owner of the
shares, thereby making it unnecessary to transfer the decedent's
interest through probate and avoiding the need for tax waivers.
</P>
<P>
   William Selsberg, a real estate lawyer in Stamford, Conn., said
that problems with title to real estate can also occur when a
couple, dividing property as a result of a divorce, fail to follow
through on things they agreed on in the divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen many instances where people have property settlement
agreements that say title to property will be transferred from one
spouse to the other, but for some reason, the transfer is never
made,'' Selsberg said. ``I can tell you that trying to get a deed
out of an ex-spouse years after a divorce is usually sheer
torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that many couples overlook when dividing property
during a divorce is that while one spouse might agree to transfer
title to a house into the other spouse's name as part of the
divorce agreement, it is unlikely that the bank that holds the
mortgage on the house will take the first spouse's name off the
mortgage and note.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that a person who transfers title to a former
spouse is still on the hook for the mortgage,'' Selsberg said,
adding that such a situation could pose problems because the
outstanding mortgage will be considered an outstanding liability
for credit purposes. And that could make it difficult for the
ex-spouse without the house to buy a property as an individual.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
