<HEADER>
A6246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KOSOVO-REFUGEE-495     10-23 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KOSOVO-REFUGEE-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW LIFE FOR A KOSOVAR REFUGEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hetem Regjepi struggled in his native Kosovo because
Serb-owned businesses refused to hire ethnic Albanians like him.
But after just five months in New York City, he earns $15 an hour
as a hotel housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Regjepi, a high school graduate who speaks little English,
signed up for a free job-assistance program that not only arranged
his interview at the St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan but also sent a
translator to help him fill out the application.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I tried to get a job by myself, but it
was very hard,'' Regjepi, 29, said through a translator at the
Bronx office of the International Rescue Committee, a nonprofit
resettlement group that assists refugees. ``I was confused,'' he
recalled of his first days in the United States. ``Back in my
country, we don't have so many questions. But now I have a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Regjepi was among the 14,000 Kosovo refugees brought over by the
United States beginning in May to ease overflowing refugee camps in
Macedonia. Many began returning home in July after NATO forces
reached a truce with Milosevic's Serbian-led government.
</P>
<P>
   But others like Regjepi have plunged successfully into
mainstream life around New York because of employment and
social-service programs created or expanded for them. The extra
help has made it possible for several hundred refugees to start a
new life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an income. I have to work to pay my apartment. I
need money to live here, so this helps me a lot,'' Kreshnik Demaj,
19, said through a translator who was helping him prepare for job
interviews at the rescue committee's Bronx office.
</P>
<P>
   Le Lieu Browne, manager of the International Rescue Committee's
jobs program, said that she had placed Regjepi and 55 other Kosovo
refugees in entry-level jobs at hotels, department stores, and
manufacturing and industrial companies. An additional 200 refugees
are seeking similar help.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Browne's program hired five Albanian-speaking case workers
from among the refugees to offer counseling on everything from how
to dress for a job interview to how to answer questions. The
committee also offers English classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to understand that the first year will be a
hardship, especially if they don't speak English and have no
American experience,'' Mrs. Browne said. A doctor or engineer
``can't get that kind of job here, but they have to start
somewhere,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of the International Rescue Committee and seven
other groups have been strengthened by a grant totaling nearly $1
million that the New York State Office of Temporary and Disability
Assistance gave them in July.
</P>
<P>
   The resettlement groups have used the state grant to find
full-time jobs for Kosovo refugees and introduce a full range of
transition services, like classes on American culture, mental
health counseling, summer programs for children and even field
trips to the Bronx Zoo and other New York landmarks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Church Avenue Merchants Block Association Inc., a nonprofit
group based in Brooklyn that has sponsored refugees since 1982,
used part of its $260,000 grant to find work for 55 Kosovars and
assist 250 more, said Joanne Oplustil, the association's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   The group offers English classes and has sponsored weekend
outings for teen-agers at museums, libraries and parks. In
addition, through a center in Brooklyn, the group hands out free
food, clothing and furniture to families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have intense needs,'' Ms. Oplustil said. ``They
literally came with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Regjepi said the extra services have not only made him feel at
home but also given him a glimmer of the promising life ahead. In
his short time in New York, he has earned recognition as an
exemplary employee at the St. Regis and was promoted to the day
shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has his own plans, his own dreams, and somebody
likes it here, and somebody doesn't,'' said Regjepi, who recently
moved his wife and young daughter into an apartment in Brooklyn.
``But I like it here and I want to stay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
