<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WRIGHT-HOUSE-REAL-620     10-23 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-HOUSE-REAL-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STATEN ISLAND, A LANDMARK 1959 WRIGHT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The house had been on the market, on and off, for
years. Depending on your perspective, it is a very 1950s house that
needs to be modernized with new baths and a new kitchen _ or it's
an architectural treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Cass has lived in the house for 40 years _ since it
was built _ and in that time has changed it very little. The drapes
are the same, as is much of the furniture. The red and black clock
originally built into the kitchen wall remains, as does the
intercom system, complete with radio. In the living room, the
built-in stereo system is still intact, with the original turntable
and eight-track cassette player.
</P>
<P>
   Red Formica still covers the kitchen counters, and the electric
burners still dominate the kitchen island. There is no Subzero
refrigerator here, no minimalist light-filtering shades to let in
the evocative treetop views from Lighthouse Hill on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mrs. Cass seems startled, and a bit annoyed, every time
a question is raised: Is this drapery the same? Is this chair from
then? Is this the same tile? Yes, yes, yes, she answers, impatient.
Why would she change anything, she asks, that had been specified by
Frank Lloyd Wright?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed a thing,'' she says. ``He was way ahead of
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wright didn't personally oversee the construction of
the house, it was built from his design, and most of the original
materials he specified remain, down to the yellow drapes in the
bedroom and the typical Wright wood end tables in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mrs. Cass sold the house for $800,000, after
originally trying to get more than 1 million shortly after her
husband, William, died in 1983, and more recently asking $890,000.
In a few days, she will move into an apartment in another section
of Staten Island, closer to one of her three grown daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers don't want to discuss the purchase, according to Marc
Schulman, who with Brian Moore signed a contract to sell the house
while they were at Falcon Properties; they have recently left to
start their own agency, the Real Estate Exchange. But, he said, the
buyers are Wright aficionados and had no problem with purchasing a
designated New York City landmark _ a status that restricts their
exterior renovation options.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, this is the only house in New York City designed
by the famous architect, best known here for his Guggenheim Museum.
It was built late in his life from a plan for prefab moderate-cost
housing. The components were made in a Midwest factory and shipped
to Staten Island for construction under the supervision of a Wright
associate, Morton H. Delson, according to the ``Guide to New York
City Landmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than a dozen of these houses for the masses were ever
built. Wright had planned to tour the Staten Island house, but
shortly before his scheduled arrival he became ill and died at age
92 on April 9, 1959.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the house, according to Mrs. Cass, came
about quite serendipitously, when she and her husband were living
in Queens and thinking about building a house in Staten Island. Her
husband, who owned an employment agency, saw Wright being
interviewed on a television program. He suggested to his wife that
she contact Wright and ask him to build them a house. He had never
heard of Wright, she said, but she had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew all about him,'' she says. ``I happened to be a reader.
I read anything and everything.'' She knew from her reading that
Wright typically had an imperious disregard for the costs of
realizing his visions. ``I forewarned him,'' Mrs. Cass said of her
husband, that Wright ``doesn't stop to think about the All-American
dollar.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Cass says she can't remember exactly what the
house cost, April Cass, one of her daughters, believes it cost
about $100,000, many thousands more than the original budget, to
build the two-story house, beginning in 1958 and finishing in 1959.
In many ways it is a simple home, with a living room, eat-in
kitchen, three small bedrooms and a master bedroom stretched out on
the main floor. Below, another floor that opens to a swimming pool
has a small kitchen, a bath, a room with a pool table, space for an
office, and a large storage area with a walk-in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   It is filled with light, blessed with gracious proportions, and
has a large amount of well-designed storage, with cabinets running
the length of the wide hallway that leads to the bedrooms. The
overwhelming feeling is of wood and woodiness. Even the closet
doors in the bedrooms match the walls, which are covered with
Philippine mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   As with all Wright projects, even the smallest details, like the
mailbox, were specified, instead of being left to homeowners who
might ruin the architecture with their own taste.
</P>
<P>
   Certain of Wright's requirements fit nicely into what the Casses
wanted. Growing up, Mrs. Cass had wanted to play the piano, but her
parents wouldn't let her. With this house, she got one, she says,
because ``there is always a piano in a Frank Lloyd Wright home.''
But she never learned to play: ``I didn't have time, between the
house and the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Cass didn't tamper with the architecture, she did
change her decorations every season. For instance, she would never
leave a painting of roses on the wall during the winter, when they
weren't growing outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she had liked best about living in the house, Mrs.
Cass declined to single out any one aspect. ``I never thought about
what I liked best,'' she says. Her daughter April, a graphic artist
in Staten Island, says that the house was a wonderful place to grow
up. To her, it was just home _ and so in college, she was startled
when a friend became angry that she hadn't thought to tell her she
had grown up in a Frank Lloyd Wright house.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cass says she has been happy to meet all the visitors who
began arriving, and signing her autograph book, after the house was
declared a landmark in August 1990. ``I didn't realize how many
people would come, especially students,'' she says. ``They were
shocked that I would let them in. But how else do you learn?''
</P>
<P>
   She believes in keeping things as they are, in preserving their
essential nature. ``We don't keep things the way they should be, in
this country,'' she says. ``You go to France, and you know you're
in France. You go to Greece, and you know you're in Greece.''
Although she is happy to let visitors see the house, she doesn't
like to be photographed herself. ``I'm not here for picture
taking,'' she says. ``It isn't about me.''
</P>
<P>
   To many, the house is known by the name bestowed by the Casses,
Crimson Beech, after an old copper beech that stood in the yard,
but to Wright scholars it is Prefab No. 1. The fact of Wright's
involvement is marked just inside the entry, by a small red ceramic
square with his initials. But his control over the details is what
really gives the identity of the architect away. In the bedroom,
the full-length mirror is built into a wall, so one couldn't be
slapped on later to detract from the angles and planes.
</P>
<P>
   After giving a tour, Mrs. Cass is asked whether she would do
anything different if she had another chance to build a Frank Lloyd
Wright house.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says. ``No. He was darn good. He thought of
everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
