<HEADLINE>
PRO BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK: HARDAWAY'S NEW TATTOO; O'NEAL HEARS THE
TICKING OF THE CLOCK; RAPTORS POINT FINGERS; RILEY REMINISCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anfernee Hardaway walked into Ancient Art, a tattoo parlor in
Memphis, Tenn., this summer with one simple request. He wanted
something printed on his right arm that signaled his rebirth as an
outstanding player after his last few frustrating years in Orlando.
He wanted something to capture his arrival in Phoenix, where he
will team with Jason Kidd to form, on paper, the most potent
backcourt in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking one night,'' he said recently, ``what can I do
to put something on my arm that reminds me of all this mayhem
that's gone on in my career?''
</P>
<P>
   He came up with ``Heaven Cent, Part II.'' The cent, he made
clear, refers to his nickname Penny rather than the $87 million
contract he signed with the Suns in the off-season. Having the
thick, black Roman letters tattooed, he said, was among the most
physically painful experiences of his life.
</P>
<P>
   It still hurt less than the last two seasons in Orlando, where
Hardaway went from being a potential heir to Michael Jordan to
being just another petulant young star trying to run an NBA
franchise by himself. He led a 1997 revolt against the Magic's
former coach, Brian Hill, was accused of taking his sweet time
getting healthy instead of helping the team during injuries last
season, and had a falling out with coach Chuck Daly that was a
factor in Daly's retiring from the game for a second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got myself in a situation thatdn't win in, and I
continued to talk and it made it worse,'' Hardaway said. Like Grant
Hill in Detroit for a while, he had trouble picking up Jordan's
torch and carrying the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a lot of pressure on me in Orlando and Grant
in Detroit,'' he said. ``The pressure of us being labeled
superstars and not getting it done was there. I went to the finals,
but we didn't win. It seemed like anything else was not good enough
after that. I never said I was the next Michael Jordan or anything.
I just wanted to win basketball games.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Phoenix and Kidd, who has possibly surpassed Gary
Payton as the top point guard in the game, came in. While Hardaway
was making a decision on his future and Orlando was trying to find
a way to sign and trade him, Kidd telephoned him several times
before he signed.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's message: ``We want you here, we need you here and nobody
has any beef about you coming. It's going to be a family
atmosphere. You're going to win. It's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway said of Kidd: ``He's awesome. He makes so many good
plays happen, controls the game and never gives up in anything he
does. It's super playing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   These marriages between All-Stars don't always last, as Hardaway
learned in Orlando in 1996, when Shaquille O'Neal left for the
Lakers. Who knows how much time will pass before Hardaway can't
keep from saying all the wrong things again and antagonizing an
entire community? For now, though, he has a new lease on his career
and does not have to carry a franchise all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   It May Be Now or Never
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Alonzo Mourning did not match up last week
in the Great Western Forum Shootout featuring Miami, the Lakers,
Phoenix and Golden State. But the game's two most dominant true
centers did share a common thought: Time is running out for their
teams to make a run toward the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that for the most part, this is our year,'' said
Mourning, whose Heat has been knocked out by the Knicks in the
first round the past two years. ``I really feel that. We've been
together for four years, gone through some adverse situations. But
we've grown and matured from that and we've still got the same
nucleus of guys. And we've improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get settled and adjusted to these new rule changes and
we start taking care of the basketball a little more, we're going
to be a dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is not predicting a championship, but he feels the Lakers
need to finally overcome their worst nemesis: themselves. ``If we
don't win it, it'll be a failure,'' he said. ``It's a real tough
conference. Everybody stacked the deck. For us, it's always been,
if we play hard and do everything right, we're a hard team to beat.
If we screw around and go through the same mess, it's going to be a
long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Lakers had been given enough time to mature as a
team, he said: ``Probably not. I'm probably to blame for that
because I don't have patience, either. Like this house around the
corner I really want to get. People want me to build my house. I
don't want to build my house. I want the house around the corner.
So I'm going to go ahead and get it. For resale value, it'll be a
bad buy because it's a custom house. But I want it. And I want it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also damped down the rumors that he and Kobe Bryant can't
coexist on the same floor. That idea gained steam before training
camp last season when the two engaged in a slap fight during a
workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Kobe's big brother,'' O'Neal said. ``I'm going to get on
him. He's going to get on me. We're going to get on each other.
That's just how brothers are. It's nothing personal. We know what
we both want.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Romper Room Session
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Antonio Davis' words last week, Charles Oakley has
another player to help him babysit the Toronto locker room. After
the Raptors lost their first two preseason games to Milwaukee and
the Los Angeles Clippers, Davis, the former Indiana forward,
demanded a players-only meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Fingers were pointed in the direction of Vince Carter and Tracy
McGrady, who only happen to be two of the most exciting young
players in the league. Carter and McGrady were said to have been
throwing down monstrous dunks and engaging fans and other players
in banter while Toronto was losing badly.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Butch Carter and Davis thought both players got caught up
in entertaining the fans. ``This game is a lot more than having two
kids go out and excite the crowd,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My good players must learn there is a proper
field-goal-attempts-to-points ratio,'' Butch Carter said. ``It's
something a kid doesn't know. It's up to me to teach him.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and the veteran point guard Muggsy Bogues did all the
talking during the meeting. The Raptors then won their next two
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Davis added, ``When you lose to the Clippers, it's time to stand
up and say something.''
</P>
<P>
   Metal Chairs and Memories
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley recently had his Miami contract extended and was given
a part-ownership stake in American Airlines Arena, the soon-to-be
new home of the Heat. So no one knows the need for a nouveau
technodrome more than the president and coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like anything else,'' he said. ``The game has changed,
the talent has changed and the marketing has created a different
perception. And obviously, the economics require suites because
people want more.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even Riley got nostalgic late last week when the
final NBA game was played at the Great Western Forum in Inglewood,
Calif. The Lakers, the Heat, the Warriors and the Suns closed down
the building for league business with preseason doubleheaders on
consecutive nights. The dimly lighted arena, which has metal
folding chairs and not much more in the way of accouterments, was
where Riley led the Lakers to four championships in the 1980s. It
will be replaced by the Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the Forum was the place where a 6-foot-5-inch defensive
specialist out of Kentucky got one of his first assignments. ``I
think I opened the building as a San Diego Rocket,'' Riley said.
``Jerry West got 44 on us _ and me. And I was here during the glory
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forum is just the latest arena to be spurned by the league
or demolished in recent years, following the Boston Garden, the
Spectrum in Philadelphia, McNichols Arena in Denver, the Memorial
Coliseum in Portland, Ore., and venerable Chicago Stadium, razed
for a parking lot across from the United Center. As dingy
crackerboxes with more memories than luxury boxes go, there's only
Reunion Arena in Dallas, the Compaq Center (formerly the Summit) in
Houston and Madison Square Garden in New York left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of great events here,'' Riley said, standing
in the corridor where his NBA career began. ``I'm talking about
concerts, too. I can remember going to see Elton John, I can
remember going to see the Eagles. I remember the heavyweight
championship fight between Ken Norton and Muhammad Ali, all the
games that I played in and also coached. It was a great part of
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
