<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6256 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BANK-CONGRESS-1STLD-W     10-23 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDNIGHT TALKS HELPED TO CLOSE DEAL ON BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert definition of Citigroup in 3rd graf. No other
changes.)  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a fund-raiser at the home here of Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., shortly after 6 o'clock on Thursday evening,
President Clinton asked one of his closest friends in the Senate,
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., how the talks were going with
Republicans over the most important financial legislation since the
Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd was not optimistic about the bill, which had reached the
point of do or die. After four days of bitter polemic between Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, the chairman of the Senate Banking Committee,
and administration officials, the two sides were stuck over highly
symbolic and racially tinged community lending rules that
threatened to rip the legislation apart.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions had become so poisoned by Thursday night that
Gramm threatened both the White House's top economic adviser, Gene
Sperling, and the head of the nation's largest financial-services
company, Citigroup, that he would pull the plug on the bill,
something neither the administration nor Wall Street wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodd returned to the Capitol and, with a handful of other
Democrats from the Banking Committee, slowly managed to turn Gramm
around in an emotional confrontation in a tiny back office crammed
with three dozen lawmakers, aides and administration officials.
There, they agreed to split a critical difference _ giving Gramm
one provision he wanted that would make community lending advocates
more accountable, and giving the White House what it wanted by
making sure banks provided credit in poor communities before
entering new lines of business.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 o'clock on Friday morning, a few scant hours after his
pessimistic report to the president, Dodd and other exhausted
Democratic lawmakers placed a telephone call to a weary Lawrence
Summers, the treasury secretary, to report that they had clinched a
deal with Gramm to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. After
eluding its advocates for decades, the agreement to deregulate Wall
Street, favored by many of the nation's most powerful business
interests, was struck.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in the middle of the night was the final chapter in
a saga that began in 1934, when Sen. Carter Glass himself tried to
undo the law that put his name into the history books. The meeting
capped a month of posturing, brinkmanship and deal-making in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And its outcome is expected to bring about one of the most
important changes in decades in the laws governing the nation's
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   This account of the roller-coaster ride of the Financial
Services Act of 1999 is based on interviews with leading Democratic
and Republican lawmakers, senior officials at the White House, the
Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department, and industry
executives and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Their horse-trading involved several deals. One, over a new
regulatory system that may wind up governing the nation's banks for
much of the next century, was reached two weeks ago between Summers
and Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, after
months of debate about their visions of the marketplace. The
agreement between Summers and Greenspan to share regulatory powers
is a centerpiece of the legislation to repeal the Glass-Steagall
Act.
</P>
<P>
   A legacy of the Great Depression, the act shattered the House of
Morgan and divided Wall Street into investment banks and commercial
banks on the theory that this would lower the risks of economic
catastrophes like the stock market crash and banking crisis of the
time. Later laws would make it difficult for banks to sell
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Wall Street sought to repeal Glass-Steagall, and
for decades Congress was unable to deliver, largely because the
three competing industries, at war over the shape of the
legislation, lobbied the lawmakers into a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in 1997 when three leading banking and
securities lobbyists met at lunch and formed an alliance. A few
months later, lobbyists from the insurance industry joined the
group. Slowly the industry battle faded, and as the united alliance
approached Congress and the White House, a new momentum developed
to repeal Glass-Steagall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, obstacles remained. Foremost was a turf battle between
the Treasury and the Fed. Both agencies supervise banks, but it was
not clear which would have the lead over the financial
conglomerates that would now be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   The White House took the position that Treasury needed to play
an important role in bank regulation in order for the Executive
Branch to implement economic policy. But Greenspan said that for
financial conglomerates, the Treasury's formulation would enable
securities firms and insurers to unfairly take advantage of the
special government subsidies intended only for federally insured
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Summers took office early in July, he decided he
would take a stab at the issue, and ordered Gary Gensler, the
undersecretary of the Treasury, to prepare options for a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Eager for new legislation, congressional leaders urged Greenspan
and Summers to come up with their own solution to the regulatory
question or have one foisted on them. Two months into Summers'
term, the two men sat for the first of many discussions on economic
theory aimed at a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were two world-class economists who were trying to find
a solution,'' said one top administration official involved in the
negotiations. ``They were both willing to grind this down to the
facts, to the point where they both allowed each other's agency to
share data even if that data contradicted what they were saying
about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has told associates that he believed the talks
ultimately succeeded because the two men spoke the same economic
language, looking at such issues as marginal costs, subsidies and
equities. He concluded that such a deal could never have been cut
by lawyers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning hours of Oct. 14, Greenspan and Summers
brokered a complex arrangement. Both agencies would share authority
under a regime in which new financial conglomerates would not be
able to take broad advantage of the economic subsidies that are
provided to federally insured banks.
</P>
<P>
   That resolved a fundamental difference between the House and
Senate versions of the legislation and propelled the measure into
high gear. Still, by the beginning of last week, there were a few
remaining barriers to a deal between Gramm and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton returned on Monday night from a trip to New Jersey,
he was informed that there had been no significant progress between
Gramm and the administration over the Community Reinvestment Act.
``It's going to be a long night of baseball and CRA,'' he told his
aides.
</P>
<P>
   Detested by Gramm, the Community Reinvestment Act of 1977 was
intended to eradicate discrimination in lending. Gramm vowed that
his bill would never expand the application of the act, and
insisted that the new measure should exempt thousands of smaller
institutions from its provisions. At the urging of civil rights
groups, the administration insisted that the new law could do
nothing to roll back the 1977 act.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the administration insisted that any bank
interested in expanding into new lines of business must have and
maintain a satisfactory record of community lending. For his part,
Gramm was also insisting that community groups be forced to
disclose any agreements that they reached with banks to increase
their lending to minorities and the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday night it became clear that House and Senate
negotiators still faced a wide gulf over the Community Reinvestment
Act. Gramm summoned Summers and Sperling. But two hours of talk
accomplished nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In later meetings with White House aides, the senator made clear
that he thought Clinton would never veto a financial services bill
just as Hillary Rodham Clinton was preparing to run for the Senate
from New York, whose biggest industry is Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials believed that Gramm's political
calculation was flawed. While Wall Street is an important
constituent of any New York senator, they figured, so are the
minorities and disadvantaged New Yorkers who now benefit from the
Community Reinvestment Act. (Both Democrats in Congress and
administration officials said that Mrs. Clinton played no role in
the legislative battle.)
</P>
<P>
   The talks fared no better on Tuesday. They began with
discussions between Sperling, Summers and Gramm. After Sperling
left the discussions to conduct talks on the budget in another
corner of the Capitol, he was summoned back by Summers, who sent a
dire message. ``Larry wants you back,'' Sperling was told. ``It's
all blowing up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gramm put forward what he called his final
proposal. At 10 that night, the Treasury Department rejected it,
issuing another threat of a presidential veto in a statement
largely drafted by Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., the ranking Democrat
on the Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that Gramm would try to corral some Senate Democrats,
top White House officials met on Thursday morning with Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, and the nine Democrats on the
Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The White House concerns were well grounded. That same day,
Gramm held a teleconference with top business executives from
around the nation, urging them to call three of the Senate
Democrats most favorably disposed toward the legislation: Charles
Schumer of New York, Evan Bayh of Indiana and Tim Johnson of South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services industry's top lobbyists trooped to
Capitol Hill on Thursday afternoon to implore the majority leaders
in the House and Senate to postpone any final votes for fear that
they would unravel the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to hold all of his Republican colleagues in line, a
frustrated Gramm was also beginning to show signs that he would
pull the legislation, just as he had killed it last year.
</P>
<P>
   After losing a pivotal vote early Thursday evening that sought
to get the deal that had been rejected by the White House inserted
in the legislation anyway, Gramm issued an ultimatum to the chief
lobbyist for Citigroup, Roger Levy. He told the lobbyist that if
Sanford Weill, the company's top executive, did not call Clinton
promptly, the legislation would be killed. Weill had been in touch
with senior administration officials at least four times that day,
but it is not known whether he placed any calls in response to
Gramm's threat.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Gramm took a telephone away from a White
House aide who was talking to Sperling, and repeated his ultimatum
that absent a quick offer from the administration for a workable
deal, he intended to kill the legislation in the next 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling pleaded for more time, telling Gramm that Dodd and
Schumer were working on a new compromise. Gramm apparently
softened, for as he hung up the telephone, he turned to an aide and
said: ``Where's Chris? I've got to find Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding Dodd, Gramm handed him the amendment that just had
failed and asked that he begin reworking it. Schumer had begun to
enlist the support of other Democrats and Republicans for his own
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The group closeted itself in the tiny office of the House
Banking Committee's staff director with top officials from the
Treasury and the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   At several points, Gramm and Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., the
ranking Democrat on the House Banking Committee, threatened to walk
out. They were cajoled to stay by Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who
headed the conference committee, and Dodd and Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, tempers had begun to fray.
</P>
<P>
   When Schumer got animated, Gramm pointedly observed, ``I'm an
old man, but I still have my hearing.'' That prompted Dodd to
observe: ``He's from Brooklyn. That's how they talk there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they whittled away their differences, ending with an
agreement over the last remaining issue, a relatively minor
provision that would require community groups to make some public
disclosures about their financial arrangements with the banks they
have pressed to make more loans to the underserved.
</P>
<P>
   The final agreement gave Gramm what he had ultimately sought _ a
statement in the legislation that the community groups would have
to be more accountable by requiring that they had to disclose their
arrangements with banks. Earlier in the bargaining, Gramm had
acquiesced to the administration's request that no banks with bad
community lending records be allowed to enter into the securities
or insurance businesses. The two sides also agreed to split the
difference on exempting small banks from the Community Reinvestment
Act. Small banks with the best lending records would get fewer
reviews for compliance with the act by federal auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 2 in the morning, the business of many years was
done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
