<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HAMED-SOTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMED WRESTLES HIS WAY TOWARD ACCEPTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Off the boxing canvas, when he isn't gyrating, or
taunting his opponents, Prince Naseem Hamed is a smart, laid-back
champion. He is also a businessman, which is why he signed a $48
million contract with HBO for as many as six fights.
</P>
<P>
   In his native England, and throughout the Arab world, he is also
a hero. But in the United States, Hamed is still fighting for
acceptance from both the general public and the boxing fan.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a question from a reporter after his rowdy wrestling
match _ that is, boxing match _ with the featherweight Cesar Soto
was so pertinent. Hamed was asked if he was worried that the
12-round fight, not a thing of beauty by anyone's standards, would
have a negative effect on Hamed's quest for acceptance in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' he said. ``The American public is
going to see a fighter with a good attitude and a lot of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question about that, and Hamed's victory on Friday
night over Soto, who has one of the hardest chins, and one of the
hardest heads, in boxing, was as much about perseverance as it was
about showmanship. Hamed's victory by unanimous decision raised his
record to 33-0 and unified the World Boxing Organization and World
Boxing Council belts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the match should be a cause of concern for the Hamed camp
in its quest for acceptance in the United States. It was an ugly
fight, a fact that was admitted by Hamed and his trainer, Emanuel
Steward. ``It wasn't a pretty fight, no,'' said Steward, ``but
sometimes the opponent is the one that dictates that.''
</P>
<P>
   Each camp spent considerable time criticizing the other, but
there was no question that Soto's plodding, stalking style
frustrated Hamed, who has an awkward fighting technique himself.
After an explosive entrance which featured the Four Tops
lip-syncing through ``Get Ready,'' flame-throwing pillars and
fireworks-spewing palm trees, Hamed took control early with several
dazzling combinations.
</P>
<P>
   But Soto (53-8-2) came back in the second round with at least
two solid punches to Hamed's head. It was around that time that a
lot of the grabbing began, initiated mostly by Soto. The fight was
spiced with such grabbing, bringing boos from the crowd of 12,500
at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The most embarrassing, and dangerous, part of the match came in
the fifth round. Hamed had slipped on the canvas while ducking a
Soto punch, almost falling to his knees. Soto then landed, it
appeared accidentally, on Hamed's back. But instead of immediately
getting up, Soto lay there, trying to intimidate Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Hamed pulled a stunt reminiscent of a wrestling
show. He flipped Soto, judo style, onto his back.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed probably should have been disqualified, but the referee,
Dale Grable, instead only deducted a point. Hamed's flip caused
Soto's trainer, Miguel Diaz, to climb into the ring and begin
screaming at Hamed's corner. Steward also jumped into the ring
before order was restored.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's superior boxing skills eventually proved too much for
Soto, and it showed on Soto's face, which was badly bloodied.
Grable's blue shirt looked almost red from all of the blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I demand a rematch,'' Soto said through Diaz, who also serves
as his translator. ``This wasn't a boxer. This was Hulk Hogan. He
just came to wrestle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamed, 25, made his 13th defense of his title.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed earned about $5 million for the fight compared with about
$1 million for Soto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
