<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KLAN-FAMILIES-505&AMP;     10-23 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-FAMILIES-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK PARENTS USE RALLY TO TEACH ABOUT HATRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that was as much education as it was
demonstration, dozens of black families from throughout New York
City brought their children on Saturday to observe and learn about
one of the nation's most notorious hate groups. They were among the
800 counterdemonstrators who surrounded the Ku Klux Klan rally on
Centre Street in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the families ventured into the crowds of chanting
protesters. Others stood on the fringes, some with food, eating as
they explained to children the history of racial hatred in the
United States and the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought them to let them know at a young age, to deepen
their understanding about the Klan,'' said Wady Watters, a
41-year-old New York City Transit worker who brought his daughter,
Ateba, 9 and son, Senefa, 10. ``They only know what they have seen
on television and what I have told them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's event drew only a handful of Klan members. But the
strong response by counterdemonstrators and the need many felt to
bring their families demonstrated how the mention of the group
evoked memories of the its much more powerful and violent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now know that they have bombed churches and houses, and
murdered hundreds of African-American people,'' Watters said of his
children, who asked him questions about the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the families who brought their children said
attending a Klan rally and seeing racial hatred firsthand was a
unique experience in New York City, with its ethnic diversity. But
many said that if their children leave the city, they want them to
understand that many people in the United States still have racist
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Watters, who lives in Brooklyn, said he wanted his children to
see that the type of hatred the Klan displayed still existed,
despite the lessons about harmony the children learn from their
teachers and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, if you don't know where you are, you
don't know where you are going,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The white supremacist group became notorious between the 1920s
and the 1960s for its intimidation of and terrorism against blacks,
Catholics, Jews and members of civil rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the Klan has fractured and faded into the
background of American hate groups, being eclipsed by other white
supremacist groups such as the World Church of the Creator and the
Aryan Nation. Some factions of the Klan have attempted to mute
their rhetoric, no longer attacking minorities, but emphasizing
white pride in an attempt to draw in more members, experts have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Sanchez, 35, who is black, brought his 8-year-old son,
Carlos Jr., close to the area where the Klan was to demonstrate.
``I'm trying to explain to him what happened, but think it is going
to be hard for him to understand,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he hoped that the images of hatred would remain in
his son's head and that in future years they could discuss the
history of the Klan and the source of its members' hatred.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The black families were also joined by whites and others who
brought their children.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna Wenthe, 36, of Bremen, Germany, who is on vacation in
Manhattan, brought her daughter, Marlene, 9, to the rally. ``In
Germany, we have the same problems. We don't have the Klan, but we
have Nazi skinheads who would just as quickly kill a black
immigrant,'' Ms. Wenthe said.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Bines, 45, an Arab-American elementary school counselor
from Brooklyn, said that he brought his three daughters to educate
them and to stand together with other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to know that this was something bad that
happened in American history,'' Bines said.
</P>
<P>
   Bines' daughter Lydia, 11, said: ``My school is full of all
different types of people you can imagine. I don't care what they
look like, they are all the same to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
