<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HARRAHS24-COX     10-23 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAHS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A gamble in New Orleans
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In its first incarnation, it was a spectacular
failure. But Harrah's is betting its new $350 million casino in
downtown New Orleans will be a spectacular success.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people hope so. The casino, which opens Thursday night,
needs to make enough money to pay the city and the state $118
million annually. It needs to make enough to pay off debts. And it
needs to make enough to avoid another closure, which would throw
2,500 people out of work _ again _ and leave a monstrous building
vacant in the middle of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years ago, Harrah's opened what was billed as the
nation's first land-based casino in a downtown setting. It was a
temporary facility, housed in a drab municipal auditorium a stone's
throw from a public housing project. It went bankrupt in seven
months. The permanent casino is a glitzy affair in a killer
location _ on Canal Street at the edge of the French Quarter,
sandwiched between half a dozen large hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrah's has obstacles, starting with the enormous tax
burden, which will eat up about a third of its projected revenues.
On top of that, state regulators, in the interest of protecting
existing businesses, have barred Harrah's from having a hotel or an
upscale restaurant on the premises. Those are amenities gamblers
look for in a casino. Food is available in a bare-bones food court
and a 250-seat buffet. Finally, there's some worrisome history: In
addition to the failure of the Harrah's temporary facility, two
riverboat casinos also have failed in downtown New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's executives don't seem concerned, nor do the Wall Street
analysts who follow the publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sevigny, president and chief operating officer for Harrah's
New Orleans, looked out the window of his 28th-floor office across
the street from the casino one day recently and counted the hotels
that surround the casino on all sides. ``There are 3,400 hotel
rooms separated from the casino only by a street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he pointed to the aquarium, the Imax theater, the Riverwalk
shopping mall, and the edge of the French Quarter, each about a
block away from Harrah's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've got a great location,'' he said. ``This is an
urban environment, and it is surrounded with the kind of amenities
tourists use. Until Detroit opened its temporary casino a few
months ago, this was the only casino in an urban environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has a temporary casino downtown and eventually will have
three Las Vegas-style casinos.
</P>
<P>
   And, Sevigny said, ``This property is fabulous. It is without
question one of the prettiest casinos in the gaming industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The casino is a fake New Orleans set right in the heart of the
real thing. There are five distinct areas mimicking different
aspects of the region. There's the Jazz Court with live jazz music
being played under a fake oak tree, and the Mansion Court, which is
supposed to feel like a Garden District tea party. In the
Smuggler's Court, a pirate ship is sinking in a swamp and Jean
Lafitte's gold tooth is blinking. And in the Mardi Gras Court,
gamblers can catch beads and doubloons from a minifloat that will
parade through the casino twice nightly. Why have Mardi Gras once a
year when you can have it all the time?
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are 2,900 slot machines taking as little as a
nickel and as much as $500, and 120 game tables. For high rollers,
there are private rooms in the ``Court of Good Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevigny isn't saying how much gamblers need to lose for the
casino to break even, but Wall Street analysts have said it's
around $700,000 a day. At least 10,000 people have to walk through
the doors daily. Annually, the break-even figure works out to about
$300 million, more than twice what the casino made in its temporary
quarters. Three New Orleans riverboats, docked in Lake
Pontchartrain, don't make that much combined.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those riverboats has a location like Harrah's. They
are in the suburbs and rely almost exclusively on local business.
Sevigny estimates more than half of Harrah's customers will be
tourists. A substantial portion will be regulars from one of
Harrah's 17 other casinos, Sevigny said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel and Patty Johnson, conventioneers in town from St. Louis,
stood outside Harrah's last week, looking downright depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sick it's not open yet,'' Patty Johnson said. She is
a regular at the Harrah's in her hometown. Asked if she would come
back specifically to gamble at the New Orleans Harrah's, she said
no.
</P>
<P>
   C.B. Forgotston, a vocal gambling opponent, thinks the casino is
doomed to failure, unless the state and city decide to ease the tax
burden. And even if it succeeds, he doesn't think it will benefit
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a success only if it brings in additional
tourists,'' he said. But he thinks most of the gamblers will be
like the Johnsons _ tourists who are in town anyway and decide to
drop by the casino. ``If the casino is drawing on people who are
here anyway, then all it does is take money away from the existing
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Froeba, general manager at the Westin Canal Place
across the street from Harrah's, thinks the casino will bring in
more tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can do nothing but help,'' he said. ``The facility is
beyond my expectations. It's spectacular. It will soon be on the
list of things you have to do when you're in New Orleans. And I
think some people will come here specifically for it, like they go
to Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
