<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NCSWAT24-COX     10-23 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCSWAT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class is in for SWAT teams
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOYOCK, N.C. _ The concussion of two pipe bombs exploding in
succession followed by the pow, pow, pow-pow-pow of gunfire
shattered the serene autumn. SWAT officers swarmed into the high
school. Inside, chaos reigned as a couple of America's new breed of
domestic terrorists fired indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   Police are used to going blind into violent situations, but they
have not been adequately prepared, in the estimation of many
experts, to tackle the new kind of school violence where they might
find themselves caught between terrified students and alienated
youth armed to the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason officials at the Blackwater Lodge and Training
Center in Moyock built the mock 15-room ``R U Ready High School''
for training exercises such as the one last month for some 400
members of the National Tactical Officers Association, an
organization of SWAT team officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with chaos _ a tremendous amount of
confusion,'' said Al Baker, retired from the New York Police
Department where he was commander of the Emergency Service Unit for
25 years. ``They are all young and all are unknowns in this large
place. There is a tremendous amount of noise. You don't know who
the shooter is. We're trying to teach them the techniques of
clearing a hostile environment. There is a lot of bleeding. This is
not something that can wait.''
</P>
<P>
   RESPONDING RAPIDLY TO TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   At last spring's massacre at Columbine High School on the
outskirts of Denver, police were accused of taking too long to get
into the school and flush out the killers, who had already turned
their guns on themselves after shooting 13 other people. One
problem cited by some experts was that eight different SWAT teams
were on the scene, causing confusion in coordinating activities.
The schoolhouse also was booby-trapped with homemade bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis at training exercises at Blackwater is on rapid
response, a kick-in-the-door philosophy of immediate entry with
guns drawn.
</P>
<P>
   In an exercise for the tactical officers here, participants ran
through drills on how to get inside school houses immediately
behind shields carried by two lead officers running abreast. They
cleared the way for paramedics to reach downed victims and flushed
out panicky students. Then they went after the pretend shooters and
``killed'' them with ``simunition,'' or small paint balls. In the
past two years, there have been six school shootings that attracted
national attention, beginning when a 16-year-old boy in Pearl,
Miss., killed two classmates and wounded seven others in October
1997 and ending with the wounding of six students at Heritage High
School in Rockdale County, Ga., in April.
</P>
<P>
   The number of deaths from school shootings has see-sawed in the
past seven years, according to the National School Safety Center in
Westlake Village, Calif. There were 32 during the 1992-93 school
year but only 11 in 1996-97. The number jumped back up to 26 in
1997-98, then dropped slightly to 19 in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   While there appears to be no dramatic increase in school
violence, law enforcement officers see a new, scary phenomenon in
incidents such as the Columbine massacre, where everyday students
suddenly become heavily armed terrorists holding classmates
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to better combat domestic terrorism such as
schoolhouse standoffs, Eric Prince, a Detroit businessman, wrote a
check to build the 5,200-acre high-tech Blackwater facility that
opened last year for law enforcement and military training.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for police dealing with hostage situations is that
the bad guys keep changing. For years, the hostage taker fit a
certain convention _ the trapped bank robber, or the angry husband
or boyfriend threatening a companion. Then, negotiation was the
standard response.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence landscape shifted in the 1980s with the spread
of crack cocaine, and police lost their footing.
</P>
<P>
   A VIOLENT TWO-DIMENSIONAL WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Gangs flourished and children fell as they were caught in
crossfires over drug turf. Drive-by shootings became commonplace in
many poor neighborhoods where the cheap-drug trade flourished.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the topsy-turvy world of street drugs, there was a
logical structure with which police could deal. A hierarchy ruled
the gangs, and drive-by shooters had their targets, even if they
occasionally hit innocent bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   At Columbine in Littleton, Colo., all the victims, in a sense,
were bystanders. How did we move from inner city gang warfare to
schoolhouse shootings?
</P>
<P>
   Among the many school systems trying to find answers is Wake
County, N.C., which last week began a pilot program to identify and
help children who are at risk of becoming violent. The schools plan
to aggressively try to locate troubled students and provide them
with therapy, mentoring and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Grossman and Gloria DeGaetano, co-authors of the book
``Stop Teaching Our Kids to Kill,'' contend that the hold violence
has on some children can be traced to early childhood. They blame
in part the neglect of parents who allow their children to sink
into a two-dimensional world of television and video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brain is like wet cement,'' said DeGaetano, an educator
and consultant who offers tips in her book ``Screen Smarts,'' a
family guide to media literacy, and on her Web page
(www.growsmartbrains.com). ``In early childhood it is
impressionable and malleable. What we put in it stays.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, retired from the U.S. Army and currently on the
faculty at the Unversity of Arkansas' Department of Psycyology and
Counseling, argues that many children have been subliminally
trained to be skilled killers _ and numbed to the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The former Airborne Ranger infantry officer and paratrooper
traces violence back beyond the advent of television in the 1950s
to the 1940s psyche of the World War II soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In World War II, we found that only 15 to 20 percent of the
riflemen would shoot at the enemy in a one-on-one situation,'' said
Grossman, the author of the Pulitzer-nominated book ``On Killing.''
``They would run and hide; they would do anything, but they would
not shoot; even if they were in imminent danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``in Vietnam we got the firing rate up. Ninety-five percent
would shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, he says, was partly due to training.
</P>
<P>
   ``In World War II, they taught them to shoot at bull's-eyes,''
Grossman said. ``When a real person popped up in front of them,
they had to look them in the eyes. In Vietnam, we taught them to
shoot at people (by using) silhouette pop-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same thing we've done with video games. We've
involved the kids in this virtual reality and they shoot at
people,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING CHILDREN TO KILL
</P>
<P>
   How much video games contribute to teen violence remains open to
debate.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing 27 studies on video games, Purdue University
assistant Professor John Sherry said he found the immediate
correlation between game play and aggression to be small.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sherry acknowledged that current data is insufficient
to draw firm conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   What the games can do, says Grossman, is teach and refine some
very scary skills. As an example, he cites Michael Carneal, the
14-year-old who shot up a prayer group at a school in Paducah, Ky.,
in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had never fired a gun,'' Grossman said. ``He steals one
from a neighbor's house and fires eight shots on the prayer circle.
He got eight hits on eight different targets. Five were head shots
and the others were (in the) upper torso. Three were DOA (dead on
arrival) and one was paralyzed. I trained Green Berets and when I
told them about this, they were stunned. These were scambling,
screaming kids. I can't find as good a shot from the annals of
criminal, law enforcement or soldier histories.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
