<HEADLINE>
MISERY AND MISFORTUNE HAUNT SCARLET KNIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Rutgers' spiraling season has come down to
the elemental goal of winning a game. Just one. But in a 38-15 loss
to Pittsburgh today at Rutgers Stadium, the Scarlet Knights looked
far away from achieving even that.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers' record dropped to 0-7 (0-4 Big East), and the threat of
repeating its 0-11 season of 1997 is becoming very real. The
Scarlet Knights face Temple and Navy the next two weeks before the
greater challenge of Syracuse and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights have excuses for their misery. Their
starting quarterback, Mike McMahon, is lost for the season with a
shoulder injury. Eight starters on defense have been lost for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of misfortune _ and the need to ease the
concern of potential recruits _ that led the Rutgers athletic
director, Robert Mulcahy, to publicly assure Terry Shea last week
that he would remain as head coach next year.
</P>
<P>
   But even the beleaguered Shea would have a problem explaining
the Scarlet Knights' anemic performance Saturday against a Pitt
team (4-3, 2-2) that had limped in with two straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's halftime lead of 24-0 could have been greater had
the Panthers not lost three fumbles, one in the end zone after an
apparent touchdown on their opening drive. (Pitt fumbled again into
the end zone in the second half.)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones, who started at quarterback last week for the first
time since 1997, aimed his passes at times and simply did not have
the arm strength to complete others. He connected on 5 of 16 passes
for 45 yards and accounted for three interceptions in the first 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman Chad Schwenk played two series in the first half,
completing 1 of 4 passes for 14 yards. Schwenk tossed a 54-yard
touchdown pass to L.J. Smith and scored on a 1-yard keeper in the
third quarter to give the score some respectability.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Rutgers, playing before a home crowd of 17,325,
threatened to catch up. With the Knights trailing by 31-15 early in
the fourth quarter, Rutgers linebacker Dax Strohmeyer intercepted a
pass, but the turnover was nullified because defensive end Wayne
Hampton was penalized for roughing the Pitt quarterback, David
Priestley.
</P>
<P>
   In a sloppy first half, the Scarlet Knights kept themselves in a
hole by gaining 7 yards on 13 first-down plays. Pitt, on the other
hand, gained an average of 6 yards on first down.
</P>
<P>
   Priestley, getting his first start since the season opener,
found a friend in the befuddled Rutgers secondary. In the first
half, he completed 16 of 23 passes for 211 yards and two
touchdowns, the first coming on a 7-yard look-in to Latef Grim to
push the Panthers ahead, 7-0, early in the second quarter. Grim,
the Big East's leading receiver, matched his season average with 6
receptions for 74 yards before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   A 47-yard punt return by Pitt's Hank Poteat set up Nick Lotz's
32-yard field goal to stretch the Panthers' lead to 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Gibson, Pitt's 6-foot-4-inch, 300-pound defensive
tackle, leaped to bat down one of Jones' passes and came down with
the interception before rumbling 7 yards into the end zone to make
it 17-0. Pitt's last score of the half came on a 7-yard pass from
Priestley to running back Nick Goings.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than enough for Pitt. The rest was exercise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
