<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A DAY OF COLLISIONS AND PROTESTS, ITALY WINS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The America's Cup challenger trials were
more demolition derby than yacht racing Saturday as the 75-foot
boats crunched together and cracked apart under a flurry of protest
flags. When the water was again calm at the end of Saturday's
matches, officials had listened to the bruised and battered
contestants and postponed the last races of the first round-robin
in the Louis Vuitton Cup series until Wednesday. Round 1 was to
have concluded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The day's combustible elements somewhat overshadowed the victory
of Italy's Prada Challenge, which improved its record to 7-0, by
defeating previously undefeated Young America by less than 10
seconds. In almost an exact rerun of its race on Friday against
another previously unbeaten American challenger, America One, the
Italian yacht Luna Rossa came from behind and was again helped by a
spinnaker mishap to beat the United Stated by a few yards in a
thrilling 12-mile yacht race here to emerge as the early favorite
to reach the final of the America's Cup in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing in 8-knot winds, very welcome after gales Friday, the
Milan-based Prada syndicate defeated Young America, the flag bearer
of the New York Yacht Club, by a margin of a boat length, or 75
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Young America, commanded by Ed Baird, led for most of the race,
and was still ahead in the last of the four legs until the
spinnaker collapsed. The battle of unbeatens more than lived up to
pre-race hype, producing a desperately close finish in which the
yachts raced for the line side by side only inches apart. When the
Vuitton regatta of 400 races over four months is completed, the
challenger to the holder, Team New Zealand, will probably come from
Italy or the American campaigns of America One and Young America.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's race on the course, 15 miles north of Auckland, was a
tantalizing preview. Under bright skies, Young America's Baird won
the start from Francesco de Angelis by a length. The skippers then
fought a furious four-leg struggle right down to the line in
on-shore southwest winds sometimes reaching 10 knots.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans fought off attacks by the Italians for three legs
but faltered on the downwind leg near the finish when a snap
shackle failed on their spinnaker. Young America slowed as the sail
flapped out of control and the Italians seized the chance to
overtake. For several minutes the bow of the pursuing American boat
almost touched the Italian boat's stern.
</P>
<P>
   Both boats flew protest flags but umpires ruled that Luna Rossa
was maintaining a proper course to the finish and that Young
America had not obstructed the Italian boat as it gybed away to the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of this race that had to do with being in the
right place on a wind shift,'' Baird said. ``And in the end, the
result was based on something breaking.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the third day in a row for snap shackle failures in
spinnakers or genoas, and Baird quipped, ``Apparently, they have
been passing these shackles around.''
</P>
<P>
   In other action, Japan's Nippon Challenge was penalized half a
point for damaging the Spanish vessel, Bravo Espana, in a
bow-to-stern collision in pre-start maneuvering that caused
substantial damage to both. And America One was struck by Dennis
Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes in another skirmish at the start line.
America One went on to defeat its compatriot by one minute.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the others in the repair shop during the next three days
will be the Swiss yacht Be Happy, which has yet to win. Be Happy's
bulkhead tore loose from the hull minutes into its race against the
French team.
</P>
</TEXT>
