<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN24-COX     10-23 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain hopes for headway as GOP field narrows
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. - George W. Bush's double-digit lead in the polls
and his commanding advantage in campaign cash prompted another
self-deprecating joke from Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always darkest before it's totally black,'' McCain said,
assessing his chances against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some cause for mirth as McCain edges closer than
ever to Bush in opinion polls in New Hampshire, site of the first
primary. The shrinking of the Republican field - Elizabeth Dole
dropped out last week and Pat Buchanan is expected to join the
Reform party Monday - is affording McCain more attention just as
voters here are starting to give the presidential race a closer
look.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is offering them a character-based campaign that draws on
his experience as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and calls on
Americans to band together against a favorite McCain target, the
``special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his latest trip to New Hampshire last week immediately
after Dole's withdrawal and the failure, again, of his campaign
finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's willingness to go against his party on campaign finance
reform issues rankles some of his colleagues, but it reinforces the
image that McCain believes is the key to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's honest. It would be wonderful to have someone we
can trust,'' said Claire Partridge, a retired secretary who showed
up at the century-old town hall in Wakefield to show her support
for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nancy Spencer-Smith, an Episcopal priest and lawyer in
Wakefield, had yet to make up her mind. But she talked about his
time as a POW.
</P>
<P>
   ``People admire the fact that he could withstand that challenge
and not be jaded or embittered,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Radio ads that began airing last week stressed the same theme,
saying that McCain has ``the character to do what's right'' and
``the courage to fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two new polls last week showed McCain beginning to close the gap
with Bush. In a Research 2000 survey, he trailed the Texan by 12
points, 39 percent to 27 percent. Bush had a 16-point advantage, 42
percent to 26 percent, in an American Research Group poll.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign sent an urgent appeal for funds via e-mail last
week, using the poll numbers and Dole's exit as its context.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strategy demands that he do well in New Hampshire on
Feb. 1, then win in South Carolina on Feb. 19 and in his home state
of Arizona three days later.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would then have two weeks to capitalize on his showings
before more than a dozen primaries March 7, including those in
California, New York and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has neither the money nor the organization to match Bush
across the nation. But he is hopeful that early strength might
swing voters his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much to my dismay, the majority of Americans still don't know
who John McCain is,'' he said in Concord. ``But if I do well here,
they will.''
</P>
<P>
   It is something more than a wing and a prayer, but well short of
a sure thing. McCain said his odds have improved, but he gave
himself only a one in three chance.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Pat Buchanan won the Republican primary here,
but could not compete with Bob Dole's superior organization
elsewhere in the country. In the 1984 Democratic primary here, a
contest McCain cites hopefully, Gary Hart upset former Vice
President Walter Mondale. But Mondale was the Democratic nominee
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the remaining Republican candidates, he has not
attacked Bush, whose rhetoric of inclusion is similar to McCain's.
While McCain's tactics have spurred talk that he wants to be vice
president, the senator said this is not so.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he is using a positive message to try to forge a
coalition of moderate Republicans, veterans, independents and some
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to broaden this campaign out from just rigid,
party doctrinaire issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His comment came just a day after he voted in the Senate to ban
partial-birth abortions. But McCain used the abortion issue to
illustrate what he means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are pro-life as I am and those who are pro-choice
(should) sit down and have a dialogue together on making adoption
easier, improving foster care, doing the things we can to eliminate
abortion, a goal which all of us share,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
