A6273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-UNITEDNATIONS24-COX     10-23 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITEDNATIONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner foundations lobby to get U.S. to pay U.N. dues
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With United Nations forces struggling to keep the
peace in Kosovo and create it in East Timor, this much is clear: On
occasion, at least, the U.S. government finds the United Nations to
be a fairly useful organization.
</P>
<P>
   The organization began both operations partly at the behest of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the United States, which was one of the founding members of
the international body 54 years ago today, is just 10 weeks away
from losing its vote in the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: nonpayment of dues. Under the organization's rules,
the U.S. owes too much money _ $1.7 billion, by the U.N.'s
reckoning _ to retain its voting power.
</P>
<P>
   But that debt will soon be paid if Ted Turner has his way.
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta media magnate announced in 1997 his gift of $1
billion over 10 years to U' _cil'' that gives veto power to China,
``one of the most flagrant human rights abusers,'' and Russia,
``the most unstable great-power regime.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said earlier this month that
unpaid dues and bureaucratic delays have made it virtually
impossible for the United Nations to respond quickly to crises like
those in Kosovo and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an organization that must respond regularly to crisis,
this is a sure path to frustration, failure and irrelevance,'' he
told the General Assembly's budget and finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the United Nations agree that more reform of the
organization is needed, but they say the world body still performs
critically important tasks .
</P>
<P>
   Turner and the Better World Fund are by no means alone in their
fight. The United Nations Association runs model U.N. programs in
schools to teach students the value of the United Nations. With 175
local chapters around the country, the association tries to
persuade local citizens to lobby their congressmen on behalf of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that between 60 percent and 70 percent of American
people favor paying the back dues, said William Luers, chairman and
president of the organization. Luers is a former U.S. ambassador to
Czechoslovakia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Eisenhower, granddaughter of President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, heads the Emergency Coalition for U.S. Financial
Support of the United Nations, an organization that includes
several former U.S. secretaries of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is the leading country within the U.N.
system,'' Eisenhower said. ``And it seems to me that if you have
made a commitment to pay your dues to an organization, and you want
to remain involved and engaged in that organization, you ought to
pay what you owe. That's a rather conservative notion _ that great
nations pay their bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower said she sees a growing realization in Congress that
the nonpayment of dues is undermining the United States' standing
with countries that do pay, and undermining the nation's national
security interests.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino, too, thinks the chances of convincing Congress to pay
part of the debt this year are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's a shrinking place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
