<HEADER>
A6274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-O'NEI     10-23 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-O'NEILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ORNERY AND HURTING O'NEILL STILL FULFILLS HIS CHILDHOOD DREAMS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Paul O'Neill was cranky and ornery, again, when he
trudged off Turner Field after Friday's workout. He rumbled past
reporters and wanted to know why they needed to interview him and
the other Yankees, a necessity O'Neill should understand since he
will have played in three of the last four World Series after
Saturday night's opener with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But most interviews with O'Neill are a struggle at first.
Eventually, O'Neill relaxes and speaks eloquently about every
subject that does not involve him, and the verbal tantrums
dissipate. Friday was more of the same jousting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you a question,'' O'Neill said to one familiar
reporter. ``When do we get time to relax?''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter reminded O'Neill that the Yankees' clubhouse had
been closed for over an hour before the workout and then asked
O'Neill if he would rather be home in Columbus, Ohio, watching the
Series on television. The question seemed to startle O'Neill, but
he regrouped and was fast with his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be out in right field,'' said O'Neill, a small
smile across his face, ``with you guys up in the press box.''
</P>
<P>
   Then O'Neill finally agreed to talk, even yelling for one
reporter whom he had rebuffed to hurry up and interview him.
O'Neill discussed the confidence the Yankees have, the excitement
of winning a World Series, the sizable obstacle the Braves will be
for the Yankees and the importance of staying focused during the
distractions created by baseball in late October.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill's most significant observation was a comment he had
made on Wednesday at Yankee Stadium. When someone had asked him
about what being a Yankee had meant to his career, O'Neill barely
waited for the question to end. He said being a Yankee had meant
everything to an Ohio boy whose goal of playing for the Cincinnati
Reds was electrifying for only one of the six years he spent there,
when the 1990 Reds went all the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been my career, in my mind, being in New York and
being part of these teams that have won here,'' said O'Neill. ``I
remember 1990 and I remember the seven years I've been here. That's
what I look back on as my career, because I've been on teams that
have had a chance to win. When you play sports, that's what you
dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are doing more of that dreaming, although it is more
reality than dreaming now that they are in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neill has had an ordinary post-season with a .276
average and one run batted in through the first eight games, he is
one of the players Atlanta must stop. That is amazing considering
that 12 days ago the Yankees learned that O'Neill had a fractured
10th rib on the right side, and doctors advised the 36-year-old to
skip the American League Championship Series and hope and pray that
he healed in time for the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was insistent on playing through the pain, and he
lobbied Manager Joe Torre the way a 17-year-old lobbies his father
for the car keys on a Friday night. O'Neill won.
</P>
<P>
   Now O'Neill's injury, which he said did not limit him in any way
during the ALCS, is hardly a major concern. Torre was so certain
about O'Neill's status against the Braves that he replaced
outfielder Shane Spencer with infielder Jim Leyritz on the roster.
Spencer was a security blanket in case O'Neill reinjured himself,
but O'Neill said: ``The last few games in Boston, I felt fine. It's
not a story anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Yankees speculated that O'Neill would have continued to
play in the post-season even if the pain in his rib was so intense
that it caused him to have trouble breathing. O'Neill had a torn
hamstring throughout the 1996 dash to a World Series title and
still made a memorable catch in Game 5 against Atlanta, so being
slowed by injuries is not a new experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tremendous resolve,'' said David Cone. ``He's miserable
when the story is him and he's in the spotlight. He couldn't wait
to declare himself healthy and make this a nonstory. You could tell
he was miserable, just the notion of being left out.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill batted only .190 (30 for 158) against left-handers this
season, so he was among the happiest to hear that Tom Glavine had
been scratched as the Game 1 starter Saturday night _ a decision
that meant he would probably face the Yankees no more than twice in
the series, and possibly just once. Still, the Series could prove
to be annoying for him with three lefties in the bullpen for
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill tried flicking away those dismal numbers by saying
everything starts fresh Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said that everyone in here should feel lucky to be
playing on this team at this time,'' said O'Neill. ``You get breaks
in games, you get breaks in life, you get breaks in baseball. It's
a big break for everyone in here to be part of this team through
this run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
