<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KLAN-RALLY-ART-500     10-23 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-RALLY-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNMASKED AND OVERWHELMED, THE KLAN IS BESIEGED AT RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standing in black and white hooded robes that
revealed their expressionless faces, 16 members of the Ku Klux Klan
staged a rally in Manhattan Saturday before hundreds of jeering
protesters who shouted, ``Klan go home!'' and various obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   If any Klansman had harbored illusions of working the hostile
crowd gathered before him Saturday, they evaporated quickly. The
rally turned violent even before the hugely outnumbered Klansmen
had a chance to say one amplified word. As Grand Dragon James
Sheeley and a handful of his colleagues entered a penned-in staging
area before the state Supreme Court building in lower Manhattan, he
was attacked by five men who had entered the area, apparently after
convincing the police that they were Klan members, too.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men leapt on Sheeley, punching him in the face before
officers intervened and arrested the man and four other people, who
shouted, ``Death to the Klan!'' as they were led off.
</P>
<P>
   With only 16 members willing to appear without their masks
Saturday, the Ku Klux Klan's low-tech rally appeared to be an
anemic, even farcical sideshow to the much larger crowd of shouting
counterdemonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   The Klansmen were unmasked after losing a legal battle with the
city that went all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a federal appeals court in Manhattan reversed a lower
court's ruling and decided that the Klan's rally could go on only
if its members did not have the anonymity they had sought behind
their pointed white hoods, powerful symbols of the organization's
racist, violent history.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge appeals court refused to overturn a lower
court's ruling against the Partisan Defense Committee, an ad-hoc
anti-Klan group, which had claimed the city violated its rights by
rejecting a request for a sound permit for a rally adjacent to the
Klan's. Lawyers for the Klan group, the Church of the American
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, argued that if its members were forced
to unmask themselves, they faced retaliation because of their
unpopular views, thus violating their First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   About 11 a.m. Saturday, the New York Civil Liberties Union filed
a petition on the Klan's behalf with the U.S. Supreme Court, and it
was referred to Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, who has responsibility
for emergency petitions from the New York region. At 2 p.m.,
Justice Ginsburg rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they were pleased with the Supreme Court
decision upholding the antimask statute. ``We are gratified by the
decision of Justice Ginsburg,'' said the city's corporation
counsel, Michael D. Hess. ``It supports the case that we presented
to the court and supports the three to nothing decision by the
second circuit court of appeals. We also feel that the policy
behind the anti-mask statute helps to avoid violence, makes people
accountable for their actions and, so far, the event has been
virtually violence-free and hopefully will conclude that way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On a makeshift stage in front of the state Supreme Court
building where placard-carrying anti-Klan protesters had gathered,
Alan G. Hevesi, the city comptroller, yelled into a microphone:
``These are stupid people. They need to blame their targets for
their own failure.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jerrold R. Nadler, D-N.Y., also spoke, though his
voice was all but drowned out by mocking shouts from the
protesters. The Klan, which once boasted of membership in the
millions, is now believed to have dwindled to about 4,000 members
as it struggles to compete against newer, bolder and more
Internet-savvy groups that, in the shrinking realm of white
supremacy, are often seen as more fashionably racist than the
cross-burning Klansmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Klan has a plan: To let it be known around the
country that they can do whatever they want,'' said Charlene
Mitchell, a labor organizer from Manhattan who came to one of the
two pre-Klan protest gatherings Saturday. ``That's why they want
all this attention, to grow their membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Quester, 36, a kindergarten teacher from Brooklyn, said,
``I hate the Klan, that's why I'm here.'' Remarking on the week of
court battles the Klan fought to win the right to rally Saturday,
he added, ``I think we should exercise our free speech so
vigorously that no one hears them at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Like some others among the protest crowd, Ms. Mitchell, 69, is a
veteran of other Klan rallies, in Cleveland, Georgia and Tupelo,
Miss., where hooded, armed Klansmen rode through town on the back
of flatbed trucks. ``It was a scary thing,'' she recalled. ``You
can't see their faces, you can't see their eyes. It's
terrorizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the specter of a few dozen members of a racist fringe
group taking a stage in lower Manhattan before hundreds of police
officers and thousands of jeering anti-Klan protesters, Saturday's
event was also filigreed with several smaller, quieter ironies.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is known for brazenly hurling epithets at blacks and
Jews, Jeffery L. Berry, the Klan's national imperial wizard, for
instance, quickly hired Norman Siegal, the head of the New York
Civil Liberties Union, who is Jewish, to force City Hall to issue a
permit. Then, last week, the city's largest black newspaper, The
Amsterdam News, and the Rev. Al Sharpton both filed legal papers
supporting the Klan's right to rally in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   (The newspaper said it had acted out of a sense of First
Amendment inclusiveness, and Sharpton clarified that he wasn't
``for the Klan,'' simply ``against the mayor.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6278 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING     10-23 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: his campaign. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it is the preponderance of New York banking and brokerage
firms at the top of Bradley's donor list that sets him apart from
the other leading candidates for the presidency. Only two Wall
Street firms are in Gore's and McCain's top 10 lists of
contributors; only one makes Gov. George W. Bush's list of 10
biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   The only firm to make the top 10 list for all four candidates is
Goldman, Sachs, whose partners and their families have contributed
$22,455 to McCain, $60,250 to Gore, $77,250 to Bush _ and $210,000
to Bradley. Bradley's success is even more notable because
Goldman's former chairman, Robert Rubin, was chairman of the
National Economic Council and treasury secretary in the Clinton
administration. Rubin is so far sitting out the 2000 presidential
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's familiarity with top bankers, brokers and bond traders
grew from his 18 years of service on the Senate Finance Committee.
He was one of the primary authors of the landmark 1986 tax bill and
the architect of a plan to address the Third World debt crisis in
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But even Bradley's opponents cannot point to anything specific
in his Senate career that would account for Wall Street's loyalty
and generosity. He proposed an increase in the capital gains tax,
advocated abolition of a variety of tax shelters and urged banks to
take substantial losses on their loans to struggling economies _
all positions that at times put him at odds with financial
executives.
</P>
<P>
   So what accounts for Bradley's popularity on Wall Street?
</P>
<P>
   Partly it is geography: Bradley attended Princeton University in
New Jersey, represented New Jersey in the Senate and still lives in
northern New Jersey. Partly it is familiarity with the people and
the lingo of Wall Street _ J.P. Morgan hired him consultant within
weeks of his leaving the Senate in 1997. Partly it is his position
as the only Democratic alternative to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And he also helped to give New York something no other area
politician has ever delivered: two NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't any of the policies that make him popular,'' said
Mark Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association.
``Part of it is he was a Knick, and a very successful one at that.
A lot of the Street are sports fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used the two years between retiring from the Senate and
establishing his presidential committee late last year to lay the
political and financial groundwork for his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his work at J.P. Morgan, Bradley signed on as a
consultant with the Gartner Group, a telecommunications research
firm in Stamford, Conn. The company paid Bradley $131,000 in 1998,
according to the personal financial disclosure statement he
released this year.
</P>
<P>
   He took part-time appointments at the University of Maryland,
Notre Dame University and Stanford, earning $170,000 last year for
a handful of lectures at each school.
</P>
<P>
   He gave more than 60 speeches _ at an average of $25,000 each _
to a variety of corporations, law firms and interest groups. Among
them were Rhone-Poulenc Rorer, a pharmaceutical company; Health
Care Information and Management Systems Society; the National Home
Equity Mortgage Association; the Association of Investment
Management Sales Executives; Key Bank; Barclays Global Investors;
the American Association of Health Plans, and First Union Capital
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   So last winter when he announced his intention to seek the
Democratic nomination for president, he had not only a rich list of
potential donors from three successful Senate campaigns, but a new
cache of contacts from his two years out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his proven ability to raise money and win elections,
Bradley seems to have benefited from disaffection among some
Democratic Party donors with Clinton and his chosen heir, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the initial interest in Bradley is the result of
Clinton-Gore fatigue,'' said Bonnie Reiss, a top New York
fund-raiser for Bradley and a member of his advisory board, ``a
feeling that they need to wash their hands of the whole
administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
