<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-UNITEDNATIONS24-COX     10-23 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITEDNATIONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner foundations lobby to get U.S. to pay U.N. dues
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With United Nations forces struggling to keep the
peace in Kosovo and create it in East Timor, this much is clear: On
occasion, at least, the U.S. government finds the United Nations to
be a fairly useful organization.
</P>
<P>
   The organization began both operations partly at the behest of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the United States, which was one of the founding members of
the international body 54 years ago today, is just 10 weeks away
from losing its vote in the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: nonpayment of dues. Under the organization's rules,
the U.S. owes too much money _ $1.7 billion, by the U.N.'s
reckoning _ to retain its voting power.
</P>
<P>
   But that debt will soon be paid if Ted Turner has his way.
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta media magnate announced in 1997 his gift of $1
billion over 10 years to U.N.-related causes, he wanted some of his
money to go to U.N. projects that help women and work to control
the world's population. He wanted some of it to go to improving the
global environment, and he wanted some of it to go to programs that
help children.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not all. Turner also wanted to create a constituency
for the world body in the United States, which would create a
political climate conducive to having the U.S. government pay its
U.N. arrears.
</P>
<P>
   So Turner set up the U.N. Foundation to distribute money to U.N.
programs that help women, children and the environment. And he set
up the Better World Fund to handle the more political side of
things _ such as campaigning for public support for the U.N. and
lobbying Congress to pay at least some of the back dues this
country owes.
</P>
<P>
   The Better World Fund is a distinct organization, but it bears a
striking resemblance to the U.N. Foundation. It is located in the
same office space on Connecticut Avenue in Washington, D.C. It has
the same president _ former Colorado Sen. Tim Wirth. And it has the
same board of directors, chaired by Turner.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out its mandate, the Better World Campaign _ the
primary project of the Better World Fund _ is running an
advertising campaign designed to increase support for the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a place for peace?'' begins one full-page ad, in
large, eye-catching letters. ``Sometimes the world seems full of
violence and hatred, terrorism and war,'' the ad continues in more
subdued type. ``Fortunately, there is a place where people can
pursue peace: The United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   After a plea for the United States to pay its outstanding dues,
the ad concludes, in bold print: ``Great nations keep their word.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad has run primarily in Washington, D.C., but has also
appeared in publications around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Other advertisements by the group stress the U.N.'s role in
bringing to justice the suspects in the bombing of Pam Am flight
103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in building an international
coalition against Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein, in negotiating
settlements of regional conflicts and in caring for refugees around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The argument is that the United Nations needs money, namely the
money the U.S. owes it, to do those jobs. And people who criticize
the United Nations for inefficient or inadequate responses to
crises should bear that in mind, said Phyllis Cuttino, executive
director of the Better World Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people don't understand about the U.N. is,
really, without the appropriate tools, the U.N. can't do the job
it's been assigned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. debt to the world body began accumulating in the
mid-1980s. In an effort to force the United Nations to adopt budget
reforms, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum (R-Kan.) sponsored an amendment to
the State Department Authorization bill to withhold 20 percent of
the country's annual assessed contributions to the organization.
According to the Better World Campaign, that made the United States
the first country to ever impose unilateral conditions on the
payment of its U.N. dues.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, payment of the dues has been tied to an an issue
that U.N. supporters say is completely unrelated. Rep. Chris Smith
(R-N.J.), a member of the International Relations Committee, has
successfully linked payment of U.N. dues to a provision that would
bar international family planning funding to any organization that
used its own, non-U.S. government funds for abortion-related
services.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the United Nations supports no abortion
activities. The amendment would prevent not the United Nations, but
the U.S. Agency for International Development from supporting
abortion-related programs in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Because that amendment was attached, President Clinton last year
vetoed a bill to pay the U.N. arrears.
</P>
<P>
   Now the debt has become large enough that, under Article 19 of
the U.N. Charter, the United States will lose its vote in the
General Assembly at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   An effort is being made in Congress to attach the same amendment
again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonpayment of the dues, however, will not affect the United
State's right to vote _ and cast vetoes _ in the more powerful U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks the United Nations itself is without blame.
Some critics contend that the U.S. money would be misspent unless
the U.N. reforms its bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in the Montreal Gazette, economics Professor
Irving Brecher of McGill University said the United Nations ``is
near the edge of financial ruin'' _ $2.6 billion in debt as of May.
More than 60 percent of the debt is due to the U.S. failure to pay
its dues.
</P>
<P>
   The world body is struggling, Brecher wrote, partly because it
is ``constrained by a never-reformed Security Council'' that gives
veto power to China, ``one of the most flagrant human rights
abusers,'' and Russia, ``the most unstable great-power regime.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said earlier this month that
unpaid dues and bureaucratic delays have made it virtually
impossible for the United Nations to respond quickly to crises like
those in Kosovo and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an organization that must respond regularly to crisis,
this is a sure path to frustration, failure and irrelevance,'' he
told the General Assembly's budget and finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the United Nations agree that more reform of the
organization is needed, but they say the world body still performs
critically important tasks .
</P>
<P>
   Turner and the Better World Fund are by no means alone in their
fight. The United Nations Association runs model U.N. programs in
schools to teach students the value of the United Nations. With 175
local chapters around the country, the association tries to
persuade local citizens to lobby their congressmen on behalf of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that between 60 percent and 70 percent of American
people favor paying the back dues, said William Luers, chairman and
president of the organization. Luers is a former U.S. ambassador to
Czechoslovakia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Eisenhower, granddaughter of President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, heads the Emergency Coalition for U.S. Financial
Support of the United Nations, an organization that includes
several former U.S. secretaries of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is the leading country within the U.N.
system,'' Eisenhower said. ``And it seems to me that if you have
made a commitment to pay your dues to an organization, and you want
to remain involved and engaged in that organization, you ought to
pay what you owe. That's a rather conservative notion _ that great
nations pay their bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower said she sees a growing realization in Congress that
the nonpayment of dues is undermining the United States' standing
with countries that do pay, and undermining the nation's national
security interests.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino, too, thinks the chances of convincing Congress to pay
part of the debt this year are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's a shrinking place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
