<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. NO HOOP-MOVIE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Southern California, where mourning the last bite of a Krispy
Kreme donut qualifies as nostalgia, we are roaring toward a maudlin
crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Let's slam on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Our U-turn through hoop history begins at the Forum, which
despite the champagne stains is out of the pro basketball business.
Careening into even deeper obscurity is the Sports Arena, a doomed
venue that Ron Harper still may be able to sniff from Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   We also are a few days removed from the tepid poetry that
lurched behind the passing of Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   With such tardy tribute in mind, let's postpone the chatter of
rules changes and Charles Barkley's vast rear end, while honoring
two guys who prevented ``professional basketball in L.A.'' from
being defined by high school kids and sneaker pimps.
</P>
<P>
   Two guys who paved the diamond lane for Kareem, Magic, ``Big
Game'' James, Coop and Pooh (Hey, no list-crashing. Shame on you,
Pooh. Now get out of here).
</P>
<P>
   Two guys you should remember during your commute from the blood
bank to the ticket window at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor and Jerry West ... thanks to them, L.A. was spared
the dubious glory of becoming a ``basketball movie'' town.
</P>
<P>
   West, responsible for most of the hires you now see in those
cool Laker V-neck jerseys, has balanced on the edge of your memory
since retiring as one of the 10 greatest players in the history of
players.
</P>
<P>
   He was so great, that at least one young, impressionable
knucklehead (guilty!) practiced running face-first into walls to
acquire the nose West developed through years of catching elbows
with it.
</P>
<P>
   As the Laker GM, he snatched Kobe from the jaws of Charlotte,
N.C. He delivered Shaq. While working near the dead end of the
first round, he conjured Vlade, A.C. and Elden. He rescued Van Exel
in round two.
</P>
<P>
   West refers to such maneuvers as ``lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he ever unlucky? He'll swear he frequently is, but even Bill
Walsh required arm-twisting before the Niners drafted Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you weak enough to embrace everything you read and
hear, Baylor possibly the greatest forward in NBA history has
become the heavy bag for Clipper punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clipper museum has been built by the silly approach of
the team owner. Baylor's greatest sin as GM has been deferring
personnel moves to coaches who know less about the game than he
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to force a player on a guy who doesn't
want him,'' Baylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the last three drafts, he has assembled a young,
talented and exciting team that figures to be humbled by free
agency and the owner's definition of appropriate business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I root for Elgin,'' says West, who remains one of Baylor's
biggest fans and loyal pals. ``He's such a great person and he
deserves to have great success.''
</P>
<P>
   West also realizes his ex-teammate deserves credit for the
impact he's had on their sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an incredible player with a great flair for the game,''
says West, who uses the word `incredible' two more times in the
next three sentences. ``When I joined the Lakers, he made me feel
comfortable here. He was great to have on your side. He was a lot
of fun, but serious about competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Baylor's skills include inventing good-natured, spirited
and ultimately worthless debates by operating with nothing more
than the raw material from a harmless greeting of ``hello.''
</P>
<P>
   But West, who frequently swaps phone calls with his opposite
number at Planet Clipper, has been known to lob his own verbal
curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry once told me Tyronn Lue couldn't play at all,'' Baylor
says. ``Then someone asked me what Jerry was going to do (in the
1998 draft), and I told the guy he was going to draft Tyronn Lue.''
</P>
<P>
   West didn't; but he did acquire Lue in a trade the next day.
</P>
<P>
   With Maurice Taylor drop-stepping his way toward free agency and
the Laker roster threatening to become Valhalla for immortally
wounded Chicago Bulls, Baylor and West must be dialing the phone
quite a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The fiber optics involved pass more hoop knowledge back and
forth than a flock of college-coaching sharpies lurking at your
nearest Nike-sanctioned jamboree.
</P>
<P>
   The wiretap was made for moments like these. But if all you can
do is dial a radio station, inform the host you're serving ``mad
props'' or one love to Elgin Baylor and Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans of our sport tend to forget very quickly,'' West says.
``The past isn't remembered with the kind of passion you find for
baseball and football.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time we prove the man wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Worm hole still open?
</P>
<P>
   Laker coach Phil ``Zen Master P'' Jackson now admits that
re-hiring Dennis Rodman would provide swell rebounding karma for
his next playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   But without Michael Jordan around to hold the leash, adding
Rodman makes about as much sense as buying a pit bull to fetch your
slippers; oh, your slippers will arrive, but you may not be able to
pry them from the dog's jaws.
</P>
<P>
   We also should mention the Clippers' phone number was on speed
dial at the offices of Team Rodman. Clips owner Donald T. Sterling
reportedly was intrigued by the idea of signing the Worm to move
tickets and dilute the anti-Sterling headlines inspired by the Mo
Taylor issue.
</P>
<P>
   But superior hoop intellects reminded him that Rodman's people
only were interested in Clipper cap room (a bit of loose change
less than $10 million), and would seek most if not all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling might have been willing to make an exception for Rodman
but only of the $2 million variety.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   According to the league's big thinkers, the presence of Jason
Kidd made run-and-jump rookie Shawn Marion a perfect fit in
Phoenix. But without the generous-and-speedy Kidd on the floor,
Marion put 20 points on the Lakers Friday. ... Wow, ex-Clipper
Rodney Rogers looks like half the player he was last season, and
that's a good thing. Were the Clippers derelict in allowing him to
skip over to Phoenix? No! He had six years (two of those in Denver)
to demonstrate any consistency; and their three-spot's in great
shape with Lamar Odom and Ty Nesby. ... Once he gets healthy, look
for the Bulls to continue shopping Toni Kukoc. ... Laker rookie
Devean George has traveled light years beyond his audition as
gifted-but-tentative Division III prospect during the Summer Pro
League at the Pyramid. ``The difference now is that he realizes he
belongs out there,'' said West, who adds George to his ``lucky''
draft list. George had been on the scouting radar since the
pre-draft nobodies went to war in Portsmouth, Va. But West had the
nerve to choose him at 23 over bigger names such as Tim Jones of
Miami (Fla.) and Georgia's Jumaine Jones. ... Yao Ming, the
7-foot-6, 19-year-old tower of potential from China, reportedly
will compete at Pauley Pavilion next month on a Chinese national
team scheduled to play UCLA in an exhibition game. ...Four out of
four NBA scouts rate 6-5 shooting guard DeShawn Stevenson
(Washington Union High, Fresno U.S.A.) as the prep hotshot
best-equipped to make the ill-advised leap to the NBA. Stevenson
verbally committed to Kansas a few days ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
