<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE ROLLS PAST TCU WITH 35-POINT BURST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As members of Rice's fifth-ranked 1949 team watched
proudly, their 1999 counterparts seemed to offer convincing proof
yesterday that time has stood still for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Yawn. Another four-game winning streak over TCU. Happens every
50 years. What bowl shall we go to?
</P>
<P>
   But while that long-ago triumph was a memorable down-to-the-wire
battle, this one was memorable for the domination of the Owls (5-3,
4-0 Western Athletic Conference), who spotted the Frogs (3-4, 2-2)
a 14-point lead and then rolled to a 42-21 victory in front of
28,535 witnesses at Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the momentum changed and they started rolling, we just
couldn't stop them,'' said defensive end Aaron Schobel, who caused
a fumble that led to TCU's only points after the first quarter. ``I
don't know what changed ... it all happened so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Owls, who rolled up 424 yards, controlled the ball for
nearly 35 minutes, and even threw two touchdown passes, the victory
was their fifth in a row and left them with the inside rail
position in the WAC title chase.
</P>
<P>
   For the Frogs, said coach Dennis Franchione, ``This is not the
end-all game. We have to put this behind us and move on. But this
may be the best Rice team I've seen. It was a typical performance _
if you can't stop them, they control the tempo and get you out of
sync]. After that, it's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice coach Ken Hatfield said, ``As much as anything, when you
look back on it, that drive to start the third quarter was as big
as there was. We took the ball and went down and scored, and that
had a big impact on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a 14-14 battle, the Owls took the second-half kickoff
and executed a textbook wishbone march, 65 yards in 16 plays
requiring a leisurely seven minutes, 16 seconds. Quarterback Chad
Richardson, who finished the day with 163 yards on 28 carries,
converted a third-and-11 with a 17-yard sprint on the option, and
fullback Jamie Tyler plunged 1 yard for the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs ran three plays and punted, and the Owls were back
quickly, zipping 61 yards in 15 seconds. Leroy Tyler ran 22 on the
drive's first play, and Richardson finished it with a 39-yard pass
to Mike Gingrich, who was 20 yards past the TCU secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 28-14, the Frogs punched out to their 36, and then
Casey Printers tried to hit LaTarence Dunbar with a swing pass.
Rice linebacker Dan Dawson stepped in front of Dunbar, picked it
off, and traveled 30 yards to the end zone untouched with 3:32
remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against their offense, you hurt yourself when you give up a
score and then go three-and-out,'' Franchione said. ``But even when
they scored again, I felt we still had a decent chance. With our
offense, being 14 down wasn't that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the interception pretty much sealed it.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU got seven points back when Richardson fumbled after being
hit by Schobel, and Bird Jones ran it 19 yards into the end zone.
But the Owls countered with a 55-yard scoring run by Tyler in the
final period.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs opened the game smartly, rolling 80 yards on their
first possession, with national rushing leader LaDainian Tomlinson
(19 carries, 133 yards) slicing through huge gaps in the line and
Printers hitting two key passes and then scoring from the 4.
</P>
<P>
   A second score followed quickly, with Printers driving the Frogs
59 yards and hitting Mike Scarborough with a 5-yard fade for the
points with 3:54 remaining in the first period. But the Owls
recovered in the second quarter, with Richardson scoring once and
hitting Bradley with the tying score from 23 yards out. For the
Owls, it was the start of a 35-point run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were in pretty good shape after the first two
drives,'' Tomlinson said. ``We had things going our way. But after
that, we were mostly standing on the sidelines, watching them go up
and down the field. It was a frustrating day.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
