<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-B     10-23 2098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' START NOT SIMPLY NET RESULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-plus years into their recovery, the Bruins have regressed
like stumbling addicts, bumbling around the ice the way they did in
1996-97 when midseason came and all we had to look forward to
around here was the June draft and some wunderkind-in-waiting named
Joe Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   What ails the Bruins? Head coach Pat Burns came out last week
and pointed to the obvious: the absence of Byron Dafoe, the cutting
loose of Dmitri Khristich, the walkaway of Tim Taylor, and the
buyouts of Dave Ellett and Ken Baumgartner.
</P>
<P>
   Burns's point: Minus those five, the product had to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   I'll buy that, but only to a point. Come the end of the
playoffs, Ellett and Baumgartner were virtually, if not totally,
out of the picture. Khristich, no matter what he says, his agent
says, or the Maple Leafs say now that they own him, folded up the
show on or about April 18, the last game of the regular season.
Based on his postseason performance and sour attitude at the end,
his subtraction is an addition.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's loss is real. He played with intelligence, passion, and
grit. He was a team guy. Sure, the Bruins can find capable bodies
to plug in that hole, be it a Sean Pronger or a Mikko Eloranta or
the Baby Bruin du jour, but Taylor was a known, reliable,
productive part of the puzzle. He was taking a pain-killing shot,
sometimes two, before every game of the Buffalo playoff series.
What more do you want than a guy's pound of flesh?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Taylor exceeded Boston's pay expectations and signed
with the Rangers for about $1.5 million a year. Great for Taylor.
He literally gave up his body for that money. Few athletes can say
that today. Boston's mistake with Taylor was not realizing his
worth _ especially with Burns as coach _ upon his arrival here in
the fall of '97. It was the same mistake the Bruins had made with
the likes of Dave Poulin and Dave Reid. Had management been
proactive and identified Taylor as a worthy employee to lock up for
the future, it would have paid him a little more than market rate
soon after his arrival and tied him up with a four- or five-year
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dafoe thing has become an out-and-out mess. Both sides share
the fault in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe opted not to go to arbitration following two seasons with
great numbers. He was guaranteed at least the $3 million the Bruins
offered and might have rung the bell for substantially more.
</P>
<P>
   Had he and his agent, Ron Salcer, made a realistic assessment of
the negotiating landscape on Causeway Street, they quickly would
have realized Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell weren't going to
spring the Vault door open for them. Heck, it took Sinden nearly 20
years and some 1,300 games to get there with Ray Bourque. Dafoe has
two years and 133 regular-season games in that black-and-gold
sweater. In this town, that means he's barely shaved up his crease
for pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, Bourque entered the '90s making around $500,000,
and that was pretty good pay for the time; only three NHLers were
at $1 million or more. Bourque won his third Norris Trophy in '90,
too, and he already was guaranteed a spot in the Hall of Fame. Just
these few years later, Dafoe won't work for six times what Bourque
made in '90.
</P>
<P>
   Antiquated thinking? OK, to a degree, because there's a new-age
club, Anaheim, paying Paul Kariya $10 million a year. But this is
Boston, with old ownership and even older management, and to expect
anything different after all these years is to believe that the
moon is made of cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   When Dafoe came with hat in hand recently and said he'd work for
Boston's base, around $3 million a year, that was the time for the
front office to realize it's important to know how to win. It was
time to do the deal, with a slight massage here and a little cash
there. To pull away now from the guts of a deal that has been on
the table for months looks and feels punitive.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it's either sign Dafoe or trade him, but don't
stand brave on short money and the shaping of incentives. Bust his
chops? For what? Soon it will be Christmas and the faithful fan
base, ever willing to pay, might begin to ask questions for the
first time since Bobby Orr left. Such as: ``Hey, Sophie, think
maybe you'd rather have a week in the Bahamas instead of going to
the Bruins-Blackhawks game tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins would not have started this season 0-5-4 with Dafoe
in net and Taylor anchoring the checking line. My guess: more like
3-3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled into thinking, however, that 0-5-4 is all Dafoe
and Taylor. Hardly. Anyone noticed how poorly the Bruins move the
puck out of their end? For two decades, that has been Bourque's
job, and thus far he hasn't shown his trademark zip and timing with
the puck. Let it be duly noted, too, that at one point last week he
was averaging 29:56 minutes per game, second only to the Blues'
Chris Pronger (age 25) and nearly 90 seconds more than Rob Blake
(age 29). Bourque is 38, and you just knew the day had to come when
he'd look 30.
</P>
<P>
   Look, the Bruins will get beyond the Dafoe signing and the
Taylor hangover. Hard to believe now, but they are better than a
.222 team. And when they are better, the key reason won't be either
Dafoe's dough or Taylor's stand-in. The reason will be the play of
Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov, Anson Carter, and Thornton. That
was the truth seven weeks ago when training camp opened, and it
will be the truth three or four months from now. As those core
forwards go, so will go the Bruins. Right now, they're not going at
all, a huge concern that has been masked by hangovers, holdouts,
and business that has become all too usual on Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   Valuable addition
</P>
<P>
   Ellett, deemed too slow to help on the Boston back line, found
himself a job with the Blues last week, signing a one-year deal
worth $1.6 million. He'll help fill the void, especially on the
power play, while Al MacInnis recovers from a foot fracture. When
MacInnis went down, the most obvious names out there were Ulf
Samuelsson (signed last week by the Flyers) and Mark Tinordi (still
on the sideline). But St. Louis general manager Larry Pleau made it
clear from the outset that he wasn't going to shell out big money.
Pleau: ``We can't afford those kinds of contracts. We aren't going
to spend $2.5 million or $3 million on a guy _ we just aren't gonna
do it. Not only does it mean tying up that kind of money on a two-
or three-year deal, but when you do something like that, it means
some of your younger players get pushed further back in their
development. No one likes to lose a player like Al, but we all go
through it. As a matter of fact, we went through it last year when
Chris Pronger went down with a bad ankle. He was out for about a
month (15 games), and other guys just had to fill in.'' . . .
Adding to the Blues' injury woes: Ex-Bruin Geoff Courtnall again is
sidelined with a concussion. Doctors have prescribed a couple of
weeks of bed rest for Courtnall, who now may be facing retirement
at age 37. Courtnall: ``I don't know why this is happening to me;
maybe somebody is trying to send me a message.'' No matter what his
decision, he'll get the balance of the $7 million he has coming for
seasons 1999-2001 . . . The Flyers, off to the worst start in
franchise history (sound familiar?), committed $4.55 million to the
35-year-old Samuelsson through next season. Keep in mind:
Samuelsson and Flyers captain Eric Lindros have been hated enemies
since the '91 Canada Cup when Lindros, then only 18 years old,
separated one of Samuelsson's shoulders with a crunching check into
the boards. Could make for some interesting bus rides . . .
Ex-Bruins coach Don Cherry recently blamed the US college hockey
influence for all the hits around the net after the whistle. Now
there's a stretch. Seems to me the Flyers were perfecting that art
back in the '70s, when the NHL viewed US colleges as the feeding
ground for practice goalies. Tragically, the Canadian influence in
the NHL dies by the shift, but it's even more tragic when Cherry,
in defense of his flag, espouses his gobbledygook as gospel . . .
If the Bruins do get around to dealing Dafoe, one potential landing
spot is Vancouver, where Wrentham's Garth Snow is sidelined with a
broken finger. Question is: What do the Canucks realistically have
to offer? Three names that could come into the mix would be Markus
Naslund, Alex Mogilny, and Todd Bertuzzi, but none of the three,
individually, would approach Dafoe's value.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate returns
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins got a second-round draft pick for losing Khristich to
the Leafs last week, and sure, something is better than nothing.
Right now, though, the Bruins need a body _ maybe a few bodies _
and some unnamed 17-year-old in Thunder Bay doesn't do much to fix
today's ills. The early rumor out of Toronto had the Bruins picking
up Yanic Perreault in the exchange. But a half-dozen games into the
new season, Perreault was the league's No. 1 faceoff man (66.4
percent success rate) and was picking up a point per game for the
Leafs. So much for that swap. However, look for the Leafs to make
another deal or two. Perreault could be moved, but not until
superstar center Mats Sundin is back from a leg fracture (at least
three more weeks) . . . Note to the NFL: That replay thing you've
got going, with the referee conducting his own peep show on the
sidelines, is far too reminiscent of the NHL's replay fiasco of the
last couple of years. Drop it now before it becomes the Super Bowl
nightmare that the NHL encountered in last season's Stanley Cup
final . . . When the Lightning visit the Vault Thursday night, look
for Ben Clymer on their back line. Clymer couldn't come to contract
terms here in Boston (Chapter No. 23567411) after being drafted
27th overall in '97. A free agent, he signed a three-year deal
worth some $2.5 million with Tampa at the start of October.
Initially assigned to the minors, he got the call ahead of Belmont
Hill's Paul Mara, the No. 7 pick in '97, only a few days into the
new season when the Bolts needed to bolster the blue line . . .
Brian Sutter's deal in Calgary won't be renewed if the Flames miss
the playoffs for a fourth consecutive season. Given his club's
start (2-5-2 headed into Saturday night) Sutter might have more
immediate concerns than what happens in March and April. Grant Fuhr
hasn't provided anything close to the hoped-for boost in the Flames
cage, and the attack overall is lifeless . . . Rumors about an
imminent Felix Potvin deal last week had Islanders GM Mike Milbury
issuing a statement saying, ``I am not entertaining offers for
Felix Potvin. He's been our best player so far. It's been our
intention to keep him.'' Potvin is hot again, after slumping badly
upon being dealt to the Isles last season. If the Isles do get
around to dumping him, look for them to wheel him for a young
forward with low salary and high upside. They could net, say, $1
million or more in payroll, enhance the offense, and bring
phenom-in- waiting Roberto Luongo up from Lowell . . . Flyers boss
Ed Snyder also had to shoot down reports last week that head coach
Roger Neilson was about to get the heave-ho and that GM Bob Clarke
was next on the loading dock. Not true, bellowed Snyder. This much
is true: With the league's No. 2 payroll, the Flyers are going to
have to get it in gear soon, or virtually everything in Philly,
including sidewalk pretzels, could change. An ESPN report last week
had the Flyers feeling out at least one club (hello, Detroit?)
about its interest in acquiring L'Enfant Terrible . . . Word around
Raleigh is that the transplanted Hurricanes will open their new
building with a season-ticket base of only 6,000 _ about half what
the league demands of would-be expansion cities before awarding
franchises . . . Ex-University of New Hampshire star Jason Krog
will make at least $1.175 million with the Islanders. The two-year
pact he signed at the end of his college career called for a pair
of $512,500 signing bonuses and a minor-league minimum of $75,000
for each of two seasons. If he makes it to Uniondale, his pay will
be prorated at $512,500. Not a bad deal for a kid who, at age 18,
was considered too small for pro scouts to take at all seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
