</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HIT MORE TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   See, it happens everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As losses mount, players begin to point fingers at the coaches
and one another. It has happened in New England under Pete Carroll.
It is happening in Hempstead, N.Y., with Jets players questioning
Bill Parcells's play-calling. It happened earlier this season in
Denver to Mike Shanahan, when a few of his players went out to
dinner and stuck a fork in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Carroll has spent so much time telling his players
not to point fingers at one another and at the coaching staff. It
is why he objected to this reporter writing about ``rumblings'' in
the locker room after the Kansas City loss, when he was questioned
for using the valuable Troy Brown on kickoffs (Brown was hurt on
the opening return) and for not activating Vincent Brisby. The
three remaining receivers got fatigued running deep route after
deep route in the absence of Brown and Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   Though coaches hate it when fingers are pointed, it does show a
human side to otherwise robotic players. It shows they care about
what's going on. Venting anger can be good.
</P>
<P>
   It has been good for Denver. After the dinner with a Sports
Illustrated reporter at which some players said the team was done
for the season, the Broncos' level of play seems to have improved.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Oakland, the theory will be tested with the Jets, who
have had unrest this past week. Even a longtime Parcells ally, New
York Post columnist Steve Serby, splattered the coach across the
pages of the newspaper, saying he not only looked like former Jets
coach Rich Kotite but coached like him as well. Serby wrote, ``The
genius doesn't live here anymore. Parcells is 1-5 and he has no one
to blame but himself. He made his backup quarterback bed and now he
has to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   An unnamed defensive player, speaking to the Newark Star-Ledger
about some of the team's defensive problems, said, ``There are some
things you just don't do. But remember, we're dealing with a
genius.'' Another player on the defensive side said, ``If you let
him tell it, he's doing all he can.'' That player didn't seem to
like the fact that Parcells tends to blame the players and not
himself for the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was criticized by an offensive player for the fade pass
to Keyshawn Johnson that he called against the Colts last week
because ``that's a tough pass in the end zone'' for an
inexperienced quarterback such as Ray Lucas. The ball was picked
off by Jeff Burris and run back 55 yards to set up the winning
field goal. Parcells did take the blame for that, saying, ``I take
full responsibility for it. You try to do what you think is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was criticized by another unnamed player just for
throwing the ball that late in the game when the Jets had run it so
well. ``We had run the ball for something like 200 yards and then
he throws it,'' said the player. Wayne Chrebet said, ``Obviously if
something works from the 50 to the 3-yard line, maybe you should
continue to go with that.'' Some players even brought up Parcells's
decision to get rid of quarterback Glenn Foley earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The locker room became even more fractured when players learned
details of the Kevin Williams situation. Most players didn't know
that Williams, a young safety, was critically ill in the hospital;
they didn't know because Parcells didn't tell anyone. Then Parcells
put Williams on an injured reserve list that allowed him to be paid
half his 1999 salary, which players thought was cheap for a guy who
was on a ventilator after a lung infection.
</P>
<P>
   It goes to show that even when the great coaches lose, they lose
control of their teams.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan found out after his 0-4 start. He lost his Hall of Fame
quarterback, John Elway, to retirement, and his All-Pro runner,
Terrell Davis, to a season-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time we had adversity,'' said Shanahan during a
conference call last week. ``How do you react to it? Do we give in?
Or do we use injuries as excuses? How do you step up? I'm pleased
with how the team's responded.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Shanahan has handled the injuries and backbiting a
bit more successfully than Parcells. That's not to say Parcells
won't handle it well himself after everyone has had their say and
stuck all of their knives in his back.
</P>
<P>
   After reading the infamous SI article, Shanahan went after his
team:
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hey, if someone believes we're going to be 0-8 the
first half of the season, if you really believe that, I'll buy your
bus ticket, plane ticket _ just tell me and I'll let you go. I
don't care how much money we're giving you.' I said, `Just go. You
can go. Go. Go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's so hard to keep doing the right thing, the genius thing,
after you've won two Super Bowls like Shanahan and Parcells have.
Eventually you have to make hard, cold decisions that can be based
more on salary cap considerations than football. Shanahan made a
couple of big mistakes in the eyes of many players and fans: He cut
Steve Atwater and replaced popular quarterback Bubby Brister with
Brian Griese.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans don't like those types of slights, and for a while it
affected the team. The Patriots went through the same thing with
Willie Clay, and unfortunately for Carroll, the problem has
lingered because Chris Carter simply hasn't been as good as Clay.
You can argue that Ty Law's tentativeness early in the season was
due in part to the fact that he didn't have Clay around to bail him
out if he took a chance and missed. Ditto for Lawyer Milloy, the
biggest critic of the move.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches don't like cracks in their teams' armor. It's easier for
guys like Parcells and Shanahan, because they've proven they can
win championships and they'll always have jobs. But Carroll won't
get that benefit if things worsen. We've seen the Cleveland Indians
fire Mike Hargrove despite five straight division titles and two
World Series appearances. It could happen here, too. Bob Kraft
isn't shy about replacing coaches; he wasn't afraid to stand up to
Parcells, and he lost him. Look at his other pro franchise, the New
England Revolution, and you'll find a new coach on the sideline
every season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are at a crossroads this week: Win and avoid the
finger-pointing, or lose and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Chargers in charge
</P>
<P>
   It's San Diego. Way out on the other end of the world. In New
England, we don't pay much attention to the Chargers, but this year
there's reason to.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, with a rookie coach, Mike Riley, and a general
manager, Bobby Beathard, who many thought had flipped his lid for
hiring him, the Chargers start Sunday's games leading the AFC West
with a 4-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   Beathard, whose son had played at Southern Cal when Riley was
the offensive coordinator there, got a brainstorm. He figured Riley
would be the offensive mind that he needed for what traditionally
has been an offense-oriented franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But the team has developed quite differently than expected.
While the advent of Ryan Leaf seems to be well off in the future
given his maturity problems as a player and a person, the Chargers
have become a team noted for defense _ defense that revolves around
linebacker Junior Seau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Junior's team,'' said Riley. ``He sets the standard
for work and practice, everything we do. I just wish every young
football player in America could spend a day with him and watch
what he does to get ready for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all see the games and how he plays in the games. He's a
fabulous player. But you know, it's all the stuff he does before
the games actually arrive that really amazes me. It's been a great
example for all of us that are new here to see exactly what he
means to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau has been able to inspire people such as John Parrella and
Norman Hand, who are now playing out of their minds on defense. The
Chargers also have taken veterans such as Chris Penn and Darryll
Lewis off the scrap heap to keep the secondary in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Norman the game ball last week,'' said Riley. ``He and
John do all of the dirty work inside. They do their job quietly
without much fanfare or attention, but it enables some of our other
guys like Junior to make plays. We recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley really didn't know what to expect when he took over. He
didn't know the inner workings of the team, except that Seau was
the leader. He was asked immediately to handle Leaf, and he
definitely has put his foot down. At one point the Chargers weren't
going to keep Leaf on their roster. But Riley, who has experience
with quarterbacks, decided to make Leaf his project while Jim
Harbaugh and Erik Kramer led the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'm surprised with what's happened,'' said Riley.
``I had no real expectations of how it would be. We are, more than
ever in my life, going game to game, getting ready to play and
knowing it's going to be hard. We've never started out a game ahead
_ we're always coming from behind _ so I didn't expect that, and
really I don't know what to expect down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   A selling point?
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking: If building a new football stadium in Foxborough
continues to be a headache, do you think Kraft will just sell and
get into the bidding for the Red Sox? . . . With the success of Jon
Kitna in Seattle, Brad Johnson in Washington, and Kurt Warner in
St. Louis, teams are going to be competing to put quarterbacks on
NFL Europe rosters. The Chargers are considering it with Leaf. The
Patriots will likely do it with Michael Bishop. ``It was the best
thing I ever did,'' said Johnson. ``I didn't play very much in
college, and in my first three or four years, I didn't play much in
the league and I needed some experience. I always had great
practices, but there's nothing like game experience. It doesn't
guarantee that you're going to have success in the NFL if you go
over there, but at least you'll have that experience to draw on.''
Of course, Leaf, who has foresight the length of his nose, said,
``It's not an option. The No. 2 pick in the draft, you're playing
in the NFL, not the World League.'' . . . Did anyone else notice
that in last Sunday's Patriots-Dolphins game, there was an O.J.
(McDuffie) and a Kato (Serwanga) on the field at the same time? . .
. Wednesday was a sad day for Chrebet. While he chatted with
reporters, his cell phone rang, and when he answered it, his face
froze as he sat back in his chair. He learned that his football
coach at Garfield (N.J.) High School had committed suicide . . . In
Dallas, they call Deion Sanders the NFL's best cover corner. In New
England, it's Law. But according to Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren,
the best cover corner in the league is his own Shawn Springs. ``He
might be the best corner I've ever coached,'' said Holmgren. ``If
you go out and say, `You cover that guy all game,' he's the guy who
can do it.'' . . . Parcells told the New York media last week that
Scott Zolak would not be returning. There had been speculation
about Zo returning to the Jets after Ray Lucas sprained an ankle,
but the Jets are expecting Lucas to be ready by next week . . . New
England players, listen up. Instead of the same old sorry quotes,
this is what other players quite confident in themselves say about
the opposition: Redskins receiver Albert Connell on Sanders: ``I
don't think Deion can cover me. I mean, he's been in the league 10
years now. He's a good corner, an All-Pro, but I feel I'm at the
stage of my game where I can get by anybody.'' That's a refreshing
comment, unlike so many guys who say the same stuff week after week
and bore their fans to tears. Atlanta corner Ray Buchanan on
Pittsburgh's Kordell Stewart: ``He looks where he's throwing the
ball. I don't know what's going on with their offense, but it's
pretty easy to read.'' Outside of Milloy's unabashed way of dealing
with things on the field and in the media, the Patriots can be a
stuffy bunch . . . Here's a different perspective on the
much-maligned Patriots offensive line, as told to the Worcester
Telegram and Gazette by Terry Allen: ``This is the best offensive
line I've played with. We're just not getting the opportunity.
These guys! How many years have they had 1,000-yard rushers?'' Hard
to believe there are five teams that run the football worse than
the Patriots, but oddly, No. 31 San Diego is 4-1 and No. 30 Seattle
is 3-2. Rounding it out, No. 29 Arizona is 2-4, No. 28 Atlanta is
1-5, and No. 27 Green Bay is 3-2. The Patriots, at 26, are 4-2, and
the Dolphins, at 25, are 4-1 . . . Agent Jack Mills, who represents
Ted Johnson, said there is a realistic chance his client can return
to active duty before the end of the regular season. ``Teddy feels
he can make it back, but he thinks it would be more the end of
November rather than the beginning of it,'' said Mills . . . Mills
also represents former Heisman winner Rashaan Salaam, who was cut
by the Browns to make room when Karim Abdul-Jabbar was acquired at
the trading deadline. Mills is in New England this weekend, and you
can expect him to approach the Patriots about Salaam, given their
running woes.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down on film critic
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith got himself in a bit of hot water in Cincinnati when
he accused teammates of not studying enough film and doing their
homework. Coach Bruce Coslet said, ``Akili needs to take care of
Akili, and everybody else is taking care of themselves. So I don't
want to hear that kind of talk. I don't think there's any problem
with our effort.'' . . . Marcus Washington, a sixth-round pick of
the Patriots, was signed to the Seahawks' practice squad. He holds
the distinction of being the only draft pick in the Bobby Grier era
who didn't make either the team or the Patriots' practice squad . .
. Bruce Smith has sacked 59 different quarterbacks in his NFL
career, and he gets a shot at No. 60, Kitna . . . Joey Galloway has
lost $900,000 in his holdout, plus he has been fined $5,000 a day
by the Seahawks for being AWOL. Nice decision . . . Coach Jon
Gruden will tell you the reason the Raiders lead the league in
rushing is Jon Richie, the big fullback who does quite a job as
Tyrone Wheatley's lead blocker. Part of the reason the Patriots'
running game hasn't worked is that Chris Floyd can't stay healthy
enough to be on the field . . . There have been 21 games decided in
the final two minutes this season, and 35 decided by 3 points or
fewer. That's more than half the 3-points-or-fewer record (67 of
240 in 1997) . . . Also up this season is passing yardage. The
average is 419.5 yards per game, compared with 400 after six weeks
last season . . . By beating the Redskins, Troy Aikman would have
his 87th victory of the decade. He is currently tied with Joe
Montana (1980s) for the most wins in a decade . . . Warner has a
131.4 passer rating through five games, completing 71.43 percent of
his passes. If he keeps it up, he could better Kenny Anderson's
record 70.55 completion rate of 1982 . . . The Patriots are fifth
in the league in sack differential. They've sacked the quarterback
20 times, two behind league leader Jacksonville, and they have been
sacked 13 times . . . Tampa Bay's Warrick Dunn has been told to
stop looking to break the big play on every carry. Dunn has 17
carries for negative yardage so far because he's spending too much
time changing directions and trying to make something happen when
there's nothing there. ``Warrick can do whatever he wants out
there, but he's got to realize it's tough to run outside in this
league,'' said coach Tony Dungy. ``In his first two years, most of
his big runs came on inside runs, and I think on some of those
inside runs he's looking to bounce it outside too soon.'' . . . The
Cardinals have a bye this week and then will debut a revamped
offensive line against the Patriots. Rookie L.J. Shelton, who was
the 21st overall pick in the draft, is moving to left tackle,
replacing Matt Joyce; James Dexter, who had been the right tackle,
is moving to left guard, replacing Chris Dishman; center Aaron
Graham and right guard Lester Holmes will keep their jobs, but they
too could be on the outs . . . The Cardinals have decided to go the
Rams route and sign a quarterback from the Arena League: Sherdrick
Bonner, who played for the Arizona Rattlers and was playing
softball in four leagues in Phoenix when he got an audition last
Tuesday. Bonner, who completed 28 of 30 passes at the audition,
will back up Dave Brown, who will start against the Patriots next
week in place of Jake Plummer (fractured finger).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
