<SLUG> BC-ROW-HEADOFCHARLES-FATHERDAUGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RI FATHER AND DAUGHTER GO BACK TO BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When most youngsters finish the 3-mile Head of the Charles
Regatta, their parents cheer for them, help them lug the boats to
the car, and drive them home. But Eleni Goesch-Karamanlidis had a
slightly different welcoming committee Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dimitrius Karamanlidis cheered her on, and yes, he helped
her put the boat on top of their car. But they were not headed home
to Narragansett, R.I. The father and daughter will trade places
Sunday when Dimitrius, 51, rows in the grand master singles race,
and Eleni will be cheering on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Eleni, 14, is the youngest competitor this weekend, but she is
no newcomer to the sport. Or to the Charles. She rowed her first
Head of the Charles two years ago, but this was the first time the
family got to double-team the event.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday father saw daughter start at Magazine Beach, then got
in his car and tried to beat the traffic to meet her at the finish.
Traffic wasn't a problem for him, but the wind was for Eleni.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I just quit racing, it was so windy,'' said Eleni as
she fastened the scull to the roof of the car, then grabbed a bagel
to chew on as she put on her long pants and sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Eleni finished ``dead last'' in the field of 26,
and she wasn't hopeful that Saturday would be any better.
</P>
<P>
   But it was, as Eleni placed 24th out of 25 starters, with a time
of 28:05.06.
</P>
<P>
   The windy conditions offset her skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only one spot, on the second mile, that actually I
could row,'' she said. ``Otherwise I kind of went with it. I really
was trying, but I don't know, it seemed like I couldn't row and
flipped over a couple times. The wind just kept working against me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was waiting to go at the start, I probably was going
faster than when I would have been racing, going the other
direction. I couldn't even get my jacket off without almost falling
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleni (who usually goes without the hyphenated last name,
despite the program listing that ``the announcers messed up all
four times''), said she had some foreshadowing about the bad
weather on the drive up Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole ride up, the boats kept moving around, they almost
fell off,'' she said. ``But I didn't think it'd be so bad till I
got out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimitrius, an engineering professor at the University of Rhode
Island, rowed a little in his native Greece, but didn't start
competing seriously until he was in his 30s.
</P>
<P>
   When Eleni was 5 years old, she was small enough to squeeze in
and ride with him. When Eleni was 7, they went to a camp in Vermont
for private lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else is just sit in the boat and try to figure it
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They thought of joining a club but haven't because the closest
one is 35 miles away in Providence. Both Dimitrius and his wife,
Hilde Goesch, live at the college.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-8-inch Eleni, who is on the cross-country team at
Narragansett High, said she might put her running career on hold to
focus on rowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go to the Olympics, and think I'm better at rowing
than running if I pay attention to it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
