<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-MIAMIWIN-DAVIS-BO     10-23 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMIWIN-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK A MATTER OF FACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Miami coach Butch Davis prepared to analyze Saturday's
game, he sat down and sighed. He was not overcome by emotion,
knowing his No. 23 Hurricanes had just won their first game since
early September. He did not break down and cry, as he did after a
double-overtime victory at Alumni Stadium two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with a Southwestern accent cultivated during a boyhood
in Oklahoma, Davis spoke purposefully. He emphasized important
points with a slight drawl, letting the words ``miraculous'' and
``defense'' and ``composure'' and ``stop Boston College'' hang in
the air a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   From the coach's confident appearance, it was hard to remember
the Hurricanes trailed the Eagles by four touchdowns early in the
third quarter. Listening to Davis, it was hard to imagine that
Miami's dramatic 31-28 victory took anything more than careful
planning and better defense.
</P>
<P>
   He made it seem smart to go for it on fourth and 17 with the
score tied, 14 seconds left, and his quarterback injured. He
graciously praised Boston College as ``outstanding,'' sounding like
any victorious coach who thought he brought the better team and
gained validation by the final score.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his team were not cocky in their postgame remarks and
celebrations, but they did not betray any doubt in themselves or
their ability to win the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked at halftime that if we were going to get back in the
game, there were going to be three things that were going to have
to happen,'' said Davis, whose team trailed, 21-0, at intermission.
``Defensively, we were going to have to make a stand. We were going
to have to stop Boston College. I thought our defensive kids
responded. The second thing I told the players was we weren't going
to win it all in one play. We weren't going to get back in it in
one play. It was going to be a long process. It was going to be
possession after possession. The third thing we talked about was we
had to create a turnover.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami went right down the checklist. The defense made
adjustments, keeping BC scoreless after it took a 28-0 advantage
with 6:18 left in the third. The Miami offense stretched its rally
throughout the second half, capping its comeback with a 30-yard
Andy Crosland field goal with three seconds remaining. A crucial
turnover came midway through the fourth quarter. Cedric Washington
fumbled and Miami's William Joseph recovered. One play later the
Hurricanes had cut the Eagles' lead to one touchdown, 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   As Miami drew closer in the second half, the visitors' sideline
came alive. Junior wide receiver Michael Stewart of Cranston, R.I.,
waved a towel in the air and flapped his arms, cheering on his
teammates. Junior linebacker Nate Webster kept muttering under his
breath, ``Comeback, comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored 21 points in a half, so we felt we could score 21
points in a half,'' said tight end Daniel Franks, who caught a
10-yard pass from Kenny Kelly to tie the game at 28. ``I think when
they came out and jumped on us, 28-0, that may have taken a little
out of us, but we never stopped fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back and we scored, that built our confidence
back up going into the next series. I think (BC) lost a little bit
of emotion on that and we just kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   After Miami scored its second touchdown, the team's attitude had
changed. At that point, the Hurricanes knew they had caught the
Eagles off guard with their two-minute offense. The second
touchdown came so easily after a 32-yard pass from Kelly to James
Jackson that the offense told the defense all it needed to do was
hold the opposition to four touchdowns. If the defense could keep
Miami at 28 points, the offense believed it could win the game.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous first half, the defense was more than happy
to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in the locker room and said, `We've got a whole other
half,' '' said linebacker Dan Morgan. ``With the offense that we
have, we knew that if we got them the ball, sooner or later they'd
start clicking. They did. We got them the ball. We did everything
we wanted to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BCLOSS-PEDROCIRIN     10-23 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCLOSS-PEDROCIRINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRINO NOT HAPPY WITH DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Cirino entered the interview room Saturday looking
downright hostile, bitter that Boston College blew a 28-0
second-half lead and lost to Miami, 31-28.
</P>
<P>
   The senior defensive back and cocaptain boldly, and angrily,
declared that the Eagles have endured such a letdown for the last
time.
</P>
<P>
   Never again, he said, will BC watch an opponent score four
unanswered touchdowns, then allow a limping quarterback to convert
a fourth-and-17 play to set up a winning field goal. Never again
will the Eagles fail to put away a heralded adversary. Never again
will they walk away that embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Saturday's loss was the worst he's ever experienced,
Cirino fired back, ``What do you think? We were up, 28-0. Without
question it was a chance for us to make a statement in this
program, make a statement throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on national TV. We have a lead like that and give up.
It's unexcusable. It's unexcusable when you're trying to develop a
program. It's something we should never let happen and something
that's never going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino tied for second in tackles among the Eagles with six. He
was part of a defense that held the Hurricanes to just four first
downs and 101 yards total offense in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   He was also there when Miami spent the last 17:11 outexecuting
the Eagles at practically every phase of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when the contest got away, Cirino said, ``It's hard to
pinpoint. We just came out in the second half and didn't play well
at all. We didn't do a good job of executing our plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk in the second half. Period. We had a 21-0 lead; we
came out and . . . the offense came out and scored a touchdown and
put us up by 28. It's unexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss left the Eagles 5-2, still one win away from bowl
consideration, and the rest of the schedule (at Syracuse, West
Virginia, at Notre Dame, at Virginia Tech) is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Cirino, ``I can't wait for next week. It will be a gut
check for this team how we respond.'' And he disputed coach Tom
O'Brien's claim that the Eagles wore down in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst moment came with 14 seconds left, when Miami
faced that fourth-and-17 from the BC 35.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kenny Kelly, battling a sprained left ankle
sustained moments before, completed a 22-yard pass to wide-open
receiver Reggie Wayne, who got his feet down after leaning to make
the catch. Andy Crosland kicked a 30-yard field goal on the next
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going for the (first-down marker),'' said
Cirino of the reception. ``I knew, and I tried to relay that to the
rest of the defensive backs. I knew they were going to try to put
themselves in position for a field goal. We just didn't execute.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory would have been BC's first over a ranked team since
a triumph over then-No. 24 West Virginia two years ago, in
O'Brien's first home game. Instead the Eagles were left to discuss
what could have been _ and what won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cirino, ``For us to give up as big a lead as we had,
regardless of who it is . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who it is. We're just as good as Miami if we
showed up today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
