<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-HEADOFCHARLES-TETI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
87 GOLD RC SET THE STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE _ Friday night and Mike Teti was calling from his car
phone, en route to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 9,000 things to do this weekend,'' the US men's rowing
team coach was saying.
</P>
<P>
   That night, it was a National Rowing Foundation fund-raising
meeting in Mystic _ then back here straightaway. ``I have to row
with my buddies tomorrow morning,'' said Teti _ and against his own
crew Sunday afternoon in the Head of the Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Teti may direct the planet's best eight, but he has a higher
calling Sunday. He's rowing bow for the 87 Gold Rowing Club, also
known as the US boat that surprisingly won a gold medal at the 1987
World Regatta.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't so long ago that Teti and his buddies are old enough
to row in the masters race. But it was long enough that 87 Gold has
no fantasies of blowing away the field in the championship event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not delusional,'' said Teti, who at 43 is the ranking
elder of the eight. ``We're not going to beat our national boat.
We're not going to beat the Germans or the Brits. We're not going
to beat Princeton or Harvard. If we get in the top 20 (of 49),
that'll be a good result. For us, the important thing is just
getting back together.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1987 crew had its 10th reunion here two years ago. Since all
but one also rowed in the 1988 Olympic eights at Seoul, they had
another 10th reunion last autumn. So why not again this year? All
but Teti, Mike Still, and John Pescatore live in the Boston area
and all of them are still in racing shape. Relatively, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how when you get older, what you perceive as being
in shape changes from when you were really in shape,'' Teti mused.
``The guys told me they row twice a week. I said, `So rowing twice
a week gets you in shape?' It used to be that rowing twice a day
got you in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, twice a week was enough for 87 Gold to beat a bunch of
college varsities last year, enough to find the swing again and
reclaim a taste of the magic from a dozen summers past.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a special boat,'' Teti said. ``No stars, but it had
this chemistry, like the US boats the last few years. Anytime we
did anything on the clock it was pretty quick. But if you'd asked
me when I got off the plane in Copenhagen if we'd win, I would have
said probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   The US hadn't won the gold medal in 13 years, most of the boat
was college kids, and their heat was brutal _ the West and East
Germans, the Soviets, and the Australians. Save your energy for the
repechage (second-chance race), coach Kris Korzeniowski told them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But midway through the race, we went through the field,'' Teti
recalled. ``We not only won the heat, we set a world record. I
thought, maybe we can win this thing. The final was actually easy _
we won by open water.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Still, the entire boat came back for the Olympics,
which the US hadn't (and still hasn't) won since 1964. Teti and his
mates led midway, but the West Germans rowed through them. Then the
Soviets caught them by a quarter of a second at the finish and
silver turned to bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we were a bit disappointed,'' said Teti. ``But about
40 seconds later I thought, well, it's an Olympic medal. I'm pretty
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans haven't won one since. They didn't win another
world title until 1994. Now, with Teti coaching, they've won three
in a row and are the chalk favorite to break their 36-year golden
drought in Sydney next year. They're also odds-on to win the
championship eights for a record fifth straight time.
</P>
<P>
   Teti took a few spins with his 99 Gold guys in practice at
Princeton last week because 7-man Garrett Miller was hurt and
replacement Sebastian Bea was still in class at Cal-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to row with the good guys for a few days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, though, Teti was back working out with the
87s, with Still and Pescatore, John Smith and Ted Patton, Pete
Nordell and Doug Burden, Mike Porterfield (subbing for fellow
Northeastern immortal Jeff McLaughlin) and cox Seth Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   For luck, they were using the same Vespoli shell that the 1997
boat rowed to win its world crown. Maybe it could restore them a
decade's youth by osmosis. The 87s still work out regularly and
most are near their Olympian weights (Teti still checks in around
185). They can still make a boat move _ just not as fast for as
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out and do steady-state, it feels the same,'' Teti
said. ``But once we go to pressure, it's not the same.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't ever be the same as it was in Copenhagen, but that's
not why the 87 Gold RC is taking to the river Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we crossed the line in 1987, that eight never rowed
again,'' Teti said. ``We just want to be back out there together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
