<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-HEADOFCHARLES-KOVEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOVEN MEETS THE ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leading the elite fleet of single scullers at the Head of the
Charles Sunday is hometown rower Jamie Koven, the 24-year-old who
will be defending his title.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, Koven will be chased by a group of
international rowers here by invitation to form a Championship
Singles division, a first for this event.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the world's top scullers will be hot on Koven's stern,
and the 6-foot-4-inch, 210-pounder welcomes the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' says Koven, a native of Green Village,
N.J., now working in Boston as a financial analyst. ``It would be
amazing if the US could have a high-caliber, elite-level race.''
</P>
<P>
   With such rowers as Luka Spik from Slovenia, Juri Jaanson from
Estonia, Andris Reinholds from Latvia, and Merlin Vervoorn from the
Netherlands, this year's Head of the Charles is taking a big step
in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lineup in Women's Championship Singles will compete
this weekend by invitation.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Koven's eighth Head of the Charles, a race he first
rowed as a freshman at Brown in 1991. He sees rowing headed in the
direction of professional events, especially outside the US where a
circuit of sprint regattas keeps most rowers at the sport
year-round, especially in this pre-Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is not as important as World Cup,'' said Koven, who
nevertheless enjoys the size and scope of the Boston event, which
has seen steady growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mix at the Head of the Charles is great. Everyone has a
life outside of rowing, and I would not like to see that change.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Koven, the kind of elite competition on the sprint
race circuits is bound to make an impact on the Head of the
Charles. And it will make his race much tougher than in other
years.
</P>
<P>
   Koven won the US National team trials in singles, as he did last
year. After finishing fifth as part of the eight in the 1996
Olympics in Atlanta, he switched to the single scull and promptly
won the gold medal at the 1997 FISA World Championships. That year,
he also won a bronze at a World Cup event in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Koven became the first US rower in 31 years to win the singles
Worlds and was named US Rowing Male Athlete of the Year. In
September of the same year, he won the Athlete of the Month award
from the US Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Koven's winning ways began at Brown, where, with just two losses
in his four years, he led the university to its first national
collegiate title of any kind in the school's 229-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Koven finished eighth in the singles at the FISA
World Championships, eighth at a World Cup event in Lucerne,
Switzerland, and first in the Diamond Single Sculls at the Henley
Royal Regatta.
</P>
<P>
   Rowing, while slowly gaining visibility in this country, still
finds itself behind running.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more community rowing,'' said Koven, ``but more people
relate to running. But rowing has a harder time selling itself to
the mainstream media than running. You need to have water and a
boat. Those things make rowing seem harder to get into.''
</P>
<P>
   And for elite-level rowers to throw themselves into the sport
full-time, they need sponsors. Koven, who will spend time at the
Princeton Olympic Training Center, has a number of sponsors _
Princeton Financial Systems, Crowley Maritime Corporation, and
Knickerbocker Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the sport is accessible to one level for
some, but I'd like to see it for all,'' he said. ``Only the rich
can participate. There were some rowers who couldn't get here from
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Koven and most of the rowers recognize that this year's
Championship Singles division is only the first step in the
direction of elite competition at the Head of the Charles. As the
event grows, said event chairman Fred Schoch, the big names will
inevitably be drawn to the Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in event sponsorship also reflect the changing times.
Longtime major sponsor BankBoston has ``run the course,'' said
Schoch, and as of last winter the Head of the Charles was looking
for a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared out of my wits in January,'' said Schoch. ``But
it came together. The event has gained recognition as a real
attraction in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and Polo Sport have signed on as major sponsors, as have
Xerox and Dunkin Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   Top rowers such as Koven like both the growing elite class in
the event and the wide-open club aspect, which gives the Head of
the Charles _ and rowing generally _ its greatest recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Head of the Charles is slow to grasp the professional
aspect of it,'' said Koven. ``It's such a big event that it changes
slowly. But it is much more competitive now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
