<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' HORRY HARRIED BY INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ One glance at the stats sheet, or a single
play this exhibition season, and it's clear something's wrong with
Robert Horry's game.
</P>
<P>
   A tough transition to the triangle offense? No, worse. Horry
said his troublesome knees feel worse than ever, and nothing seems
to help.
</P>
<P>
   Horry is just 4 of 15 from the field in 50 minutes of playing
time and has generally looked out of sorts the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the offense, I know where to go.... It's just that my
body is not allowing me to do the things I want to do,'' Horry said
before Friday's game against Phoenix. He then went out and played
barely a minute before heading to the locker room because of pain
in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Horry is day-to-day. By his own account, his status
sounds more uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Horry has long suffered from tendinitis in his right knee and
has developed the same condition in his left. But the 29-year-old
veteran said the problem has grown worse, and he's not sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew,'' he said. ``They (team trainers) just say my
legs are weak. I do everything to keep them strong, but it's not
helping. Both of them now. It used to be just one.''
</P>
<P>
   Without any lift in his legs, Horry's shots are falling short.
And the pain is the worst it has ever been, he said. The knees only
sometimes respond to daily treatment. ``Some days they do, and some
days they don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly bad news for the Lakers, who not only are
thin at power forward already, but need struggling veterans Horry
and Rick Fox to provide some punch and leadership in their second
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers probably will begin the season with 36-year-old A.C.
Green in the starting lineup, backed up by Horry and perhaps
35-year-old John Salley. Travis Knight is recovering from a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson tried to give Horry a jumpstart Thursday by
putting him in the starting lineup. Horry said he's better off
starting because his muscles are loose from pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Ty's time: Tyronn Lue, the Lakers' speediest player but also
their shortest at 6-feet even, scored his first five points of the
exhibition season Friday night. But the second-year guard hasn't
played more than seven or eight minutes in any game yet.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who prefers taller guards, said Lue still can find a
place in his game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he showed last night what he can do for the team _
just, boom, get out and start generating energy on the floor,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lue, who became a crowd favorite late last season, hopes to
overcome his size deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait like I did last year and when my chance
comes, I'll be ready,'' he said. ``I know what I can do, and I know
I can play in this league, so I'm going to stay confident in
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster movement: All of the Lakers' healthy players will see
action as they play three games in three days, starting today in
Bakersfield. Jackson then plans to reduce the roster before the
exhibition finale, Thursday in Anaheim against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers thin at power forward, Jackson also said there
is ``a possibility'' he will look to sign a free agent once other
teams make cuts and indicated he had a player in mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
