<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, MIRACLE IS MIAMI'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do miracles never cease?
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Doug Flutie engineered the Miracle in Miami
when he completed a 48-yard Hail Mary touchdown pass to Gerard
Phelan that put Chestnut Hill on the map, sent Boston College's
football team soaring into the Cotton Bowl, and made a Heisman
Trophy winner of the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the No. 23 Miami Hurricanes snapped a three-game
losing streak and eased the bitter memory of that stinging setback
by fashioning a miraculous comeback of their own. Trailing, 28-0,
Miami pinned the Eagles with their worst loss of the season by
rallying for 31 unanswered points in the final 17:11 to score a
31-28 triumph on Andy Crosland's 30-yard field goal with three
seconds left before an ashen-faced Alumni Stadium crowd of 44,058.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Charge of Chestnut Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Bewitching at BC.
</P>
<P>
   Call it what you will.
</P>
<P>
   Senior free safety Pedro Cirino knew what to call the debacle:
``Unexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles appeared destined for their sixth victory of the
season, a possible bowl berth, and perhaps even their first
appearance in the Top 25 after an impressive first-half showing
against a ranked opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, the Eagles were not prepared to go the distance
against the Hurricanes. John Matich missed a 33-yard field goal
attempt wide, Cedric Washington fumbled inside the BC 10, and BC's
backpedaling defense allowed Miami quarterback Kenny Kelly to
convert a fourth-and-17 play with a 22-yard pass to Reggie Wayne
that set up Crosland's winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who hobbled the final six plays on a severely sprained
left ankle, completed 20 of 36 passes for 218 yards and three
touchdowns to lead the Hurricanes to scores on five of their last
six possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is about coming to Boston that makes for
these kind of games,'' said Miami coach Butch Davis, who was
reduced to tears in his last visit to Chestnut Hill two years ago
when the Hurricanes snapped a four-game losing streak by pulling
out a 47-45 victory in double overtime. ``Last time, a double
overtime, and today some kind of miraculous effort by our kids in
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, it was apparent the Hurricanes were going to need
some kind of miracle when the Eagles scored on three of their first
four possessions, including the first two, to surge to a 21-0 lead
at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I thought we gave a great effort today,'' said BC coach
Tom O'Brien, whose team (5-2 overall, 2-2 Big East) must pick up
the pieces before traveling to Syracuse next week. ``When you play
a Top 20 team like that, you can't fumble the ball away like we did
there in the second half. We can't miss a field goal. You have to
give them credit. They took advantage of those opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck, who completed 18 of 35 passes
for 139 yards, gave BC a 7-0 lead when he found tight end Bryan
Arndt from 17 yards out. Then, after BC's defense shut down the
Hurricanes on their second possession, William Green capped a
14-play, 88-yard drive _ sustained by a Miami roughing-the-kicker
penalty on Matich's 44-yard field goal _ with a 2-yard burst that
made it 14-0 with 3:47 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Rowe made it 21-0 when he scored on an 8-yard run up the
middle that capped a five-play, 48-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got behind so much because of poor play, but they played
exceptionally well,'' Davis said. ``They played outstanding. Their
kids made plays. They blocked. They caught the ball. They were
giving us fits on defense. It took a while to try and regain our
composure and find the things we felt would give us a chance to get
back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Davis preached three things to his team: Make a
stand on defense. Don't try to win it all on one play. Create a
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hurricanes emerged from their locker room, they were
stunned to discover that the Eagles had not. Clearly, it was not
the same BC team that had smacked the Hurricanes in the mouth in
the first half. That was evident when Miami answered Washington's
3-yard TD with a 12-play, 79-yard drive capped by Kelly's 12-yard
TD pass to fullback Will McPartland.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles went three and out on their next possession, a
sense of dread seemed to grip the crowd. After Matich missed the
33-yard attempt with 11:29 to go, momentum quickly shifted to
Miami's side when a simple Kelly screen pass turned into a 32-yard
touchdown by James Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who led all rushers with a career-high 183 yards on
29 carries, then fumbled on the next play. One play later,
Jackson's 6-yard TD pulled Miami within 28-21. BC's offense
sputtered, and Miami scored on its third consecutive possession
when Kelly found tight end Daniel Franks with a tying 10-yard TD
with 3:51 to go.
</P>
<P>
   When Hasselbeck threw three consecutive incompletions, Miami
took over at its 47 with 3:16 to go. It was plenty of time for a
miracle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
