<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DENVERADV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER BOOT WOULD BRAKE SPECULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The topic never goes away completely. When the
Patriots are winning, it is dormant, like a hibernating bear. But
once the losses start, it awakens.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the topic is still groggy, half-asleep. There's a yawn
here and a stretch there, but for the most part it's not rousing.
</P>
<P>
   The topic is Pete Carroll's future, of course.
</P>
<P>
   When the team was 4-0, there was little mention of the job
Carroll was doing, no need to discuss his employment status, a
topic that was revisited over and over last season by talk shows
and columnists.
</P>
<P>
   Things were exacerbated after the first-round playoff loss to
Jacksonville, when Bobby Grier said he would conduct an evaluation
of the entire operation, including Carroll. The coach survived the
evaluation, which included input from some veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Carroll began asserting himself. Though
there were people to answer to _ Grier, Andy Wasynczuk, and Bob and
Jonathan Kraft _ he took a strong stand on player personnel and the
workout program. He made changes in training camp, making it
tougher, with more days in full pads, more running, more studying.
The result was terrific: a 4-0 start, with fewer of the injuries
that killed the team a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what. A funny thing happened on the way to 16-0. The
Patriots have lost two straight games, by a total of 3 points _ one
on a missed field goal in the hostile environment of Arrowhead
Stadium in Kansas City, the other when the Dolphins were able to
drive 59 yards in the final 2:10 to score the go-ahead touchdown
while leaving only 23 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was stirring.
</P>
<P>
   Was the topic about to awaken from its long offseason nap?
</P>
<P>
   We heard the front office was displeased after the Miami loss.
The talk show callers were again complaining about the coaching,
ripping the offense for being able to score only one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of the ``typical'' Carroll October/November swoon
resurfaced, though it was somewhat lost in the Red Sox fever that
overtook the area.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``crossroads'' was used a lot this past week. And with
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots don't beat the Broncos Sunday, they will be on a
road well-traveled in the Carroll era: the one that leads them
close to .500 when the leaves begin to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   It's the vaunted midseason dip, which is usually followed by the
late-season surge, which is usually followed by the early exit from
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a win could take them to a road less
traveled, toward a consistent season like the one they had in 1996,
up a mountain and all the way to a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is no different from the other 30 NFL coaches; they will
tell you that all of the games are important; they claim it's the
media or the fans who place certain importance on one game over
another. But Sunday's game in Foxborough _ whether Carroll accepts
it or not _ is one that could keep the whispers about his future
sleeping soundly.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are not the ``world champion'' Denver Broncos as we
once knew them, they're still a team to be concerned about. They
have straightened out their earlier problems, and they seem to be
clicking with Brian Griese plugged in for John Elway and Olindas
Gary plugged in for Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, you see, still have other players who led them to
Super Bowl victories the past two seasons. They still have a tough
defense. Those who thought the Broncos' season was over following a
Sports Illustrated dinner invitation in which a player or two said
they were done after an 0-4 start have decided they are alive after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sunday's game will be difficult. Not as difficult as
originally thought when the schedule came out, but not as easy as
when the Broncos were 0-4 and in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been unable to finish things off the last two
weeks. The practice week was devoted to this. Finishing off an
opponent can be a daunting task for a team that runs the ball at a
2.9-yards-per-carry clip and must rely on Drew Bledsoe not only for
its big plays but for third-down conversions and short-yardage
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches also will tell you they take the schedule one game at a
time. In this case it is wise to do so, but glancing slightly
ahead, the Patriots have a Halloween date in Arizona, where the
Cardinal offense is in shambles because Jake Plummer is out with a
fractured finger and the running game is one of the worst in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll knows the mental fragility of the NFL player. He knows
how quickly the tide can turn, one day riding the wave, the next
day fighting to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll must figure out what ails the offense against a tough
Denver defense; he must find a running game that is at least
respectable and can create balance. He must have Bledsoe hitting
his deep receivers. He must have Ben Coates as a centerpiece of the
offense. He must create a defense that will confuse even the poised
Griese, and he must create an environment in which Ty Law can make
plays as he did a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   He must create a scenario in which the sometimes sullen
Foxborough crowd will jump out of its skin and holler so loudly
that the Denver offense can't hear a thing.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m. we will know a little more about whether the topic
will rise again or whether it will rest in peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
