<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT BUSH SAYS SEEING STARVING KIDS ON TV PROMPTED HIS
SENDING TROOPS TO SOMALIA  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION _ Former President Bush conceded Saturday that
he ordered U.S. troops into Somalia in 1992 after seeing
heart-rending pictures of starving waifs on television, but he said
American leaders must be ``very wary'' when tempted to employ
military might to ease human suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that as he and his wife, Barbara, watched television
at the White House and saw ``those starving kids in quest of a
little pitiful cup of rice,'' he phoned Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney and Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please come over to the White House,'' Bush recalled telling
the military leaders. ``I _ we _ can't watch this anymore. You've
got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   They settled on a contingent of 28,000 U.S. forces that helped
open supply lines into war-torn Somalia and especially into
Mogadishu, its capital. ``And we ended the starvation,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Such humanitarian operations have ``less to do with vital
national security interests'' and are ``being understandably
debated today,'' Bush told a conference on U.S. military
interventions at Texas A&AMP;M University. The session was sponsored by
the Washington-based Center for the Study of the Presidency and two
A&AMP;M units, the George Bush School of Government and Public Studies
and the Center for Presidential Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The former president described his first two uses of U.S. force
abroad _ in 1989 to oust Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega and in
1990-91 to drive the forces of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein from
Kuwait _ as straightforward defenses of U.S. security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In Somalia, Bush said, ``our mission was different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was use of force,'' he said, ``And it's one that I think a
president has to be very wary of, because of the precedent. We
cannot be the world's policeman. We cannot put force in place every
time a president or Congress sees a terrible tragedy of genocide,
of starvation, whatever it might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This use of force in Somalia was the exception that proved the
rule that force should be used when our vital national interests
are at stake,'' Bush said. ``To be fair, I put saving American
lives in the vital category but not the humanitarian gesture. Maybe
it's kind of illogical, but that's at least the way I interpret
these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many places where national disasters strike and
tribal warfare comes out. They all want help, they all need help,
but we cannot always use force.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful of the presidential campaign being conducted by
his son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the former president steered
clear of most of the political implications of interventions and
did not criticize any military involvements under his successor,
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush limited his comments on U.S. involvement in Somalia to the
period during his presidency. Less than a year after Bush was
defeated by Clinton, the U.S. force in Somalia had been reduced and
made part of a U.N. operation aimed more at nation-building than
humanitarian relief.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 3, 1993, a firefight with a local militia faction
resulted in the deaths of 18 U.S. servicemen and the body of a dead
U.S. soldier was dragged through the streets of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
