<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-NFL-ARENA-AZR &LR;      10-23 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA LEAGUE GAINING RESPECT AROUND NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is two weeks ago in St. Louis, and 65,872 fans are
screaming inside the Trans World Dome for quarterback Kurt Warner,
who is picking apart the San Francisco 49ers as if they're the San
Jose SaberCats.
</P>
<P>
   Warner throws for 177 yards and three touchdowns _ in the first
quarter alone. He finishes with 20 completions in just 23 attempts,
323 yards and five touchdowns in a laugher, making the Rams, once
the joke of the NFL, the only unbeaten team left.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, in Indianapolis, Miami Dolphins wide receiver
Oronde Gadsden makes four catches for 132 yards, including a
48-yard reception that set up his game-winning touchdown grab, one
he makes by outleaping a Colts defender in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   From Des Moines to Portland, from Orlando to Albany, from
Phoenix to Nashville, Arena Football League coaches, executives,
players and fans are cheering these rising NFL stars that they
still call their own. They are giving thanks to Warner and Gadsden
for bringing long-due credibility to a 13-year-old, eight-man game
that once was considered a circus ring, a joke, to the purest of
football purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Kurt is on an undefeated Rams team and doing great, it
just gives (the Arena league) a great boost,'' said former Rattlers
quarterback Sherdrick Bonner, whose ego received another boost this
week after the Cardinals signed him as their third quarterback.
``There was some talk last year after I got signed (by the Atlanta
Falcons as a practice player). But nobody made a huge splash,
except for maybe Oronde Gadsden. Now, you hear scouts saying,
`We've been looking in the wrong places.'
</P>
<P>
   ``These (Arena) guys have game experience on a pro level. You
can't take that away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Gadsden went from hotel to lavish apartment living,
from being rookie of the year in the Arena league with the Portland
Forest Dragons to one of the NFL's top rookies by averaging 14.9
yards a catch and tying O.J. McDuffie for the Dolphins' lead with
seven touchdown receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, Warner was fielding questions such as ``how
many players are there on each side in an Arena game?'' Now some
are asking if he could be the NFL player of the year. He could if
he continues this pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is a lot of people ask me what it feels like
to be in the NFL playing, but it is all about playing football,''
Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   But, until now, the chasm in talent between the NFL and the
Arena league, skeptics said, was wide and deep. The Arena league
was supposed to be the black hole of pro football, a place where
NFL rejects wind up, never again reaching NFL peaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known,'' said Rattlers Coach Danny White, a former
Dallas Cowboys quarterback who quickly was convinced the Arena
league was worthy by the speed and quickness and toughness it took
to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who used a summer of seasoning in NFL Europe, playing
quarterback for the Amsterdam Admirals after three years with the
Iowa Barnstormers, only got the chance because of Trent Green's
untimely misfortune. Warner was elevated to starter in preseason
after Green suffered a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Vermeil said he thought his team could win with
Warner, but not because of Warner, who has thrown for 15 touchdowns
and 1,328 yards in leading the Rams to a 5-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Warner has been intercepted three times, has
completed 71.4 percent of his passes and has a 131.4 passer rating.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil and others credit Warner's success to his Arena
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all attribute the qualities Warner has displayed _ the
ability to throw on the move, throw to a tight place and throw with
accuracy and a lot of flair _ to his having played in the AFL,''
former NFL head coach and CNN/SI.com columnist Ron Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   After ripping apart the 49ers, Chris Berman gave this
wise-cracking advice on ESPN's Prime Time: ``Everybody coming out
of college, play in Arena Football, then you'll be good.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent ``Sports Illustrated'' issue has Warner on the cover
with the question: Who is this guy? &QL; 
More visibility &QL; 
How visible has the 50-yard indoor war become around the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Buccaneers quarterback Trent Dilfer was spotted
recently inside the locker room wearing an Arena Bowl XIII cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Dilfer said. ``Kurt's been great. I think there's
a lot of people (in the Arena league) playing well and they've just
got to be discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Warner to remind people that years ago quarterback Paul
Justin went from the Rattlers, where, in 1993, he led them to the
Arena league semifinals with a broken wrist, to the Indianapolis
Colts, where, at times, he filled in as a starter, without Warner's
off-the-charts success.
</P>
<P>
   Now Justin is Warner's backup in St. Louis, and four Iowa
newspapers are sending reporters to cover Warner's games, making
the pride of Cedar Falls front-page news for three weeks at the
``Des Moines'' ``Register,'' the Iowa media following him around as
if he's a Heisman Trophy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the (Arena) league says, `We can't pay Kurt enough
money for what he's doing,' '' said Barnstormers media relations
director Dick McDonald, who receives about two calls a day from
national media requesting background on Warner's Barnstormers days.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals kick returner and receiver Mac Cody, who played a year
in the Arena league with the Orlando Predators, isn't awed by
Warner's numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, not even the NFL, could ignore what they did in tight
confines, Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people in the NFL who take notice of you,''
said Cody, who was waived by the Rams in preseason, before the
Cardinals claimed him. ``If you go out and have a tremendous game,
that will open anyone's eyes, from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattlers receiver/linebacker Hunkie Cooper, who had a failed
attempt with the New Orleans Saints after an Arena league MVP
season in '93, said Warner and Gadsden just took their same game to
a bigger field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing the same thing in the NFL that they did in the
Arena league,'' Cooper said. ``Kurt is having a field day, and
Oronde is making plays.'' &QL; 
Partnership &QL; 
Warner's rise comes on the heels of the NFL forming a partnership
with the Arena League with a chance of eventually investing in it.
</P>
<P>
   It will never be a farm system for the NFL, but what Warner is
doing has to send a message to NFL personnel directors, said Jim
Foster, the Barnstormers' owner who invented Arena football on the
back of a manila envelope while watching an indoor soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of writers ask, `Do you think the NFL will be
swarming all over the Arena League next year?' '' Foster said. ``I
don't think it will get to that extent, but it sends a message,
that for no other reason it's a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have a steal with Warner, who is grateful to earn a '99
salary of $250,000, the league minimum for a second-year player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, they're selling tickets like crazy,'' Foster said.
``They're almost sold out for a year now. We've got two buses and a
charter plane to see the Nov. 14 game. There's a lot of residual
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams in the NFL have to say, `We need to scout these
guys more seriously.' They've got to be more focused on the Arena
League.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals General Manager Bob Ferguson has looked at the Arena
game closely since the early '90s when he was part of the Buffalo
Bills. When a defensive back went down, then-coach Marv Levy had
Ferguson get on the phone with Durwood Roquemore, then a star for
the Orlando Predators, and ask for his help.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of picks (in the Arena league),'' Ferguson said.
``In fact, he had a couple with us. He played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as players such as Warner and Gadsden get their chances,
many others wait for theirs. Such as Rattlers offensive specialist
Calvin Schexnayder, who set three single-season Arena league
receiving records two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two or three guys in the (Arena) league that are
better than Oronde,'' Rattlers Vice President Gene Nudo said.
``Like anything in life, it's fate and timing, being in the right
place at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, at 30, is still the Rattlers' heart and soul, and, while
watching Warner and Gadsden do well, it returns hope to a guy that
the NFL once deemed too small (5-foot-8) and too slow for the big
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have to look at (the Arena league) now,'' Cooper
said. ``They'll see the talent. You have to look at what the person
does when he has the football, how he overcomes adverse situations.
That carries over. Everywhere I've been, I've been a winner, no
matter if I make it to the NFL or not. I probably missed the
opportunity because the age factor sets in and the way that's
treated. But I know I can play in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner sees the respect coming, comparing it to the '60s when
the American Football League merged with the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same thing . . .,'' Bonner said. ``It got no
respect. It was treated like a Single-A league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
