<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Cornhuskers don't scare Texas 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Go beyond the wild-eyed atmosphere created by
the 84,082 crammed into Royal-Memorial Stadium. Also take it beyond
one heckuva of an entertaining afternoon of college football, and
what kind of impact the final score surprise had on the national
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Shove aside all the above, along with the Xs and 0s mumbo-jumbo,
and the huge plays and the critical mistakes. Leave it alone for
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, attempt to place yourself in Children of the Corn
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is killing these Nebraska people, who have a severe dislike
for all things Texas, including the University of. This ``Texas
thing'' eats at them like stalk rot. Two hundred acres barren of
corn would be easier to take than losing yet again to the Texas
Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   But lose, of course, the Cornhuskers did Saturday on a
beautiful, wind-blown Hill Country afternoon. Since the advent of
the Big 12 Conference, the Longhorns are 3-for-3 against Nebraska,
and this time it ended the No. 3 'Huskers' perfect season and dream
of a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska nose tackle Steve Warren summed up the gut ache that's
involved. ``Just hearing that fight song again walking off the
field, it was a bad experience,'' he said. ``They just have our
number.''
</P>
<P>
   This number was 24-20, as Texas roared back after a seemingly
out-of-it first half. The Cornhuskers led 13-3 at intermission and
the 'Horns' offense had been so inept, gallant quarterback Major
Applewhite heard boos late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone ever wants to measure the size of Applewhite's
heart, you'd better bring a tailor's tape. The Major is up and the
Major is down, but he's never down and out. Applewhite rallied the
'Horns in the second half, dealing Nebraska the kind of loss that
coach Frank Solich called ``tough for our football team and our
football program.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this one eats right at the foundation of a storied
``program.'' And yes, Solich needed a win to appease the corn crowd
back home. At the final gun Saturday, some 7,000 loyal 'Husker fans
seated in the north end zone had the look of Titanic passengers
clinging to the rail as the last crammed lifeboat floated away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not easy,'' noted safety Clint Finely, one of many
Texans (Cuero) on the Nebraska roster. ``Three times since I've
been at Nebraska is hard to take. We don't lose to anybody three
straight times.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much, anyway. Florida State has four straight bowl game wins
over the 'Huskers. Oklahoma won three straight in the mid-'80s. But
the ``Texas thing'' stings more, simply because of history and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska had to be dragged kicking and screaming into the Big
12. The 'Huskers had a personal playpen in the Big Eight,
particularly after the demise of Oklahoma as a power. And with the
Big 12 came stricter academics standards for jocks, which Nebraska
bitterly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   It was Texas and Texas A&AMP;M that had the political clout to lead
the way in the formation of the Big 12, and also in pushing through
those academic guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Huskers' revenge was supposed to come on the football
field. Except in three years, Nebraska is 1-4 against the Longhorns
and A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought we'd lose to Texas three times in a row,''
said quarterback Eric Crouch, who was unable to generate big plays
off the bread-and-butter option Saturday. ``But give Texas credit,
despite all our mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska caused self-wreckage by losing three fumbles, two
inside the 'Horns' 10-yard line. ``We had control of the game,''
said 245-pound running back Dan Alexander. ``The only way we could
lose was to beat ourselves with mistakes, which we did. It's not
that we're jinxed against them. We just have bad luck when we play
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Mack Brown, the Texas coach, happened to think
otherwise. ``Those fumbles were caused by hard tackling. We feel we
created those turnovers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it happened. And what also happened was
that Nebraska led, 20-17, with just under eight minutes to play and
the heralded ``Black Shirt'' defense couldn't hold it.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Longhorns were moving south to north in that
game-winning 60-yard drive, against the wind. All of the 37
previous points had been scored with the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the whining. Texas won the game because Texas won the
game. The Major came out throwing and connecting all through the
second half, including the clutch drive in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say he's too short and too slow,'' Finely, the safety,
said of Applewhite, ``and all that may be true. But I'll tell you
what he also is: a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Children of the Corn, the losing doesn't happen often,
except to Texas. And that's the hardest part of all.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
