<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDE DITKA LUCKY HE DIDN'T GET FIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His close friends wonder if last Sunday was the beginning of
Saints Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka's latest meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   His punishment for making an obscene gesture, swearing at a fan
and grabbing his crotch in the home loss to Tennessee could have
been much worse than the $20,000 fine the Saints levied at Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   He could have lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ditka visited team owner  &UR; Tom Benson a day after the
incident and said he was ready to accept being fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to honor that (contract) as long as they want me
here, but I told Tom the minute he wants to make a change, I
understand,'' Ditka said. ``Listen, you're nobody until you're
fired. But if you've been fired twice, you're really somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, I'll live through it. Tom knows my feelings.
I went in and apologized to him. I said, 'Listen, I'm the most
understanding guy in the world. Any change you make, I'll
understand.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Benson never considered firing Ditka or asking for his
resignation. But Ditka's relationship with the Saints fans, who
used to adore him, could forever be changed by last Sunday's lack
of class.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka was upset that the Saints, who led, 10-0, couldn't score
in the final 12 seconds of the first half after having a first and
goal at the Tennessee 1.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked off the field at halftime, several fans screamed at
him. He swore at them and flipped them off.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of the game, with fans chanting, ``Ditka
sucks,'' he grabbed his crotch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrong,'' Ditka said of his behavior. ``I was wrong. It
was done out of frustration. But that doesn't give me any right to
act that way.'' &QL; 
Kicking themselves
</P>
<P>
   Giants kicker  &UR; Brad Daluiso thinks there is a reason why he
suffered a season-ending knee injury on the final play of last
Monday night's victory over the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God was looking down and said, `Whoever that idiot is
who kicked to Deion, I'm going to blow his knee out,''' Daluiso
said. ``That's the dumbest thing I've ever seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Daluiso shouldn't be so hard on himself. It wasn't his decision
to avoid a squib kick with one second on the clock and the Giants'
leading, 13-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``My original thought was to squib kick,'' said Giants Coach
 &UR; Jim
 &UR; Fassel, the former Cardinals offensive coordinator. ``But I knew
(special teams coach)  &UR; Larry MacDuff did a lot of research on that
situation and knew what they liked to do. He suggested we bloop a
kick, which would give us a chance to get down and cover it. He
said we had worked on covering that in practice, and I knew we had.
So we went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daluiso kicked it longer and higher than he should have and
right to the one player who could beat the Giants, the Cowboys'
 &UR; Deion
 &UR; Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys then ran their version of the Stanford band play,
lateraling the ball down the field for what appeared to be a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants, Fassel and MacDuff were saved when the officials
ruled that Sanders' pitch to  &UR; Kevin Mathis was a forward lateral,
which is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Had the play stood, Fassel would have been crucified in the New
York press; MacDuff, formerly University of Arizona's defensive
coordinator, likely would have been fired, and the Giants would
have committed the second biggest late-game blooper in league
history.
</P>
<P>
   They also committed the other one, not taking a knee in a 1978
game. Instead, they handed off and fumbled and the Eagles'  &UR; Herman
Edwards returned it for a game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel wasn't there that day. But he was on the Stanford
sideline in 1982. He was an offensive assistant when rival Cal beat
the Cardinal by racing through the Stanford band. &QL; 
Midnight riders
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs Coach  &UR; Gunther Cunningham returned to Baltimore last week
for the first time since the snowy, March night in 1984 when the
Colts sneaked out of Maryland for Indianapolis in moving vans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got called into  &UR; Jimmy Irsay's office,'' Cunningham said of
the son of the former Colts owner. ``He said, `You guys have got to
pack.' I looked out the window and there were the police dogs. I
felt like a thief getting away in the night. It was such an eerie
sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was a Colts assistant at the time under Coach  &UR; Frank
Kush, the longtime Arizona State boss.
</P>
<P>
   He never came back to Baltimore until last Thursday night the
Chiefs played the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a tough deal for me,'' Cunningham said of
leaving Baltimore 15 years ago. ``Frank (Kush) always told me the
city's important in football. I love the working-class towns where
they support their football. I always said if the truck drivers
like what I'm doing, I'm OK. They're the real fans.'' &QL; 
History lesson &QL; 
It's not easy to put Dolphins quarterback  &UR; Dan Marino's 60,000
passing yards in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The 60,000 yards would translate into about 34.1 miles, 163
trips up and down the Washington monument, 600 football fields, 3.1
miles longer than the European Chunnel and seven-tenths of a mile
more than 21 trips across the Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco. &QL; 
Another curse
</P>
<P>
   All New Englanders know about the ``Curse of the Bambino,'' the
81 years the Red Sox have gone without a World Series championship
as punishment for letting  &UR; Babe Ruth go to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots, who host Denver today, have a curse of their
own. They have gone 19 years without a victory over the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   New England has lost 11 consecutive times to Denver, the longest
streak in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   In their past four victories over the Patriots, the Broncos have
outscored them, 132-45, and outrushed them, 602 yards to 230. &QL; 
Quick kicks
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are 8-2 in their past 10 games, the two losses
coming against today's opponent, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Benched Vikings quarterback  &UR; Randall Cunningham, on the team's
offensive struggles: ``We've been saying it's urgent for a while.
It's a F-U-N-K funk.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers lose today in Minnesota, they will have suffered
three consecutive defeats for the first time in a non-strike year
since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   By throwing only one touchdown pass last week, the Rams'  &UR; Kurt
Warner failed to break Packers quarterback  &UR; Brett Favre's record of
16 touchdown passes in the first five games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Diana Ditka, wife of the Saints coach, on her husband's 60th
birthday: ``I've never been to bed with a 60-year-old man. I'm
going to get him a Viagra cake.'' &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TOP FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. JacksonvilleBooooring but effective. 2. St. LouisClimb on board
the Super Bowl express. 3. MiamiAll those who think Damon Huard is
better than Dan Marino stand up. 4. TennesseeFinally has learned
how to run the ball. 5. San DiegoDefense. Defense. Defense. &UR; THE
BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
31. ClevelandContinues to lead in the Peter Warrick sweepstakes.
30. CincinnatiAkili Smith has saved Bruce Coslet's job for now. 29.
New OrleansHow many think Mike Ditka will be coaching the Saints
next year? 28. AtlantaNothing has gone right for the defending NFC
champions. 27. New York JetsTuna boat floundering and Rick Mirer is
back at the helm. ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; St. Louis Rams: Finally, the Rams have made believers out of
us, but not because of former Iowa Barnstormers quarterback Kurt
Warner. He's not the biggest reason for the Rams' shocking
offensive numbers. It's the offensive line. Led by former
first-round pick Orlando Pace, the line makes sure Warner never is
touched. Isaac Bruce is one of the best receivers in the league.
The defense is opportunistic. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New England Patriots: The bend-and-break defense doesn't work.
But that's exactly what the Patriots did in the last few minutes at
home against the Dolphins last week. They also can't run the ball.
They had an eight-point lead with two minutes left and couldn't get
a first down. This is one of the NFL's most talented teams but
always seems to underachieve. They take a two-game losing streak
into today's game against Denver, a team the Patriots never seem to
beat. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified Jets defensive player, on Coach Bill Parcells'
play-calling in last week's 16-13 loss to the Colts: ``There are
some things you just don't do. But, remember, we're dealing with a
genius.'' &QL; 
ODD-SHAPED BALL &QL; 
Former Arizona State linebacker Derek Smith could afford his own
apartment after being drafted by the Redskins in 1997. But instead
he chose to live in the Cooper family's basement in Herndon, Va.
</P>
<P>
   When the Redskins were on the road, the Coopers would pet-sit
Smith's pit bull. When the Redskins were at home, Smith would
compete in bow-and-arrow shooting contests and Parchessi games with
the Cooper's son, Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Smith no longer lives there. He got married last February. And
Chad Cooper now is a a blue-chip football recruit who is headed to
Virginia Tech. But Smith still keeps in touch with the family,
including coming over to the house to participate in the
rubber-band shooting ``wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were so vicious, I did not dare to go into the
basement,'' Chad Cooper's mother, Connie said. &QL; 
SHORT SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Packers quarterback Brett Favre was so bad in last week's 31-10
loss at Denver, he had a dismal passing rating of 9.6, the lowest
of his career. He completed only 7 of 23 passes and was intercepted
three times.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three games, Vikings second-year receiver Randy Moss
has 22 catches for 367 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback R.W. McQuarters of the 49ers, on the release of
starting cornerback Mark McMillian, who was beaten for two
touchdown passes in last week's loss to Carolina: ``I was shocked.
I checked to make sure my stuff was still here. It sends a message
around the league, they (teams) expect you to perform. If they
don't feel you're playing (well), they'll get rid of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob McNair, owner of the new Houston expansion team, wants to
call the team the ``Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have scored only four times in their past 28
possessions. During that stretch, they have missed four field
goals, thrown three interceptions and lost two fumbles. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)PNI.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
