<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HOLDS ON FOR VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOZEMAN, Mont. _ Amid the confusion, the head-shaking and the
passionate pleading with the defense for just one more stop, there
was Jaumal Bradley. He was the only guy in a Cal State Northridge
football uniform who was smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this,'' said Bradley, the only CSUN player expressing
that opinion. After all, this was a depressing,
``how-could-this-happen-again?'' kind of ending.
</P>
<P>
   But Carson Souter's 48-yard field-goal attempt was two feet wide
to the right, Montana State had not completed an amazing comeback
and suddenly all Bradley's teammates were feeling as good as he
was.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN had a 24-21 victory over Montana State on Saturday, ending
a three-year losing streak to the Bobcats in front of a homecoming
crowd of 10,007.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN improved to 4-3, 3-2 in the Big Sky Conference. The
Matadors won their first road game of the season, but only after
holding off the Bobcats (3-4, 1-3), who trailed 24-0 late in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any doubts about us winning,'' said Bradley,
even after MSU recovered an onside kick with 31 seconds left,
eventually setting up Souter's attempt with six seconds remaining.
``It made the game exciting. Always as a little kid, you think
about the game-winning field goal. I kind of knew he was going to
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley !ital!hoped!off! Souter would miss, because a loss would
have demoralized CSUN's defense, which swarmed the Bobcats for
three quarters only to see the Matadors' offense go into a funk and
not score a point in the final 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystique that Montana State has against us,'' said CSUN
interim head coach Jeff Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   If last week's domination of Sacramento State was the defense's
comeback game of the season, Saturday would be the knockout punch.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors forced out, in order, Montana State's top kickoff
returner (Arie Grey), their top tailback (Lathian Tyler) and top
receiver (Chip Hobbs). All in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Grey left with a leg injury in the first quarter after a strong
hit by reserve running back Alan Taylor on his only kickoff return;
Tyler had a hip pointer and had 21 yards on seven carries; and
Hobbs had more concussions (one) than receptions (zero).
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came and were physical,'' Kearin said. ``We're
tackling better, and we're coming up and hitting people with a
little more `oomph.' There was a lot of (MSU) offensive production
sitting on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, CSUN did everything. The Matadors had a season-high
seven sacks and broke up four passes. Montana State only ran 10
plays and gained 50 yards in the first quarter as CSUN took a 10-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Senior cornerback Chazz Moore, who didn't allow a reception on
his side of the field, helped force the Bobcats' rotating
quarterbacks _ Kasey Harte and Dusty Broderick _ into a combined
18-for-48 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as executing my assignment,'' Moore said, ``I feel like
this is one of my better games _ thus far. I still have a lot of
work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors gave up 388 yards _ almost 100 below their season
average, which ranked last in the Big Sky entering the game. And
Shawnbay Jones, a senior defensive lineman who made a team-leading
12 tackles, sensed the confidence level is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we come out, we try to make a statement,'' Jones
said. ``We know in our hearts we are better than the stats show.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana State had the same fourth-quarter magic as last year,
when the Bobcats rallied for 16 points and beat CSUN 32-26, though
it wasn't the Matadors' defense that collapsed. At least two
factors (18 penalties and offensive complacency) contributed to
MSU's comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't throw the ball as deep as we usually do,''
said Bradley, who had a season-low 53 yards rushing. ``It's
something new for us, to have a lead. We just need to learn how to
put a team away.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN quarterback Marcus Brady, who was 30 of 47 for 340 yards
and two interceptions, said this was a rare case where the Matadors
got too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to hold the lead instead of expanding it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin agreed and took the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really playing as hard the second half as we were
the first half,'' he said. ``We throttled down a little bit. That
may be why we got slowed up on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, none of the Matadors cared they had almost let a
sure-win slip away. They won on the road against a quality
opponent, something none of the contenders for the Big Sky title
can claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get a road win,'' said wide receiver Drew Amerson,
who had nine catches for 156 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
