<HEADLINE>
EXPOS PROSPECT HAS REAL GAME, NAME TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually, when center fielder  &UR; Milton Bradley steps to the plate,
he doesn't hear people yelling his name. He hears them yelling word
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dies out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after he gets a hit. This Milton Bradley indeed has
game.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old switch-hitting Montreal Expos prospect who is
playing for the Phoenix Desert Dogs in the Arizona Fall League was
named player of the week for Oct. 12-18, after hitting .526 with
two triples, a home run, six RBIs. He also scored seven runs and
stole three bases.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Bradley was hitting .475 with two homers and 11 RBIs
and had a nine-game hitting streak through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is moving up the ranks, along with his high school
rival, Diamondbacks' prospect  &UR; Nick
 &UR; Bierbrodt, a left-hander, who isn't able to play in the Fall
League, because of an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   The two competed against each other in Long Beach, Calif.,
before signing out of high school in '96. Bierbrodt was the
Diamondbacks' first pick. The Expos took Bradley in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no race to see who gets (to the major leagues)
first,'' Bradley said. ``He's a pitcher and I'm a hitter, so he's
more likely to advance faster than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who hit .329 in Class A ball last season, will join the
Expos in spring training, but isn't sure where he'll be placed to
begin the season. &QL; 
Together again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So much for saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching prospect  &UR; John Patterson keeps saying
hello to fellow pitcher  &UR; Brad
 &UR; Penny, who has been popping up in his life since Penny was traded
to the Florida Marlins as part of the  &UR; Matt Mantei deal July 9.
</P>
<P>
   They came into the Diamondbacks' organization out of high school
together in 1996. They were teammates last year at Class A High
Desert and the beginning of this season at Double-A El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the trade, they teamed up at the Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're together in the Fall League, teaming up with the
Scottsdale Scorpions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like he never left,'' Patterson said. &QL; 
Around the league &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Desert Dogs'  &UR; Rob Bell (Cincinnati Reds) was named
pitcher of the week for throwing five innings of no-hit ball,
facing the minimum of 15 batters in one game.
</P>
<P>
   Maryvale's  &UR; Dustin Carr (Tampa Bay Devil Rays) had a nine-game
hitting streak. He is second in the league in hitting at .471,
trailing Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa Solar Sox had a 12-3 record, the best start in the Fall
League since the Grand Canyon Rafters started 14-2 in '97. The
Rafters, by the way, had the worst record through Wednesday at
4-11.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two starts, Scottsdale's  &UR; Grant Roberts (New York
Mets) did not yield an earned run in seven innings. Meanwhile,
Maryvale reliever  &UR; Jamie Brewington (Cleveland Indians) has not
allowed a run in 8 innings. &QL; 
D-Back prospects &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How the Diamondbacks six prospect fared through Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Jack Cust was hitting .304 with two homers and 10
RBIs, 11 runs scored and had a .492 on-base percentage (third best
in the league).
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Jeff Andrews was 0-2 with a 16.62 ERA in three games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eric Knott was 2-1 with a 4.32 ERA in 8 innings with four
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ben Norris was 0-0 with a 6.55 ERA in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was 0-2 with a 5.00 ERA in nine innings. He walked six
and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Jeremy Ward was 0-0 with two saves and a 2.35 ERA in 7
innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
