<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNST-PURDUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE BEATS PURDUE, 31-25  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN U. BACON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. _ Purdue was 12 yards away from ruining
Penn State's undefeated season and, perhaps, its chance of winning
the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Brees, who riddled the Nittany Lions for 379 yards and 2
touchdowns, had marched Purdue down the field with less than a
minute left after Penn State had missed a 47-yard field goal that
would have given it a 9-point lead with just over a minute
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 68,355 was on its feet, begging Brees to work his
magic, as he had all season.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Penn State defense that met the challenge. Four
times it repelled the Boilermakers _ one tipped pass, three
incompletions _ as the Nittany Lions held on for a 31-25 victory.
</P>
<P>
   For Joe Paterno, Saturday's victory was the 315th of his career,
moving him past Amos Alonzo Stagg into third place among
major-college coaches and within eight of Bear Bryant's record
total. It was the 10th consecutive victory for Penn State, the
second-longest winning streak among major colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The result also continued the Nittany Lions' mastery over
Purdue. Since Penn State (No. 2 in the Associated Press poll and
No. 5 in the New York Times computer ranking) joined the Big Ten in
1993, it has won all four of its games against the Boilermakers
(No. 16 AP and No. 20 in The Times).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest game we've had on both sides of the
football,'' Paterno said after the game. ``They know what they're
doing and Brees is clever.''
</P>
<P>
   Brees, Purdue's Heisman Trophy candidate, is on target to become
the first quarterback in school history to complete over 60 percent
of his passes. He demonstrated the poise of his predecessors _ who
include Len Dawson, Bob Griese, Mike Phipps and Jim Everett _ in
completing 31 of 48 passes.
</P>
<P>
   But Brees was finally stopped by Penn State's defense, which is
led by linebacker LaVar Arrington, the favorite to win the Butkus
award. Arrington singlehandedly converted a sack of Brees into Penn
State's first touchdown and smothered Purdue's second field-goal
attempt. The block, Arrington's second of the season, sent the
teams into halftime tied at 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   While Penn State tailback Eric McCoo could manage just 10 yards
on nine carries in the first half, and the Nittany Lions'
two-quarterback offense struggled to get only six first downs,
Purdue rolled to 17 first downs on Brees' 223 yards passing to
eight different receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the most explosive offense we've faced this
season,'' Arrington said. ``It's not just Drew Brees. He's
outstanding, but it's also their offensive line, and they've got
some really good receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Boilermakers' third possession, Brees completed passes of
13, 28 and 30 yards to set up Sedrick Brown's 2-yard touchdown run.
It was the only time a team has scored in the first quarter against
Penn State's defense all season. But Arrington stole Purdue's
momentum on its next series, when he caught Brees cocking his arm
to throw the ball, forcing a fumble at Purdue's 2-yard line.
Arrington picked up the ball and walked into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come at you from different directions and come at you
with speed,'' Purdue Coach Joe Tiller said. ``It makes for a lot of
sleepless nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue came back with another impressive drive, culminating in a
9-yard pass from Brees to Donald Winston in the back of the end
zone with 10 minutes 42 seconds left in the half, giving the
Boilermakers a 14-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Penn State defense jump-started the Nittany Lions again when
Mac Morrison recovered Antoine Neal's fumbled punt return at the
Purdue 43-yard line. Two plays later, Penn State quarterback Kevin
Thompson completed his team's first long gain of the day when he
threw a 39-yard pass down the sideline to Eddie Drummond to tie the
game at 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions broke the tie on the second half's first play from
scrimmage. From Penn State's 22-yard line, Thompson stepped back
and threw the ball toward the sideline at midfield, where Chafie
Fields cut underneath the Purdue coverage, grabbed the ball and
galloped about 50 yards unchallenged. The uncharacteristically bold
play put Penn State ahead by 21-14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
