<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME COULD BE RUNNING OUT FOR DESIGNATED HITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two recently concluded league championship series, each
great in its own way, also punctuated the vast difference between
the American and National leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The times of the games in the AL were so much longer than those
in the NL that it undoubtedly will raise the issue of the
designated hitter once again. Commissioner  &UR; Bud Selig plans to use
the lengthy game times in the AL to further fuel his desire to
eliminate the DH once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Although a pair of the NL games lasted longer than four hours,
each one of those went into extra innings, including the instant
classic of Game 5, which lasted 15 innings and nearly six hours.
Two of the ALCS games dragged past the midnight hour, an incredible
feat considering neither went into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   One way baseball thinks it can speed up games is the complete
elimination of the DH, an idea that has gained momentum in recent
months and years. To get the players union to agree to such a move,
one possible plan baseball has is to add a 26th player to each
roster.
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of news that will probably not sit well with
players such as Seattle's  &UR; Edgar
 &UR; Martinez, Tampa Bay's  &UR; Jose Canseco or Cleveland's  &UR; Harold Baines,
all of whom have made a career out of being a full-time designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The union does not want to lose 14 designated-hitter spots, most
of which are highly paid. But how could the union possibly put up a
fight if baseball offered to add 30 spots while taking away just
14?
</P>
<P>
   Don't underestimate Selig on this matter. This is the same
person who initially heard he would never get interleague play or
the wild card through the proper channels. Both are now staples of
the major league landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wants to start saving time on games again. Eliminating
the designated hitter is one sure way to set that plan in motion. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
The 2000 schedules have been released and, once again, interleague
play will remain the way it's been, with each division playing its
sister division only. Which club has the best interleague record
since it was introduced in 1997? &QL; 
Expansion envy? &QL; 
While the Diamondbacks wound up running away with the National
League West championship, the other expansion club, the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays, finished in last place in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took different paths, and for the path we have chosen, I
don't think this organization has to take a back seat to anyone and
won't,'' Devil Rays General Manager  &UR; Chuck LaMar said. ``I think
our development plan is in place, and when it is all said and done,
we will reach the levels that the Arizona Diamondbacks have reached
and, hopefully, surpass those levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a lot like Arizona simply spent more money than Tampa
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did take different paths, and ours is the one that will
take time before the complete book is written,'' LaMar said. &QL; 
The Vaughn sweepstakes &QL; 
It's beginning to appear likely that the Cincinnati Reds will vie
not to participate in the upcoming negotiations for free-agent
outfielder  &UR; Greg Vaughn, who hit 45 home runs and had 118 RBIs for
the Reds last season.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn wants a four-year deal for at least $10 million per
season. At age 34, Vaughn may have trouble finding a suitor for his
talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think a 50- to 65-million-dollar deal for a
34-year-old player fits us economically or baseballwise,''
Cincinnati General Manager  &UR; Jim Bowden said. ``We probably won't be
a player in the Vaughn negotiations.'' &QL; 
Philly Phollies &QL; 
The Philadelphia Phillies may have bungled their chance of getting
a new stadium at their desired site in the Center City area of
Philadelphia. The next option, which is appearing more likely, is
to remain in south Philadelphia, right across the street from
Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the Phillies delay, the more construction costs will
soar.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling reason for the front office needing a new
stadium built as quickly as possible, however, is that they could
sentence themselves to being unable to compete if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Though the added revenue would sure help the Phillies, a larger
issue is looming. Within a few years, the Phillies could be left
playing at the only NL stadium with artificial turf, which is a
difficult sell to any prospective free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman  &UR; Scott Rolen, arguably the Phillies best
all-around player, has already complained about the fake grass
taking a toll on his still-young body. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Surprisingly, it's the Florida Marlins, who have compiled a 31-18
record since interleague play became a part of the major league
landscape. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Wonder what this says about Mark McGwire?: Legendary St. Louis
shortstop  &UR; Ozzie Smith had this to say about  &UR; Brian Jordan, whom
the Cardinals lost to free agency last winter: ``He was the best
clutch hitter in the organization.'' As for the Cardinals, Smith
added, ``There are a lot more questions than answers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Forget the animals, it's the other hunters who should beware:
Fired Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove offered this gem when asked
if he planned to do any hunting this winter: ``Now would not be a
good time to put a gun in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Ken Reitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Does it really matter?: There's a lot of talk about the winner
of this World Series earning the label as the team of the 1990s.
That's all fine, but one argument against such talk should be
centered on this question: Who was the team of the 1980s?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Another $6 million and they could have matched Kevin Brown's
contract: The Los Angeles tax assessor recently valued Dodger
Stadium at $99.92 million. The breakdown showed the actual stadium
valued at $41 million and the land surrounding the park at $52
million. Another $6 million value was placed on equipment inside
the stadium. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Philadelphia center fielder  &UR; Doug Glanville joined  &UR; Lou Gehrig,
 &UR; Eddie Collins,  &UR; Fresco &UR; Thompson and  &UR; Red Rolfe as the only Ivy
Leaguers to reach 200 hits this century. Glanville graduated from
Penn. Gehrig accomplished the feat eight times.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves have played 91 postseason games during the
1990s, easily the most of any club in the majors. Of those 91
games, Atlanta has played 18 extra-inning games, including three
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks and Florida Marlins have agreed to postpone the
deadline for Arizona to send a player to be named as part of the
 &UR; Matt Mantei deal from last July. It's not expected to be a
big-time prospect.
</P>
<P>
   One of many reasons Colorado was so enthralled with hiring
 &UR; Buddy Bell as manager was his willingness to move to Denver on a
year-round basis. Neither of the previous managers,  &UR; Don Baylor and
 &UR; Jim Leyland, made Denver his winter home. Leyland actually lived
in a conference room at Coors Field after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers requested and received permission from the
San Diego Padres to interview hitting coach  &UR; Merv Rettenmund, who
has enjoyed many successes with the Padres, Angels and Athletics.
The Padres will allow Rettenmund to leave, if that's his desire. If
he does, Detroit would probably hire former Cubs Manager  &UR; Jim
Riggleman.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals easily have the most experience in their
executive branch, at least when it comes to people who have held
general manager duties. Aside from GM
 &UR; Walt Jocketty, St. Louis has  &UR; Jerry Walker,  &UR; Bob Gebhard and  &UR; Bing
Devine. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
The Diamondbacks' annual end of spring-training games at Bank One
Ballpark will see a new face come to the Valley. The Boston Red
Sox, who open the season on the road against Seattle, will play a
pair of spring-training games at the BOB early next April.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, who appear set to trim their $45 million
payroll, are offering everyone but  &UR; Tony Gwynn and  &UR; Trevor Hoffman
to anyone who is interested. That means ace
 &UR; Andy Ashby, who will be paid $6 million in 2000, is available.
Expect several clubs to line up and try to pry Ashby away.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect St. Louis to exercise  &UR; Donovan Osborne's $5 million
option for next year. Osborne, who again was injured, will instead
receive a $500,000 buyout. The Cardinals, though, plan to try and
sign Osborne at a reduced rate, an idea that sits fairly well with
Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati badly wants pitcher  &UR; Pete Harnisch to undergo
arthroscopic surgery on his pitching shoulder. The right-hander,
though, is balking at the prospect of going under the knife.
Harnisch won 15 games and missed only two starts in the
just-completed season. The club is worried that Harnisch will go
down next season and wind up missing two months. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
