<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CREASE RULE HAS GOALIES ON EDGE, FRUSTRATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably won't find too many goalies rejoicing over the
NHL's decision to revert back to the old in-the-crease rule, where
now, a toe or inadvertent skate blade in the paint won't take a
goal away.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there's been more traffic in front of the net than
a policemen's convention at Dunkin' Donuts. Goalies are getting
folded, spindled and mutilated _ all within reason, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks mainly to  &UR; Brett Hull's controversial goal that ended the
Stanley Cup Finals last season, the league now allows skaters in
the crease so long as they don't interfere with the play. It's
called the ``no harm, no foul'' rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they don't call any penalties on them, the guys
will abuse it,'' laments New Jersey Devils goalie  &UR; Martin Brodeur.
``The big problem for me is because I play a lot outside my net,
and I get hooked and I get pushed off of more than I did in the
past. It gets frustrating when the referees don't call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Count former goalie  &UR; John Davidson as a big proponent of the
change. It's time goalies face the music, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see they have to be men again. Real men,'' the
ABC television analyst said. ``The game is about guys going to the
net and trying to score. Goalies have been sacred lambs or sacred
cows, however you want to call it, for too long. They've been given
a free ride. They can take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goalies are back to is swinging their sticks at ankles
and the backs of legs to get guys to move out of their line of
fire. Great. I miss those  &UR; Billy Smith explosions.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the former goalie for the Islanders and Kings, was
infamous for blowing his fuse and retaliating when players took
extra liberties in his space. Expect to see a lot of goalies going
``Billy bonkers'' this season. &QL; 
Russian roulette &QL; 
The knock on many Russian-born players over the years has been that
they take too many nights off, that their hearts aren't always in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Although that's certainly not true with every Russian, a great
deal of them have carried the reputation and seldom done anything
to debunk it. Vancouver's  &UR; Alexander Mogilny suggested it's a
losing battle. Stereotypes don't die easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always going to be a Russian, and there's never going to
be anything positive about Russians,'' he said. ``That's fine. I
know there's not much you can do to change how people think. (But)
there's not many people who've accomplished what I've accomplished
in this game, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I care. People say I don't care. The question is
impossible to answer. I care very much about my game and my
performance. That's all that matters to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravo. But now listen to Mogilny's former teammate,  &UR; Pavel Bure,
now with the Florida Panthers. He's sat out the past few games
nursing a sore groin and says it doesn't make much sense for him to
play hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play, I feel you have to give 100 percent,'' Bure said.
``If you can't give 100 percent, what's the use in playing? You're
hurting yourself. You're hurting your teammates. And you're fooling
nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bure was just being honest, but comments like those don't help
dissolve the myth surrounding Russian hockey players. In today's
NHL, you simply have to learn how to play through pain. And that
goes for everyone. &QL; 
Great respect &QL; 
If you get a chance, check out  &UR; Wayne Gretzky's new book,
``99'':``'' ``My Life in Pictures'' ($29.95, Dan Diamond &AMP;
Associates, Mint Publishers). The photos alone, many of them never
before seen, are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   But Gretzky also takes the time to jot down a few memories about
each picture. There's a great shot of him with the Coyotes'  &UR; Rick
Tocchet, a former teammate in Los Angeles and in two Canada Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Tocchet is one of the most respected players in the game
today,'' Gretzky writes. ``Each year, you can count on him both to
score 30 to 35 goals and be as tough as anyone in the league. I've
always admired his work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky repeated those sentiments Friday night after visiting
Tocchet and the Coyotes in the visitor's locker room following
Phoenix's 6-3 win against the Kings at the Staples Center. The
Great One is a genuine fan of Tocchet's and is proud to call him a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, whose 2,777 penalty minutes rank seventh in league
history, will play in his 1,000th NHL game on Tuesday. &QL; 
Sticking together &QL; 
Nice job by the Colorado Avalanche to somehow not only stay afloat,
but to remain ultracompetitive in the tough Western Conference
despite losing so many players.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche lost three pretty big ones to the Rangers via free
agency _  &UR; Theo Fleury,
 &UR; Sylvain Lefebvre and  &UR; Valeri Kamensky. The club also has been
without its best player, center
 &UR; Peter Forsberg, who is out until December following shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But despite that, and the fact that seven of the team's first
nine games were on the road, the Avalanche was 4-3-2 and 3-1-1 in
its past five games entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got good hockey from everyone,'' said Coach  &UR; Bob
Hartley. ``The veterans have done a great job, and the rookies are
showing very well again. Those young players have been a big help
to us. We had a good training camp, and we've worked very hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the guys are in great shape, and that's allowed us to
get through the tough part of the schedule.'' &QL; 
Quit overreacting &QL; 
Last week's incident involving Pittsburgh's  &UR; Darius Kasparaitis and
Chicago's  &UR; J.P. Dumont didn't look as bad as all the attention it's
received. Kasparaitis saw Dumont charging at him with his head down
and simply raised his elbow to protect himself and get the
Blackhawks' rookie out of his way.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem malicious or over the line on his part, but
because Kasparaitis is who he is _ one of the hardest hitters in
the game _ the Blackhawks, specifically General Manager  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Murray, and the NHL took exception. Kasparaitis was suspended for
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look out for things on the ice if Mr. Kasparaitis wants
to play that when he comes to town,'' Murray said. ``I hope he will
be a man, drop the gloves and settle it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever makes them happy, Kasparaitis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to play that way, I'm happy to do that,'' he
said. ``Their whole team is going to be in the penalty box. That's
their style of play. I'm not scared. Philadelphia tried to kill me
two years ago and it didn't happen. Nothing's going to happen this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but mark your calendar for Dec. 26. That's the next
time the Penguins play at Chicago. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. DetroitCarve it in stone. You know it and I know it. The Red
Wings will be playing in the Conference Finals.  &QL; 
2. Dallas A recent run of injuries has got Coach Ken Hitchcock
shaking in his Buster Browns.  &QL; 
3. San Jose Just moving up the charts like a new pop music
sensation.  &QL; 
4. New Jersey So he hasn't scored for two years in the playoffs,
but Bobby Holik already had six goals in six games.  &QL; 
5. Toronto They say newcomer Dmitri Khristich isn't a team player.
Who cares? &UR; BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
28. Chicago They had scored one goal more than the Coyotes (20)
through the same number of games (seven) and still were winless at
0-4-3.  &QL; 
27. Boston Coach Pat Burns is seething. So are Bruins fans, who are
clammoring for the B's to re-sign Byron Dafoe _ at any price.  &QL; 
26. Buffalo Dominik Hasek has already retired.  &QL; 
25. Calgary GM Al Coates says it's too early to panic.  &QL; 
24. Islanders Hey, you guys still interested in Robert Reichel? ON
THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Florida Panthers: Off to a flying start at 5-1-1 (before Frida vs.
Calgary) and enjoying a plush, easy early-season schedule. Six of
their first seven games were at home and they responded by going
4-0-1 in their own digs. Not too shabby, although the Southeast
Division is the weakest in the NHL. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Buffalo Sabres: Things are getting pretty interesting on this team.
Did Coach Lindy Ruff push the panic button by apparently deciding
to play muscial chairs with his goalies? Looks that way, though you
can't blame him for giving young prospect Martin Biron a chance. Or
can you? &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
 &UR; Carolina Hurricanes Coach Paul Maurice on the team's slumping power
play unit: ``I have a great agreement with the 'Canes' management.
I don't ask them about season tickets and they don't ask me about
the power play.'' &QL; 
LOOSE PUCKS &QL; 
It's easy to poke fun at the Rangers and their $60 million payroll.
Hey, I did it just last week. But Dean Lombardi, the general
manager of the San Jose Sharks, made an excellent point the other
day about his counterpart, Rangers' GM Neil Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``His boss came right out and said, `If you don't make the
playoffs, you're out of a job,' '' Lombardi said. ``It's a tough
environment to work in. What is the alternative there? If you're
Neil Smith, what do you do? You can't build in New York. They want
to build now.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting to see the Flyers sign veteran defenseman Ulf
Samuelsson to a two-year, $4.55 million contract. Samuelsson has
had some major wars over the years with Philadelphia captain Eric
Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still owe him a few things,'' Samuelsson said. ``He's a
broken shoulder ahead of me, a broken nose ahead of me. It's been
nothing personal. When I played against him, I always tried to nail
him. But I'm still a few hits behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of old defensemen, Chris Chelios appears to have
settled himself in with the Detroit Red Wings. He's planting roots
in the area, his kids are entrenched in a local youth hockey
program, and he now says quite flatly that the Red Wings ``are my
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he still doesn't forget from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going through hotels asking where the Hawks' pregame
meal is and all kinds of little slip ups like that,'' Chelios said.
``I call up restaurants for people and say, `This is Chris Chelios
of the Blackhawks . . .' I'm still (messing) up.''
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill had Edmonton trading unsigned power forward Bill
Guerin to Colorado for either Chris Drury or Milan Hejduk.
Avalanche GM Pierre Lacroix, though, squelched the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade Hejduk or Drury for any reason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers GM Glen Sather, meanwhile, beat up on Guerin in the
papers once again: ``He's looking for $3 million a year. Why
doesn't he just ask for $7 million or $8 million? What's the
difference? You're still being stupd. It's just a degree of how
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting comparison to Detroit Coach Scotty Bowman
notching his 1,100th career NHL victory last weekend. That's more
wins that 21 NHL franchises have ever won.
</P>
<P>
   At his current pace, Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr is on pace to
finish with 459 shots on goal, which would be the second-highest in
league history behind the 550 taken by Boston's Phil Esposito in
1970-71.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you can't score if you don't shoot. It should be no
surprise that when Jagr rifled 403 shots on goal in 1995-96, he
finished with 62 goals _ his career high to this day. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
