<HEADLINE>
SCRIMMAGE SHOWS HOUSE HE HAS LOTS OF HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Arizona State's basketball team needs senior
guard Eddie House as much as House needs the freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Together, in their first scrimmage Saturday at Wells Fargo
Arena, House felt good in the knowledge that he won't have to do it
all for the Sun Devils to succeed this season.
</P>
<P>
   House, of course, poured in most of the points and hit two free
throws with four seconds left to give the Maroon a 59-58 victory
over the Gold in an officiated scrimmage that had four 10-minute
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Tanner Shell's reconstructed ankle held up well
in his first all-out game since having surgery shortly after
leading Mesa Mountain View to the 5A state basketball title last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Shell's intensity on defense and hustle around the basket helped
bring the Gold back from an early 15-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Tommy Smith, who gained 20 pounds of muscle
since last season, showed off his athleticism with two alley-oop
dunks that had many in the crowd whooping.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman point guard Kyle Dodd showed poise and intelligence and
a soft jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kyle is playing really good for a freshman,'' House said.
``He's showing a lot of composure. He showed floor leadership out
there. He's patient. He is getting it done. And he's not the only
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen forwards Shawn Redhage and Donnell Knight showed
glimpses of promise. Knight finally got untracked in the final
quarter when he scored six straight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real good situation,'' House said. ``They want to win.
They want to fight hard for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donnell Knight came up to me and said, `We're going to do what
it takes to get you to the (NCAA) Tournament.' When he's a senior,
he's going to want the freshmen to do the same thing for him. I
appreciate that a lot. It's great that they're not looking to the
future. They're looking for right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Rob Evans sees similarities between this group of
freshmen and a 1995-96 freshman group he brought to prominence at
Mississippi during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these guys are a little bit ahead,'' Evans said. ``I'm
really pleased with the young kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
