<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN LIVES WITH CONSEQUENCES OF SELLING MCGWIRE'S 70TH HOME RUN
BALL 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY OSCAR AVILA  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Never, not once, did Philip Ozersky wish that he had
sat somewhere besides the left-field box in Busch Stadium that fall
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Not when the e-mailers called him a loser and other names too
nasty to print. Not when his privacy vanished in less than a day.
Not when he wondered whether he was wasting the chance of a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking back to the game, Ozersky knows that a slight change in
angle, or a wind blowing a few miles per hour stronger, would have
sent Mark McGwire's 70th home run soaring in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always go back through your life and wonder if you would
change anything,'' Ozersky said. ``If you change one thing, your
whole life would change.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd had some bad things happen to him, ``but I wouldn't
change them. They happen for a reason. I caught that ball for a
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   At work Ozersky tries to make sense of life's whims.
</P>
<P>
   In a complex near Forest Park, Ozersky, 27, and an army of
researchers at the Human Genome Project are mapping the 6 billion
pieces that make up human genes. Those multicolored lines on his
computer screen show a DNA sequence _ just one microscopic
difference can change a person entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky's life changed Sept. 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When the ball came shooting toward his section, Ozersky's heart
leaped. But his head stayed clear. Other eyes darted, but they were
slow. A beat slow.
</P>
<P>
   The ball banged off a back wall. But Ozersky, working the
angles, didn't care where the ball was. He guessed where the ball
would be.
</P>
<P>
   Then he threw his 180-pound frame under the metal bleachers
toward a prize that was his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged from the pile with a piece of baseball history that
promised to make him rich, a millionaire. Famous. The American
Dream.
</P>
<P>
   The police knew this, too, so they whisked Ozersky and his
girlfriend (whom he had met in the same box a year earlier) into
the bowels of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky ran into a tunnel, under the seats, the crowd's cheers
still audible. He held the ball up as if it were the Olympic torch.
</P>
<P>
   He ran and ran.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea where he was going.
</P>
<P>
   It's a crisp autumn day about a year later. The leaves are
falling, and baseball is close to crowning a champion. Ozersky has
just returned from lunch at the St. Louis Bread Co. in the Central
West End.
</P>
<P>
   The work load was light today, although the task remains
daunting. Researchers need to map 1 billion bases in DNA. After six
years they recently celebrated the completion of their 100
millionth sequence.
</P>
<P>
   As Ozersky lingered in the lobby, researchers in white lab coats
streamed in and out. He chatted with an acquaintance about the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   A clerk at the information desk can't help interrupting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you the guy who caught McGwire's ball?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me,'' Ozersky replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he worked in this building,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky gets this a lot. He's a minicelebrity in St. Louis. Fans
greet him at Cardinals games; strangers quiz him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what'd you do with it?'' the clerk asks curiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold it.''
</P>
<P>
   The clerk nods and smiles in approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that's right,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that, at first, Ozersky didn't know what was right.
After sprinting through the tunnel for post-game interviews, the
lifelong Cardinals fan was prepared to hand the prize back to
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The groundskeeper who caught No. 62, the ball that broke Roger
Maris' single-season record, handed McGwire the ball back before a
national television audience. He became a hero.
</P>
<P>
   The fan who caught No. 63 became a public enemy after he decided
to sell his souvenir. Other home-run catchers joined him on the
hate list.
</P>
<P>
   After considering it for a few weeks, Ozersky decided to sell
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to compare me with the guy who caught No. 62,''
Ozersky said. ``I think both of our decisions were good decisions
for us. Of course, not everyone agreed with my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Few caught the fans' wrath like Ozersky. Memorabilia experts
predicted that the ball could fetch as much as $10 million. He
quickly became the poster boy for greed in St. Louis.
( more )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
