<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6568 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BASEBALL2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      10-23 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN LIVES WITH CONSEQUENCES OF SELLING MCGQIRE'S 70TH HOME RUN
BALL 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ ``On the radio dial, at any point of the day, people
were talking about Phil as though he was the devil incarnate,''
said Daniel Paisner, whose book The Ball features Ozersky. ``He was
just doing something that any one of us would have done in the same
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The shots bothered Ozersky, but he couldn't bypass the chance to
provide for his family and for his own retirement. And he saw the
ball not as a jackpot but as a chance to do some good.
</P>
<P>
   One America Online e-mail message spoke for many in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously represent the worst elements of professional
sports today: individualism, self-gain, self-centeredness, etc.,
etc.,'' the e-mail message read in part.
</P>
<P>
   ``GET A LIFE. If you really believe that you'll have more
friends now that you've got some more money to party with, then you
obviously are too lame to gain friends on your personal attributes
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was signed, ``A baseball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   What that fan, and others, didn't realize is that Ozersky had a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky wrote a letter to McGwire in December. ``As not only a
Cardinals fan but also an avid baseball fan, it was a very
difficult decision for me not to return the ball,'' he wrote.
``However, I could not overlook the effect the sale of this
baseball may have on the lives of me and my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speculation on what the ball might sell for is
astonishing, and I turn to you as a role model of how to handle
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ozersky's ideal scenario, someone would buy the ball from
him, use it for a series of profitable promotions and eventually
return it to McGwire. Ozersky would be rich and have money to
contribute to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Under one plan, the maker of a line of plush toys similar to
Beanie Babies proposed a line of McGwire bears. Each bear would
have a serial number. The company would hold a contest in which the
winner would present the baseball to McGwire at this year's
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky wasn't sure the idea would work.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential buyers proposed unusual ideas. One wanted to take
the ball apart, add 1 inch of its thread to new balls and re-sell
them.
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance, Ozersky said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ozersky decided to auction the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk at Ozersky's office cuts to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' she whispers. ``How much did you get?''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky pauses and enunciates his jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-point-seven million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The clerk's eyes widen as if she's seen a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably bought yourself a new car,'' she says. ``I would
have bought me a new car. A Lexus, or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly,'' Ozersky says as he walks away.
</P>
<P>
   So what is a millionaire supposed to look like?
</P>
<P>
   Does he drive a Lexus? Does he wear Armani?
</P>
<P>
   Does he look like Donald Trump, who on a New York promotional
visit told Ozersky: ``You're a pretty good businessman, from what I
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phil Ozersky's case, a millionaire comes to work in a 1994
Ford Probe, in need of a shave, wearing a Cal baseball cap and
flannel shirt.
</P>
<P>
   He still rents a house in the suburb of Olivette with his
girlfriend and a childhood friend. He still goes to ball games.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky's one major purchase was a house in Florida for his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to be conscious of staying who you are,''
Ozersky said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have met Ozersky only after he became famous. But
here's a glimpse into his personality just hours before his big
moment.
</P>
<P>
   In batting practice he snagged a ball hit by Cardinal Ron Gant.
It's a baseball fan's dream. After countless games, he had a ball
of his own.
</P>
<P>
   He turned and gave it to a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now I can't believe I did that,'' Ozersky said. ``I just
felt bad because it was sitting right by her feet.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. A bigger prize awaited.
</P>
<P>
   After paying about $1.2 million in taxes, Ozersky has given
about $250,000 to charity, including money for Cardinals Care, the
American Cancer Society and the Leukemia Society of America.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to start a summer camp for abused children, McGwire's
main charity. When he was younger, Ozersky had worked as a camp
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he really emerges out of all this as a true hero, the
way he has lived his life, the choices he has made with his
money,'' Paisner said. ``He has been really inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky, however, is a reluctant hero. He changed his home
number long ago, but he still gets requests from charities. He has
given countless interviews: ESPN, morning zoos, the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   A wacky Dutch television program called ``Gekkenhuis,'' or
``Crazy House,'' even flew Ozersky to Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to work, although the whirlwind forced him to cut
back. He never thought of quitting his $29,000-a-year job.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky loves his co-workers. And he believes in their mission,
which could be one of the great scientific breakthroughs of modern
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say that I'm more proud to work on this than
being any part of baseball history,'' he said. ``This is what I'd
rather tell my grandchildren about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky has few souvenirs of his wild year.
</P>
<P>
   His desk is free of any mementos or clippings next to his thick
binders of genetic charts and uneaten apple.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky's first, and only, encounter with McGwire came at a
January charity auction. He bid $11,000 for a drawing of the
slugger. They made small talk, and McGwire autographed the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Philip,'' he wrote, ``Great catch!''
</P>
<P>
   The ball itself ended up in the hands of comic-book publisher
Todd McFarlane, who has taken it on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky saw the ball when it stopped in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fan that he is, Ozersky sometimes wishes he could just
grip the ball, just hold the gem that changed his life. This was
the ball that made so many people happy, not just baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's happy just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   As Paisner said: ``It doesn't matter who bought it. It'll always
be Phil's ball. It'll always be his moment. You can't buy that from
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
