<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURAL ART REVIVAL BRINGS TOWNS TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERVILLE, Kan. _ Here and in a score of other Kansas towns,
people are buying paint in 5-gallon buckets, popping the lids and
creating art on the sides of old mercantile buildings, railroad
depots, warehouses, banks and just about anything else standing.
</P>
<P>
   They're painting murals.
</P>
<P>
   Even ancient silos have been turned into art. And one artist is
convinced that those grain elevators that dot the Kansas landscape
like faraway white cathedrals are just waiting to become the
biggest canvases of all.
</P>
<P>
   From here in Waterville to places like Syracuse on the far
western edge of the state and in between _ Marysville, Harper,
Great Bend, Council Grove, Winfield, Pittsburg, Lucas, Protection
and a dozen other Kansas towns _ the wayfarer can find murals whose
caliber ranges from the dexterity of professional artist Stan Herd
to a group of high school students who've bedecked an empty wall
with the unique perceptions of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there are more murals being done today than anytime
since the WPA (Works Progress Administration) during the
Depression,'' said Maggie Hall-Bicker, a Winfield artist who, with
$4,000 worth of paint, turned an old warehouse into a collage of
railroads, farms and the Flint Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Hall-Bicker dated the revival of the art form to the early
1990s, when people realized again that murals could celebrate a
town's history and culture, boost the growing preservation movement
and attract spectators and tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Sullins, who runs an insurance agency on U.S. 50 in
Syracuse, a one-stoplight Hamilton County community of 1,600
abutting Colorado, couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would just roar through here on the highway,'' she
said. ``Eyes straight ahead. Now they stop and take pictures of the
mural. And they not only stop, but they spend money here. They get
something to eat. They shop. They spend some time here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Syracuse mural, depicting scenes of the town's history, is
145-feet long and 10-feet high. It was commissioned locally and
done by Mike Fallier, a Syracuse native who now lives in Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm for murals recently led the Kansas Sampler
Foundation to publish in its newsletter a list of 10 muralists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've become extremely popular,'' said Marci Penner, who
heads the foundation in Inman. ``Some, like Stan Herd, just pop out
at you. His mural in Wilmore is just wonderful. But then there are
a few that aren't so well-done. But say this: They're trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Winkenwader, a farmer and artist who lives just north of
Waterville, has done murals in Maryville, Blue Rapids and here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had the bug,'' said Winkenwader, 62. ``I liked oils
and watercolors better than just drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because art wasn't offered in high school, Winkenwader took an
art correspondence course. He farmed. He worked for the soil
conservation service. He always painted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd work for the ASCS (conservation service) days, come home
in the evening and farm, and then I'd paint way into the early
morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkenwader figured he had done about 12 murals in the three
towns, all commissioned by banks, churches and historical groups,
or private individuals. He'll pull in just a few hundred dollars on
each.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Winkenwader said he loved what he was doing. And he
said he was used to conditions most art types would rebel at _
painting, for instance, in high summer on corrugated barn siding
that has been used to cover a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The heat just blazes out at you, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Winkenwader is accustomed to the locals who
stand over his shoulder asking questions and offering advice. He
likes knowing the community is behind him, literally.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the recent Brooklyn Museum imbroglio with its
dung-splattered Madonna, a severed hog, and other shock art,
Winkenwader allowed that flinging malodorous substances around
Waterville or Blue Rapids would surely bring men in white coats and
large nets.
</P>
<P>
   Fallier agreed, adding that the New York art world ``gets all
the headlines while we're out here starving to death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's just the way it is,'' he added. ``What's nice is
that your art really means something to the people. I've had calls
from friends out in Syracuse saying that one mural has changed the
whole town. I painted it, but it's their mural.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Caldwell of Hutchinson, who has done murals in Arlington
and Great Bend, said the proprietary frame of mind Kansans take on
as they watch the transfiguration of a wall or building may speak
volumes about the real role of art in peoples' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell and other muralists believe in participatory art. One
recent mural had parts of it painted by ``artists'' ranging from by
youngsters barely old enough to hold a brush, to senior citizens in
their 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lay it out almost the same as one of those paint-by-number
kits, only bigger,'' he said. ``That mural becomes something that
kid can go back to when he's a young man or then a father and say,
`I helped paint that.' That means something.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said some towns initially had doubts about the murals.
Great Bend, he said, was an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a hard time getting the first wall,'' he said. ``Now
we've got 10 done. And there are 14 walls waiting. Once they see
what happens with a mural, people go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, said Caldwell, there's a practical streak to Kansans
embracing murals. A ballpark figure for a good-sized mural in a
small town should run from $7,000 to $9,000, he said. Compare
demolition, removing the rubble, landscaping, and ending up with an
empty lot and you're likely talking comparable money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what you find with murals is once they're up and as long
as they're maintained, the whole neighborhood around them brightens
up,'' he said. ``It's just something that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As for getting the money to do the mural, Fallier said bingo
games financed the ones in Harper. Rosslyn Schultz of the Grass
Roots Art Center in Lucas said a mural there was done with in-kind
donations such as buckets of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Conchita Reyes, an official with the Kansas Arts Commission in
Topeka, said there was some state matching fund money available for
murals, roughly $2,000 plus a little more for ``technical
assistance,'' i.e. the artist. Currently such grants are being used
for murals in Pittsburg and Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Fallier said his commissions usually came by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One town sees what another has done, and you get a call,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said he had been negotiating with a grain company to
turn one of their massive elevators into a cattle stampede scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to paint them every so often anyway,'' Caldwell
said. ``Can you imagine? A herd of cattle charging at you as you
pull into some little town? Wouldn't that be something to see in
Kansas?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
