<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION </SLUG>
 2TAKES-KAN  
 KC's SCHOOL DISTRICT WOES MIRROR TREND FACING OTHER DISTRICTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and KEVIN HOFFMANN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri's move last week to strip the Kansas
City School District of state accreditation mirrors a nationwide
trend of states intervening in their struggling urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   From New Jersey to Illinois to California, governors, lawmakers
and education leaders are growing increasingly restless with the
dismal performance in many big-city classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems now more than ever that states are intervening in the
chronically troubled districts,'' said Todd Ziebarth, policy
analyst for the Education Commission of the States, a nationwide
nonprofit group that analyzes state education policies. ``It seems
for the past five or six years, at least one or two states have
done some type of intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziebarth said state politicians were being pulled into troubled
school districts because of local officials' inability to turn
around poor test scores and low graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two states now have legislation that allows them to take
over an academically troubled district, according to data from the
Education Commission. At least 10 states have exercised such
authority, although the level of control varies from state to
state.
</P>
<P>
   The states' actions have helped correct financial and management
flaws of troubled districts, Ziebarth said. Unfortunately, state
officials have had minimal success at improving the academic
problems that often spurred them to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the first thing either a state or (a state-appointed
official) takes on are the financial problems, the management
problems, the infrastructure problems,'' he said. ``Changes in the
classroom seem to be more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kirst, a Stanford University education professor and
former president of the California state school board, has studied
state interventions. He agreed with Ziebarth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for Missouri will be can they do anything to
change the quality of the classroom. Can they connect this to
improving education at the classroom level?'' Kirst said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman says he thinks he
can.
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said the state board's decision to remove the Kansas
City district's accreditation should not be viewed as punitive.
Instead, he said, it should send a clear signal to students,
parents, school officials and community leaders that the city faces
an academic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   And time is running out. Without substantial progress in the
next two years, the district could be dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   State intervention alone, however, does not guarantee success.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Schundler, mayor of Jersey City, N.J., said that his city's
school district had seen only minimal improvement in test scores
and no improvement in the graduation rate since the state took over
in 1989, citing ``academic bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jersey City case marked the first time a state intervened in
a local school district.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Peretzman, a spokesman with the New Jersey Department of
Education, disagreed with Schundler and pointed out substantial
gains in the Jersey City district and other New Jersey school
districts under state control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence shows there has been substantial improvement,''
Peretzman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Jersey City district had met 37 percent of the
state's ``monitoring indicators'' before the intervention. The
district today meets 94 percent. He said not only had test scores
improved, but also the graduation rate.
</P>
<P>
   Peretzman acknowledged that the state first addressed
mismanagement problems. He said that New Jersey districts were
``highly dysfunctional'' and that those changes had to happen
before any improvement in the classroom could occur.
</P>
<P>
   Schundler, however, said it was time to stop shifting
accountability from one political body to another and instead make
the districts accountable to parents. If parents are unhappy with
the way their children are being taught, he said, school board
members should have to stand for another election.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra, executive director of the Education Law Center in
Newark, N.J., an advocacy group representing urban schoolchildren,
said state officials must help develop plans to put troubled
districts on a path to improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra said, however, that state officials would be in for a
long haul if they simply moved in and replaced the school board,
the superintendent or even the principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to turn and look at these schools and say, `What
do we do now?' And they are going to face the same old problems the
district had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra said that thorough assessments of teacher training,
curriculum and leadership within the individual schools must occur
before any improvement would take place in the urban classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Kansas City) is like our urban districts, they don't have
the capacity to do these sort of assessments,'' Sciarra said.
``These are districts constantly in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's loss of accreditation gives the state board
authority to replace the elected local school board with an
appointed panel. But Bartman and state Board of Education President
Betty Preston said they had no desire to take over the operation of
the Kansas City system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is volunteering for this job with the idea of wanting
to run the school district, that's for sure,'' Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bartman said his department would send officials to
Kansas City this week to help the district begin meeting the
state-ordered improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody (including the state) has got some responsibility to
improve performance,'' he said.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
