<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION </SLUG>
 2NDTAKE-KAN  
 KC's SCHOOL DISTRICT WOES MIRROR TREND FACING OTHER DISTRICTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and KEVIN HOFFMANN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The district and the community must focus
their efforts, he said, adding that his department stood ready to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be partners in a resolution, not just evaluators
and spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bartman says, he thinks revoking Kansas City's
accreditation _ forcing the state to confront one of its biggest
educational challenges _ will help speed Missouri toward having its
public schools rank among the nation's top five by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   One urban education expert called the state board's decision an
act of political courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a state really not willing to tolerate low performance
from minority and low-income kids, and that's an important message
for the state to send,'' said Alfred Hess, director of the center
for urban school policy at Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of many states that are willing to take on their
big cities. The politics of big city vs. state is pretty fierce.
This is a pretty gutsy move.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hess, who has studied state intervention in the Chicago
public schools, said the action had a downside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also sends a message that the state doesn't think the city
schools are very good,'' Hess said. ``And that's bad news for real
estate agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Berkley, chairman of the Civic Council's education policy
committee, agreed that the state action would not help economic
development efforts in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be fallout from it, no doubt,'' Berkley
said. ``How far it will go I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkley also said that the problems confronting schools in
Kansas City confronted the other districts in almost every major
American city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happen now to have been given a status that highlights
that even more,'' Berkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is we are actually on the upswing right now with
momentum and potential. Hopefully, being given this status will not
stop that momentum, but create a greater sense of urgency and
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartman acknowledged that he might have spent considerable
political capital in pushing for the loss of state accreditation.
But he said he felt that it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 10 percent of our kids not learning, and they
haven't been for a long period of time,'' Bartman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults have to take some risks, too. We think it's measured.
You do what you can to anticipate, and you measure the risk. In the
end, you try to do what's right and pay the consequences.''
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
