<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
 
TEXAS STUNS Nebraska AGAIN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
AUSTIN, Texas _ The clock expired and Texas tailback Hodges
Mitchell dropped to his knees to kiss the turf at Royal-Memorial
Stadium. Moments later, he embraced teammate Ryan Nunez before
pulling away and playfully pounding Nunez's shoulder pads. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nebraska who?,'' Mitchell yelled. ``Nebraska who?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technically, that would be the third-ranked Cornhuskers, who
fell for a third consecutive time as a decisive favorite in a Big
12 matchup against the Texas Longhorns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time, No. 18 Texas prevailed, 24-20, Saturday as a
nine-point underdog in front of a stadium-record crowd of 84,082.
Once again, the Longhorns erased a fourth-quarter deficit in
stunning the Cornhuskers and Las Vegas oddsmakers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this time, said Texas players, they did not surprise
themselves. Not like in 1996, when Texas pulled a 37-27 upset in
the Big 12 title game to win as a 21-point underdog. And not like
last season, when the Longhorns prevailed, 20-16, as 17-point
underdogs in Lincoln, Neb. That one ended the Cornhuskers' 47-game
home winning streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This one, by contrast, simply helped Texas (6-2, 3-1) hang on to
its share of first place in the South Divison standings while
dropping Nebraska (6-1, 3-1) a game behind No. 7 Kansas State (7-0,
4-0) in the North Division race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason this is an upset is because they're No. 3 and
we're No. 18,'' said Nunez, whose 39-yard catch jump-started Texas'
game-winning, fourth-quarter touchdown drive. ``I expected to win
all along. Even when we were down, 13-3, we expected to win. At
some point, you kind of get the feeling that we've got their
number.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown put it more succinctly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a freak deal. It wasn't something anybody
planned on, because defensively, we were so bad,'' Brown said.
``This year, we thought we were a much better football team with a
chance to win.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas capitalized on that opportunity, thanks in large part to a
defense that forced three turnovers, including two inside the
Longhorns' 10-yard line. Although Nebraska racked up 429 yards, 120
came on three completions, on drives that ended in two turnovers
and one field goal. Longhorns defenders focused on stopping
quarterback Eric Crouch's option runs and limited him to 35 yards
on 17 carries (2.1 per attempt). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were rolling the dice \Rwith blitzes\S, trying to get to
him and upset his rhythm,'' said Texas defensive coordinator Carl
Reese. ``We wanted to make someone else beat us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Nebraska, no one else surfaced. But the Texas offense, after
a dismal first half, rebounded with a vengeance after
intermission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same offense that produced no net yards _ and no first downs
_ on five consecutive first-half possessions cranked out touchdown
drives of 35 and 58 yards in the third quarter to erase a 13-3
deficit. Most of the damage came from quarterback Major Applewhite,
who connected on 6 of 6 passes in the third quarter for 110 yards,
including a 13-yard touchdown strike to Kwame Cavil that put Texas
on top, 17-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Nebraska responded with a 44-yard scoring drive in the
fourth quarter, giving the Cornhuskers a 20-17 lead with 7:41
remaining. Texas countered with a 60-yard march in four plays,
covering the final 17 on a swing pass to tight end Mike Jones, who
bounced off Nebraska defenders Keyuo Craver and Ralph Brown on the
way to the end zone.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt people grabbing at my legs, so I kept pulling away,''
Jones said. ``As soon as I got in the end zone, I felt like I was
in a different place. It was like I was having an out-of-body
experience, watching myself score. I'll never forget it. It was the
greatest high I've ever experienced on a football field.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teammates were pretty happy, too, especially after linebacker
Anthony Hicks' blitz forced a fourth-down incompletion on
Nebraska's final offensive play. Afterward, Crouch and the
Cornhuskers maligned themselves for missed opportunities. Crouch
called it ``very disappointing'' to be part of the first Nebraska
team to drop three consecutive games to a conference opponent since
losses to Oklahoma in 1985-87. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, a fifth-year senior, smiled and insisted he is not
surprised to have played on teams with a combined mark of 3-0
against a school with three national championships in the 1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``An upset? No. We were just the better team this Saturday,''
Hicks said. ``The way we played, we could have beaten most
anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the team Texas beat Saturday, to the surprise of many
outside the Longhorns' locker room, was Nebraska. Once again. &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:Jimmy Burch, (817) 390-7760 &QL; 
 &LR; tagbottom:jburch &LR; star-telegram.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
