<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD BUT NO WIN FOR VAN RAAPHORST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even before USC embarked on its game-failing drive
in the final two minutes, quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst had sliced
Stanford's secondary apart with his arm, his savvy and his
escapability.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, all the things he's not supposed to be able to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it, Stanford was so not in awe of Van Raaphorst's
record-setting performance that it challenged him to make a play in
the final minute to win. He didn't, and despite throwing for a
USC-record 415 yards the Trojans lost 35-31 to the Cardinal at the
Coliseum on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they would play back in a prevent (defense),'' USC
freshman receiver Kareem Kelly said. ``They insulted our offense by
coming up and doing what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, if that's the case, is a slap in Van Raaphorst's face.
The redshirt junior broke Brad Johnson's six-year school mark of
most passing yards in a game (392), but it was the 16 yards he
didn't get that hurt the most.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst scrambled to create time, connected on a pair of
64-yard touchdown passes and showed poise and composure that makes
Carson Palmer's absence easier to take. Van Raaphorst's career day
included career-highs of 25 completions, 51 attempts and three
touchdowns. But it was little consolation after he was intercepted
on the last play of the game at the Stanford 7-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what I threw for, we needed to win,'' said Van
Raaphorst, who was on the verge of tears in the locker room. ``I
feel bad. Nothing matters. The stats don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this isn't how the most prolific passing display in
Trojans history should turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst nearly threw for more yards in this game than
Palmer did before his collarbone injury (490), but offsetting the
64-yard TD passes to Marcell Almond and R. Jay Soward was the
third-quarter interception that gave Stanford its first lead.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst never took his eyes off Soward, his intended
receiver, and Chris Johnson stepped in and returned the pick 30
yards to put Stanford up 28-24. It was the first of three
second-half interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Mike gave us a chance to win,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``He threw the deep ball well, audibilized well. We
didn't protect him down the stretch. Mike's a great competitor. He
needed help from some people at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the knocks on Van Raaphorst _ a lack of arm strength,
speed and big-play ability _ were pushed aside in for the first 58
minutes. But the most important one _ an ability to lead a team to
a comeback on the final drive _ remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so poised and calm the whole time,'' USC running back
Chad Morton said. ``That's why I like being next to him in the
huddle. This isn't all on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst had the chance to add conspicuous-by-its-absence
late-game heroics to his portfolio when the Trojans' defense gave
him the ball on the Stanford 45 with 2:08 to play. He even made a
critical fourth-down play when he waited until he was hit to dump
the ball off to Morton, who darted for the first down to keep USC's
hopes alive with under a minute to play.
</P>
<P>
   But after a third-and-4 pass fell incomplete with nine seconds
left, Van Raaphorst was left with one more chance. And now he's
left with the memory of Tim Smith intercepting the ball and running
out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's there to say?'' Van Raaphorst asked. ``I can't think of
anything right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
