</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDERIES-PITCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GLAVINE SICK, MADDOX GETS THE CALL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The telephone rang late at Bobby Cox's house Friday
night and, as with many late-night phone calls, it was not good
news.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine, the Atlanta Braves' designated starting pitcher for
Game 1 of the World Series, was at home sick with an intestinal
virus and would not be able to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I've got to get a hold of Maddux,''' Cox, the Braves'
manager, said, referring to Greg Maddux, who pitched Game 1
Saturday night, a 4-1 loss to the Yankees, instead of Game 2 on
Sunday night. But Cox said Glavine told him, ``No, I've called him
and he's ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was ready. He pitched brilliantly through seven innings
Saturday night, but left the game in the eighth inning with the
score 1-1 and the bases loaded. John Rocker relieved Maddux, but
those three base runners came around to score and were the
difference in the game. Maddux, who was charged with the loss,
allowed four runs, two of them earned, on five hits and three
walks, and struck out five. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Cox said about Glavine's illness, ``but
things like this do happen. Tommy has pitched at times with a bad
arm through his career, shoulder, elbow, two broken ribs, two bad
knees, a bad ankle, an infected toe and never missed a start that I
can remember. He's really sick, dehydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Braves, beset by a seasonlong string of devastating
injuries and illness, encountered their latest medical hurdle.
Glavine had caught the bug that had leveled his family. His stepson
and wife were ill during the National League Championship Series
against the Mets and, after Friday's workout and news media
session, Glavine felt sick enough by 11:15 p.m. to tell Cox there
was no way he could pitch Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he hoped that Glavine, a left-hander, would be fit
enough to start Game 3 on Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium. If
healthy, he would then also be available to start Game 7, if that
is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   He had been scheduled to start Games 1 and 5. Cox wanted Glavine
to start the Series opener because he had not pitched since
throwing seven shutout innings against the Mets in Game 3 of the
League Championship Series on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox juggled his rotation around Glavine's illness. Glavine
will have 10 days of rest if he goes in Game 3, but if there is a
Game 7 he will have his regular four days of rest. Kevin Millwood,
who was scheduled to start Game 3, will instead start Game 2, and
John Smoltz remains the Game 4 starter.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the sudden change in the rotation produced a
dramatic drop for the Braves. Glavine, a two-time Cy Young award
winner who is 1-0 with a 1.38 earned run average in the post-season
this year, gave way to Maddux, a four-time Cy Young award winner,
who entered the game 1-1 with a 2.14 e.r.a. in the 1999 post-season
and who had last pitched in Game 5 of the League Championship
Series, on Oct. 17. Maddux threw only lightly in the outfield
during Friday's workout, so he was fully rested.
</P>
<P>
   One impact of the change in pitchers was on the Yankees' lineup.
Ricky Ledee, a left-handed hitter who was 0 for 3 Saturday night,
started in left field instead of Chad Curtis, a right-handed hitter
who would have played had Glavine pitched. Manager Joe Torre did
not find out about the switch in pitchers until he arrived at the
park about 2:30 p.m., when he looked at the lineup sheet and a
clubhouse attendant told him Glavine was sick.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, too, was unruffled by the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, it's the same, except it might be easier because
we're at home,'' he said. ``Physically, the only difference is I
get to hit. I don't know if that's good or bad for us. I was
looking forward to pitching at Yankee Stadium. I hadn't gotten to
pitch there during the regular season. It's always been a dream of
mine to pitching in that stadium. What better time than the World
Series?''
</P>
<P>
   If there is any additional concern for Cox now, it is that the
virus does not sweep through the Braves' clubhouse, as illnesses
regularly do. But Glavine stayed at home Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think,'' Millwood said, ``that's he's going to be
coming around kissing anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
