term for butlers, students study the art of table setting and
serving a formal dinner at the Starkey International Institute for
Household Management. Until the school opened in Denver, most
students had either been trained in the great homes of the very
rich or had emigrated from England, where there are training
schools and a long tradition of butlers learning their craft as
underbutlers. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DENVER -- Oct. 23, 1999 -- BUTLER-BOOM-2, 10-23 -- Mary
Starkey, founder of the Starkey International Institute for
Household Management, a school in Denver that markets itself as the
Harvard of high-end household help, talks to students about the art
of preparing and serving a formal dinner. Mrs. Starkey's
10-year-old school, based in a Georgian mansion near the Colorado
Capitol dome, now graduates about 60 certified household managers a
year. She plans to expand next year with a second training mansion
in the Washington area. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DENVER -- Oct. 23, 1999 -- BUTLER-BOOM-1, 10-23 -- In a
class for would-be butlers, Lahn Graham, left, and Jean Voecks
study the geometry of table setting at the Starkey International
Institute for Household Management. These are lucrative and
stressful times in the annals of household help in the United
States. Never before have there been so many wealthy Americans with
so many big houses that need tending. In New York, Washington and
Los Angeles, placement agencies that specialize in servants for the
rich say that the demand for experienced household managers exceeds
the supply. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
