<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SERIES24-COX     10-23 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game One yanked from Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves spent three days convincing the media and
themselves that this team was different from the one that lost to
the Yankees in the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went out in Game 1 of the 1999 World Series on
Saturday night and did their best imitation of the team that lost
to the Yankees in '96.
</P>
<P>
   For seven innings, the Braves' Greg Maddux outdueled the
Yankees' October wonder, Orlando Hernandez, thanks to Chipper
Jones' awakening from a 60 at-bat power slumber with a solo home
run in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But like the last four games of the '96 Series, the Braves had
the bottom yanked out from under them in a 4-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, trailing 1-0 in the best-of-seven, will send Kevin
Millwood against David Cone in Game 2 on Sunday night at Turner
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' homer in the fourth inning turned out to be one of two
hits for the Braves. The 1-0 lead it provided lasted until the
eighth inning, when the ever patient Yankees lineup scored four
runs against Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had allowed a base-runner in five of the first seven
innings _three reached second base _ but held the Yankees scoreless
by mixing in three strikeouts, a double play and a couple of weak
grounders to stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That quality work got swallowed in a wobbly eighth inning, when
the Yankees loaded the bases on Scott Brosius' third single of the
game, a pinch-hit walk by Darryl Strawberry and an error by first
baseman Brian Hunter, who had a ball slip out of his hands on a
Chuck Knoblauch sacrifice bunt attempt. Maddux thought he had Derek
Jeter struck out on an 0-2 pitch away, but didn't get the call,
then watched Jeter tie the game with a no-out single to left to
make it 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker was called in to stop the damage, but only
contributed, falling behind to Paul O'Neill 3-1 before giving up a
two-run bouncing single to right. Rocker struck out the side, but
not before giving up another run on a bases loaded walk to Jim
Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   That inning all but wrapped up the Braves' fifth consecutive
World Series loss and the Yankees' ninth consecutive World Series
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees haven't lost in the World Series since Game 2 of
1996, when Maddux pitched eight shutout innings in a 4-0 Braves
victory. The Yankees won the next four to stun the Braves in 1996
and four more to sweep the Padres last season.
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Glavine sitting at home with a terribly timed case of
the stomach flu, Maddux played emergency starter. It was his third
Game 1 start of the postseason and first Game 1 start in a World
Series since 1995 when he beat the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He drew the Yankees best postseason starter.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the Cuban defector with the high leg kick and sliding
arm angle, has been virtually untouchable in his two years of
playing in October. Entering Saturday night's game he was 4-0 with
an 0.97 ERA in five starts, 2-0 with a 1.17 ERA this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome than those numbers for the Braves was his
bloodline. Hernandez is the half-brother Livan Hernandez, who
terrorized the Braves for 15 strikeouts in a 2-1 Marlins victory
against Maddux and the Braves in Game 5 of the 1997 NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez came close _ with 10 strikeouts in seven
innings. By the time NLCS MVP Eddie Perez struck out for a second
time in two at-bats on a Hernandez curve, El Duque had matched his
postseason high in strikeouts with nine, and it was only the second
out of the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   For the first couple innings, progress against him meant a
little contact, which Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko supplied with
back-to-back outs to right field. That and an Andruw Jones walk in
a 10-pitch at-bat in the second inning ended a roll of eight
strikeouts from Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   But he was staring down a 1-0 deficit after a poor 1-0 pitch to
Chipper Jones, who turned on a belt-high fastball for his first
home run this postseason and first ever homer in a World Series
game. Jones had hit a paltry .217 in the postseason from the left
side with more strikeouts (six) than hits (five).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
