r s BC-FBC-BAGGARLY-COLUMN-L     10-23 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAGGARLY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT, PASADENA, STANFORD IS ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another week, another Stanford victory, another
step closer to the school's first Rose Bowl appearance in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a member of the Tournament of Roses Committee, you
might as well pull your crimson blazer over your head.
</P>
<P>
   Because if this Stanford team represents the conference in
Pasadena on Jan.1, things could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there's no doubting Stanford is the best the Pac-10
has to offer, which is a little like being the finest-tailored suit
in a thrift store.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal won another game Saturday, coming back from a 21-0
deficit to stun USC 35-31 at the Coliseum. It was the latest stop
on their undefeated run through the conference, which includes a
10-point victory over UCLA and a 50-22 mugging at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has a game and a half on the rest of the conference,
with games remaining at Washington, at Arizona State and home
against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   If Stanford wins the Pac-10 championship, it will bring the
worst defense Pasadena has seen since... oh, wait. Nearly forgot.
UCLA plays there every other week.
</P>
<P>
   But be it Stanford or another of the Pac-10's not-so-fearsome
.500 teams, the conference champ will get Penn State. Or, if the
Nittany Lions are snapped up to play in the Sugar Bowl for the
national title, the next at-large BCS team.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the second-place team from the Big 10, but not
necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, Ohio State, Michigan, Wisconsin _ they all seem like
mismatches. But it could be worse. It could be an at-large team.
Like, say, Florida. Or Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Granddaddy of 'Em All could be reduced to a New Year's Day
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   If USC second-stringer Mike Van Raaphorst can throw for 415
yards against this Cardinal defense (a Trojans all-time single-game
record), then what could a real quarterback do?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Stanford gave up 415 passing yards Saturday. Along
with 587 total yards, 24 first downs, 212 rushing yards and a pair
of 64-yard TDs.
</P>
<P>
   And won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stats don't look pretty,'' Stanford cornerback Ruben
Carter said, ``but stats don't matter much in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be true in the perspectiveless Pac-10, which has
become a bastardized version of the Western Athletic Conference.
The games have turned into stat-stuffed shows of offensive
gluttony.
</P>
<P>
   Or defensive incompetence, depending on your point of view.
Either way, it's an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single team is ranked in the top-25 of the two major
polls. Mathematically, it's possible for every conference team to
be bowl ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   On the national landscape, the Pac-10 is a speed bump.
</P>
<P>
   Check that. Speed bumps are designed to slow things down. Pac-10
defenses have shown no such ability.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stanford, the conference's top team according to the
standings, is unranked. What's worse, it has an 0-2 nonconference
record.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cardinal's two defeats weren't particularly pretty. One
was a 44-39 loss to San Jose State _ a WAC team, for crying out
loud _ and the other was a 69-17 lashing at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It was more of the same porous Stanford defense Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst hit Marcell Allmond with a 64-yard touchdown at
2:50 of the first quarter. It was the Trojans' longest play from
scrimmage this season. Two quarters later, Van Raaphorst tied that
mark with a 64-yarder to R.Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   Soward dropped another bomb, a guaranteed 70-yard TD catch at
the start of the fourth quarter, after he had beaten cornerback
Chris Johnson down the field by a full 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything bad about Stanford,'' Soward
said, ``... but we could've had that all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow though, Stanford came on top again. Came another game
closer to their first Pac-10 title since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal remains on a collision course for the Rose Bowl _
``collision'' being the operative word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
