</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD LIVES IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyrone Willingham calls it living in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Stanford head coach had no problem with defensive
lineman Willie Howard sprawling in celebration on the Coliseum turf
following Stanford's improbable 35-31 victory over USC on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he enjoyed seeing offensive tackle Jeff Cronshagen
sitting on the Cardinal bench happily soaking in the atmosphere of
the victory with no thoughts of the next three weeks on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why he had to grin when he saw quarterback Todd Husak
searching the crowded field until he could give teammate Tim Smith,
who salted away the win with a last-play interception at the
Cardinal goal line, a big hug.
</P>
<P>
   That's also why Willingham didn't want to hear anything more
about the latest victory on what is becoming to look more and more
like a Rose Bowl tour once the sun came up today.
</P>
<P>
   ````This is a huge win for us,'' said Willingham, having no
trouble keeping a calm exposure despite the chaotic afternoon.
````And (today) it's on to the next one. Washington becomes the
focus of our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try, but maybe it's time to focus on what it takes to be in
Pasadena on New Year's Day. Stanford, at 5-0 in Pac-10 play, leads
Arizona State, Washington and Arizona by one game in the loss
column. So, let's look at next week versus Washington, but also
take a peek at a road game against Arizona State and the conference
finale against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to dust off the old tales of New Year's Day 1971
and 1972 when the Cardinal last played in a Rose Bowl. Maybe it's
time to teach the unedecated why the 1971 defense was called the
Thunderchickens.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for us media members to admit - gulp - that we
were wrong to project before the season that Stanford was the
eighth best team this conference has to offer. Maybe it's time to
remember that a Stanford team that loses to San Jose State can
still play in Pasadena - like the 1971 Cardinal squad did.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about living in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ````It's hard not to think about it (the Rose Bowl),''
linebacker Riall Johnson grudgingly admitted. ````We have to have
that as a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   See, now was that so hard?
</P>
<P>
   ````But we can't do that by not playing them one a time,''
Johnson countered quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Husak, a St. John Bosco High graduate, emerged from the
victorious locker room and spoke of the highs and lows that can
envelop a college football season. He gave an example, discussing
the 1997 season when the Cardinal were 4-1 and nationally ranked
before losing five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ````This is nice,'' Husak said, ````but we could lose the rest
of the games and not even go to a bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   There were things on Saturday to indicate that might not be so
farfetched of a notion. Stanford, after all, did fall behind USC,
21-0, before the teams changed sides to begin the second quarter.
The Cardinal defense did allow Mike Van Raaphorst, who wouldn't
have been playing if Carson Palmer didn't lower his shoulder
against Oregon, to throw for 415 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, perhaps, this is an offense which couldn't
gain an inch on fourth down at the Stanford 45-yard line with 2:08
remaining and the Cardinal clinging to a 35-31 lead. Husak ducked
his head into the line of scrimmage in search of the needed inch
and came up two inches short.
</P>
<P>
   ````I felt it was bad spot,'' Husak said.
</P>
<P>
   All they needed was an inch. The spot shouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ````My thought process was if we get one inch, we win the
football game,'' Willingham said. ````I felt confident we could get
what was needed. Was there a risk involved? No question about it,
but I weighed the risk and thought it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision failed and the game suddenly hinged on the
110th-rated defense in the land.
</P>
<P>
   ````I went to (Willingham) and said `You're going to go for it
aren't you?','' defensive coordinator Kent Baer said. ````I felt
confident if we didn't get it then (the defense) would go out and
get them stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   It took every bit of the defense's energy to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ````I'm sure there still are some non-believers out there,''
Husak said. ````But, I'll tell you, there isn't one non-believer in
that locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Non-believers? Husak knows all about them.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't earn a full-time starting job at St. John Bosco until
hs senior season and colleges weren't exactly beating down his
door. In fact, his options consisted of Stanford and, well,
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Stanford was right. On Saturday, he was 20 of
32 for 290 yards with touchdowns of 23 and 16 yards and the
game-winning score on a 1-yard plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ````I'm not trying to prove anything to (the schools that didn't
offer a scholarship),'' Husak said. ````I've proven that I can
play. What's important to me is proving we can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
