r s BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     10-23 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS CRUMBLE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's USC joke: What does a Trojan do when he gets dealt a 21
in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Fold.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive me if that sounds harsh. But how often do teams blow
21-point first half leads, in consecutive games no less? USC stands
3-4 on its fast-eclipsing season and DOA in the comatose Pac-10,
and no one will blame Trojan fans if they decide to skip the second
half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 35-31 loss to Stanford at the Coliseum was no better
or worse than the loss at Notre Dame a week ago. A mediocre team
that is poorly coached found a way to lose, and that's pretty much
what one has come to expect of the Trojans now for more than a
decade now.
</P>
<P>
   They can neither live up to their old reputation nor any
down-sized expectations, like competing annually for the Pac-10
title. Those hopes for '99 are as dead as UCLA's, the only saving
grace.
</P>
<P>
   The sad sight here Saturday was emotionally spent young USC
players trying to painfully explain why they again lost a football
game the same way. The questions weren't nearly as probing as the
answers were telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a question of heart,'' said USC safety David Gibson.
``It isn't that we didn't play hard enough, or that we don't want
it bad enough. We were all aware that `we can't blow this lead.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Van Raaphorst, the junior subbing for Carson Palmer who
threw for a school-record 415 yards but also three interceptions,
wore the look of someone zipping body bags, consumed by dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to expound on,'' he said. ``If you guys
figure it out, let me know. I can't give you any perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's mental,'' said cornerback Antuan Simmons, who
intercepted two passes but was also the primary corner on two
Cardinal touchdown passes. ``It's not physical. I'm not tired.
We're just not making the plays when it's for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   When a team loses is just a matter of timing. The common ground
is that USC, at best, is fundamentally inconsistent and poorly
prepared. Stanford contributed to USC's brisk 21-0 start with a
soft early zone, poor punting and a halting offense adjusting to a
new different starting tailback, Brian Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford began making its adjustments in the second quarter, and
except for one more long USC touchdown pass and one specious
Stanford coaching decision in the final minutes, it dominated the
rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   On a day the offense netted 587 yards (238 of it in the first
quarter), for example, there were still questions to ask about Paul
Hackett's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Like, why does Hackett ask Van Raaphorst, who does not have the
long arm or quick release of Palmer, to throw the same kind of
passes, virtually all of them on the perimeter, down the sidelines
or long, slow-developing out patterns?
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst doesn't move well, either, yet there he was
running plays in the last minute off play-action with Stanford
selling out to crush the pocket. Why not throw in some shotgun
formations, which would give Van Raaphorst time and better
visibility?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use the shotgun,'' said Hackett. Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the question of why USC still can't seem to stop
any kind of running game. Stanford's netted 160 Saturday, and it
did its best work on its gamewinning touchdown drive, with nine
rushes among 14 plays on a 55-yard drive that, on a day of big
plays and quick strikes, took 6:38 off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett had all of the answers, of course. This was the other
sad sight. His post-game discourse was clinical, like that of an
attending surgeon who just watched someone else lose a patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting tired of these,'' he said. ``When you fumble, when
you throw interceptions, when you shank punts, when you miss field
goals ...''
</P>
<P>
   This was entirely consistent with Hackett's comments this week,
when he publicly called out the seniors for a lack of leadership.
Those comments showed little compassion or sensitivity for the very
small group of seniors who start, like Gibson, the everloyal Chad
Morton and Wendrell Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter Saturday asked Hackett why he doesn't seem to
accept much of the responsibility for the losses, Hackett bristled
and belittled the question and questioner.
</P>
<P>
   We're spoiled, of course. For years, standup coaches like Terry
Donahue and John Robinson rarely pointed fingers at the players,
even when it might have been warranted. Robinson's second tour at
USC was messy, but he still went out on his shield. To do so would
have been a breach of family.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett may not understand family. What he does understand is
that by blaming the seniors, who are as good as gone anyway, he
shifts blame to the guy who recruited the seniors, Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun may not be in Hackett's arsenal, but he runs a great
mis-direction. From now on, let's call him Blackjack Paul Hackett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-23-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
