<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991023.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-23 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-2     10-23 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT BRAVES, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: 10  photos , NYT09-NYT18, are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reggie Jackson won the right to be called Mr. October
for his post-season exploits. Orlando Hernandez might be Mr.
October, the Sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez permitted one hit in seven innings, striking out 10,
and the Yankees rallied for four runs in the top of the eighth
inning, defeating Atlanta and Greg Maddux, 4-1, in Game 1 of the
World Series Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' David Cone will face Kevin Millwood of the Braves
in Game 2 on Sunday night. Atlanta's Tom Glavine, who had been
scheduled to pitch Game 1, was scratched after he came down with a
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking their 25th World Series title, the Yankees are winning
in the post-season with even greater efficiency than they did last
year, when they took 11 of 13 games en route to the championship:
they have won eight of nine games this year.
</P>
<P>
   The only hit off Hernandez in his seven innings was a home run
slugged by Chipper Jones in the fourth, and Maddux shut out the
Yankees into the eighth, holding that 1-0 lead. Maddux had been the
winning pitcher in the last shutout of the Yankees in the World
Series, in Game 2 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Brosius rolled a single through the left side of the
infield, his third hit, leading off the eighth. Yankees Manager Joe
Torre decided to forgo the bunt and sent Darryl Strawberry to
pinch-hit for Hernandez, and Maddux walked him. Chad Curtis ran for
Strawberry, and there were runners on first and second and nobody
out. The potential tying and leading runs were on base, and now
Torre called on Chuck Knoblauch to bunt the runners along.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch pushed a bunt between the onrushing Maddux and the
charging first baseman Brian Hunter. As Knoblauch sprinted toward
first, Hunter tried to recover, gloved the ball and dropped it, and
Hunter was charged with an error. Bases loaded, nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter fell behind, no balls and two strikes, took a close
pitch for a ball and then slammed a single through the left side of
the infield, all runners advancing a base and Brosius' run tying
the game. Maddux walked off, and the left-hander John Rocker
relieved to pitch to Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who had done so poorly against left-handers this year,
got ahead in the count, 3-1 _ one of Rocker's errant pitches had
bounced against the backstop and returned directly to catcher Eddie
Perez, great fortune for the Braves _ and then muscled a ball
through the right side of the infield. Curtis and Knoblauch raced
home, and by the time the Braves finished firing the ball around
the field, the Yankees led, 3-1, and had runners at second and
third.
</P>
<P>
   Later, with the bases loaded, Rocker walked the pinch-hitter Jim
Leyritz to force in the fourth run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front sacked Atlanta Saturday afternoon, the temperatures
dropping, the winds gusting. When Maddux strolled to the mound for
the top of the first inning, it was 49 degrees and there were
predictions that the temperature would drop near 40 by game's end;
the wind blew across the field, straight in from left-center field,
straightening the flag above Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Batboys scrambled to corral hot dog wrappers and napkins, and
the picture-glass windows on the private boxes shimmered in the
breeze. Yankees third baseman Brosius breathed warm air into his
glove. Infielders staggered and lunged to catch pop-ups. George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, donned the same outfit
as he did in Boston last weekend (baseball people are notoriously
superstitious): heavy parka with a hood, Yankees baseball cap. So
long as Maddux and Hernandez could comfortably grip the ball, they
were working in conditions highly favorable to them.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez came into the game with an impeccable record in the
post-season: four victories in five starts, with the Yankees
winning his only no-decision, and a 0.97 earned run average in
October. The Braves had hit him hard in regular-season games the
last two years, but this was different. Hernandez seems to focus
deeply during big games, catcher Jorge Posada said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his baseball pants high, with the long, dark blue socks,
and a long-sleeved shirt, Hernandez chewed gum ferociously on the
mound until he set his body to throw, and then his jaws would stop
and he stared at the hitters and began his delivery, which seemed
to confound the Braves from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw a two-strike slider to the first hitter he
faced, Gerald Williams, and Williams swung wildly, as if he swung
in the dark. Bret Boone anticipated an outside slider and was
overpowered when Hernandez zipped a 91-mile-an-hour fastball under
his hands. Jones looked for something on the outside corner with a
full count and Hernandez fooled him, too, throwing a fastball over
the inside corner. Three batters, three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out seven in the first three innings, and if
this seemed familiar to the Braves, you would not have blamed them:
the last time a Hernandez brother faced them in the post-season, in
1997, Livan Hernandez struck out 15 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque made one serious mistake in the first three innings,
with one of his fastballs to Ryan Klesko _ who had been 5 for 5 in
his career against Hernandez _ and the Atlanta slugger hammered the
ball to right field. A home run, on a summer day. But when his
drive met the stiff wind, his drive lost, dying and falling into
the glove of O'Neill in right.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to the dugout, Klesko glanced over his shoulder
toward right field, disbelieving, and he appeared to mutter aloud
to teammates as he returned his bat to the rack:  &UR; You've got to be
kidding me. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, however, were having the same sort of success
against Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra, here to be introduced as part of baseball's
All-Century Team on Sunday, lounged on the Yankees' bench before
the game and remembered how, two days after Don Larsen's perfect
game in the 1956 World Series, Johnny Kucks arrived at Ebbets Field
to find a baseball resting in the heel of one of his baseball
spikes, left there by the coach Frank Crosetti. That is how Kucks
learned how he was to start the deciding game of the World Series
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had a similar experience. Glavine, scheduled to pitch
Game 1, was beset by a virus and called Maddux late Friday night
and told him he would probably not be able to pitch. Torre, the
Yankees' manager, learned of the switch Saturday afternoon, when a
teen-age clubhouse attendant relayed the Braves' lineup from
Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox, mentioning _ oh, by the way _ that
Glavine was sick.
</P>
<P>
   The change really made no difference, Knoblauch said before the
game, because after watching both pitchers for years on cable
television, the Yankees were going to be just as familiar with
Maddux as they were with Glavine. Hopefully, Knoblauch said, ``we
can get his pitch count up by the fifth or sixth inning, and he
won't be around that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux threw seven pitches in the second inning, 11 in the
third, eight in the fourth; he was around far longer than the
Yankees would have preferred, throwing strikes, sinking his
fastball, throwing it inside to left-handers and running it back
over the inside corner of the plate. He did this to right-handers
as well, his fastball appearing to be outside, out of reach, until
it darted over the outside fringe of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two runners reach scoring position in the first
three innings, but Maddux struck out Bernie Williams with Jeter on
second in the first inning, and after Brosius reached second in the
third inning, Knoblauch popped out and Jeter grounded to second.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out Boone to open the fourth, and after falling
behind one ball and no strikes to Jones, Hernandez tried again to
pound an inside fastball past the probable National League most
valuable player. But Jones would not cooperate, turning and
launching the ball down the right-field line; Jones stood at home
plate and watched until he was sure the ball would curl on the
inside of the foul pole. It was his first home run since Sept. 23,
the first run of the World Series, the first hit for the Braves _
and the only hit Hernandez would allow.
</P>
</TEXT>
